</OL>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="intro">Introduction</A></H2>
<DL>
<DD>In the past, the general area of trademark and unfair competition law has been decidedly colorful.  As one court recently noted:<P>
<DL>
<DD>
Saddam Hussein wants to keep advertisers from using his picture in unflattering contexts.  Clint Eastwood doesn't want tabloids to write about him.  Rudolf Valentino's heirs want to control his film biography.  The Girl Scouts don't want their image soiled by association with certain activities.  George Lucas wants to keep Strategic Defense Initiative fans from calling it "Star Wars."  Pepsico doesn't want singers to use the word "Pepsi" in their songs.  Guy Lombardo wants an exclusive property right to ads that show big bands playing on New Year's Eve.  Uri Geller thinks he should be paid for ads showing psychics bending metal through telekinesis.  Paul Prudhomme, that household name, thinks the same about ads featuring corpulent bearded chefs.  And scads of copyright holders see purple when their creations are made fun of.<P>
</DL>
<EM>Vanna White v. Samsung Electronics America, Inc.</EM>, 989 F.2d 1512, 1512-13 (9th Cir.), cert. denied, 113 S. Ct. 2443 (1993).  It should be no surprise, therefore, that in 1994 companies and individuals have sought to further expand the boundaries of trademark law and to seek the passage of new legislation to protect their competitive interests.  Companies must be aware, therefore, of the potential rights they or others may have before making or implementing business plans.  The following discussion highlights some of the hottest issues in the area.<P>
</DL>
</DL>
<H2><A NAME="color">COLOR AS A TRADEMARK</A></H2>
<UL>
<LI>The traditional rule is that color, per se, is not capable of appropriation as a trademark.  That is, one seller cannot make a product or its packaging in a certain color and prevent competitors from adopting the same color for their products or packaging.  Color in connection with a definite design may, however, be protected as part of the overall trademark.  The circuits are split on the question of whether to give color alone the protection of a trademark.  The majority of circuits have refused to grant such protection.  <EM>Qualitex Co. v. Jacobson Products Co., Inc.</EM>, 13 F.3d 1297 (9th Cir.), cert. granted, 115 S. Ct. 40 (1994); (trademark registration for green-gold color in connection with dry cleaning press pads is invalid; court held one cannot register color alone as a trademark; <EM>Nutra Sweet Co. v. Stadt Corp.</EM>, 917 F.2d 1024, 1027 (7th Cir. 1990), cert. denied, 499 U.S. 983 (1991) (blue packet for tabletop sweetener not protectable as a trademark).  <EM>Cf. Master Distributors, Inc. v. Pako, supra</EM>, (blue leader for tape may be protected as a trademark); <EM>In re Owens-Corning Fiberglass Corp.</EM>, 227 U.S.P.Q. 417 (Fed. Cir. 1985) (pink for fiberglass a protectable trademark); <EM>Brunswick Corp. v. British Seagull Ltd.</EM>, No. 941049-1050, 1994 U.S. App. LEXIS 25150 (Fed. Cir. 1994).  (Court rejected per se rule regarding protection but determined that color black could not be registered for Mercury's outboard motors because black is functional); <EM>R.L. Winston Rod Co. v. Sage Mf'd Co.</EM>, 29 U.S.P.Q.2d 1779 (D. Mont. 1993) (plaintiff failed to show that color green for graphite fishing rods was a protectable trademark).<P>
<LI>The traditional rule is justified by the "color depletion" or "color monopolization" theory.  As one court explains:  "If they may thus monopolize red in all of its shades, the next manufacturer may monopolize orange in all of its shades and the next, yellow in the same way.  Obviously, the list of colors will soon run out."  <EM>Campbell Soup Co. v. Armour & Co.</EM>, 175 F.2d 795, (3d Cir. 1949), cert. denied, 338 U.S. 847, 94 L.Ed. 518, 70 S. Ct. 88 (1949).  See, e.g., <EM>First Brands Corp. v. Fred Meyer, Inc.</EM>, 809 F.2d 1378 (9th Cir. 1987) ("Under the color depletion theory, there are a limited number of colors in the palette which may be depleted if trademark registrants prevail."); <EM>Diamond Match Co. v. Saginaw Match Co.</EM>, 142 F. 727 (6th Cir. 1906), cert. denied, 203 U.S. 589 (1906) ("The primary colors, even adding black and white, are but few.  If two of these colors can be appropriated for one brand of tipped matches, it will not take long to appropriate the rest.").<P>
<LI>Color depletion supporters further argue that, while in theory there may be hundreds of shades of colors, the ordinary person has a limited ability to distinguish shades.  Practical limitations may also limit the range of colors available for a product or package.  See Summerfield, <EM>"Color as a Trademark and the Mere Color Rule:  The Circuit Split for Color Alone."</EM>  68 Chi.-Kent L. Rev. 973, 996-997 (1993).  (For example, only a certain number of colors are available for children's toys because of government toxicity standards.  Dark colors are unattractive for containers of many food products, such as milk and ice cream.  "Dark colored packages tend to look used, and people do not want to buy goods that look as if they had been handled a lot.")<P>
<LI>On the other hand, others note that the color depletion theory ignores economic realities.  Economic pressures generally limit the number of competitors in any one field.  Thus, in actuality, there are plenty of colors available for a company to select that are not being used by their competitors.  See, e.g., <EM>Master Distributors Inc. v. Pako Corp.</EM>, 986 F.2d 219 (8th Cir. 1993) ("Until secondary meaning has been established in every distinguishable shade of color  . . . there will always be an option available to a new market entrant."  Court noted a color atlas listed 1,266 colors); <EM>DAP Products v. Color Tile Mfg., Inc.</EM>, 821 F. Supp. 488 (S.D. Ohio 1993) ("While there may be attractive arguments in favor of the color depletion theory, the court concludes that it is not a persuasive theory in light of available contemporary technology.  There are a myriad of colors and shades available for products today that were certainly not available in the past."  Preliminary injunction granted against use of 3-1/2 gallon red bucket containing mastic adhesive.).<P>
<LI>On September 26, 1994, the United States Supreme Court granted certiorari in the Qualitex, supra, case for the sole purpose of deciding whether color per se should be registrable as a trademark in order to resolve the split in the Circuits.  The question formally before the Court is whether the Lanham Act prohibits registration of color per se.  The Court may, however, wander from this issue and discuss the protectability of color as a trademark under unfair competition principles and Section 43(a) of the Lanham Act.<P>
<LI>We anticipate that the Supreme Court will hold that the Lanham Act does not prohibit registration of color per se as a trademark.  On its face, the statute does not explicitly bar the registration of color as a trademark.  Indeed, there are currently numerous registrations for marks consisting mainly of a single color.  The Court may also indicate that the protection of color as a trademark should be determined using established trademark principles of secondary meaning, inherent distinctiveness and functionality, rather than by the application of any per se rule.<P>
</UL>
<H2><A NAME="thenet">THE INTERNET</A></H2>
<UL>
<LI>Advertising, marketing and communicating with customers over global computer and information networks is becoming an increasingly important component of running a successful business.  While the National Information Infrastructure may be years away, the Internet is up and running with millions of active users.  Domain names, the computer addresses in cyberspace, are being assigned at a rate of over 1,300 per month.  Companies should consider reserving domain names before desired addresses are taken by someone else.<P>
<LI>Some companies have not reacted quickly to the need for domain names.  For example, McDonalds lost out on mcdonalds.com.  The holder, who can be reached at ronald@mcdonalds.com, is willing to sell the domain name to McDonalds for a fair price.  MTV has a similar problem.  While working at MTV, video disc jockey Adam Curry used the domain name mtv.com for a daily entertainment update.  When Curry left MTV, he kept his Internet service running with the mtv.com address.  MTV promptly sued, and while Curry has agreed not to use the lucrative mtv.com address during the pendency of the lawsuit, he refuses to willingly give up the domain name to MTV.<P>
<LI>Companies may also take advantage of a competitor's failure to reserve a domain name.  The college test preparation service The Princeton Review surprised its key competitor Stanley Kaplan by grabbing the domain name kaplan.com.  After binding arbitration The Princeton Review was forced to give the kaplan.com domain name to Stanley Kaplan.<P>
<LI>Internet domain names are assigned on a first come-first serve basis by the Internet Network Information Center (InterNIC).  InterNIC can be reached at 703/742-4777 or at hostmaster @ internic.net.  Demand for domain names has been so overwhelming that InterNIC has recently limited domain names to one per company.<P>
<LI>InterNIC does not allow preemptive reservations of domain names.  If your business is not yet ready to connect to the Internet, there are a variety of private companies that will identify whether particular domain names are available, reserve a domain name for you, set up that domain name on their computer and hold it for you until you are ready to form your own connection to the Internet.  Service providers may also send you any inquiries addressed to your domain name.<P>
<LI>Steps must be taken to prevent others from using your company's name or marks as Internet domain names.  While InterNIC will not knowingly register a misleading name, it does not become involved in any disputes over registration.  Disputes over misappropriation or use of confusingly similar domain names are private matters between the parties.  It is likely that general principles of trademark and unfair competition law will apply in cyberspace.<P>
<LI>Businesses should review their trademark portfolios and verify that they hold trademark registrations for the block format of the company's name and major products.  To strengthen trademark rights in domain names, companies should consider filing trademark applications for these names for use in connection with online services and computer networks.<P>
</UL>
<H2><A NAME="minn">MINNESOTA'S ANTI-DILUTION STATUTE</A></H2>
<DL>
<DD>On August 1, 1994, Minnesota became one of a growing number of states to enact a "anti-dilution" statute.  Minnesota's statute provides:<P>
<DL>
<DD>Likelihood of injury to business reputation or of dilution of the distinctive quality of a mark or trade name shall be grounds for injunctive relief, regardless of the presence or the absence of competition between the parties or likelihood of confusion, mistake, or deception.<P>
<DD>For the purposes of this section, the following terms have the meanings given them:<P>
</DL>
<DL>
<DD>
<OL>
<LI>"dilution" means the lessening of the capacity of an owner's mark to identify and distinguish goods or services; and<P>
<LI>"distinctive quality" means the mark is inherently distinctive or has acquired distinctiveness, and the mark is well known or famous.<P>
</OL>
</DL>
Minn. Stat. § 325D.165.  Minnesota courts have not yet interpreted Minnesota's anti-dilution statute.  The statute could significantly expand protection for established trademarks.<P>
</DL>
<UL>
<LI>Protection of trademarks has traditionally been afforded through actions for trademark infringement.  To prove a trademark infringement claim, a plaintiff must show that the defendant's use of a mark is likely to cause confusion, deception or mistake that the defendant's goods or services were produced by, sponsored by or otherwise affiliated with the plaintiff.  Anti-dilution statutes, on the other hand, do not require any showing of "likelihood of confusion."  A trademark owner can seek to enjoin a use of a mark even if a reasonably prudent buyer is not likely to mistake the origin or affiliation of a product.<P>
<LI>Anti-dilution statutes have been commonly used to attack uses which tend to weaken or "blur" the unique association of a well-known trademark with the trademark's owner.  See, e.g., <EM>Polaroid Corp. v. Polaraid, Inc.</EM>, 319 F.2d 830 (7th Cir. 1963).  (Prohibiting the use of the mark POLARAID in connection with the installation of refrigeration and heating systems.)  <EM>See also Ringling Bros.-Barnum & Bailey Combined Shows, Inc. v. Celozzi-Ettleson Chevrolet, Inc.</EM>, 855 F.2d 480 (7th Cir. 1988) (enjoining defendant used-car dealer's use of the slogan THE GREATEST USED CAR SHOW ON EARTH); <EM>Tiffany & Co. v. Boston Club, Inc.</EM>, 231 F. Supp. 836, 844 (D. Mass. 1964) (enjoining Boston restaurant's use of New York jeweler's TIFFANY mark).<P>
<LI>Anti-dilution statutes have also often been invoked in instances of "tarnishment,"  i.e., when a defendant uses the same or a similar mark in a way that creates an undesirable, unwholesome, or unsavory mental association with the plaintiff's mark or product.  For example, the Eighth Circuit recently found that the publication in a St. Louis humor magazine of a mock advertisement for "Michelob Oily", featuring such graphics as a can of Michelob® spilling out of an oily fish, tarnished Anheuser-Busch's famous Michelob® mark by suggesting that Michelob® contains oil.  <EM>Anheuser-Busch, Inc. v. Balducci Publications</EM>, 28 F.3d 769, 777 (8th Cir. 1994).  <EM>See also Community Fed. Sav. and Loan v. Orondorff</EM>, 678 F.2d 1034, 1035-37 (11th Cir. 1982) (defendant's use in connection with a strip club of a mark similar to bank's COOKIE JAR mark for automatic tellers); <EM>Eastman Kodak Co. v. Rakow</EM>, 739 F. Supp. 116, 118 (W.D.N.Y. 1989) (defendant's use of the name KODAK in connection with a sexually-explicit comedy act); <EM>American Express Co. v. Vibra Approved Lab. Corp.</EM>, 10 U.S.P.Q.2d 2006, 2014 (S.D.N.Y. 1989) (defendant's use of mark similar to the AMERICAN EXPRESS mark in connection with a "condom card").<P>
<LI>A recent decision of the Second Circuit illustrates that anti-dilution statutes are broad enough to provide protection to strong marks beyond the bounds defined by the usual notions of blurring and tarnishment.  In <EM>Deere & Co. v. MTD Products Inc.</EM>, 1994 U.S. App. LEXIS 33042, 32 U.S.P.Q.2d 1936 (2d Cir. 1994), the Second Circuit affirmed a district court's invocation of New York's anti-dilution law in granting a preliminary injunction against a television commercial for MTD's "Yard-Man" line of lawn tractors.  In the commercial, MTD portrays Deere's well-known "leaping deer" silhouette as a small, animated creature.  The deer looks over its shoulder, running in apparent fear, as it is pursued by a Yard-Man lawn tractor and a barking dog.  According to the advertisement's producers, the message of the commercial was that Deere, the market leader, had much to fear from MTD's Yard-Man line of less costly but allegedly comparable lawn tractors.  After noting that that commercial did not result in the "blurring" of a mark by use on a dissimilar product or the "tarnishment" of a mark by portraying it in an unwholesome context, the court determined that MTD's alteration of Deere's mark had the potential to lessen the selling power of a distinctive mark.<P>
<LI>While Minnesota's anti-dilution statute is broad and offers a potentially powerful and expansive tool for trademark owners, the statute does have significant limits which should not be overlooked:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Minnesota's anti-dilution statute explicitly limits its protection to marks that are "well known or famous."  Courts in other states have also limited protection from blurring and tarnishment to "well known or famous" marks.  This limitation could significantly restrict the use of the anti-dilution statute.<P>
<LI>Minnesota's anti-dilution statute creates a right to injunctive relief but does not provide for the award of monetary damages.<P>
<LI>The injunctive relief obtained may be limited.  Some courts have held that injunctions granted under anti-dilution statutes should be limited geographically to the state under whose law the action was commenced.  <EM>Compare Hyatt Corp. v. Hyatt Legal Services</EM>, 610 F. Supp. 381 (N.D. Ill. 1985) and Deere & Co., 32 U.S.P.Q.2d 1936 with <EM>Champions Golf Club, Inc. v. Sunrise Land Corp.</EM>, 846 F. Supp. 742, 759 (W.D. Ark. 1994); Eastman Kodak, 739 F. Supp. at 120 n.3; <EM>Instrumentalist Co. v. Marine Corps League</EM>, 509 F. Supp. 323, 340 (N.D. Ill. 1981), aff'd, 694 F.2d 145 (7th Cir. 1982).<P>
</OL>
</UL>
<H2><A NAME="immoral">IMMORAL, DISPARAGING OR SCANDALOUS TRADEMARKS</A></H2>
<UL>
<LI>In the past, 15 USC § 1052(a) has been invoked by the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office to refuse registration of QUEEN MARY for women's underwear, (<EM>Ex parte Martha Maid Mfg. Co.</EM>, 37 U.S.P.Q. 156 (Comm'r Pats. 1938)), MADONNA for wine (<EM>In re P.J. Valckenberg, GmbH</EM>, 122 U.S.P.Q. 334 (TTAB 1959)), and SENUSSI, the name of a Moslem sect whose adherents are forbidden the use of tobacco, for cigarettes (<EM>In re Reemtsma Cigarettenfabriken GmbH</EM>, 122 U.S.P.Q. 339 (TTAB 1959), aff'd, 289 F.2d 506 (1961)), on the grounds that the marks were immoral, disparaging or scandalous.<P>
<LI>Because the scandalous nature of a mark is determined in the context of contemporary attitudes, more recent decisions have allowed the registration of marks that before may have been once considered immoral or otherwise not appropriate.  See, e.g., <EM>In re Old Glory Condom Corp.</EM>, 26 U.S.P.Q.2d 1216 (TTAB 1993) (OLD GLORY CONDOM CORP with a design featuring a condom with stars and stripes suggesting the American flag); In re Hershey, 6 U.S.P.Q.2d 1470 (TTAB 1988) (BIG PECKER BRAND for t-shirts); In re Madsen, 180 U.S.P.Q. 334 (TTAB 1973) (WEEK-END SEX for magazines).<P>
<LI>With the increasing pervasiveness of political correctness, it should not be surprising that 1994 saw significant controversy in connection with 15 U.S.C. § 1052(a)'s prohibition against registration of trademarks consisting of immoral, disparaging or scandalous matter.<P>
<LI>In <EM>In re Mavety Media Group</EM>, 33 F.3d 1367 (Fed. Cir. 1994), the Federal Circuit reversed the PTO's refusal to register the mark BLACK TAIL for an adult entertainment magazine featuring photographs of nude and scantily-clad African-American women on the grounds that the mark was a scandalous and vulgar reference to female African-American sexual partners.  The magazine's owner argued there were alternative meanings of the terms in question, such as a "non-vulgar" reference to a woman's "rear end" and a reference to a type of full dress tuxedo worn by men at formal occasions.<P>
<LI>The Federal Circuit noted that "even if members of this panel find the mark BLACK TAIL disgustingly scandalous, the legal conclusion that a trademark comprises scandalous matter must derive from the perspective of [a] substantial composite [of the general public]."  The Court held that where there are possible alternative interpretations of the meaning of the terms in question, the PTO could not refuse registration of a mark without further factual support for its conclusion that a substantial composite of the general public would find the mark scandalous.<P>
<LI>In <EM>In re Hines</EM>, 31 U.S.P.Q.2d 1685 (TTAB 1994), the PTO initially invoked § 1052(a) to refuse to register for t-shirts, sweatshirts, shorts and hats the mark BUDDA BEACHWEAR with a drawing depicting a figure similar to the likeness of Gautama Buddha who is revered by Buddhists.  In initially refusing to register the mark, the PTO found that the particular portrayal of Gautama Buddha, "whose image is the subject of devotion of Buddhists each and every day", "in palm tree-emblazoned casual wear for commercial purposes . . . slights, depreciates and cheapens Buddha and Buddhism", and therefore is "disparaging" within the meaning of § 1052(a).<P>
<LI>After receiving the Federal Circuit's opinion in <EM>In re Mavety Media Group, Ltd.</EM>, the PTO reconsidered its position and decided to defer final decision on registration of BUDDA BEACHWEAR until after publishing the mark for opposition and considering the opinions of members of the general public during the opposition period.  <EM>In re Mavety Media Group, Ltd.</EM>, 32 U.S.P.Q.2d 1376 (TTAB 1994).<P>
<LI>In <EM>Harjo v. Pro Football Inc.</EM>, 30 U.S.P.Q.2d 1828 (TTAB 1994) the PTO dismissed most of the Washington Redskins' affirmative defenses to a § 1052(a) based challenge to the team's valuable REDSKINS trademark registrations.  The petitioners in Harjo are a group of Native American persons enrolled as members of federally-recognized tribes.  The petitioners seek cancellation of the team's registrations on grounds that "the term REDSKIN is a pejorative, derogatory, degrading, offensive, scandalous, contemptuous, disreputable, disparaging and racist designation for a Native American person."  Among the affirmative defenses dismissed by the PTO were lack of standing, equitable estoppel, and laches.<P>
<LI>The PTO's dismissal of many of the team's affirmative defenses does not constitute a final ruling on the petitioners' request for cancellation of the registrations.  The team may still assert various defenses, including the First Amendment.  A final ruling from the PTO will likely come in 1995.<P>
</UL>
<H2><A NAME="trade">TRADE DRESS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>"Trade dress" is the total image or overall impression of a company's product, packaging and advertising.  Traditionally, trade dress was thought to consist only of the appearance of labels, wrappers and containers used in packaging the product.  Trade dress is now defined to encompass the total look of a product and its packaging and even includes the design and shape of the product itself.  Trade dress has been held to include such things as the cover of a book; a magazine cover design; the appearance of a teddy bear; a Rubik's cube puzzle; the shape of a classic automobile; the appearances of a lamp, a sports shoe, a video game console, water meter and even the decor of a restaurant.<P>
<LI>To be protectable, trade dress must be distinctive and nonfunctional.  Recently, courts have been reluctant to find protectable trade dress or infringement of any trade dress rights.  The following cases are illustrative:<P>
<OL>
<LI>In <EM>Aromatique Inc. v. Gold Seal Inc.</EM>, 31 U.S.P.Q.2d 1481 (8th Cir. 1994), the Eighth Circuit cancelled two federal trademark registrations for the plaintiff's alleged trade dress and reversed the district court's judgment of trade dress infringement.  The trade dress for the plaintiff's potpourri products included a pillow-shaped double cellophane bag closed with a cord tied in a square knot bow.  The Court held that since this type of package was commonplace, the plaintiff had not presented sufficient evidence of secondary meaning, and the various features of the dress were functional, there was no trade dress protection available.<P>
<LI><EM>Speciality Surgical Instrumentation v. Phillips</EM>, 30 U.S.P.Q.2d 1309 (M.D. Tenn. 1994) (Color gray used in promotional materials for surgical instruments is not protectable trade dress.  Gray background highlights design of instruments in catalogues and there is a competitive need for color gray in industry.  The color is, therefore, primarily functional and cannot be protected.)<P>
<LI><EM>Jungle Rags Inc. v. Rainbow Graphics Inc.</EM>, 29 U.S.P.Q.2d 1704 (M.D. Fla. 1993) (Cartoon drawing of an animal with a primarily nonfunctional applique flap forming animal's mouth was not protectable as trade dress because it was not inherently distinctive and there was no showing of acquired secondary meaning.)<P>
</UL>
<LI>If registered, however, trade dress protection can be formidable.  In <EM>Shakespeare Co. v. Silstar Corp. of America, Inc.</EM>, 9 F.3d 1091, 28 U.S.P.Q.2d 1765 (7th Cir. 1993), cert. denied, 114 S. Ct. 2134 (1994), the court refused to cancel the federal trademark registration for Shakespeare's "Ugly Stik" fishing rods for both salt and fresh water fishing.  These rods feature a "clear tip."  Shakespeare had obtained a federal trademark registration for the clear tip.  The defendant argued that the clear tip was functional and, therefore, could not be protected as a trademark.  This case underscores the importance of obtaining a federal registration.  Marks registered on the Principal Register and in continuous use for five years can become incontestable under 15 U.S.C. § 1065, significantly limiting the grounds a defendant has available to challenge the validity of the mark and registration, including functionality.  Because Shakespeare's trademark registration for its clear tip had become incontestable, the registration could not be cancelled for functionality.<P>
</UL>
<H2><A NAME="misc">MISCELLANEOUS CHUCKLES</A></H2>
<UL>
<LI>Each year has its fair share of amusing cases.  1994 was no different.  For example, <EM>Munsingwear Inc. v. Jockey Int'l Inc.</EM>, 31 USPQ 2d 1146 (D. Minn. 1994) involved the marketing of a horizontal-fly version of men's underwear by Jockey.  Munsingwear contended that Jockey's "Pouch" line of briefs infringed Munsingwear's rights in its horizontal fly design.  In determining whether there was likelihood of consumer confusion between the parties' horizontal fly underwear, the court ruled that the presence of likelihood of confusion should be based on a comparison of the parties' products in their pre-sale, or packaged, form.  This time frame was selected based on the astute observation that after underwear is sold, it is customarily concealed under other articles of clothing.  Thus, the potential for customer confusion is unlikely due to the lack of post-sale exposure.<P>
<LI>In late December 1994, Carl Sagan lost his battle with Apple Computer.  In connection with its new Power Macintosh 7100-66 computer it was designing, Apple has used Sagan's name as an in house code for the computer.  Sagan complained to Apple contending, inter alia, that the use of his name was an invasion of privacy.  After receiving Sagan's complaint, Apple engineers changed the moniker to "BHA," short for "BUTT HEAD ASTRONOMER."  Sagan sued for copyright infringe-ment, unfair competition, libel, invasion of privacy, and violation of his right of publicity.  The Court dismissed Sagan's lawsuit in large part because Apple's use of "BHA" had been strictly in-house.  Truth as a defense to the libel charge was not discussed by the Court.<P>
</UL>

