<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Recent developments in the law of cyberspace</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Introduction</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
1994 saw a number of important developments relating to the law of cyberspace (e.g., the Internet, on-line services, bulletin boards).  Just as a decade ago, when the courts first struggled with the application of copyright law to computer programs, courts today are now facing the first generation of cases relating to cyberspace.  These lawsuits and related legislative developments may define the basic principles governing the law of cyberspace for years to come.
</DL>
<H2>Copyright</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Copyright infringement is endemic in cyberspace.  While much copying is justified by the doctrine of fair use, which permits in limited circumstances what would otherwise technically be infringement, illegal copying poses a significant problem for copyright owners.  The copyright system is threatened by cyberspace because of the ease of copying, the problems of effective enforcement, and the Internet sub-culture which asserts that "information wants to be free."<P>
<LI>As the Internet and on-line services expand from a community of users to a major avenue for commerce, these problems will surely persist, and because of the stakes involved, require some type of resolution.  The courts and Congress will struggle with finding the right balance between the public good that comes from a virtually-unlimited immediately-accessible library of information and the necessity for providing creators of content with a fair economic return and some degree of control over their works.<P>
<LI>Although most infringement takes place at the individual end-user level, the liability of on-line providers and bulletin board operators is a key legal issue because enforcement at the end-user level is currently impractical.  The debate over liability for on-line providers echoes the debate over the liability of videocassette manufacturers which was resolved in favor of the manufacturers in Sony Corp. v. Universal City Studios, Inc., 464 U.S. 417 (1984), which held that Sony was not liable as a contributory infringer for selling VCRs even though many consumers would use the machines for copying television programs and movies.<P>
<LI>The key legal question is whether on-line providers are liable, either as direct infringers or as contributory infringers, for infringements conducted by subscribers through the on-line services.  Generally, direct copyright infringement is a strict liability offense; a defendant may be found liable as an infringer even though it is not aware of the infringement.  Contributory infringement requires either knowledge of the infringement or supervisory responsibility over the infringer.<P>
<LI>The first decision in the area was Playboy Enter., Inc. v. Frena, 839 F. Supp. 1552 (M.D. Fla. 1993).  Playboy obtained summary judgment for copyright infringement against a bulletin board operator who allowed Playboy photographs to be uploaded, displayed, and downloaded.  The court found direct infringement even though the BBS operator testified that he did not know and had no reason to know of the infringements.<P>
<LI>In Sega Enter. Ltd. v. Maphia, 30 U.S.P.Q.2d 1921 (N.D. Cal. 1994), the game company obtained a preliminary injunction against a BBS operator who encouraged the uploading and downloading of Sega games.  The court found that Sega would likely prove at trial both direct and contributory infringement by the BBS operator.<P>
<LI>While suits by individual companies against small BBS operators may stop some infringement, a wholesale assault on on-line infringement of sound recordings was launched on behalf of the music publishing industry in Frank Music Corp. v. CompuServe, Inc..  This pending class action copyright infringement suit filed on behalf of the music publisher principals of the Harry Fox Agency (which is a central clearinghouse for rights in music other than performance rights) asserts copyright infringement against CompuServe for maintaining a bulletin board--MIDI/Music Forum--in which songs (such as Frank's "Unchained Melody") are uploaded and downloaded.  The forum is one of about 1700 that CompuServe carries but does not run.  It is owned by a third party which warrants against infringement and warns subscribers not to commit copyright violations.<P>
<LI>In July 1994 the NII Task Force Working Group issued its "Green Paper" on copyright law relating to cyberspace. (Its proposals are summarized in the copyright section of the seminar materials.)  The major on-line service providers submitted comments on the Green Paper recommending that they be liable for infringement only if (1) they have actual knowledge that infringing material has been or is being transmitted to, or resides on, their systems, and (2) having knowledge such material is infringing, and the ability and authority to stop its transmission or remove it, fail to stop the transmission or remove it from their systems in a reasonable time.<P>
<LI>As the Green Paper noted, technological means of tracking transactions and licensing may lead to reduced application of the doctrine of fair use. One of the report's proposals is to provide for express criminal liability (limited to a $2,500 fine) for removing or altering copyright management information associated with a digitally encoded work.  The Association of Shareware Professionals has recommended in its comments on the Green Paper that the new legislation provide that the conduct should be treated as equivalent to an infringement of the entire work and also has recommended providing express protection for shareware licenses.<P>
<LI>With so much material going on-line and traditional contracts either not covering such distribution or being ambiguous, authors may sue for breach of contract and copyright infringement when their works are placed by publishers in cyberspace.  In Tasini v. New York Times, 93 Civ. 8678(SS) (S.D.N.Y. 1994), freelance writers sued newspapers, periodicals and electronic publishers for distribution of their articles on-line and in CD-ROMs.<P>
<LI>Since jurisdictional boundaries do not coincide with activity in cyberspace, new jurisdictional and territorial issues are likely to arise.  The Ninth Circuit recently held that mere authorization of extraterritorial acts of infringement is not copyright infringement.  Subafilms, Ltd. v. MGM-Pathe Communications Co., 30 U.S.P.Q.2d 1746 (9th Cir. 1994).  This principle has not been tested in a case involving on-line infringement.
</UL>
<H2>Trademark and Unfair Competition</H2>
<UL>
<LI>In 1990 less than one hundred companies were registered with the Internet's central registry InterNIC.  Today, more than 20,000 are registered.  The Internet domain registration system has spawned a race to acquire commercially valuable names and thwart competitors from using their own names.<P>
<LI>Just as 800 numbers opened up an opportunity for entrepreneurs to control the best numbers and sell them later to companies who needed them, the Internet registration system has led to enterprising companies acquiring famous names for the same purpose (e.g. mcdonalds.com, coke.com, abc.com).<P>
<LI>Direct competitors have used the same technique.  Princeton Review, a major test tutoring company, registered both its name and the name of its main competitor, Stanley Kaplan.  The companies arbitrated the dispute and settled.<P>
<LI>In a widely reported case, a former employee of MTV kept his personal Internet domain name of mtv.com after he left the company and went into business for himself.  MTV sued for trademark infringement and the cyberjockey counterclaimed.  The case is pending.<P>
<LI>Trademarks also are a source of protection for copyright owners whose works are downloaded or displayed without permission.  For example, in Sega v. Macchia, Sega sued for trademark infringement as well as copyright infringement.  The trademark violation was based upon file descriptor headings which used the Sega mark and on the presence of the mark on the games themselves.  Trademark infringement may sometimes permit a more powerful remedy than copyright infringement because treble damages may be available and because attorneys fees may be available for trademark infringement but not for copyright infringement.
</UL>
<H2>Defamation</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Usenet groups and on-line forums permit messages to be sent to millions of readers around the world.  Because these groups and forums promote a culture of free expression and place a premium on pithiness, the possibilities for defamation are rampant.<P>
<LI>Cubby, Inc. v. Compuserve, Inc., 776 F. Supp. 135 (S.D.N.Y. 1991), established the basic principle that on-line providers should be treated like bookstores, newsstands and libraries, which are not liable for defamation unless they know of the content of the defamatory material.<P>
<LI>In Medphone Corp. v. Denigris, Civ. Action No. 92-3785 (D.N.J. 1992), a medical equipment company sued an investor whose critical remarks on the Prodigy Money Talk bulletin board allegedly caused the stock to tumble.  The case settled.<P>
<LI>A Prodigy user posted the following message about a public stock offering on the Money Talk bulletin board:  "THIS IS FRAUD, FRAUD AND CRIMINAL..."  The company has sued Prodigy and the message writer for $200 million.  Prodigy claims that it should be treated like Compuserve in the Cubby case.  The plaintiff claims Prodigy should be held to a higher standard because it has forum editors and electronically screens for obscenity and hate messages.  The end-user, who formerly worked at Prodigy and who allowed numerous employees to use his account number for internal purposes, denies that he posted the message.<P>
<LI>Just as the provider will ordinarily be insulated from liability for libel, it also will not be liable for the information it makes available.  In Daniel v. Dow Jones & Co., Inc., 520 N.Y.S.2d 334 (Civ. Ct. N.Y. 1987), a New York court held that a publisher of electronic data base is not liable to investor who relied on false information to make losing investment since the subscriber does not have a special relationship with the provider and the First Amendment protects provider.<P>
<LI>Libel law maintains a distinction between public figures and private figures.  Public figures are those who have achieved general fame or notoriety and those who voluntarily inject themselves or are forced into the public eye with respect to a particular subject.  Gertz v. Robert Welch, Inc., 418 U.S. 323, 351 (1974).  Liability for defamation of a private figure does not require as high a degree of intent as for defamation of a public figure.  One of the grounds for this distinction is that the private figure, unlike the public figure, does not have access to the media to combat the libel.  The existence of the Internet somewhat undermines this distinction since anyone has sufficient access to make any message known to millions at any time.<P>
<LI>In Suarez Corp. v. Meeks, Case No. 267513 (Cuyahoga Cty., Ohio C.P.), a company which relied on Internet E-Mail for direct marketing sued a newsletter publisher who called the program a "scam."  The publisher's defense included the argument that since the plaintiff had distributed its E-mail on the Internet, it should be treated as a public figure, which would require the plaintiff to prove actual malice.  The case reportedly settled for a nominal sum; the plaintiff was unable to prove damages since the publicity from the lawsuit caused sales to soar.<P>
<LI>In September 1994, a fundraiser for Veterans of Foreign Wars state organizations sued for libel in the Southern District of Florida.  The alleged libel started in an article in the Kansas City Star; it was then republished by Datatimes, which makes newspaper articles available on-line for subscribers; a Prodigy subscriber then republished the libel on Prodigy.  The defendants include the newspaper and its reporter, Datatimes, and Prodigy.
</UL>
<H2>Obscenity</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Distribution of sexually explicit and obscene material has proliferated on the Internet, particularly in the distribution of graphic files.  For example, almost 100,000 pornographic photos were found stored on a computer at the Lawrence Livermore Nuclear Weapons research lab.<P>
<LI>The prevailing law on obscenity is that it must be judged under local community standards.  Miller v. California, 413 U.S. 15 (1973).  Is this standard obsolete once distribution is electronic and available everywhere?<P>
<LI>In July, 1994, a San Francisco couple that run a BBS called Amateur Action that allows downloading of explicit photographs were convicted of transmitting obscenity through interstate phone lines.  The case was brought by a prosecutor in Memphis, where standards for obscenity under the Miller v. California standard are far stricter than in the Bay Area.  United States v. Thomas, (W.D. Tenn. July 28, 1994).
</UL>
<H2>Federal Law Governing Cyberspace</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
A patchwork of federal laws in addition to intellectual property laws are central to the legal structure of cyberspace.<P>
</DL>
<UL>
<LI>The government in such cases may attempt to rely on traditional criminal laws such as wire fraud to catch bulletin board operators who commit copyright infringement.  In U.S. v. LaMacchia, Case No. 94-10092-RGS (April 4, 1994), an MIT student who operated a not-for-profit BBS which encouraged downloading of copyrighted computer programs, contends that the wire fraud statute (18 U.S.C. § 134) which he is charged with violating does not cover on-line copyright infringement.  Although copyright law includes criminal provisions, it does not cover not-for profit infringement.  On December 30, 1994, a federal judge dismissed the indictment.<P>
<LI>Congress has also passed a number of laws specifically governing computer communications.  The Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, 18 U.S.C. § 1030 et seq., passed in 1986, is the basic federal law which prohibits hacking.  Robert Morris, the Cornell student who authored the Internet Worm, was prosecuted under this act.<P>
<LI>The Electronic Communications and Privacy Act (ECPA), 18 U.S.C. § 2510 et seq., outlaws the interception or disclosure of electronic communications.  There are exceptions for on-line providers.  The ECPA does not cover internal company E-mail.<P>
<LI>In 1994, the Fifth Circuit affirmed the trial court's decision in Steve Jackson Games v. United States Secret Service, (W.D. Tex. 1993).  After a bulletin board suspected of harboring hackers was wrongfully raided and the company's e-mail seized, it sued under the ECPA and the Privacy Protection Act, 42 U.S.C. § 2000 et seq. ("PPA"), which prohibits seizure of material intended for public dissemination.  After trial, the judge held that the Secret Service violated the ECPA's prohibition on unauthorized disclosure, but did not violate the prohibition on interception because only stored communications were seized.  The court also held that the PPA was violated.<P>
<LI>The Export Control Act prohibits export of encryption software without a license from the State Department under the International Traffic in Arms Regulations, 22 C.F.R. § 120 et seq..  Thus, the widespread distribution since 1991 of Phillip Zimmerman's PGP public key encryption software over the Internet to computers outside the U.S. violates this law (and may constitute patent infringement as well since Zimmerman is not the patent owner).<P>
</UL>
In conclusion, the courts have just begun to scratch the legal surface of cyberspace.  1995 will undoubtedly be a year of increasing activity, debate, and guidance.

<HR>

Last changed 1-May-95<P>

