<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Who Owns Your World Wide Web Home Page</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
Businesses are setting up World Wide Web Home Pages at an astronomical rate.  Very often, however, important questions about ownership and other rights in the Home Page are overlooked.  To ensure that your Home Page is an economically valuable asset, it is important to consider ownership and other intellectual property issues at the outset.  By doing so, you will be better able to maximize the value of your new cyberspace storefront.<P>
This article examines general intellectual property issues involved with the adoption, creation and use of World Wide Web Home Pages.  While intellectual property law provides a default answer to many of the questions involved with these issues, you can (and often should) contractually modify these default results.  Accordingly, you should consider consulting with an attorney who is knowledgeable about intellectual property law and conversant in the technology and business aspects of Web sites.  While it is preferable to address these issues before developing your Home Page, if you already have a Home Page many of these issues still should be addressed before a dispute arises.<P>
</DL>
<H2>Who Owns Your Internet Address</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
Your Internet address is the primary method by which others locate and visit your Home Page.  While you may, depending on the situation, generate some traffic due to links from other Web sites, the most important gateway that the rest of the electronic community has to your Home Page is your Internet address.<P>
World Wide Web Home Pages are set up, generally, on a particular node on a domain registered to your company.  While it is unclear whether you have an actual ownership interest in your domain name and Internet address, it can be safely assumed that if a domain name has been assigned and registered to you by the Internet Network Information Center (InterNIC), then this domain name may not be given away or used by another party without your permission.  Presumably, you can give permission to use a domain name registered to you in exchange for money, in effect allowing you to "sell" your address.<P>
Notwithstanding InterNIC's ability to assign and register an Internet address to you, another party may be able to prevent you from using a particular domain name under traditional trademark law.  Generally, if your use of a particular domain name would result in a likelihood of confusion as to the source or sponsorship of your site or your connection or affiliation with another person or company, your use may be infringing.<P>
For example, while working at MTV, video disk jockey Adam Curry set up an Internet site with the domain name mtv.com, an address which had been assigned to him by InterNIC.  His site offered, among other things, a daily entertainment update.  When Curry left MTV, he kept his Internet service running with the mtv.com address.  MTV promptly sued Curry for, among other things, trademark infringement, claiming that consumers would mistakenly believe that the mtv.com site was offered or authorized by MTV.  Curry agreed not to use the lucrative mtv.com address during the pendency of the lawsuit.  He maintains, however, that even if he loses the infringement suit and is not allowed to use the mtv.com address, he still is the owner of this address and can thereby prevent anyone else, including MTV, from using mtv.com.  Regardless of the outcome of the suit, by using a domain name without assessing the trademark implications, Curry subjected himself not only to considerable legal expenses, but he also had to change his Internet address, causing a loss in the goodwill he had developed in this domain name.<P>
Accordingly, before selecting a domain name and an address for your Home Page, and especially before you invest resources in making others aware of your address, you should conduct a trademark availability search to determine if your address is available from a trademark perspective.  As is evident from the above scenario, you should do this whether the domain name is already registered to you or if you are about to apply for it.  In addition, once you have determined that an address is available for your use, it is vital that you protect your trademark rights in this address.  One method of protecting and strengthening your trademark rights is to seek a federal trademark registration.  Among the many advantages of obtaining a federal registration are the ability to collect attorney's fees if you are successful in a trademark infringement suit and to put others on notice that you consider your domain name to be a protectable trademark, thereby helping to prevent others from adopting similar names.<P>
</DL>
<H2>Other Trademark Issues</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
In addition to your domain name being a trademark, your Home Page is likely to display one or more of your company's trademarks or service marks.  Just as it is important to ensure that your Internet address is available from a trademark perspective, it is also necessary to determine whether any mark you intend to use on your Home Page is available for such use.  For instance, even though your mark may be available for use in your normal trade and advertising channels, that same mark may cause consumer confusion if you use it on a Web Home Page. For that reason, it is important to conduct a trademark availability search.<P>
Similarly, you should act to protect your rights to the marks which you plan to use on your Home Page.  You may wish to consider filing federal trademark or service mark applications for your existing marks and any proposed marks for use in connection with online services or computer networks.<P>
Finally, you should verify that you are using your marks in a manner which best protects your trademark rights.  For example, you should display the appropriate notification next to your mark, namely ? for federally-registered marks, ? for non-federally registered trademarks, and ? for non-federally registered service marks.  Next, you should make sure that your marks are used properly: marks are adjectives, not nouns.  Finally, if you have created a unique product or service, you should work diligently to make sure that the consuming public is able to identify it with a generic name in addition to your mark which is the brand name.  The consequence of not providing the consuming public with a generic name by which to call your product or service could result in your losing all trademark rights to your mark, as has happened in the past to once-valuable marks such as escalator, monopoly and aspirin.<P>
</DL>
<H2>Ownership of Your Home Page</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
Your Home Page has many different aspects, each of which may be owned by a different party.  This is particularly true in light of the fact that most businesses use an outside developer to create their Home Page.  As the business owner, you want to be assured that your Home Page will continue to operate efficiently, can be updated and modified, and will not be copied by your competitors.<P>
There are three separate elements to the ownership of a Home Page:  (1) the content, which refers to the textual, graphical, audio and other material which is displayed on and used by visitors to your Home Page; (2) the look and feel of the interface, namely the screens, organization, patterns, operational control features and the like; and (3) the coding, which refers to the computer instructions which operate the Home Page and which generate the content and the look and feel.<P>
For each of these three elements, you and your developer will need to determine who will have what rights.  There is no correct or best answer to these questions -- the more ownership or exclusivity rights you want, the more you will likely have to pay.  Part of the question of who gets what rights in each of these three elements is determined, at least as a default position, by the source of the material.  The source of materials can be grouped into four categories:  (1) material that is created by you (or an employee of yours); (2) material that is created for you; (3) material which has been purchased or licensed, such as software tools or applications, photographs, clip art or a commercial database; and (4) material in the public domain.  As a general rule, the person creating the material (or the employer of that person) owns all copyright rights to the material, absent a written agreement to the contrary.<P>
A large portion of the material making up your Home Page will likely be material that was created by or for you.  If you, or an employee of yours, creates this material, you will be considered to be the author for copyright purposes.  On the other hand, if an independent contractor, such as an advertising agency or a computer consultant, designs and creates your Home Page, that party will be considered to be the author for copyright purposes.  Absent a written contract assigning you copyright rights to this work, the author will retain control over the work, including rights of distribution, copying and creating further modifications, subject to whatever rights have been licensed to you.<P>
If you and your developer jointly create the material, then you may be considered "joint authors" under copyright law.  Unless there is a written agreement providing otherwise, as joint authors you will each have complete rights to individually exploit the material, subject to a duty to account to the other party for profits.<P>
As you might guess, your rights to any purchased or licensed material will be governed by the contract granting you or the developer the rights to use that material.  If your Home Page was created using purchased or licensed material, or depends on such material, it is imperative that the contract from the owner grant you (either directly or via the developer) adequate rights for a sufficient period of time to allow you to continue using and modifying the material.  Although many tools used to create Home Pages are available as shareware or freeware, and thus are assumed by the software community to be freely available, they are generally still subject to a copyright license.  You should, therefore, carefully review the grant of rights for each piece of shareware and freeware that you (or your developer) use to ensure your rights are sufficient.<P>
Finally, there is material which is freely available, either because it is in the public domain or is available under a "fair use" defense.  This includes any material which (1) is not copyrightable due to insufficient creative expression, (2) has been dedicated to the public domain or (3) constitutes functionally required industry standards.  You should require that the developer warrant that it will use only originally created material, public domain material or duly licensed material, and you should obtain an indemnity agreement for any intellectual property infringement.<P>
In addition, it is important to note that copyright law covers only the expression of ideas and not the ideas themselves.  Therefore, factual information, such as the daily temperature, is freely available for you to put on your Home Page, even if you obtain this information from another news source.  A unique compilation or organization of information, however, may be copyrightable.  Before using any material which you or your developer did not create, you should consult an intellectual property attorney.<P>
For each of these three elements (content, look and feel, and coding), you should carefully consider what rights you want and what rights you are willing to give to your developer.  Depending on your purposes in creating a Home Page, it often will be shortsighted to leave these issues to the default positions provided by copyright law, or, worse yet, to accept the developer's proposal because you are unwilling to invest the resources in obtaining advise on these matters.  Set forth below are some issues that you may wish to consider, although your individual business goals and requirements may lead to different conclusions.<P>
<OL>
<LI>In most cases, the business owner will want to own all the copyright  rights in content of the Home Page.  As the developer will likely be creating some of the content, or at least adapting it from another medium, the development contract should assign all copyright rights in the content from the developer to the business owner.<P>
<LI>While you may wish to have a relatively unique look and feel for your Web site, you may also wish to use some standard features so that users will be able to easily operate and navigate your Home Page.  Furthermore, using standard software packages to create a Home Page greatly reduces development costs.  This often results in Home Pages which have some common features and similarities in their look and feel.  Most likely, you will rely on the developer's expertise and experience to design the look and feel of your Home Page.  While it is not essential that the developer assign you copyright ownership of the look and feel, you should consider requesting at least a perpetual license to use the look and feel in the current version of your Home Page and any future modifications.<P>
<LI>You will have to assess whether you wish to pay the developer an up-front fee for all copyright rights in the look and feel; an up-front fee just for using the look and feel and a separate fee if you wish to make modifications or enhancements to the Home Page which incorporate the look and feel; an arrangement in which you pay a continuing royalty; or some other variation.  Whichever option you choose, you should require that the developer guarantee that it has sufficient rights in all aspects of the look and feel, including those which are created using commercial tools or which incorporate licensed features, so that the developer is able to grant you whatever rights you mutually agree upon.  You also may wish to consider asking the developer for a non-competition agreement.  This agreement could be broad, such as prohibiting the developer from developing Home Pages for competitors in your particular industry, or narrower, such as prohibiting the developer from using the look and feel on any competitors' products.<P>
<LI>Finally, you must address the coding for the Home Page.  The developer will most likely want to be able to use the coding that it creates for you on other projects, and in most instances this will not result in a competitive disadvantage to you.  Furthermore, since it is possible to create a Home Page which looks and operates identical to yours using different coding, it is not absolutely essential that the developer grant you any copyright rights to the coding itself.  In order to more easily facilitate updates or error correction, however, you will likely want to retain some rights in the coding, such as a non-exclusive license to correct errors.  You may also wish to request that the developer place a copy of the coding with a software escrow agent in the event that the developer goes out of business.<P>
</OL>
</DL>
For further information or assistance, please contact Gary Weinstein at (800) 328-4393 or at <A HREF="mailto:gweinstein@faegre.com">gweinstein@faegre.com</A>.<P>
This article is intended solely to alert readers to issues and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.

<HR>

