<HR>
<H2><A NAME="intro">INTRODUCTION</A></H2>
<DL>
<DD>The 1994 copyright decisions rendered by the federal courts evidenced the continuing evolvement of copyright law in response to technological changes.  Courts refined their application of traditional copyright principles to subject matters such as computer software and multimedia works.  They also reaffirmed the copyright owner's right to control the dissemination of works in digitized form and clarified the rights of end users to make fair use of another's copyrighted work without permission.<P>

On the Congressional front, there was much talk but no new legislation.  Perhaps the most significant development was the issuance of a "Green Paper" report by the Working Group on Intellectual Property Rights on "Intellectual Property and the National Information Infrastructure."  In analyzing the state of current copyright laws in view of new technologies, the report concluded that "the coat was getting a little tight," and while there was no need for a new one, "the old one needs a few alterations."  Some of the changes to the copyright law suggested by the report may find their way into legislation as early as this year.
</DL>
<H2><A NAME="case">CASE LAW NOTES</A></H2>
<H3><A NAME="supreme">UNITED STATES SUPREME COURT</A></H3>
<DL>
<DL>
<DT><B>Commercial Parody May Be Fair Use</B>
<DD>The U.S. Supreme Court reversed the Sixth Circuit's conclusion that 2 Live Crew's rap parody of Roy Orbison's song "Oh, Pretty Woman," was not a fair use.  The Supreme Court emphasized that the fair use doctrine "is not to be simplified with bright-line rules" and reexamined the suggestion in its prior rulings that commercial uses of copyrighted material are presumptively unfair.  The Supreme Court held that a commercial use is simply one factor to be considered that tends to weigh against a finding of fair use.<P>
The Supreme Court also noted that in examining the first fair-use factor--the purpose and character of the use -- "transformative" uses of a work are more likely to be fair uses.  A "transformative" use is one that adds something new to the copied work.  In this case, the 2 Live Crew parody served as a commentary on Roy Orbison's song.  The Supreme Court stated that "the more transformative the new work, the less will be the significance of other facts, like commercialism, that may weigh against a finding of fair use."  <EM>Campbell v. Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.</EM>, 510 U.S. --, 114 S. Ct. 1164, 127 L.Ed.2d 500, 29 U.S.P.Q.2d 1961 (1994). <P>
<DT><B>Attorneys' Fees: Dual Rule Rejected</B>
<DD>In a copyright action in which the singer/songwriter John Fogerty successfully defended himself against a claim of copyright infringement, the Supreme Court resolved a conflict among the circuits and rejected the "dual rule" for awarding attorneys' fees under the Copyright Act.  Under the "dual rule," a prevailing copyright plaintiff may be awarded attorneys' fees in the discretion of the court, while a prevailing defendant does not receive an award unless the plaintiff's claim was either frivolous or brought in bad faith. <P>
In reaching its decision, the Supreme Court found nothing in the legislative history or the plain language of § 505 of the Copyright Act suggesting that prevailing defendants should be treated differently from prevailing plaintiffs.  It observed that the public interest is best served by encouraging meritorious claims.  While evening the playing field, the Supreme Court declined to adopt Fogerty's argument that fees should be awarded automatically to the winning party, ruling that the award under the statute is clearly discretionary.  <EM>Fogerty v. Fantasy, Inc.</EM>, 114 S. Ct. 1023, 127 L.Ed.2d 455, 29 U.S.P.Q.2d 1881 (1994).
</DL>
</DL>
<H3><A NAME="appeal">UNITED STATES COURTS OF APPEALS</A></H3>
<DL>
<DL>
<DT><B>Copyright Office's Interpretation of "Cable System" Upheld</B>
<DD>The Eleventh Circuit reversed the district court's invalidation of the Copyright Office's regulations denying satellite broadcasters status as "cable systems" and the right to obtain compulsory licenses.  The district court based its ruling on an earlier Eleventh Circuit case in which the appellate court held that satellite carriers were "cable systems" for the purposes of the Copyright Act.  Notwithstanding its earlier decision, the Eleventh Circuit reversed the trial court because the Copyright Office's interpretation of the Copyright Act in this instance was not arbitrary, capricious, or manifestly contrary to the clear meaning of the statute.  <EM>Satellite Broadcasting and Communications Ass'n of Am. v. Oman</EM>, 17 F3d 344 (11th Cir. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Agency Defense Rejected: Infringer May Not Rely On Owner's Investigator</B>
<DD>The Eighth Circuit reversed the granting of summary judgment to the defendant who had reproduced photographs owned by the plaintiff.  The trial court had granted summary judgment on the theory that the plaintiff effectively had licensed the copying by submitting its photographs to the defendants via a private investigator who had signed a standard "hold-harmless" agreement that required him to represent, among other things, that he was the "owner" of the photograph submitted for reproduction.  The Eighth Circuit observed that the agreement had been concocted merely to circumvent liability and that the defendant was well aware of the plaintiff's ownership of the copyright in the photographs based on the copyright notice clearly marked on the photographs and the plaintiff's prior warnings to the defendant.  <EM>Olan Mills Inc. v. Linn Photo Co.</EM>, 23 F.3d 1345 (8th Cir. 1994) <P>
<DT><B>Fair Use In Copying Lobbyist's List</B>
<DD>The Sixth Circuit affirmed a trial court's grant of summary judgment for the defendant that had copied a list compiled by the plaintiff.  The list consisted of state legislators' names with asterisks next to the names the plaintiff deemed important.  The Sixth Circuit agreed with the trial court's conclusion that the defendant's use of plaintiff's list was a fair use.  The Sixth Circuit noted that the most important element of fair use analysis, effect upon the potential market for the original, weighed in favor of the defendant because the plaintiff's "market" (i.e. its ability to retain members) was not harmed, and perhaps even enhanced, by the defendant's dissemination of the list.  <EM>National Rifle Ass'n of America v. Handgun Control Fed'n of Ohio</EM>, 15 F.3d 559 (6th Cir. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Copying for Internal Purposes Not Fair Use</B>
<DD>The Second Circuit affirmed a district court's ruling that Texaco's practice of photocopying articles from scientific journals archived in its library for use by its researchers did not amount to a fair use.  The court analyzed the four statutory factors and concluded that (1) the first factor--the purpose and character of the use--weighed against Texaco because the dominant purpose of the use was to assemble a set of papers for future reference, "thereby serving the same purpose for which additional subscriptions are normally sold, or . . . for which photocopying licenses may be obtained"; (2) the second factor--the nature of the copyrighted work--weighed in Texaco's favor because the content of the articles was predominantly factual in nature; (3) the third factor--the amount and substantiality of the portion used--weighed against Texaco because Texaco copied the entire works; and (4) the fourth factor--the effect upon the potential market for or value of the work--weighed against Texaco because, although without the copying Texaco would have increased the number of its journal subscriptions only somewhat, the lost potential licensing revenue from "traditional, reasonable, or likely developed markets" was significant.  <EM>American Geophysical Union v. Texaco Inc.</EM>, 37 F.3d 881 (2d Cir.), reh'g denied, amended, 1994 U.S. App. LEXIS 36735 (2nd Cir. Dec. 23, 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Infringement</B>
<DL>
<DT><B>Computer Programs:  Altai Test Adopted by Fifth Circuit</B>
<DD>The Fifth Circuit applied the "abstraction--filtration-comparison" test formulated by the Second Circuit in <EM>Computer Associates Int'l, Inc. v. Altai, Inc.</EM>, 982 F.2d 693 (2d Cir. 1992) to a claim of infringement of the plaintiff's copyrighted software.  In doing so, the court reversed the district court's finding that the plaintiff's input and output formats for its computer program were unprotectable as non-literal ideas.  <EM>Engineering Dynamics v. Structural Software</EM>, 26 F.3d 1335 (5th Cir. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Derivative Works</B>
<DD>The First Circuit affirmed the district court's decision that the plaintiff could recover statutory damages for the defendant's copying and renting of an unregistered derivative work where the underlying work was registered.  The plaintiff held an exclusive license to distribute a Cambodian-language version of a Chinese-language soap opera.  Consequently, two works were at issue, the original registered version in Chinese and the unregistered derivative work which was the original dubbed in Cambodian.  The First Circuit held that under the license the plaintiff had the exclusive right to use the original video images in the underlying work in concert with a Cambodian soundtrack and that therefore it could maintain a lawsuit for infringement of that portion of the derivative work that was part of the underlying work.  The First Circuit stated that it was irrelevant that what was actually distributed by the plaintiff was a derivative work.  In addition, the First Circuit held that because four episodes of the soap opera were at issue, the trial court erred by granting statutory damages for only one work, so that the plaintiff was entitled to statutory damages for the infringement of four works.  <EM>Gamma Audio and Video, Inc. v. Ean-Chea</EM>, 11 F.3d 1106 (1st Cir. 1993). <P>
<DT><B>Extraterritoriality: Authorizing Copying Abroad is Not Infringement</B>
<DD>On a petition for rehearing en banc, the Ninth Circuit overruled its earlier decision in <EM>Peter Starr Prod. Co. v. Twin Continental Films</EM>, 783 F.2d 1440 (9th Cir. 1986), and ruled that the mere authorization in the United States to commit an infringing act occurring entirely abroad does not constitute copyright infringement.  According to the court, the use of the phrase "to authorize" in section 106 of the Copyright Act does not create a separate category of liability unrelated to the lawfulness of the authorized act.  It also reaffirmed the principle that United States courts lack jurisdiction over wholly extraterritorial acts of infringement.  Therefore, the defendants' acts of authorizing the making and selling abroad of videocassette copies of the plaintiffs' copyrighted film, even though they were not within the defendants' license to grant, were not actionable; the infringing acts of making and selling the videocassettes did not occur in the United States and therefore could not be subject to the jurisdiction of the United States' courts under the Copyright Act.  <EM>Subafilms, Ltd. v. MGM-Pathe Communications Co.</EM>, 24 F.3d 1088 (9th Cir. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>"Inverse Ratio" Rule Rejected by Eleventh Circuit</B>
<DD>The Eleventh Circuit rejected the use of the so-called "inverse ratio" rule adopted by some courts.  The court determined that the rule, which permits an inference of copying without the amount of proof required to show substantial similarity between the plaintiff's and the defendant's works if there is clear and convincing evidence of the defendant's access to the plaintiff's work, had never been adopted in the Eleventh Circuit so that the presence of access would not dispose of the requirement to prove substantial similarity.  <EM>Beal v. Paramount Pictures Corp.</EM>, 20 F.3d 454 (11th Cir.), cert. denied, 1994 U.S. LEXIS 3460 (1994). <P>
<DT><B>Willful Infringement Found Where Infringer Ignored Notices</B>
<DD>The Seventh Circuit outlined several factors that courts may consider in determining whether the defendant's infringing acts were "willful."  Among these factors are whether the defendant ignored notices from the plaintiff that the defendant's acts were unlawful, whether the defendant sought legal advice, and whether the defendant treated the matter as a nuisance.  The court held that the defendant's failure to contact the copyright owner demonstrated willfulness where the defendant ignored a notice from the U.S. Customs Service stating that the allegedly infringing copies of the copyright owner's work being imported by the defendant had been impounded.  <EM>Wildlife Express Corp. v. Carol Wright Sales, Inc.</EM>, 18 F.3d 502 (7th Cir. 1994). <P>
</DL>
<DT><B>Jurisdiction:Songwriter's Contacts with Texas Insufficient for Personal Jurisdiction</B>
<DD>The Fifth Circuit held that, in a declaratory judgment action to determine ownership of the copyright in a song, the relevant activities for determining whether the exercise of personal jurisdiction is appropriate are circumscribed.  The court concluded that the activities of the nonresident defendant--who claimed that the plaintiff's song infringed the copyright in his song--in distributing and publicly performing his own song nationwide and mailing a demand letter to the plaintiff in Texas were insufficient contacts to subject him to jurisdiction in Texas.  The court noted that its analysis might have been different in an action where the claim was one of infringement by the defendant's song.  <EM>Ham v. La Cienega Music Co.</EM>, 4 F.3d 413 (5th Cir. 1993). <P>
<DT><B>Ownership</B>
<DL>
<DT><B>Works Made for Hire</B>
<DD>In giving further definition to what constitutes a work created by an employee within the scope of his or her employment for purposes of treating it as a "work made for hire," the Fourth Circuit overturned the district court's conclusion that the use to which the employer was going to put the work was a relevant factor.  The appellate court observed that a work is created within the scope of his or her employment if the work is of the kind the employee is employed to create, is created substantially within the authorized time and space limitations set by the employer and is created at least in part for the purpose of serving the employer.  In the case before it, the Fourth Circuit concluded that the fact that the software created by the employee was created at home and for demonstration purposes rather than a commercial product was not important where the employee is at least appreciably motivated by a desire to further the employer's goals.  <EM>Avtec Systems, Inc. v. Peiffer</EM>, 21 F.3d 568 (4th Cir. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Registration of Later Ratified Assignment Valid</B>
<DD>Following the lead of the Ninth Circuit, the Eleventh Circuit made clear that the validity of a copyright registration does not necessarily turn on when a written transfer of the copyright is made.  The court of appeals disagreed with the district court's conclusion that because the plaintiff's predecessor had only an oral assignment in the copyright at the time he registered it, the registration was ineffective and thus the plaintiff was barred from bringing a lawsuit.  Noting that a valid oral contract existed with regard to the assignment of the copyright before it was registered, the Eleventh Circuit held that an oral assignment of a copyright ratified after the fact or confirmed by a written memorandum satisfied the writing requirement of the Copyright Act.  Therefore, even though the writing did not exist at the time of registration, the registration was valid because the transfer was later confirmed in writing.  Consequently, the plaintiff did have the right to bring a lawsuit to protect its copyright.  <EM>Arthur Rutenberg Homes v. Drew Homes, Inc.</EM>, 29 F.3d 1529 (11th Cir. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Actors Not Joint Authors of Play</B>
<DD>For the first time, the Seventh Circuit addressed the test to be used in determining whether a "joint work" is created within the meaning of § 101 of the Copyright Act.  The Seventh Circuit affirmed a district court's grant of an injunction preventing the defendant from performing the plaintiff's plays and from using a videotape of the plaintiff's plays.  The district court held that although some of the actors in the plaintiff's plays had collaborated in creating the script, the actors' contribution was not enough for them to make them joint authors.  Following the test used by the Second Circuit in <EM>Childress v. Taylor</EM>, 945 F.2d 500 (2d Cir. 1991), the Seventh Circuit held that in order for a work to be a "joint work" under § 101, the authors must mutually intend to create a joint work and each author's contribution must be separately copyrightable.  <EM>Erickson v. Trinity Theatre</EM>, 13 F.3d 1061 (7th Cir. 1994). <P>
</DL>
<DT><B>Preemption:Antipiracy Statutes Not Preempted by Copyright</B>
<DD>The Ninth Circuit affirmed the district court's rejection of a petitioner's argument that California's antipiracy law was preempted by the Copyright Act.  The Ninth Circuit noted that the purpose of the California law was broader than that of the federal copyright laws and included protecting the public from being victimized by false and deceptive commercial practices and criminalizing the selling of recordings whose labels do not disclose the manufacturer or author.  <EM>Anderson v. Nidorf</EM>, 26 F.3d 100 (9th Cir. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Remedies</B>
<DL>
<DT><B>Taxes Deductible in Calculating Non-Willful Infringer's Profits</B>
<DD>The Second Circuit reversed a trial court's ruling that income taxes paid on profits may not be deducted in determining an award of profits under the Copyright Act.  The Second Circuit held that, at least where the defendant's infringing acts are not willful, a claim for infringing profits means profits actually made.  A defendant's income tax expense is therefore deductible overhead in appropriate cases when calculating an award of profits.  In <EM>Design v. K-Mart Apparel Corp.</EM>, 13 F.3d 559 (2d Cir. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Evidence of Limited Profit from Photo in Magazine Admissible</B>
<DD>The Fourth Circuit affirmed a trial court's decision to allow the defendant to introduce evidence regarding its profits.  The trial court had allowed the defendant, which had published a photograph in its magazine taken by the plaintiff without his permission, to categorize its revenues and to present testimony that demonstrated that the bulk of this revenue would have been earned even absent its infringement of the plaintiff's work.  The plaintiff complained that the jury should have only been exposed to the total amount of revenue generated by the defendant's magazine.  The Fourth Circuit affirmed the trial court's breakdown of the revenues into categories as supporting an accurate finding of the profits earned by defendant actually attributable to its publication of the plaintiff's photograph.  <EM>Walker v. Forbes, Inc.</EM>, 28 F.3d 409 (4th Cir. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Enjoined Party Entitled to Execute on Bond for Wrongful Injunction</B>
<DD>The Ninth Circuit held that a party enjoined under Fed. R. Civ. P. 65(c) is usually entitled to execute on the bond posted by the plaintiff for damages resulting from the injunction where it turns out the party enjoined had the right all along to do what it was enjoined from doing.  The fact that the party seeking the injunction acted in good faith is not a defense to a claim of wrongful injunction.  <EM>Nintendo of America, Inc. v. Lewis Galoob Toys Inc.</EM>, 16 F.3d 1032, 29 U.S.P.Q.2d 1857 (9th Cir.), cert. denied, 115 S. Ct. 85 (1994). <P>
</DL>
<DT><B>Seizures: Seizure Remedy Excludes Non-Infringing Business Records</B>
<DD>The Sixth Circuit held that the district court abused its discretion by issuing an ex parte seizure order that allowed the plaintiff to seize not only software that allegedly infringed its copyrights, but also the defendant's business records.  The court determined that section 503(a) of the Copyright Act only allows the impoundment of goods that infringe the plaintiff's copyrights and articles that can be used to copy those infringing goods.  Since the business records did not fall within either of these categories, the court ruled that the order authorizing their seizure was improper.  The court also noted that the Supreme Court's Copyright Rules relating to seizure and impoundment promulgated under the 1909 Copyright Act and purportedly in effect today had no applicability since the order itself was not authorized.  Further more, the order could not be justified under Fed. R. Civ. 65(b) because that rule only permits ex parte restraining order intended to preserve the status quo until a hearing can be held, and the search of business records went beyond preserving the status quo.  <EM>First Technology Safety Systems v. Depinet</EM>, 11 F.3d 641 (6th Cir. 1993). <P>
<DT><B>Transfers: Statute of Frauds Not Satisfied by Post Expiration Signature</B>
<DD>The Ninth Circuit held that a letter, purportedly confirming the existence of an exclusive copyright license to the plaintiffs, did not satisfy the "in writing" requirement of section 204(a) of the Copyright Act.  The Ninth Circuit noted that the letter was not signed until a year and a half after the expiration of the term of the alleged license, and held that in order for it to serve its function as the basis for each party's rights, it must be executed at close to the same time the agreement is made and also be a product of the parties' negotiations.  <EM>Konigsberg Int'l v. Rice</EM>, 16 F.3d 355, 29 U.S.P.Q.2d 1789 (9th Cir. 1994). <P>
</DL>
</DL>
<H3><A NAME="district">UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURTS</A></H3>
<DL>
<DL>
<DT><B>BBS Operator Liable for Infringement</B>
<DD>The district court found that the operators of a computer bulletin board upon which unauthorized copies of the plaintiff's computer games were uploaded and downloaded by unknown users was liable for copyright infringement.  The court found that the uploading of the games was done with the operators' knowledge and that the downloading of the games by users to make additional copies was facilitated and encouraged by the bulletin board operator.  The court further concluded that, even if the defendants did not know exactly when games would be uploaded or downloaded, their role in providing the bulletin board facilities, direction, knowledge and encouragement amounted to contributory copyright infringement.  <EM>Sega Enterprises Ltd. v. MAPHIA</EM>, 857 F. Supp. 679 (N.D. Cal. 1994). <P>
In a similar action, the district court in Minnesota issued a preliminary injunction against the operator of a bulletin board which contained unauthorized copies of plaintiff's application software.  <EM>Microsoft Corp. v. Chung, F. Supp.</EM> (D. Minn. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Synchronization Rights Not Applied to Televised Performance</B>
<DD>The district court held that the defendant's use of the plaintiff's sound recording did not infringe the plaintiff's copyright in the recording.  The defendant used the sound recording on a television show which was broadcast on over one hundred television stations across the country.  The plaintiff argued that he was entitled to synchronization rights under § 114(b) of the Copyright Act.  After examining the legislative history of § 114, the trial court disagreed, finding that the plaintiff's rights in the sound recording "could only be infringed by the unauthorized sale or public distribution of video tapes, audio cassettes or compact discs containing his sound recordings to the general public . . . ." (Emphasis in the original).  The trial court also ruled that the defendant's use of the sound recording did not constitute a derivative work and that the defendant's use actually constituted a "performance" of the recording which, because § 114(b) does not confer performance rights upon the copyright holder, did not infringe the plaintiff's copyright.  Finally, the court found the defendant's broadcast of the work was protected under the "ephemeral recording" exception contained in § 112 of the Copyright Act, which allows certain "transmitting organizations" to make a single copy of a work under certain circumstances.  <EM>Agee v. Paramount Communications</EM>, 853 F. Supp. 778 (S.D.N.Y 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Vicarious Liability Not Imposed on Trade Show Organizer</B>
<DD>In denying the plaintiffs' claim for vicarious liability against the organizers of a computer trade show for music performed there, the district court concluded, in a trial on stipulated facts, that the plaintiffs had failed to establish a case for direct infringement.  The court concluded that it was the plaintiff's burden to show that the performers of the music did not have authorization to perform it before liability could be imposed vicariously on the show's organizers.  In reaching this conclusion, the court acknowledged that its decision was in conflict with a number of other courts that have imposed vicarious liability without an explicit finding that the alleged direct infringers were not authorized to perform the music.  <EM>Polygram Int'l Publishing, Inc. v. Nevada/TIG, Inc.</EM>, 855 F. Supp. 1314 (D. Mass. 1994). <P>
<DT><B>Seizures: Supreme Court Copyright Rules Not Followed</B>
<DD>The district court refused to grant the plaintiffs an ex parte order to impound the defendant's allegedly infringing videocassettes.  The court stated that it is given the authority under § 503(a) of the Copyright Act to order the seizure of all copies of a plaintiff's work and the instrumentalities to make such copies.  It also noted that such orders are not mandatory.  The plaintiffs argued that they met the requirements of the Rules of Practice adopted by the United States Supreme Court pursuant to rulemaking power conferred on the Court by the Copyright Act ("Copyright Rules") and that, therefore, their seizure order was adequate to protect the defendants' rights.  The district court noted that the Copyright Rules are inconsistent with the discretion afforded courts under § 503(a) and are of "dubious constitutional validity" in light of the Supreme Court's subsequent decisions regarding seizures.  Consequently, in denying the order, the district court held that the plaintiffs' order did not comply with the Court's later decisions and did not sufficiently support the plaintiffs' claim that a seizure order was necessary.  In addition, the district court ruled that the order violated the defendants' Fourth Amendment rights because it did not specify with requisite particularity the premises to be searched or the articles to be seized.  <EM>Paramount Pictures Corp. v. Doe</EM>, 821 F. Supp. 82 (E.D.N.Y. 1993). <P>
<DT><B>Transfers: First Sale Doctrine Not Applied to Program License</B>
<DD>The district court issued a preliminary injunction preventing the defendants from selling MS-DOS and Windows.  The defendants claimed that the Copyright Act's "first sale doctrine" permitted their sales because they had purchased the programs from authorized licensees of Microsoft.  The court found, however, that the defendants had failed to sustain their burden of tracing the chain of title to the products to a first sale by Microsoft.  Microsoft had presented evidence that it was its practice to grant a license to use those products, but not to transfer actual ownership.  Such a license, the court concluded, is not a "sale" for purposes of the first sale doctrine.  Accordingly, defendants' sales, which also were not authorized under the terms of the license agreement which prohibited the sale of stand-alone products, infringed Microsoft's copyrights.  <EM>Microsoft Corp. v. Harmony Computers & Elecs., Inc.</EM>, 846 F. Supp. 208 (E.D.N.Y. 1994).
</DL>
</DL>
<H2><A NAME="proposed">PROPOSED LEGISLATION:</A></H2>
<DL>
<H3>PROPOSED CHANGES TO COPYRIGHT LAWS BY INFORMATION SUPERHIGHWAY TASK FORCE</H3>
<DD>A group headed by Assistant Secretary of Commerce and Commissioner of Patents and Trademarks Bruce Lehman has issued a report recommending certain changes to the current copyright laws in light of the proposed national information superhighway.  The report, which was issued last July as part of the work of the Information Infrastructure Task Force appointed by President Clinton, concludes that the information superhighway has the potential to increase access to information and entertainment resources greatly.  It observes, however, that the potential of the information superhighway will not be realized fully if these resources are not protected effectively when disseminated. <P>
In particular, the report notes that, today, nearly any work can be "digitized," i.e., translated into binary code, and can then be stored, transmitted and used in that format.  It cautions that, with the advent of a national, high-speed, high-capacity electronic information system, one individual could, with a few key strokes, deliver perfect copies of digitized works to scores of individuals. <P>
The report focuses its discussion on whether the current copyright laws need to be changed in view of digital technology.  In addition, the report more generally addresses the application of the copyright laws to multimedia works. <P>
The report takes the position that, with the proliferation of works in an environment in which they all appear as digital bits so that they cannot easily fit into any of the eight enumerated types of works set forth in the Copyright Act, it may be time to eliminate such classifications altogether.  The report also recognizes that developing a multimedia work often requires licensing rights from numerous sources--for text, images, film clips, narration, and music--and that identifying the owners of the copyrights in these different works can be difficult.  Despite this difficulty, the report rejects the notion that any national compulsory license system should be implemented.  Rather, the report favors allowing the marketplace to develop appropriate licensing schemes. <P>
After reviewing existing intellectual property protection and after evaluating how new technology and educational efforts could enhance protection for copyrighted works, however, the authors of the report do conclude that the Copyright Act should be altered in several areas. <P>
<H3>DISTRIBUTION BY TRANSMISSION</H3>
<DL>
<DD>The report recognizes that one of the major effects of high-speed digital communications will be its utilization as a means both to distribute the work itself and to distribute copies of the work.  In view of this fact, the report recommends the following specific changes to the Copyright Act: <P>
Exclusive right to transmit.  The report suggests that because, in the world of the information superhighway, a preferred means of distribution from one location to another may be via transmission, the Copyright Act should be amended explicitly to include distribution by transmission as one of the exclusive rights of the copyright holder. <P>
Reproductions may be transmitted.  The report notes that the Copyright Act currently contemplates a transmission only of a performance or a display of a work.  Since a reproduction of a work also may be transmitted, the report recommends that the definition of "transmit" be modified to reflect this fact.  Where the transmission may result in both a copy being distributed and the communication of a performance or display, the "primary purpose or effect" test should be used to determine which result predominates. <P>
Importation by transmission.  Recognizing that copies of works can be introduced into the United States via transmission, the report suggests that the ban on unauthorized importation of works acquired outside the United States be revised explicitly to prohibit importation of works "whether by carriage of tangible goods or by transmission." <P>
Publication by transmission.  Consistent with its other recommendations, the report suggests that the definition of "publication" in the Copyright Act include distribution of copies or phonorecords by transmission. <P>
Limitation on the first sale doctrine.  With certain exceptions, the Copyright Act currently allows the owner of a particular, lawfully-made copy of a work to dispose of it in any manner without infringing the copyright owner's exclusive right of distribution.  The report recommends, however, that this first sale doctrine not apply to distributions by transmission, because a transmission may involve both the reproduction of the work and the distribution of the reproduction. <P>
</DL>
<H3>RESTRICTING TECHNOLOGY THAT DEFEATS COPYRIGHT PROTECTION SYSTEMS</H3>
<DL>
<DD>The report adopts the widely-held view that the digitized works that will be utilized on the information superhighway may be easily copied and that such copying may be difficult to detect.  Because these problems make traditional copyright enforcement through infringement actions difficult, the report contemplates that copyright owners will look to technological protection mechanisms and systems, as well as the law, to inhibit copying.  To encourage reliance on such mechanisms and systems, the report recommends that the Copyright Act be amended in a number of respects to prohibit the importation, manufacture, and distribution of devices and services that defeat anti-copying systems. <P>
</DL>
<H3>PROTECTING THE INTEGRITY OF COPYRIGHT MANAGEMENT INFORMATION</H3>
<DL>
<DD>The report recognizes that certain information associated with a work--such as the name of the copyright owner and the terms and conditions for using it--may be essential for works to appear and be utilized efficiently and successfully on the information superhighway.  Accordingly, the report recommends that the Copyright Act be amended to prohibit fraudulent inclusion or removal of such information, with fines of up to $2,500. <P>
</DL>
<H3>PUBLIC PERFORMANCE RIGHT FOR SOUND RECORDINGS</H3>
<DL>
<DD>The report notes that direct digital transmissions of sound recordings may soon supplant current forms of distributing phonorecords via cassette or compact disc.  It also observes that some of these transmissions will constitute public performances of the sound recordings, rather than copies, and may become a preferred alternative to buying copies for listening. <P>
Under current law, sound recordings are the only works whose copyright does not include the exclusive right to perform the work publicly.  Therefore, to play a record on the radio, the radio station need only obtain a license from the copyright holder of the work that was recorded, but not from the owner of the copyright in the recording itself.  The report recommends that this anomaly be rectified. <P>
The report supports two bills introduced in Congress this past session that would grant a limited performance right in sound recordings.  Under these bills, the rights afforded the copyright holder in a sound recording would be expanded to include performance of the recording by "digital transmission."  It would not, however, extend to live public performances such as at a club, or to analog transmissions received over the radio.  (At this time, neither bill has made it out of committee.) <P>
While the report represents the author's preliminary examination and analysis of copyright law and its application and effectiveness in the context of the information superhighway, it is likely that its recommendations will be proposed formally into legislation sometime next year.  Public comment on the report closed on September 28, 1994.  Comments are available for public inspection at the Scientific and Technical Information Center of the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, Room 2C07, Crystal Plaza 34, 2021 Jefferson Davis Highway, Arlington, Virginia, between the hours of 9 a.m. and 4 p.m., Monday through Friday.
</DL>
</DL>

