<TITLE> InterNIC Issues New Trademark Policy for Domain Names </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>InterNIC Issues New Trademark Policy for Domain Names</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Gary S. Weinstein</h4>
<p>

Domain names, such as faegre.com, are the electronic addresses of computers on the Internet.  Much like novelty telephone numbers, domain names are assigned on a first-come-first-serve basis by a non-profit organization called InterNIC.  In the past, this led to problems such as The Princeton Review surprising its major competitor Stanley Kaplan by reserving the domain name kaplan.com, or companies such as McDonalds learning that in order to obtain the domain name mcdonalds.com, it would have to pay a ransom to the party who had registered that domain name.<p>

To deal with such problems, InterNIC recently instituted a new policy related to the trademark implications of domain names.  First, when applying for a domain name, an applicant is required to warrant that (i) its use of the domain name will not result in trademark infringement, (ii) it has a bona fide intention to use the domain name on a regular basis, and (iii) it is not seeking to use the domain name for any unlawful purpose.  Furthermore, the applicant must agree to indemnify InterNIC and its affiliated organizations for any claims relating to the use of the domain name. <p> 

Second, if at any time another party claims that it owns the trademark rights to a domain name by submitting to InterNIC a valid United States Trademark Registration (or a foreign equivalent) with a filing date or date-of-first-use prior to the first use of the domain name, then the domain name registrant will have thirty days to submit proof that it also has valid trademark rights in that name.  Satisfactory proof would include a certified copy of a United States Trademark Registration (or a foreign equivalent) or a court order supporting the claimed rights.  Furthermore, the domain name registrant must also indemnify InterNIC from any costs InterNIC might incur relating to the dispute and post a bond to cover any possible damages.  <p>

If the domain name registrant submits sat-isfactory proof that it owns trademark rights in the domain name, agrees to hold InterNIC harmless and posts a bond to cover any possible damages, it can continue to use the domain name until the dispute is resolved or a court grants a temporary order ruling otherwise.  If the domain name registrant fails to meet these three requirements and chooses not to adopt a new domain name, then InterNIC will suspend the domain name until the dispute is resolved or a court grants a temporary order.  If the domain name registrant does choose to adopt a new domain name, then InterNIC will allow the domain name registrant to use the old and new domain names simultaneously for ninety days.  Regardless of whether the domain name is suspended, InterNIC itself will not become involved in the dispute.  The parties will have to resolve the dispute either through arbitration or in court.  <p>

While there are questions relating to this new policy and whether it could withstand a legal challenge, unless you have a United States Trademark Registration (or foreign equivalent) for your domain name, InterNIC can suspend your electronic address with only thirty days advance notice.  The prudent course for any business that has developed goodwill in a domain name is to apply for a United States Trademark Registration that covers the domain name.  Even if you have a trademark registration, you still will have to defend your rights to use the domain name, if challenged.  The risks of losing the domain name during the pendency of the dispute, however, are likely to be significantly reduced.<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Gary Weinstein by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:gweinstein@faegre.com"><EM>gweinstein@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


