<TITLE> Patenting a Floppy Disk: Availability of Software Patents Increase </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Patenting a Floppy Disk: Availability of Software Patents Increase</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Daniel A. Tysver</h4>
<p>


<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>here is currently greater opportunity than ever before for software developers to obtain patent protection for their computer programs.  Both the Federal Circuit Court of Appeals, the appeals court with authority over all patent appeals, and the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office have recently taken action to expand the scope of patent protection available for computer software.<P>

In a series of rulings, the Federal Circuit discussed the scope of the U.S. patent laws.  Under the U.S. Patent laws, patents may be granted on any new and useful process, machine, manufacture, or composition of matter.  Historically, computer software was considered to be a mathematical algorithm, and not a process, machine, manufacture or composition of matter within the meaning of the patent laws.  As such, computer software programs could not be patented alone, as the programs were not statutory subject matter.  Instead, in order to obtain a patent for software, the software had to be patented in connection with some external machine, such as part of a computer modem, or as part of a separate process, such as a process for curing rubber.  <P>

In a recent holding, however, the Federal Circuit found computer software to be patentable even where the external machine was comprised of only simple digital electronic circuits, namely a barrel shifter and an arithmetic logic unit.  In a second decision, the Court allowed a patent for software where the external component was only a generic machine with computer memory on which the software was stored.  These rulings indicate that software patent applications written to include a reference to the computer on which the software is executed, or a reference to the computer memory on which the software is stored, can be patentable.<P>

While at first the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office resisted the Federal Circuit's expansion of statutory subject matter, the Office has reconsidered its position and has now announced new examination guidelines for evaluating the patentability of computer related inventions.  The guidelines state explicitly that computer programs embodied in a tangible medium, such as a floppy diskette, are patentable subject matter . . . .  Rather than focusing on whether the invention is considered statutory subject matter, the guidelines instruct the patent examiners to focus on the novelty of the invention itself.  <P>
		
Under these guidelines, a computer software will be considered patentable simply by including a reference to a tangible medium.  Since software is always stored in some medium, whether it be a floppy disk, random access memory (RAM) or a CD-ROM, every software program should now be considered to be statutory subject matter.  Of course, software must still meet the other criteria of patentability, including novelty, utility and nonobviousness.<P>

Although computer software is already protected by copyright law, the possibility of seeking patent protection for computer software should be seriously considered by all software developers in light of these new developments.  While copyright law protects software against the copying of all or a portion of the software, it offers no protection against the independent development of similar software, i.e., software that is created without copying.  In contrast, patent protection prevents anyone from making, using, or selling the patented product, even if the infringing product was independently developed.  Also, patent law is designed to protect innovative ideas and can cover such things as the program logic and particular functions in the software.  Copyright law, however, protects only against the copying of a particular expression of an idea and not against copying of the underlying concepts embedded in the software.  <P>

Patent law contains strict requirements regarding the timely filing of applications; patent rights can be lost if an application is not filed in time.  As a result, software developers desiring patent protection should take steps to have a patent applicantion filed as soon as possible after the invention has been made.  <P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Dan Tysver by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:dtysver@faegre.com"><EM>dtysver@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

