<TITLE>Education Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="intel3.gif"><P>

<H2>Education Law</H2>
</CENTER>
<p>
<H4>Overview of Our Practice</H4>
<P>
Faegre & Benson's Education Law Group is uniquely positioned to assist large and small educational institutions deal with the complex legal issues they face.  Faegre & Benson advises educational institutions on a wide variety of matters, including federal and state tax issues, employee benefits and pension plans, labor and employment issues, accommodation of the disabled, intellectual property, endowment fund management, fund-raising and charitable gifts, tax-exempt bond financing, corporate governance, real estate and student housing, student affairs, professional liability and risk management, and First Amendment and other issues affecting religious educational institutions.

<p>

We are one of only a few firms in the region with practice groups concentrating in nonprofit organizations, public finance and issues related to section 403(b) tax sheltered annuities and retirement plans for church affiliated institutions.  The Firm has a long history of service to the charitable and nonprofit community and we are proud to have represented many of the region's leading educational and charitable institutions.

<p>

<h4>Approach</h4>
 
Faegre & Benson's Education Law Group uses a team approach to provide the depth and breadth of expertise required to meet the complex legal demands of educational institutions.  It is our experience that clients are best served when their legal needs are provided by a relatively small team of lawyers, one of whom serves as the primary contact for the client.  When necessary, we draw on the expertise of specialists from other practice groups in the Firm, including the construction and governmental affairs groups.

<p>

<h4>Representative Services</h4>

Examples of services to our Firm's educational clients include the following:

<UL>
<LI>Preparation of sexual harassment, sexual violence, sexual misconduct and student conduct policies and training materials
<LI>Representation in student disciplinary proceedings 
<LI>Defense of sexual harassment and discrimination claims before federal, state and local enforcement agencies
<LI>Representation in termination of tenured faculty
<LI>Representation in collective bargaining negotiations and arbitrations
<LI>Advice regarding personnel policies and practices, including faculty handbooks
<LI>Redesign of faculty retirement plans after Tax Reform Act of 1986
<LI>Design and implementation of severance and early retirement arrangements
<LI>Advice regarding unrelated business income tax on income from rental of facilities and from research services
<LI>Advice regarding disclosure obligations in fundraising solicitations
<LI>Serving as bond counsel for school districts and the Minnesota Higher Education Facilities Authority in connection with tax exempt general obligation bond issues and private activity bond issues
<LI>Representation of 501(c)(3) organizations in IRS audits, including those conducted under the coordinated examination program
<LI>Establishment of deferred giving programs, including compliance with federal and state registration and reporting requirements
<LI>Development of student housing policies and agreements
<LI>Design of nonprofit/for-profit joint ventures
<LI>Litigation prevention and management
</UL>


<p>

