<H2><b>Environmental Law</b></H2><P>
</CENTER>

Lawyers in Faegre & Benson's environmental practice regularly represent clients in litigation and administrative proceedings, including Superfund actions, toxic tort litigation and the defense of criminal environmental claims.  They also advise clients on permits and compliance matters, environmental impact statements and insurance coverage.  The Firm has successfully handled problems faced by manufacturers and handlers of toxic and hazardous substances at all stages, from prevention to litigation.
<p>
<H3>Articles of Interest</H3>
<IMG ALIGN=baseline HSPACE=10 SRC="../images/blue.gif"><A HREF="#EMF">New Study on Alleged Link Between Electromagnetic Field Exposure and Leukemia and Brain Cancer</A><P>

<IMG ALIGN=baseline HSPACE=10 SRC="../images/blue.gif"><A HREF="#asbestos">OSHA  Asbestos Regulations Impose New
Obligations On Building Owners</A><P>
<P><P>
<A NAME="asbestos">
</A><H2>OSHA Asbestos Regulations Impose New
Obligations On Building Owners
</H2><P>

<h4>by</h4>

<h4>Paul S. Moe</h4>

<font="+2"><b>Introduction</b></font>
<br>

The federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) promulgated nearly 200 pages of new regulations related to asbestos-containing materials (ACM).<STRONG>1</STRONG>  Many of the far reaching provisions of the regulations will be effective October 1, 1995.<STRONG>2</STRONG>  The regulations will have a significant effect on several industries, including construction firms, asbestos abatement contractors, and shipbuilding interests.  In addition, many businesses with real estate holdings (that may not previously have been subject to OSHA requirements) must take steps to protect employees from certain asbestos risks, and must disclose asbestos-related information to employees, building managers, tenants, and successive property owners.<p>

<font="+2"><b>Background</b></font>
<br>

Asbestos is a common mineral that was widely used in the United States until the 1970s for a variety of commercial purposes, including fireproofing, vinyl floor tiles, textured paints, ceiling and acoustical tiles, pipe insulation, furnaces, walls, boilers and brake linings.  Since asbestos is processed into microscopic fibers that can remain airborne for long periods of time, it can be difficult to contain the fibers once they have been released.  According to OSHA, asbestos levels in a building can become hazardous if concentrated amounts of fibers are released into the building air as a result of any disturbance of the ACM in the building.   OSHA has identified certain studies that purport to show a link between exposure to significant amounts of asbestos and asbestosis (a disease with symptoms similar to emphysema), lung cancer, and cancer of the chest lining or abdominal cavity.  The risk of health problems caused by merely working in an office building with ACM, however, has been described as minimal.  Researchers have asserted that the likelihood of death from exposure to asbestos in a commercial building is as probable as death from a shark attack or the bubonic plague.<STRONG>3</STRONG>  The risk to building occupants from asbestos contained in the building has been compared to smoking one-half of a cigarette in a lifetime.<STRONG>4</STRONG> Although the risk to building  occupants  may be  minimal, OSHA concluded that it should take action to limit repeated exposure to asbestos by (among others) maintenance and custodial employees. 
<br> 

In response to its concerns about the health risks for employees who work directly with asbestos or ACM,  beginning in 1974  OSHA enacted regulations that protected workers in two distinct areas.  OSHA established a construction industry standard for activities related to direct contact with asbestos, and a general industry standard that covered all activities involving contact with ACM that were not otherwise covered by the construction standard.  In connection with these two standards, OSHA established extensive requirements for working with asbestos.  OSHA established permissible exposure limits (PELs), which serve as a benchmark for the maximum permitted exposure to airborne asbestos fibers that a worker can have in an eight-hour day.  The construction standard included very detailed techniques for asbestos abatement and demolition work.  
<p>
<font="+2"><b>OSHA's New Requirements</b></font>
<br>

The new regulations greatly extend the reach of OSHA's jurisdiction, and include the following new requirements:
<p>
<font="+2"><b>Duties of "Building/ Facility Owners"</b></font>
<br>

Based on the premise that "building/facility owners " (as defined below) are often "the only and/or the best source of information concerning the presence of ACM,"<STRONG>5</STRONG>  OSHA imposed broad new obligations on commercial and industrial property owners.  OSHA defined  building/facility owner as the legal entity, including a lessee, which exercises control over management and record keeping functions."<STRONG>6</STRONG> This broad definition includes many property owners or lessees that have no employees, or who otherwise have not considered themselves to be under OSHA's jurisdiction.  The new regulations require building/facility owners to disclose to their own employees (if they have any) and to employers of employees who may be exposed to asbestos, the existence of ACM and "presumed asbestos containing materials" (PACM)<STRONG>7</STRONG> in the building or facility, as identified by an industrial hygienist.  (Building/facility owners are exempt from this requirement if the building was constructed after 1979, or if qualified analysts have determined that the building is free of asbestos.)  Once notified of the existence of the ACM and PACM, the employer of the housekeeping staff - if different from the building/facility owner - must promptly satisfy the disclosure obligations it has to such employees.  Since the regulations require disclosure of PACM, as well as ACM, all building/facility owners must at least conduct visual surveys to identify all ACM and PACM on the property.
<p>
<font="+2"><b>Notification of Employees</b></font>
<br>

Employers must develop and implement a rigorous training program for all employees who may be exposed to airborne concentration limits above the PELs.  This program must explain, among other matters, the health effects associated with asbestos exposure, procedures implemented to protect employees from exposure to asbestos, the use of respirators and protective clothing, and a description of the medical surveillance program required by OSHA.  Training must be provided at least annually to each such employee.  Employers must also post warning signs in and around areas where airborne concentrations of asbestos exceed (or where there is a reasonable possibility they may exceed) the PELs.
<br>

Employers must also provide an "asbestos awareness training course" for all employees who do housekeeping or custodial work in facilities where ACM or  (PACM) are present.  This course must describe the health effects of asbestos, the location of ACM and PACM in the facility, techniques for recognizing damaged  ACM and PACM, and appropriate housekeeping techniques related to ACM and PACM.  This course must be held annually.
<p>
<font="+2"><b>Record Retention and Disclosure</b></font>
<br>

Under the new rules, a building/facility owner is required to take measures to protect a subsequent purchaser's employees by disclosing certain information about asbestos in the building/facility.  Such owners must maintain records related to any ACM and PACM in the building/facility, and disclose such information to successive owners.    OSHA acknowledges that such disclosure requirements are a significant extension of its regulatory power.  Several court challenges to OSHA's ability to promulgate such a requirement have already been filed.<STRONG>8</STRONG> 
<p>
<font="+2"><b>Standards Modified</b></font>
<br>

OSHA reduced the PELs to half of the previously permitted levels.  In addition, employers whose employees work directly with asbestos have new, more stringent exposure control methods that must be followed. 

<p>
<font="+2"><b>Conclusion</b></font>
<br>

For employers whose employees work directly with asbestos (including construction and demolition workers), OSHA's new control requirements provide very detailed techniques for such work.  The most significant effect of the regulations, however, is to require "building/facility owners" to take steps to protect housekeeping and custodial workers, even when such workers are not employed by the owner.  As a general matter, OSHA now requires owners of commercial and industrial buildings to do the following:

<UL>
<LI>perform a visual survey of ACM and PACM in a building;
<LI>disclose the results of such survey to its employees (if any) and to the employers of any housekeeping or custodial workers at the property;
<LI>retain the survey, together with any other information about ACM or PACM at the property; and 
<LI>deliver such records to the purchaser of the property. 
</UL>


Many organizations that were previously unconcerned with OSHA regulations (because, for example, they had no employees) must now be concerned with OSHA's efforts to significantly broaden its jurisdiction in the name of worker protection.
<br>

This Issue Update is intended only to provide general background information about this area of the law, and should not be construed as legal advice.<BR>
<OL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>59 F. R. 40963 (codified at 29 CFR Parts 1910, et al.).
<LI>29 CFR §§1910.1001 (o), 1915.1001(q) and 1926.1101 (q).
<LI>Johnine J. Brown, Asbestos Removal:  A Really Major Boondoggle, Rudnick & Wolfe, 2 The Environment 1 (Spring 1990).
<LI>Michael J. Bennett, Asbestos Danger Compounded by Unnecessary Removal Efforts, Kansas City Times, Monday, July 4, 1988, at 1 (quoting Sir Richard Doll of Oxford University).
<LI>29 CFR §1910.1001 (j), 29 CFR §1926.1101 (k).
<LI>29 CFR §1910.1001 (b), 29 CFR §1926.1101 (b).
<LI>Presumed asbestos containing materials includes asphalt and vinyl flooring material installed in 1980 or earlier, thermal system insulation, sprayed on or trowled on surfacing material, and debris in work areas where such material is present.  29 CFR § 1910.1001(b).
<LI>See e.g., American Federation of State and Municipal Employees, AFL-CIO v. Reich, No. 94-1576 (D.C. Cir. filed August 18, 1994); Building and Construction Trades Department, AFL-CIO v. Reich, No. 94-1575 (D.C. Cir. filed August 18, 1994).
</OL>
<p>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><br>


If you have any questions, please contact Paul Moe at 612/336-3334 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:pmoe@faegre.com">pmoe@faegre.com</A>.<p>

<A NAME="EMF">
</A><H2>New Study on Alleged Link Between Electromagnetic Field Exposure and Leukemia and Brain Cancer</H2><P>

<h4>by</h4>

<h4>Bruce Jones and Andrea M. Fike</h4>

This report is the second in a series of reports designed to inform you of developments in the debate that electromagnetic fields do or do not play a role in the development of various diseases.  Our first report focused on the effect this debate has on real estate and construction businesses.  This report highlights the results of a recent scientific study which examined a group of electric utility workers in an effort to determine whether such workers suffered adverse health effects from their exposure to electromagnetic fields.
<BR>

The study was conducted at the University of North Carolina School of Public Health at Chapel Hill, North Carolina, and examined mortality among electric utility workers and the possible relationship between magnetic field exposure and leukemia and brain cancer in electric utility workers.  This study is significant because it is very recent and because it relates to a sizable study group.  The study's most significant findings are that there is no association between leukemia and magnetic field exposure but that there is an association between cumulative exposure to magnetic fields and the risk of developing brain cancer.
<BR>

The study was sponsored by the Electric Power Research Institute.  Nearly 140,000 workers were included in the study.  These workers were employed by five power companies: Carolina Power and Light Company, Virginia Electric Power Company, PICO Energy Company, Tennessee Valley Authority, and Pacific Gas and Electric Company.
<BR>

The study examined worker mortality rates based on the duration of exposure to magnetic fields and based on cumulative exposure to magnetic fields.  In order to estimate cumulative exposures for various occupational categories, researchers measured personal magnetic field exposures of randomly selected study subjects.  Personal magnetic field exposures were measured using an Average Magnetic EXposure (AMEX) meter which subjects wore for a work shift.  The AMEX meter accrues an electrical charge proportional to the cumulative magnetic field the worker comes in contact with, generating a time-weighted average exposure.  Based upon the magnetic field exposure measurements, the researchers created a job-exposure matrix.  Information regarding the duration of exposure and cumulative exposure levels of study subjects and the study group's mortality rates was compared to mortality information for the general population to determine whether any association between exposure to magnetic fields and leukemia or brain cancer exists.
<BR>

The study found that, as a group, the electric utility workers were healthier than the general population and that overall cancer mortality was lower than what would be expected based on mortality rates for the general population.  This result was not surprising to the researchers, who postulate that electrical utility workers are likely to be a group of healthy individuals due to a self-selection process.  The study also found that leukemia, including leukemia subtypes of acute myeloid leukemia and chronic lymphocytic leukemia, was not related to duration of employment in exposed jobs or to increasing cumulative magnetic field exposure.  However, a weak association between brain cancer and duration of work in exposed jobs was found in the study, and a stronger association between brain cancer and cumulative magnetic field exposures was also found.  Based on the study data, brain cancer mortality increases by a factor of 1.94 for each microtesla-year of exposure in the prior two to ten year period.  Significantly, the greatest increase in risk occurred for exposures accruing in the previous 2-10 year period, suggesting that any adverse effect of magnetic field exposure has a relatively short latency period.
<br>

It is important to recognize that no one study can prove or disprove a causal relationship between electromagnetic fields and disease.  Even the researchers for this study believe that conclusions regarding whether or not magnetic fields cause cancer still can not be drawn based upon existing research, including their study.  However, electrical utilities, product manufacturers and others interested in the claims of a relationship between various illnesses and electromagnetic fields should be aware of the study as part of their overall monitoring of this issue.
<br>

If you have any questions about the University of North Carolina study or would like additional information on the legal issues related to electromagnetic fields, please call Bruce Jones at (612) 336-3342, Andrea Fike at (612) 336-3392 or the attorney at Faegre & Benson with whom you work most closely.
<p>
<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><br>


If you have any questions about the University of North Carolina study or would like additional information on the legal issues related to electromagnetic fields, please contact Bruce Jones, Andrea Fike or the attorney at Faegre & Benson with whom you work most closely.  Bruce Jones is available at 612/336-3342 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A hREF="mailto:bjones@faegre.com">bjones@faegre.com</A>.  Andrea Fike is available at 612/336-3392 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:afike@faegre.com">afike@faegre.com</A>.<p>

