<A NAME="attorney">
</A><H2>Attorney Liability
Under the Fair Debt Collection Practices Act 
</H2><P>

<h4><i> A recent U.S. Supreme Court decision promises continued litigation against lawyers 
engaged in collection proceedings on consumer debts.
</i></h4>
<h4>by</h4>

<h4>Ann Marie Hanrahan</h4>
On April 18, 1995, the U.S. Supreme Court held that attorneys who regularly, through litigation, collect consumer debts fall within the definition of debt collector under the Fair Debt Collection Practices Act (the FDCPA).  Heintz v. Jenkins, 514 U.S. ---, 115 S. Ct. 1489, 131 L. Ed. 2d. 395 (1995).  This decision follows years of litigation concerning the scope of attorney liability under the FDCPA.  
<br>
Prior to 1986, the FDCPA contained an exception for collection work done by attorneys.  When Congress deleted this exception, it left an open question as to exactly when an attorney was covered by the Act, and, to a lesser extent, when an attorney's actions will actually violate the Act.
<br>
The FDCPA defines debt collector as one who uses interstate commerce or the mails in any business the principal purpose of which is the collection of debts, or who regularly collects or attempts to collect . . . debts owed to another.  While there are no specific parameters for when an attorney has crossed the line into regular debt collection, one court has set forth the following factors:  the volume of the attorney's collection activities; the frequency of the use of the collection letter in question; and whether or not there was found to be an ongoing relationship between the attorney and the collection agency he represented.  Cacace v. Lukas, 775 F. Supp. 502, 504 (D. Conn. 1990) (citation omitted).  Filing warrants and sending post-judgment letters have both been held to be debt collection for purposes of the Act.
<br>
Until Heintz, courts were split as to whether pure litigation activities constituted debt collection. In Heintz the Supreme Court held that the Act applies to all attorneys who regularly collect consumer debts, even those who do so through legal proceedings. The Court noted that Congress did not replace the attorney exception with a more narrow litigation exception, and that the plain language of the statute seems to encompass attorney debt collectors. 
<br>
From other FDCPA decisions, a number of general rules emerge that an attorney can follow to avoid FDCPA liability: 
 
<UL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>Be aware of how often the firm collects debts and the type of debts collected.  While there is no set formula, if consumer debt collection is a significant part of the firm's practice, its actions are probably covered by the Act.
<LI>After Heintz, traditional debt collection activity (sending dunning letters, etc.) as well as debt collection litigation (including, presumably, the mere filing of a complaint) may expose an attorney to potential liability.  Post-judgment collection activities are also covered by the Act.
<LI>Be aware of the least sophisticated consumer standard.  For example, while in-house counsel are not covered by the Act, if a letter sent by such counsel gives the impression to the least sophisticated consumer that the counsel is an independent attorney, liability may exist.
<LI>Does a collection letter give any impression that a lawsuit may be filed when none is actually intended?  This may expose an attorney to liability.  The test is not whether a consumer was fooled, but whether the least sophisticated consumer would be.
<LI>Sending form collection letters signed by an attorney when the attorney has not personally reviewed the individual file has been held to be a violation of the Act since it suggests that an attorney has been specifically retained in con-nection with that particular debt.  In fact, a case has been brought in federal court in Minnesota against a law firm on just those grounds.  
</UL>

While the above rules will help to avoid liability, it is important to remember that the activities discussed here are not the only potential FDCPA violations for attorneys.  They are just among those that have been litigated against attorneys.  The Act imposes many requirements, all of which apply to attorneys who regularly collect consumer debts.  Once counsel are covered by the Act (i.e., they are regularly collecting consumer debts, etc.), further research is needed to assure compliance and avoid exposure to liability.
<br>
<I>R. Christopher Sur contributed to this article
</i><p>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><br>

