<A NAME="EMF">
</A><H2>New Study on Alleged Link Between Electromagnetic Field Exposure and Leukemia and Brain Cancer</H2><P>

<h4>by</h4>

<h4>Bruce Jones and Andrea M. Fike</h4>
This report is the second in a series of reports designed to inform you of developments in the debate that electromagnetic fields do or do not play a role in the development of various diseases.  Our first report focused on the effect this debate has on real estate and construction businesses.  This report highlights the results of a recent scientific study which examined a group of electric utility workers in an effort to determine whether such workers suffered adverse health effects from their exposure to electromagnetic fields.
<BR>
The study was conducted at the University of North Carolina School of Public Health at Chapel Hill, North Carolina, and examined mortality among electric utility workers and the possible relationship between magnetic field exposure and leukemia and brain cancer in electric utility workers.  This study is significant because it is very recent and because it relates to a sizable study group.  The study's most significant findings are that there is no association between leukemia and magnetic field exposure but that there is an association between cumulative exposure to magnetic fields and the risk of developing brain cancer.
<BR>
The study was sponsored by the Electric Power Research Institute.  Nearly 140,000 workers were included in the study.  These workers were employed by five power companies: Carolina Power and Light Company, Virginia Electric Power Company, PICO Energy Company, Tennessee Valley Authority, and Pacific Gas and Electric Company.
<BR>
The study examined worker mortality rates based on the duration of exposure to magnetic fields and based on cumulative exposure to magnetic fields.  In order to estimate cumulative exposures for various occupational categories, researchers measured personal magnetic field exposures of randomly selected study subjects.  Personal magnetic field exposures were measured using an Average Magnetic EXposure (AMEX) meter which subjects wore for a work shift.  The AMEX meter accrues an electrical charge proportional to the cumulative magnetic field the worker comes in contact with, generating a time-weighted average exposure.  Based upon the magnetic field exposure measurements, the researchers created a job-exposure matrix.  Information regarding the duration of exposure and cumulative exposure levels of study subjects and the study group's mortality rates was compared to mortality information for the general population to determine whether any association between exposure to magnetic fields and leukemia or brain cancer exists.
<BR>
The study found that, as a group, the electric utility workers were healthier than the general population and that overall cancer mortality was lower than what would be expected based on mortality rates for the general population.  This result was not surprising to the researchers, who postulate that electrical utility workers are likely to be a group of healthy individuals due to a self-selection process.  The study also found that leukemia, including leukemia subtypes of acute myeloid leukemia and chronic lymphocytic leukemia, was not related to duration of employment in exposed jobs or to increasing cumulative magnetic field exposure.  However, a weak association between brain cancer and duration of work in exposed jobs was found in the study, and a stronger association between brain cancer and cumulative magnetic field exposures was also found.  Based on the study data, brain cancer mortality increases by a factor of 1.94 for each microtesla-year of exposure in the prior two to ten year period.
Significantly, the greatest increase in risk occurred for exposures accruing in the previous 2-10 year period, suggesting that any adverse effect of magnetic field exposure has a relatively short latency period.
<br>
It is important to recognize that no one study can prove or disprove a causal relationship between electromagnetic fields and disease.  Even the researchers for this study believe that conclusions regarding whether or not magnetic fields cause cancer still can not be drawn based upon existing research, including their study.  However, electrical utilities, product manufacturers and others interested in the claims of a relationship between various illnesses and electromagnetic fields should be aware of the study as part of their overall monitoring of this issue.
<p>
<font="+2"><b>Note:</b></font><br>

This Issue Update is intended solely to alert readers to professional liability issues and is <B>not</B> intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this Issue Update.
<P>
<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><br>

If you have any questions about the University of North Carolina study or would like additional information on the legal issues related to electromagnetic fields, please contact Bruce Jones, Andrea Fike or the attorney at Faegre & Benson with whom you work most closely.  Bruce Jones is available at 612/336-3342 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A hREF="mailto:bjones@faegre.com">bjones@faegre.com</A>.  Andrea Fike is available at 612/336-3392 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:afike@faegre.com">afike@faegre.com</A>.<p>

