	Access to deposition taken in post-judgment collection proceedings<P>
	
<EM>Wisconsin ex rel. Cowles Media Co. v. Washburn County Circuit Court</EM>, 
	20 Media L. Rptr. 1744 (Wis. Ct. App. 1992) <BR>
	Access to preliminary hearing<P>
	
 <A NAME="libel"></A><H3>Libel and Slander</H3>

<EM>Aequitron Medical Inc. v. CBS Inc.</EM>, 23 Media L. Rptr. 1631 (S.D.N.Y. 1994)<P>

 <EM>Andrescu v. Lane</EM>, 5 Media L. Rptr. 1290 (Colo. Dist. Ct. 1979) <BR>
	Summary judgment on constitutional malice issue for defendant in libel action by harness racing driver over broadcast alleging race fix <P>

<EM>Benigni v. Cowles Media Co.</EM>, 22 Media L. Rptr. 2120 (Minn. Ct. App. 1994) <BR>
	Defamatory meaning<P>
 
<EM>Bowers v. Loveland Publishing Co.</EM>, 773 P.2d 595 (Colo. App. 1988) <BR>
	Reporting of police blotter subject to New York Times rule in Colorado<P>
 
<EM>Brooks v. KWGN of Colorado, Inc.</EM>, 773 P.2d 1098 (Colo. App. 1988) <BR>
	Opinion, intentional infliction of emotional distress<P>
	
<EM>Burns v. The Denver Post, Inc.</EM>, 606 P.2d 1310 (Colo. App. 1979) <BR>
	Summary judgment affirmed on opinion issue<P>
 
<EM>Capan v. Daugherty</EM>, 402 N.W.2d 561 (Minn. Ct. App. 1987) <BR>
	Opinion privilege <P>

<EM>Clausnitzer v. Cowles Media Co.</EM>, 18 Media L. Rptr. 1137 (Minn. Dist. Ct. 1990) <BR>
	Quotations <P>

<EM>Colfax Avenue Irrevocable Trust v. Denver Post Corp.</EM>, (Colo. Dist. Ct. 1994) <BR>
	Successfully defended The Denver Post in jury trial on libel claims<P>

<EM>Conroy v. Kilzer</EM>, 789 F.Supp. 1457 (D. Minn. 1992) <BR>
	Libel by implication; fair report privilege; intentional infliction of emotional distress<P>

<EM>Diversified Management, Inc. v. The Denver Post, Inc.</EM>, 653 P.2d 1103 (Colo. 1982)<BR> 
	Matters of public concern subject to New York Times rule in Colorado<P>

<EM>Hahn v. Board of Publications</EM>, 10 Media L. Rptr. 1671 (Colo. Dist. Ct. 1984)<BR>
	Summary judgment affirmed on constitutional malice issue<P>
 
<EM>Hannon v. Timberline Publishing, Inc.</EM>, 19 Media L. Rptr. 1244 (Colo. Dist. Ct. 1991) <BR>
	Newspaper column that satirized plaintiff's business is nonactionable rhetorical hyperbole, and article that concerned plaintiff's purchase of hotel but did not name him is not libelous per se<P>

<EM>Hartman v. Associated Newspapers</EM>, 9 Media L. Rptr. 1699 (D. Minn. 1983)<BR>
	Complaint dismissed for failure to specify allegedly defamatory statements<P>

 <EM>Janklow v. Newsweek, Inc.</EM>, 788 F.2d 1300 (8th Cir. 1986) (for amici) <BR>
	Opinion privilege<P>

<EM>Milsap v. Milwaukee Journal Newspaper</EM>,  23 Media L.  Rptr. 1349 (D. Minn. 1994)<BR>
	Dismissing defamation claim for lack of personal jurisdiction<P>

<EM>Paisley v. The Minneapolis Star and Tribune Company</EM>, No. 790256 (Minn. Dist. Ct. 1985) <BR>
	Jury defense verdict based on substantial truth of article on National Guard company's
	treatment of "prisoner" in POW training exercise<P>

<EM>Patten v. Minneapolis Star Tribune</EM>, 21 Media L. Rptr. 1385 (Minn. Dist. Ct. 1992)<BR>
	Summary judgment based on substantial accuracy of newspaper articles<P>

<EM>Pelzer v. Minneapolis Star and Tribune Co.</EM>, 7 Media L. Rptr. 2507 (Minn Dist. Ct. 1981)<BR>
	Summary judgment for newspapers in libel action by county sheriff<P>

<EM>Pring v. Penthouse International Ltd.</EM>, 695 F.2d 438 (10th Cir. 1982), cert. denied,  462 U.S. 
	1132 (1983) <BR>
	Satirical portrayal of a contestant in Miss America pageant not actionable in libel, 
	invasion of privacy, or outrageous conduct <P>

<EM>Russell v. McMillen</EM>, 685 P.2d 255 (Colo. App. 1984) <BR>
	Summary judgment affirmed on constitutional malice and opinion issues<P>
 
<EM>Russell v. Turnbaugh</EM>, 18 Media L. Rptr. 2189 (D. Colo. 1991) <BR>
	Report by newspaper on its own copyright infringement litigation against competing 
	newspaper absolutely privileged as a report of judicial proceedings<P>

<EM>Schuster v. U.S. News & World Report, Inc.</EM>, 459 F.Supp. 973 (D. Minn. 1978),
	aff'd, 602 F.2d 850 (8th Cir. 1979) <BR>
	Group libel <P>

<EM>Sheftel v. Russell</EM>, 17 Media L. Rptr. 1252 (Colo. App. 1989) <BR>
	Political advertisement's use of terms mafia and gang to describe campaign efforts of plaintiffs and associates to mislead the voters is protected opinion<P>

<EM>Student v. The Denver Post Corporation</EM>, 23 Media L. Rptr. 2181 (Colo. Dist. Ct. 1995)<BR>
			Summary judgment on constitutional notice<P>

<EM>Swanton v. Ute City Tea Party Ltd.</EM>, 22 Media L. Rptr. 2560 (Colo. Dist. Ct. 1994) <BR>
	Newspaper article and headline were not defamatory and were fair report of public 
	proceeding; subsequent retraction is not relevant to determination of whether original 
	article was defamatory <P>

<EM>Torgerson v. Minneapolis Star & Tribune Co.</EM>, 7 Media L. Rptr. 1805 (Minn. Dist. Ct. 1981) <BR>
	Law school dean was public figure; court awarded attorneys fees to press<P>

<EM>Whitaker v. The Denver Post, Inc.</EM>, 4 Media L. Rptr. 1351 (D. Wyo. 1978) <BR>
	Summary judgment on public figure status and constitutional malice.  Wyoming lawyer's 
	past participation in Wyoming politics renders him public figure for purposes of 
	libel action based upon criminal activity<P>

<EM>Wild v. St. Paul Companies</EM>, 612 F.2d 341 (8th Cir. 1979) <BR>
	Defamation/civil rights claim<P>

<A NAME="privacy"></A><H3>Invasion of Privacy and Related Torts</H3>

<EM>Albertson v. Newton Daily News</EM>, 20 Med. L. Rpt. 1578 (S.D. Ia. 1992) <BR>
	§1983 defense<P>

<EM>Brooks v. KWGN of Colorado, Inc.</EM>,  773 P.2d 1098 (Colo. App. 1988) <BR>
	Intentional infliction of emotional distress<P>

<EM>Cramlet v. Multimedia (Phil Donahue Show)</EM>, 11 Media L. Rptr. 1707 (D. Colo. 1985)<BR> 
	Conspiracy, intentional infliction of emotional distress<P>
 
<EM>Gilbert v. Medical Economics Co.</EM>, 665 F.2d 305 (10th Cir. 1981) <BR>
	Magazine article concerning plaintiff's psychiatric history privileged because of its 
	plausible relationship to article's thesis of medical profession's inadequate self-policing<P>

<EM>Jones v. Palmer Communications</EM>, 440 N.W.2d 884 (Iowa 1989)<BR>
	Libel, privacy and related tort claims<P>

<EM>Rolfshus v. Time, Inc.</EM>, 5 Media L. Rptr. 1443 (Minn. Dist. Ct. 1979) <BR>
	Two-year defamation statute of limitations applied to bar claim for invasion of privacy, 
	although cause of action itself has never been recognized in state<P>

<EM>Sirany v. Cowles Media Co.</EM>, 20 Media L. Rptr. 1759 (Minn. Dist. Ct. 1992)<BR> 
	Successful defense against claims regarding alleged promise not to 
	publish obituary<P>
	
<A NAME="labor"></A><H3>Labor and Employment Law</H3>

<EM>Star Tribune (Machinists Union)</EM>, 93 LA 14 (1989)<BR> 
	Labor arbitration, including (1) the discharge of a union-represented editor for poor performance, (2) the discharge of three union-represented employees whose physical impairments limited their ability to perform their required duties, (3) the assignment of "new work" -- the make-up of advertisements using computers -- to union-represented employees, (4) the assignment to non-union employees of the delivery of a new publication, and (5) the failure to select a union steward for a lead position<P>

<EM>Star Tribune (Newspaper Guild)</EM>, 295 NLRB 543 (1989) <BR>
	Established that applicants for union-represented jobs could be tested for the use of unlawful substances, a case that was argued before the full National Labor Relations Board<P>

<EM>Star Tribune (Teamsters Union)</EM>, 100 LA 1106 (1993) <BR>
	Labor arbitration in which the arbitrator sustained the discharge of a union-represented truck driver for falsifying his federal Department of Transportation-required hours logbook.<P>

<EM>Stuempges v. Parke, Davis & Co.</EM>, 297 N.W.2d 252 (Minn. 1980)<BR> 
	Employment defamation issues<P>
	
<A NAME="intellectual"></A><H3>Intellectual Property and Entertainment</H3>

<EM>ASCAP Litigation:  e.g., Prophet Music Inc. v. Shamla Oil Co. Inc.</EM>, 26 U.S.P.Q.2d 1554 <BR>
	(D. Minn. 1993); <EM>Tempo Music, Inc. v. Christenson Food & Mercantile Co.</EM>, 806 F.Supp. 816 (D. Minn. 1992)
	Enforcing ASCAP members' copyrights in musical compositions in more than 100 
	federal cases in Minnesota<P>

<EM>Chavez v. Kravitz</EM>, No. 4-91-565 (D. Minn. 1992)<BR>
	Representation of international recording artist Lenny Kravitz in an action involving authorship rights to the song Justify My Love recorded by Madonna<P>

<EM>Columbia Pictures Industries, Inc. v. Golden Gate Video</EM>, No. 3-93-396 (D. Minn. 1993)<BR>
	Seizure of pirated videocassettes on behalf of members of The Motion Picture Association of America<P>

<EM>Columbia Pictures Industries, Inc. v. American Cablevision</EM>, No. 4-93-723 (D. Minn. 1993)<BR>
	Representation of members of The Motion Picture Association of America in their claims for interest on copyright payments from cable operators<P>

<EM>Dayton Hudson Corp. v. Rouillard</EM>, No. 94-019101 (Minn. Dist. Ct. 1994)<BR>
	Representation of retailer alleging trademark dilution by sexually-explicit magazine<P>

<EM>Learn PC v. Prentice-Hall</EM>, No. 3-94-1072 (D. Minn. 1994)<BR>
	Representation of distributor of computer training videos in breach of contract dispute<P>

<EM>MacPhail v. Colorado Capitol City Broadcasting Co.</EM>, 586P.2d 1339 (Colo. App. 1978)<BR>
	Summary judgement for defendant in trademark infringement and unfair competition action involving "Denver Magazine"	<P>

<EM>Microsoft Corp. v. Chung</EM>, No. 3-94-1087 (D. Minn. 1994)<BR>
	Seizure of pirated software from computer bulletin board<P>

<EM>Moore v. Columbia Pictures Industries, Inc.</EM>, 17 U.S.P.Q.2d 1226 (D. Minn. 1990) and 982 F.2d 939 (8th Cir. 1992)<BR>
	Representation of Columbia Pictures and MCA Records in a copyright infringement action involving the song On Our Own recorded by Bobby Brown as the title track to the motion pictures Ghostbusters II<P>

<EM>Nelson v. PRN Productions, Inc.</EM>, 873 F.2d 1141 (8th Cir. 1989)<BR>
	Representation of the musical artist formerly known as Prince in a copyright infringement action involving the song You Got the Look<P>

<EM>Ontrack Computers Systems, Inc. v. S & S International, Ltd.</EM>, No. 4-93-753 (D. Minn. 1994)<BR>
	Misappropriation of trade secrets claim pertaining to anti-virus software<P>

<EM>Paulsen v. LIVE Entertainment, Inc.</EM>, No. 4-91-542 (D. Minn. 1991)<BR>
	Defending entertainment company in breach of contract and securities litigation<P>

<EM>In re Target Stores' Complaint Regarding Wal-Mart's Deceptive National Advertising, 
	National Advertising Division</EM><BR>
	Claims involving deceptive national advertising slogan and in-store price comparisons<P>

<EM>Rockler v. G.C.R. Publishing, Inc.</EM>, No. 3-94-22 (D. Minn. 1994)<BR>
	Defending magazine publisher against claims of copyright infringement<P>

<EM>U.S.A. Hockey, Inc. v. North American In-Line Hockey Assn.</EM>,  (D. Minn. 1994)<BR>
	Representation of U.S. national governing body for hockey in trademark dispute with 
	in-line hockey association<P>

<EM>Ventura v. Titan Sports</EM>, No. 3-91-811 (D. Minn. 1994)<BR>
Representation of LJN Toys and Putnam Publishing in a right of publicity case<P>

<A NAME="taxation"></A><H3>Taxation</H3>

<EM>Catholic Archdiocese of Denver v. City & County of Denver</EM>, 741 P.2d 333 (Colo. 1987) <BR>
	City sales tax may not impose different burdens upon different forms of 
	newspaper distribution<P>

<EM>Des Moines Register & Tribune Co. v. Commission of Revenue</EM>, No. CL 53-31240 
	(Iowa Dist. Ct., Polk Cty, 1984) <BR>
	Successful action for refund of use taxes on newsprint and ink<P>

<EM>Minneapolis Star & Tribune v. Minnesota Commissioner of Revenue</EM>, 460 U.S. 575 (1983)<BR>
	Special use tax on newsprint and ink violated First Amendment <P>

<A NAME="restraint"></A><H3>Prior Restraint</H3>

<EM>Gardebring v. Cowles Media Co.</EM>, 16 Media L. Rptr. 1697 (Minn. Dist. Ct. 1989) <BR>
	Identities of deceased children and their families<P>

<EM>Marshall v. Egan</EM>, No. C1-94-013844 (Minn. Dist Ct. 1994)<BR>
	One-day trial; court denied plaintiff's request to use state "anti-stalking" statute to bar 
	television reporter from videotaping her or from asking her questions in public places<P>

<EM>Lambert v. Polk County</EM>, 723 F. Supp. 128 (S.D. Iowa 1989) <BR>
	Seizure of home video by law enforcement<P>

<A NAME="privilege"></A><H3>Reporter's Privilege</H3>

<EM>Aeguitron Medical Inc. v. CBS Inc.</EM>, 24 Media C. Rptr. 1025 (S.D.N.Y. 1995)<BR>
Qualified privilege for nonbroadcast information applied in civil action against news organization, but was overcome under particular circumstances.<P>
<EM>Artes Roy v. Aspen</EM>,  20 Media L. Rptr. 1647 (D. Colo. 1992) <BR>
	Subpoena quashed<P>

<EM>Bell v. City of Des Moines</EM>, 412 N.W. 585 (Iowa 1987) <BR>
	Reporter's privilege for videotape outtakes<P>

<EM>Denver Post Corp. v. Colorado Civil Rights Division</EM>, 22 Media L. Rptr. 2478 
	(Colo. Dist. Ct. 1994) <BR>
	Quashing civil rights agency's subpoena for name of advertiser, on statutory grounds<P>

<EM>Gagnan v. District Court</EM>, 632 P.2d 567 (Colo. 1981) (amicus curiæ) <BR>
	Reporter's privilege given limited recognition in Colorado<P>

<EM>Lamberto v. Bown</EM>, 326 N.W. 2d 305 (Iowa 1982) <BR>
	Reporter's subpoena<P>

<EM>Minnesota v. Ross</EM>, 22 Media L. Rptr. 2509 (Minn. Dist. Ct. 1994) <BR>
	Quashing subpoena to appear at criminal sentencing hearing<P>

<EM>Stanfield v. Polk County</EM>, 18 Media L. Rptr. 1262 (Iowa Dist. Ct. 1990) <BR>
	Subpoena of freelance journalist<P>

<A NAME="other"></A><H3>Other Litigation</H3>

<EM>Camellia City Telecasters, Inc. v. Tribune Broadcasting Co., Inc.</EM>, 762 F. Supp 290 
	(D. Colo. 1991)<BR>
	Summary judgement for defendants on claims of illegal tying of purchases of programming for Chicago and New York stations to purchases for Denver<P>

<EM>Cohen v. Cowles Media Company</EM>, 501 U.S. 663 (1991) <BR>
