<HEAD><TITLE>Faegre & Benson</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="index.gif"><P>
<P><P>
<h2>Pro Bono and Community Service</h2>

</CENTER>

<center><img width=420 src="archfile.gif" lowsrc="archfile.jpg">

</center>
<p>

Founded in Minneapolis in 1886, Faegre & Benson a firm of more than 275 lawyers in offices in
Minneapolis, Denver, Des Moines, Washington D.C., London, Frankfurt, and Almaty
(Kazakhstan).  Faegre & Benson represents both businesses and individuals in virtually all areas
of civil law.  Faegre & Benson provides comprehensive pro bono legal services, leadership and
financial support to numerous community service and charitable/non-profit organizations.
Faegre & Benson is participating in the ABA Law Firm Pro Bono Challenge.  Pro Bono Activities
(Limit of 10): Faegre & Benson's pro bono practice is largely driven by the interests of our
lawyers and can be categorized in several broad areas, as follows:
<p>
<font="+2"><b>LOW INCOME / POVERTY LAW PRACTICE</b></font>
<br>
Each of Faegre & Benson's offices provides significant pro bono representation to individuals
referred by Legal Aid and other legal services organizations in their respective communities.
Faegre & Benson lawyers also devote substantial time to volunteer leadership positions in these
organizations.  Some of Faegre & Benson's major projects include:
<br>

<b>Minnesota Indian Women's Resource Center (MIWRC) Pro Bono Legal Clinic.</b>  In March 1994 Faegre & Benson, in partnership with Volunteer Lawyers Network, established a
pro bono legal clinic in the heart of the urban Indian community in Minneapolis.  Faegre &
Benson draws upon a team of 35 specially-trained attorneys and legal assistants to staff
theMIWRC clinic every Wednesday and to provide legal or referral services in such areas as:
family law, housing, credit/debt and criminal law.
<br>


<b>VLN's Housing Court/Unlawful Detainer Clinic.</b>Faegre & Benson receives referrals from Volunteer Lawyers Network every other Friday to
provide low-income clients legal representation in Hennepin County Housing Court in unlawful
detainer or tenant remedy matters.
<br>


<b>Thursday Night Bar.</b>Faegre & Benson's Denver office is a participant in the Denver Bar Association's clinical program
for the disadvantaged.  Faegre & Benson's lawyers provide legal services in the areas of family
law, consumer law, housing and bankruptcy law.
<p>

<font="+2"><b>ENVIRONMENTAL PUBLIC INTEREST PRACTICE</b></font>
<br>
Faegre & Benson has a national reputation for its environmental pro bono practice.  Some
highlights areas follow:<p>

<ul>Argued a case before the U.S. Supreme Court (Lujan v. Defenders of Wildlife, 504 U.S. 555,119
L. Ed. 2d 351, 112 C. Ct. 2130 (1992)) challenging the Department of Interior which refused to
apply the Endangered Species Act to federal agency foreign aid projects.
<p>
Litigated several matters resulting in the preservation, maintenance or expansion of
national parks, wilderness and wildlife areas such as the Boundary Waters Canoe Area
Wilderness (northern Minnesota), the Frank Church River of No Return Wilderness area (central
Idaho), and Bighorn National Forest (north central Wyoming).
<p>
Litigated a matter to enforce the Endangered Species Act in connection with U.S. assistance to
the Three Gorges Dam Project in China.
<p>
Represented environmental groups in litigation which resulted in a ban on certain uses of
strychnine; litigated an endangered species act case which ended hunting season on a
threatened species in Minnesota; and litigated a case involving military overflight in a national
wilderness area.
</ul>

Faegre & Benson has provided a broad array of legal services on environmental issues as local,
regional and national counsel for the following groups:<p>

Izaak Walton League<br>
Wilderness Watch<br>
Voyagers National Park Assoc.<br>
Wilderness Society<br>
Friends of Animals & Their Environment<br>
Sierra Club<br>
Defenders of Wildlife<br>
Prairie Island Indian Community<br>
Nature Conservancy<br>
Humane Society of the U.S.<br>
Friends of the Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness
<p>

<font="+2"><b>CIVIL AND HUMAN RIGHTS PRACTICE</b></font>
<br>

Faegre & Benson provides a wide range of pro bono legal services to protect civil and human
rights in the U.S. and worldwide.  Faegre & Benson's efforts have been primarily through projects
with the Minnesota Advocates for Human Rights, including: the Refugee and Asylum Project and
the Death Penalty Project (habeas corpus cases).  Faegre & Benson has also provided civil
rights pro bono matters through the Individual Rights Foundation and the National Lawyers
Committee for Civil Rights Under Law.  Faegre & Benson provides representation for post-
conviction criminal appeals and/or assists pro se litigants through the Minnesota Public Defender
Program, the Federal Pro Bono Project, and the Federal Public Defender Program.
<p>

<font="+2"><b>TRANSACTIONAL PRO BONO PRACTICE</b></font>
<br>

Faegre & Benson's business lawyers provide pro bono legal services to a variety of transactional
pro bono projects in the areas of corporate law, trademark law, tax, trusts and estates, non-profit
and real estate law.  Some major projects or clients include:
<br>

<b>The White Earth Land Recovery Project.</b>Faegre & Benson is pro bono general counsel for this non-profit organization which seeks to
recover land for the White Earth Indian Reservation in northern Minnesota.  Faegre & Benson
has provided legal services in obtaining tax exemption, land acquisition, and preservation of
historic Indian burial sites.
<br>

<b>Metropolitan Economic Development Association.</b>  Faegre & Benson provides corporate probono legal services and leadership to MEDA, a non-profit organization providing assistance to minority-owned businesses in Minnesota.
<br>

<b>Milestone Growth Fund.</b>  Faegre & Benson has served as pro bono legal counsel for this specialized non-profit investment
company which seeks to provide needed capital investments to small business owned by socially
or economically disadvantaged persons.  Faegre & Benson provides legal services in all aspects
of structuring the investments, including negotiations and closing.
<br>

<b>American Refugee Committee.</b>  Faegre & Benson has provided general counsel legal services, including such areas as
corporate, securities and employment law, to ARC in its efforts to serve refugee populations
throughout the world.
<br>

<b>Charter Schools.</b>  Faegre & Benson represents several charter schools and one servicing organization in issues of
non-profit governance, contracts, employment law and constitutional issues.
<p>

<font="+2"><b>PRO BONO OPPORTUNITIES FOR SUMMER ASSOCIATES</b></font>
<br>

<b>Summer Associate Program</b>  Faegre & Benson pairs its summer associates with our attorneys who supervise the associates
under the Minnesota Student Practice Rule.  Summer associates staff a Volunteer Lawyers
Network clinic site and interview potential pro bono clients with poverty law issues.
<br>

<b>Pro Bono Summer Internships</b>  Sierra Club/Faegre & Benson Environmental Law Fellowship provides law students with
anopportunity to devote a summer to public interest environmental litigation. Typical intern
projects have included litigation over wolf hunting in Minnesota, grizzly bear management in the
Northern Rockies, and protection of the Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness.<br>

John C. Benson Pro Bono Internship provides law students with an opportunity to devote a
summer to public interest and pro bono legal matters, with a focus on the delivery of legal
services to the poor and human/civil rights matters.
<p>
<font="+2"><b>SPECIAL RECOGNITION/AWARDS</b></font>
<BR>

<b>Minnesota Advocates for Human Rights, 1994 Volunteer Award.</b>  To James Volling of the Minneapolis office in recognition of his exceptional work in the Death Penalty Project, including representation of habeas corpus appeals for death-row inmates; providing training of other lawyers in habeas matters; and providing advice to foreign lawyers on death penalty laws in their own countries.


<b>Minnesota Advocates for Human Rights, 1994 Volunteer Award.</b>  Legal Assistant Sheryl Fried of the Minneapolis office was recognized in a shared award for her
significant work in the collection of information to assist in prosecuting war crimes committed in the former Yugoslavia.
<br>

<b>Colorado Lawyers Committee 1993 Individuals of the Year.</b>  To Michael Cook and Catherine Lemon of the Denver office for their work as co-chairs of the
Colorado Lawyers Committee Foster Care Task Force.  Cook and Lemon were recognized for expert skills and tireless efforts to bring about fundamental change in Colorado's child welfare
system to improve protection of foster children and expansion of their rights.
<br>

<b>Metropolitan Economic Development Association, 1992 Volunteer of the Year Award.</b>  To Walter Pickhardt of the Minneapolis office for his outstanding contribution to the success of
small, minority-owned businesses in providing legal advice to MEDA clients, particularly in the area of corporate tax matters.
<br>

<b>Minnesota Advocates for Human Rights, 1992 Volunteer Award.</b>  To John Mandler of the Minneapolis office in recognition of:  his legal research and study of
habeas corpus reforms in Argentina; drafting briefing papers for the United Nations on several
legal concerns relating to the Draft Declaration on Disappearances; and preparation of legal
briefs in relation to human rights and international extradition laws.
<br>

<b>Minnesota Advocates for Human Rights, 1991 Volunteer Award.</b>  To Duane Krohnke of theMinneapolis office in recognition of his commitment and pro bono work
with the Committee's Refugee and Asylum Project.  Krohnke has represented Salvadoran and
Afghani clients in asylum matters, has provided training for asylum attorneys, and provides
expert counsel regarding immigration law and policy.
<br>

<b>National Sierra Club, William O. Douglas Award, and Sierra Club, Northstar Chapter
Environmentalist of the Year Award, 1985.</b>  To Brian O'Neill of the Minneapolis office in recognition of outstanding contributions of pro bono
legal services in matters relating to the environment, including litigation regarding the protection
of the Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness in Minnesota.
<p>

<font="+2"><b>Information</b></font>
<br>
Contact Faegre & Benson at 1-800-328-4393 or e-mail our Pro Bono Coordinator<A HREF="mailto:jboderma@faegre.com">Jodie Boderman</A> for a brochure or more details.
<p>

