<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> 1997 Intellectual Property Invitation - Plain Text</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<p align=center>
<FONT SIZE=+2>F</FONT>AEGRE & <FONT SIZE=+2>B</FONT>ENSON <FONT  SIZE=-1>LLP</FONT>
</p>


<p align=center>
cordially invites you to an all day seminar on issues
<br>

relating to Intellectual Property
</p>

<p align=center>
<FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>Intellectual Property <EM>1997</EM></STRONG></FONT>
</p>

<blockquote>
Thursday, March 6, 1997
<br>
Minneapolis Hilton and Towers
<br>
Minneapolis, Minnesota
<p>

<STRONG>Keynote Luncheon Speaker:</STRONG>
<br>

Hubert H. (Skip) Humphrey III
<br>

<EM>Attorney General</EM>
<br>

State of Minnesota
<p>


<STRONG>Continuing Education</STRONG>
<br>
Minnesota Continuing Legal Education credits have been requested.
<p>

<STRONG>Registration</STRONG>
<br>
The fee for the seminar is $55 per person.  Lunch is provided; a complimentary reception follows the program. A booklet of informational materials will be provided at the door.
<p>
To register, please contact <A HREF="mailto:apeterso@faegre.com">Amy Petersen</A> at 612/336-3969 or 800/328-4393. 
<br>
<hr>
<p align=center>

Intellectual Property
<br>

SEMINAR TENTATIVE SCHEDULE
<br>

March 6, 1997
</p>

<FONT  size=+1><B>8:00 a.m. - 8:30 a.m.</B></FONT>
<br>


<STRONG>Hilton Third Floor, Lobby</STRONG> - <EM>Registration and Continental</EM> Breakfast

<p>

<FONT  size=+1><B>8:30 a.m. - 9:00 a.m.</B></FONT>
<br>

<STRONG>Hilton Ballroom</STRONG> - <EM>Opening Session</EM>

<p>

<FONT  size=+1><B>9:15 a.m. - 10:30 a.m.</B></FONT>
<br>

<STRONG>Salon A</STRONG> - <EM>Recent Developments on the Internet</EM>
<br>
The rapid growth of the Internet as a means for communicating information and transacting business has forced courts to apply traditional principles of law to cyberspace.  This session will examine recent developments in the law relating to the Internet, including personal jurisdiction, domain name disputes, junk e-mail, trademarks on the Internet, and the E-Data patent.
<P>


<STRONG>Salon E</STRONG> - <EM>Nuts & Bolts of Patents and Trade Secrets</EM>
<br>

<STRONG>Trade Secrets:</STRONG>  The trade secret segment of our presentation identifies the basic parameters of trade secret law and distinguishes trade secrets from other methods of protecting intellectual property.  We then describe the elements of a trade secret protection program.  We conclude by explaining how to protect trade secrets during employee transition.
<br>

<STRONG>Patents:</STRONG>  The patent segment of our presentation will describe the practical aspects of patent law so that the business person can better incorporate patenting strategies into competitive business planning.  We first explain how to recognize and protect patentable inventions so that valuable patent rights are not inadvertently lost.  We then explain how patent rights can be used to help meet specific business objectives.  We conclude by providing an overview of patent enforcement procedures.
<p>

<STRONG>Duluth Room</STRONG> - <EM>Litigating Patent Cases After Markman
</EM>
<br>

The <EM>Markman</EM> decision could potentially revolutionalize the jury trial system for patent cases.  This session highlights the various arguments made by each side of the debate.
<p>
 
<FONT  size=+1><B>10:45 a.m.  - 12:00 p.m.</B></FONT>
<br>
		
<STRONG>Salon A</STRONG> - <EM>Selling Online</EM>
<br>
Because of the vast marketing and communications potential associated with the use of the Internet and online services, many companies are building web sites and selling their goods and services online.  This session will explore issues associated with sales of goods and services in online environment.  In particular, we will discuss a number of the legal concerns associated with selling retail goods over the Internet, such as the implications of accepting credit card orders, gathering and using data about clients and prospective clients for marketing purposes, enforcing licenses for software distributed under webwrap agreements, and selecting and enforcing appropriate warranties and limitations on liability.
<p>

<STRONG>Salon E</STRONG> - <EM>Nuts & Bolts of Trademarks and Copyrights</EM>
<br>

Trademarks and copyrights can be amongst the most valuable of a business' assets.  This session will provide an overview of the law that protects these assets, with an emphasis on what business people and business lawyers need to know to maximize the value of their business' rights.  Trademark topics covered will include selection and availability of a mark, federal registration procedure, proper use of a mark, and the remedies available for trademark infringement.  Copyright topics covered will include copyrightable subject matter, copyright ownership and works for hire, copyright notice and registration, and the scope of copyright protection. 
<p>

<STRONG>Duluth Room </STRONG>- <EM>Protecting Intellectual Property in Business Transactions</EM>
<br>

This seminar will provide an overview of strategies for protecting and maximizing the value of intellectual property in the course of mergers and acquisitions, financings, licensing, partnering and joint ventures as well as in relationships with employees, customers, suppliers and other business partners.  The focus will be on recurring issues such as representations and warranties, due diligence, confidentiality agreements, noncompete agreements and ownership and control of intellectual property.
<p>



<FONT  size=+1><B>12:00 p.m. -1:30 p.m. - Lunch</B></FONT>
<br>

<STRONG>Ballroom</STRONG> - <EM>Keynote Speaker Hubert H. (Skip) Humphrey III</EM>
<p>

<FONT  size=+1><B>1:30 p.m. - 2:20 p.m.</B></FONT>
<br>

<STRONG>Salon A</STRONG> - <EM>Censorship on the Internet</EM>
<br>


As use of the Internet proliferates, conflicts are arising over appropriate regulation of the content of cyberspace communications.  Congress enacted the Communications Decency Act, but a court declared it unconstitutional.  An electronic bulletin board operator in California was convicted in federal court in Memphis, Tennessee, on criminal charges.  Law enforcement authorities in Germany threatened prosecution of CompuServe, an Ohio-based company, for the content of material available through CompuServes network.  In light of such developments, this seminar will provide an overview of issues related to Internet content regulation, including such issues as the First Amendment, jurisdiction, choice of law, defamation and privacy.
<p>

<STRONG>Salon E</STRONG> - <EM>Recent Developments - Patents</EM>
<br>

Significant new developments occurred in many areas of patent law in 1996.  These developments involved not only substantive changes in the law, but also several issues of first impression appearing in Federal Circuit decisions throughout the year. Several Federal Circuit decisions also interpreted the insubstantial differences test for determining infringement under the doctrine of equivalents, which was a test announced by the Federal Circuit in the important Hilton-Davis decision.  Meanwhile, the Hilton-Davis case itself is on appeal to the United States Supreme Court, which could render its decision at anytime now.  The patent bar eagerly awaits the Supreme Court decision to see how it will affect the test for determining infringement under the doctrine of equivalents.  A number of unusual district court decisions also appeared, which could be the harbinger of even more change in the patent laws in the event that such lower court decisions were to be upheld by the Federal Circuit on appeal. This session will provide an overview of these recent developments, so that patent attorneys and business persons alike can more fully appreciate how these developments might affect how patents can and cannot be used to support strategic business planning and meet specific business objectives.

<p>

<STRONG>Duluth Room</STRONG> - <EM>Insurance Issues in Intellectual Property Litigation</EM>
<br>

Insurance coverage for intellectual property disputes is an important consideration for litigants.  Cases that have held for both the insured and the insurer regarding the duty to defend and indemnify will be discussed, along with a brief outline of the procedural steps to be taken by insureds and insurers in the process of determining the applicability of insurance coverage.
<p>

<FONT  size=+1><B>2:30 p.m. - 3:20 p.m.</B></FONT>
<br>

<STRONG>Salon A</STRONG> - <EM>Spiders on the Web:  Avoiding Liability in the Use of the Internet</EM>
<br>

Use of the Internet may involve legal risks including claims for copyright infringement, libel and slander, harassment, trade secret misappropriation, and trademark infringement.  This presentation will focus on practical suggestions for businesses using the Internet or allowing employees access to the Internet.  Specific topics to be covered will include electronic mail policies, domain name selection, web page content, use of hyperlinks, and the development of bulletin boards.
<p>

<STRONG>Salon E</STRONG> - <EM>Recent Developments - Copyright Law</EM>
<br>

This session will explore recent developments in the law of copyrights, including recent legislation and international agreements.  The presentation will include discussion of the issue as raised in a recent Fifth Circuit case <EM>Chavez v. Arte Publico Press</EM>, 59 F.3d 539 (5th Cir. 1995).  The case is still pending reconsideration after remand from the U.S. Supreme Court subsequent to its decision in <EM>Seminole Tribe of Florida v. Florida</EM>, 517 U.S. ___, 116 S.Ct. ____, 134 L.Ed. 252 (1996), which limited Congress ability to abrogate states Eleventh Amendment sovereign immunity.  The presentation will provide background regarding why Congress cannot generally abrogate a states sovereign immunity and the limited circumstances under which it can.  It will also include a discussion of how a state might waive its immunity.  Finally, the presentation will discuss practical steps a client dealing with the state can take to protect himself or herself should the courts decide that a state may exercise their eleventh amendment sovereign immunity against copyright infringement suits brought in federal court.
<p>

<STRONG>Duluth Room</STRONG> - <EM>Changing Prescriptions for Intellectual Property in Medical Technology</EM>
<br>

Intellectual property laws of great importance to the medical technology industry are in a state of transition.  Congress recently enacted legislation which limits the remedies available against infringers of patented medical and surgical procedures.  District and Federal Circuit court decisions reflect a trend away from broad claim constructions and hostility toward the Doctrine of Equivalents as we await the Supreme Courts <EM>Hilton Davis</EM> decision.  Contracts for the acquisition and licensing of intellectual property rights continue to be critical to the successful commercialization of medical technology, and are therefore frequent topics of dispute.  In the future, the diagnosis and treatment of intellectual property issues in the medical technology field will clearly be enhanced by greater up-front focus on the patent application process and forward-thinking contract drafting.  This seminar session will describe these developments and address their impact on medical technology companies.
<p>
		
 
<FONT  size=+1><B>3:30 p.m. - 4:20 p.m.</B></FONT>
<br>

<STRONG>Salon A</STRONG> - <EM>Next Generation Internet Legal Issues</EM>
<br>

While virtually all Internet law is new, this session will explore several upcoming issues which are on the back burner but which could impact you over the next few years.
<p>

<STRONG>Salon E</STRONG> - <EM>Recent Developments - Trademarks</EM>
<br>
This session presents our annual review of recent developments in the always-entertaining world of trademarks and trade dress.  This year's session will address, among other topics, the developing case law interpreting the year-old Federal Trademark Dilution Act, the Warnervision opinions and their impact on intent-to-use applications, recent attempts to register sound marks, and the year's legislative developments.  The session will close with Felicia Boyd's traditional pronouncement of the Best (and Worst) of 1996, a fast-paced and energetic review of the silly and the sublime from the trademark and trade dress opinions of 1996.
<p>


<strong>Duluth Room</strong> - <EM>Intellectual Property in Transactions with the Government and Compliance with Government Export Controls</EM>
<br>
Transactions with the Federal Government can take various forms, including supply contracts, service contracts, software development contracts, Cooperative Research and Development Agreements (CRADAs), and others.  In addition, companies engaged in the licensing or sale of intellectual property to foreign parties often fail to recognize that such transactions are subject to U.S. export control laws which can expose such companies to severe potential consequences if the laws are violated.  This presentation will discuss methods for protecting your intellectual property in government transactions and maximizing your rights in intellectual property resulting from such transactions.  The discussion will include recent developments under the Freedom of Information Act, Department of Defense software and technical data regulations, the impact of new commercial item acquisition procedures, and remedies for the governments violation of intellectual property rights.  An introduction to the scope and framework of U.S. export laws will be presented together with an update on recent developments in export controls on encryption software.
<p>
<FONT  size=+1><B>4:20 p.m. -5:30 p.m.</B></FONT>
<br>

<STRONG>Ballroom</STRONG> - <EM>Reception</EM>
<p>
<hr>
<i><font size=-1>
Copyright &copy; 1997 Faegre &amp; Benson LLP, all rights reserved.<p></i>
</font>

</BODY>
