<IMG SRC="intel3.gif"><P>
<H2>Bankruptcy/Insolvency Litigation</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>

<blockquote>
Recent years have seen a dramatic increase in bankruptcy-related litigation.  Fraudulent conveyances, preferences, contract assumption/rejection issues, claim objections, objections to discharge, intellectual property issues, environmental problems, commercial disputes, and lender liability issues are only a few of the subject areas encountered in bankruptcy litigation.
<P>

Faegre & Benson lawyers have substantial experience and capability in all areas of bankruptcy and related litigation.  In large complex bankruptcies of publicly held corporations, in smaller reorganizations, and in complex cases involving individuals and partnerships, our firm brings experience, skill, and strength to representation of clients interest.  Although most bankruptcy and insolvency matters are best resolved through effective negotiation, when necessary, our lawyers have pursued litigation remedies.  Faegre & Benson lawyers pursued to the United States Supreme Court and won the leading case recognizing rights of unsecured creditors to prevent equity holders from retaining ownership of a reorganized enterprise over the objections of unpaid unsecured creditors.  That case, <EM>Norwest Bank Worthington v. Ahlers</EM>, 485 U.S. 197 (1988), endorsed application of the "Absolute Priority Rule" in bankruptcy which provides unsecured creditors their strongest leverage for preventing confirmation of plans of reorganization unfair to the interests of creditors.
<P>

Other major bankruptcy appellate litigation by Faegre & Benson lawyers has included decisions involving successful challenges to abusive bankruptcy planning, and challenges to open-ended debtor exemption statutes.  In bankruptcy litigation matters, our firm has represented secured creditors, indenture trustees, unsecured creditors, lessors, committees, shareholders, intellectual property holders, and debtors. 
<P>

Effective representation of clients in bankruptcy and insolvency matters frequently requires more than bankruptcy expertise.  The breadth and strength of the law firm enables our bankruptcy litigators to draw upon experience in numerous complex legal areas which may arise.  Our lawyers experience in tax, real estate, leasing, mergers and acquisitions, shareholder and officer/director litigation, lender and professional liability litigation, antitrust and trade regulation, securities, employee benefits and ERISA matters, labor, environmental claims and liabilities, intellectual property, banking, securitization, international matters, construction, insurance, governmental relations, and other areas, enables our bankruptcy/insolvency litigators to draw upon virtually any area of legal expertise as the need may arise in litigation.
<P>

Effective bankruptcy litigation demands a blended expertise. Our experience in bankruptcy/insolvency matters is not limited to particular types of clients, and our experience in representing diverse interests gives our lawyers judgment and insight in addressing the complex mix of competing interests in bankruptcy matters. For example, our experience in representing debtors and unsecured creditors is helpful in representing secured creditors in bankruptcy matters.  Our experience in representing secured creditors is likewise helpful in representing unsecured creditors, shareholders, committees, insurers, and debtors.  For example, our banking and secured lender experience enables us to scrutinize claims and conduct of secured creditors asserting priority over claims of unsecured creditors, and provides insight into what is feasible in negotiations with secured creditors.  Our lawyers representation of debtors in several major Chapter 11 cases (Frontier Airlines and America West Airlines, for example) similarly provides insight from the debtors side of the table in plan negotiation and other aspects of bankruptcy reorganization.
<P>

Many disputes, of course, are best resolved through effective negotiation, not litigation.  Alternative dispute resolution can be a useful tool, and we have experience in all types of alternative dispute resolutions, but effective representation in this area is enhanced by lawyers ability and willingness to litigate when the need arises.
<P>

The experience of Faegre & Benson lawyers in non-bankruptcy litigation is an important resource.  Faegre & Benson lawyers were lead trial counsel for Alaska fishermen and other business interests in the <EM>Exxon Valdez</EM> litigation, and obtained a highly-publicized verdict of over $5.237 billion in damages.  Defense accomplishments tend to have a lower profile, but our lawyers have an impressive track record in this area as well.  "High-tech" capabilities in litigation matters can be important, and we have the experience and litigation support services to utilize the resources.  Most cases, of course, do not require such a level of investment, but, if necessary, our bankruptcy litigators can draw upon such resources.
<P>

Our domestic offices are located in Minneapolis, Denver, and Des Moines, and our contacts with local counsel throughout the country permit us to provide clients with effective representation in significant bankruptcy matters wherever they may arise.  Our extensive use of computer technology and communications, and the firms dedication to lean staffing, permit us  to provide cost-effective representation on a national basis.
<P>

Major bankruptcy litigation representations by Faegre & Benson lawyers have included the following:

<UL>
<LI><EM>Norwest Bank Worthington v. Ahlers</EM> (obtained reversal in U.S. Supreme Court endorsing application of Absolute Priority Rule in bankruptcy)
<P>
<LI>Centran Corporation (committee representation involving 114 adversary proceedings and numerous contested claim objections, resulting in recoveries to estate of over $5 million)
<P>
<LI>Citi-Equity Group, Inc. (represent operating trustee in complex bankruptcy involving over $100 million in assets and claims subject to litigation)
<P>
<LI>T. G. Morgan, Inc. (trustee representation involving over 100 adversary proceedings, resulting in recoveries to estate of over $2 million)
<P>
<LI><EM>In re Apex Oil Co.</EM> (litigation of plan confirmation to protect rights of class of 850 claimants)
<P>
<LI><EM>In re Frontier Airlines, Inc.</EM> (litigated rights over funding and distribution of three defined benefit plans resulting in over $15 million to estatehandled all litigation necessary to resolve over 5,000 trade claims amounting to $750 million)
<P>
<LI><EM>In re Continental Airlines, Inc.</EM> (oversaw litigation and resolution of unsecured and priority tax and administrative claims against the estate totalling in the billions of dollars as well as handling other litigation, including successful turnover and contempt proceedings against major creditor involving $5 million in cash, successful defense of actions regarding various bond issues, and defeating U.S. claim of offset, preserving $5.0 million for the estatenow on appeal)
<P>
<LI><EM>In re Monus</EM> (defended fraudulent conveyance attack on sale of National League baseball franchise)
<P>
<LI><EM>In re Peoples Bankshares, Ltd.</EM> (shareholder representation in complex bankruptcy and related litigation involving an Iowa bank holding company; obtained cash recoveries of over $1.2 million for clients).
<P>
<LI><EM>In re National Cattle Congress, Inc.</EM> (represented purchaser of foreclosed real estate in complex bankruptcy of Iowa racing and gaming operation; successful litigation of "cram-down" and valuation issues resulted in gain of over $1.6 million for client under confirmed plan of reorganization).
<P>
<LI>Baldwin United Corporation (represented numerous securities dealers in claims for contribution in complex bankruptcy, resulting in settlements in excess of $20 million for clients)
<P>
<LI>Olympia Holdings P*I*E Nationwide (represented several defendants in rate undercharge claims)
<P>
<LI>Frederick & Nelson Department Stores (represented Dayton-Hudson Corporation in disputes over entitlement to intellectual property interests)
<P>
<LI>Endotronics, Inc. (represented inventors of cell research technology in patent dispute with debtor)
<P>
</UL>

Bankruptcy "planning" cases  successfully represented creditors in several appellate cases involving objections to abusive bankruptcy planning.


