<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000"><BASEFONT SIZE=3>
<CENTER>

<IMG SRC="intel3.gif"><P>
<H2>Bankrupcty Committee 
Representation

</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>

<blockquote>
Faegre & Benson has substantial experience and capability in all areas of corporate bankruptcy reorganization and litigation.  In both large complex bankruptcies of publicly held corporations and in smaller reorganizations, our firm brings experience, skill, and strength to representation of creditors interests.
<P>

Faegre & Benson lawyers pursued to the United States Supreme Court and won the leading case recognizing rights of unsecured creditors to prevent equity holders from retaining ownership of a reorganized enterprise over the objections of unpaid unsecured creditors.  That case, <EM>Norwest Bank Worthington v. Ahlers</EM>, 485 U.S. 197 (1988) endorsed application of the "Absolute Priority Rule" in bankruptcy which provides unsecured creditors their strongest leverage for preventing confirmation of plans of reorganization unfair to the interests of unsecured creditors.
<P>

The breadth and strength of the law firm enables our bankruptcy lawyers to draw upon diverse experience and expertise in the many complex legal areas which may arise in a Chapter 11 case.  For example, our banking and secured lender experience enables us to scrutinize claims and conduct of secured creditors asserting priority over claims of unsecured creditors.  Our experience with banks and other financial institutions provides insight into what is feasible in negotiations with secured creditors.  Our lawyers representation of debtors in several major Chapter 11 cases (Continental Airlines and America West Airlines, for example) similarly provides insight from the debtors side of the table in plan negotiation and other aspects of bankruptcy reorganization.
<P>

Effective representation of creditors committees frequently  requires more than bankruptcy expertise.  Our firms experience in tax law, real estate, leasing, mergers and acquisitions, shareholder and officer/director litigation, lender and professional liability litigation, employee benefits and ERISA matters, labor environmental claims and liabilities, intellectual property,  banking, construction, insurance, international matters, and other areas, enables our bankruptcy lawyers to draw upon virtually any area of legal expertise as the need may arise in complex bankruptcy proceedings.
<P>
 
Faegre & Benson lawyers have represented unsecured creditors committees in several major bankruptcy cases, including:
<P>
<blockquote>

<STRONG>Colorado Ute Electric Association, Inc.</STRONG>, a generating and transmission system supplying bulk power to over 70% of the state of Colorado filed Chapter 11 on March 30, 1990.  A plan of reorganization that will in all probability pay creditors in full was confirmed in February 1992.
<P>

<STRONG>MiniScribe Corporation</STRONG>, a Chapter 11 case of a large disk-drive manufacturer filed in January 1990, in which a sale of the assets was achieved and recovery through litigation is being sought against former management and others.
<P>

<STRONG>Kaiser Steel Corporation</STRONG>, filed Chapter 11 in February 1986 and confirmed a plan in September 1988.  Representation of the Retired Employees Subcommittee resulted in some 7500 retired employees obtaining the majority stock position in the reorganized company through a trust which funds the health care needs of the retirees.
<P>

<STRONG>Centran Corporation</STRONG>, a Chapter 11 case of a natural gas marketing company filed in January, 1993, in which a sale of the debtor's assets was achieved and, as a result of the sale and approximately 100 preference actions, unsecured creditors recovered more than half of their claims.
<P>

<STRONG>Hawaiian Airlines, Inc.</STRONG>, a Chapter 11 case in which a complex and comprehensive set of long-term agreements with American Airlines allowed this regional and international carrier to successfully emerge from reorganization in September, 1994.
<P>

<STRONG>Ruhr/Paragon, Incorporated</STRONG>, a Chapter 11 case of an advertising agency filed in March, 1995, in which a sale of the debtor's assets and confirmation of a liquidating plan resulted in unsecured creditors recovering approximately 80% of their claims.
<P>

</blockquote>

We have also represented bondholder committees or indenture trustees in several major bankruptcy cases, including:

<UL>
<LI>Gillet HoldingsIndenture Trustee for $550,000,000 in zero coupon notes.
<LI>Interco IncorporatedIndenture Trustee for $387,000,000 of subordinated discount debentures.
<LI>Reserve Mining Company (LTV)Indenture Trustee for $200,000,000 of pollution control revenue bonds.
<LI>American Continental CorporationIndenture Trustee for $50,000,000 of senior debentures.
<LI>G. Heileman Brewing CompanyIndenture Trustee for $35,000,000 of secured debentures.
</UL>


Representation of unsecured creditors committees in bankruptcy is difficult, and somewhat risky for lawyers.  Because legal fees and expenses of committees generally are paid from the bankruptcy estate, not by particular creditors, lawyers for committees bear the risk that fees may not be paid if the debtors bankruptcy estate has insufficient unencumbered assets to pay administrative expenses.  Also, fees are paid only to the extent approved by the Court, after scrutiny and opportunity for objection by interested parties and the United States Trustee.  Our firms philosophy is to staff all matters in a lean and efficient manner, and our rates generally are competitive with or lower than those of most law firms of our size.  In committee representation, even though our fees are not the obligation of particular creditors, we adhere to that philosophy, and view committee representation as an opportunity not only to provide professional representation in bankruptcy, but also, through effective representation,  to develop lasting professional relationships with creditors. We thus have an incentive to perform an excellent service at a reasonable price.


</blockquote>
