<HEAD>
<TITLE> A Victory Over Soreheads </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>A Victory Over Soreheads</H2>

<H4>By</H4>

<H4>Robert L. Schnell, Jr. and Jeffrey D. Hedlund</H4>

<FONT SIZE=+2>L</FONT>ast month the United States Supreme Court handed down its decision in Gustafson v. Alloyd Co., Inc., ruling 5-4 that buyers of securities were not entitled to pursue the liberal remedies the Securities Act of 1933 gives to victims of "prospectus" fraud unless those victims were actually cheated by the use of a "prospectus."  Although such a result seems so obvious as to be unworthy of the time of the Supreme Court, the case provoked two vigorous dissents and was widely and negatively reported as limiting protections for stock buyers.  The real story behind the decision, however, is its illustration of the mounting threat posed by, what Garrison Keillor recently described in The New York Times as, a "nation of soreheads" who seek to blame others and refuse to accept responsibility for the consequences of their own conduct.<P>

The facts of Gustafson are quite straightforward: plaintiffs negotiated to buy the stock of a private company, protecting themselves with the usual array of contractual protections, representations and warranties.  Unfortunately for the buyers, however, an audit of the company after the sale showed that the company was making less money than expected.  The buyers had available all the tools in their contractual arsenal, but they had not negotiated for a provision letting them walk away from the deal if the company's profits were not as expected.<P>

The buyers attempted to remedy that defect by employing section 12(2) of the Securities Act of 1933, a provision with powerful remedies for buyers of securities who are defrauded in their purchase of a security "by means of a prospectus or oral
communication."  Section 12(2) gives successful plaintiffs the option of rescinding the transaction, and does not require the proof of intent to defraud on the part of the defendant or of actual reliance on the part of the buyer.  Rather, section 12(2) is in some ways a strict liability provision for sellers of securities, making those who make misstatements liable unless they can prove that they did not know, and in the exercise of reasonable diligence could not have known, of the falsity of their statement.  In this age where we have all become accustomed to playing "Monday morning quarterback" without the slightest hesitation, proving the "could not have known" part of the defense standard is properly regarded as a long-shot in the best of cases.<P>

However, the buyers in Gustafson faced one major hurdle to employing the remedies of section 12(2) -- the transaction employed no document that looked anything like a "prospectus." Anyone who has ever been asked to buy stock on a public offering has probably seen a prospectus.  It has a distinctive appearance, is filled with detailed disclosures of financial and business information, contains extensive disclaimer and cautionary language in most cases, and is prepared with heavy lawyer and accounting involvement.<P>

In a private sale transaction like that involved in Gustafson, there is no "prospectus" in the ordinary sense.  In fact, the typical private sale transaction involves an extensive due diligence investigation by the potential buyer, and aggressive, arm's length negotiations.  That situation is a world apart from the offering of stock on preestablished terms to faceless buyers whose only investigation is limited by practical circumstances to a review of a document furnished by the promoters of the investment.  The facts in Gustafson fit the typical private sale mold -- extensive due diligence leading to a detailed, heavily negotiated stock purchase agreement.<P>

Lacking a prospectus in the normal sense, the Gustafson plaintiffs seized on the definitional section of the Securities Act in an attempt to perform the magic of turning a document created to memorialize arm's length negotiations -- the stock purchase agreement -- into the legal equivalent of a document generated to inform those who must rely on someone else to gather information -- the prospectus.  Under the admittedly creative theory advanced by the Gustafson plaintiffs, a "prospectus" could be any written communication, even a note on a cocktail napkin from your broker at lunch.<P>

Although the Gustafson case arose from a private stock transaction, it raised issues extending far beyond that context, for brokers routinely send out research reports or other written communications about stocks to their actual or potential customers.  If those are all considered a "prospectus", and subject brokers to the sort of strict liability the Securities Act establishes, then brokers would become targets virtually any time a stock on which they have written anything experiences a market decline.<P>

One obvious negative consequence of that broad approach is the chilling effect it would have on the transmission of information about securities.  The capital formation process in the United States is correctly regarded as the most efficient and successful in the world in large measure because of the quantity and quality of its information flows.  Were analysts and others in the information chain subjected to strict Securities Act liabilities, they -- like journalists without the protection of the Supreme Court's "actual malice" standard -- would think at least twice before circulating information that had not been subjected to the rigors of the prospectus drafting process.  The imposition of Securities Act liabilities on such activities would simply price most routine research out of the market, to the disadvantage of our capital markets and investors.<P>

By the narrowest of margins, the Supreme Court reached the sensible result by holding that the term "prospectus" is a term of art referring to the commonly seen booklet of information about a newly offered stock, and does not mean just any writing.  Even the dissenters agreed that good public policy supported the majority.<P>

If you think about it, the case shouldn't have been that hard.  Why should the language of the Securities Act be tortured to help a large, sophisticated buyer of a business who had ample ability to protect itself and just failed to do an adequate job?  Why shouldn't such a buyer be required to bargain for the contractual protections it desires and be foreclosed from seeking to rewrite the contract under the Securities Act after the fact?  As Keillor advised his nation of soreheads, the government "can't come to your home and blow your nose.  You have to do that yourself, my dear."  Fortunately, at least this time, the Supreme Court agreed.<P>

Robert L. Schnell, Jr. and Jeffrey D. Hedlund are attorneys with Faegre & Benson in Minneapolis and filed an amicus curiae brief with the U.S. Supreme Court in the Gustafson case.  If you have any questions, please contact Robert by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:rschnell@faegre.com"><EM>rschnell@faegre.com</EM></A> or Jeffrey by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:jhedlund@faegre.com"><EM>jhedlund@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

<HR>

Last changed 19-Dec-95<p>

