<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Education Department Issues Guidance on Peer Sexual
Harassment Policies </title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>
<h2>Education Department Issues Guidance on Peer Sexual
Harassment Policies</H2>

<FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>s we reported in our last Issue Update, in two recent decisions, United States Circuit Courts of Appeal reached contrary conclusions regarding a schools liability for student-to-student sexual harassment under Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972.  Compare <EM>Davis v. Monroe County Board of Education</EM>, 74 F.3d 1186 (11th Cir. 1996), with <EM>Rowinsky v. Bryan Independent School District</EM>, 80 F.3d 1006 (5th Cir. 1996).
<P>

In response to the controversy created by these decisions, the Office for Civil Rights of the U.S. Department of Education (OCR), the agency responsible for enforcing Title IX, issued draft policy guidelines to advise educational institutions of the standards OCR will use in investigating and resolving hostile environment claims based on peer sexual harassment.
<P>

Liability of educational institution for peer sexual harassment.  According to OCR, a school is not necessarily responsible under Title IX for the actions of the harassing student.  A school may be liable if:
<OL>
<LI>a hostile environment exists;
<LI>the school has notice of the harassment; and
<LI>the school fails to take reasonable, timely and effective corrective action.
</OL>

In addition, OCR may hold a school liable for sexually harassing conduct by third parties, e.g., members of a visiting athletic team.  However, OCR will consider the level of control the school has over the alleged harasser in evaluating liability.
<P>

Behavior that constitutes sexual harassment. Unwelcome sexual advances, requests for sexual favors and other verbal or physical conduct of a sexual nature constitute sexual harassment when the conduct is so severe, persistent, or pervasive that it affects a students ability to participate in or benefit from an educational program, or creates a hostile or abusive educational environment.  In determining whether behavior constitutes sexual harassment, OCR will examine the following:
<OL>
<LI>the degree to which the conduct affected one or more students education;
<LI>the type, frequency and duration of the conduct;
<LI>the number of individuals involved;
<LI>the age and sex of the alleged harasser and the target of the harassment;
<LI>the size of the school, location of the incidents and context in which they occurred;
<LI>other incidents at the school involving the same students; and
<LI>incidents of gender-based, but non-sexual, harassment such as verbal or physical aggression, intimidation, or hostility based on sex, but not involving sexual activity or language.
</OL>


<STRONG>Notice requirement.</STRONG>  It is OCRs position that the mere presence of peer sexual harassment does not impose liability on a school.  A school must fail to take appropriate action after having notice of the sexual harassment to be in violation of Title IX.  According to OCR, a school has notice when it actually knows, or with the exercise of reasonable care should have known, about the harassment.  A school receives notice when:
<OL>
<LI>a student files a grievance or complaint with a teacher about a fellow students sexually harassing behavior;
<LI>a student, parent or other individual contacts other appropriate personnel such as a principal, campus security officer, bus driver, teacher or staff member;
<LI>an agent or responsible employee witnesses the harassment; or
<LI>the school should have known about the harassment through a reasonable or diligent inquiry.
</OL>


<STRONG>Schools response.</STRONG>  When a school has notice, it must take reasonable, timely and effective corrective action.  OCR lists the following appropriate responses:
<OL>
<LI>appropriate steps should be taken to end the harassment, such as counseling, discipline or changes in housing arrangements;
<LI>appropriate steps should be taken to prevent any further harassment;
<LI>steps should be taken to ensure that there is no retaliation against the student complaining of harassment; and
<LI>a school should conduct a full and thorough investigation of any incident or complaint.
</OL>

<P>

<STRONG>Prevention.</STRONG>  OCR suggests that schools adopt and publicize a policy specifically prohibiting sexual harassment and provide training to administrators, teachers, and staff.  Appropriate classroom information should be given to students to ensure that they understand the types of conduct that can be sexual harassment and that there is a grievance procedure in the event that they are a victim of sexual harassment.  
<P>

<STRONG>Grievance procedures.</STRONG>  	  Under Title IX, a school is required to adopt a grievance procedure providing for the prompt and equitable resolution of complaints of discrimination on the basis of sex.  In evaluating a grievance procedure, OCR looks for:
<OL>
<LI>notice to students, parents and employees of the procedure;
<LI>application of the procedures to complaints alleging harassment by students;
<LI>adequate and reliable investigation of complaints by an impartial investigator, including the opportunity for the parties to present witnesses and other evidence;
<LI>designated time-frames for the major stages of the complaint process;
<LI>notice to the parties of the disposition of the complaint; and
<LI>steps taken to prevent reccurrence of any previous harassment and to correct its effects on students.
</OL>

The procedures should be readily available and understandable to all students.
<P>

The guidance issued by OCR can be an effective tool for schools in drafting effective policies and in determining how to respond to these difficult situations.  However, the precise legal standard that will be applied in determining if and when a school will be liable for peer sexual harassment may remain uncertain until the United States Supreme Court considers the issue.  
<P>

This Update is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to educational institutions and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this Update.  <P>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>
If you have questions about the issues raised in this Issue Update, please contact Dan Wilczek at (612) 336-3243 <A HREF="mailto:dwilczek@faegre.com"><EM>(dwilczek@faegre.com)</EM></A> or Jacques Cowan at (612) 336-3364 <A HREF="mailto:jcowan@faegre.com"><EM>(jcowan@faegre.com)</EM></A>.<P>


<HR>

