<HEAD>
<TITLE> Podberesky v. Kirwan Race-Based Scholarships </title>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<h2><EM>Podberesky v. Kirwan</EM> 
Race-Based Scholarships</H2>



<FONT SIZE=+2>O</FONT>n October 27, 1994, the Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals found unconstitutional a merit-based scholarship program at the University of Maryland for which only African-American students are eligible.  <EM>Podberesky v. Kirwan</EM>, 1994 WL 587092 (4th Cir. (MD)).  The case demonstrates the difficult hurdles that a public university must overcome to justify race-conscious scholarships under the Constitution.  Because the issue in the case was the constitutionality of a scholarship program offered by a public institution, the case most likely has no impact on private colleges and universities.<p>

Daniel Podberesky sued the University of Maryland, alleging that the race-conscious scholarship program violated the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.  The University argued that the program was justified by its need to address four present effects of past discrimination:  1) the University's poor reputation in the African-American community; 2) an under-representation of African-Americans in the student population; 3) the low retention and graduation rates of African-American students; and 4) a racially hostile atmosphere on campus.  Although he met the academic requirements of the program, Podberesky was ineligible for the scholarship solely because he is not black. <p>
		
The District Court granted summary judgment to the University, finding that there were sufficient present effects of past discrimination to justify maintenance of the program and that the program was narrowly tailored to remedy those effects.  <p>

<h4>'Strict Scrutiny' Appeal</h4>

Podberesky appealed and argued that the scholarship program was invalid under the strict scrutiny test that the Supreme Court developed to analyze the constitutionality of race-conscious affirmative action plans.  The Fourth Circuit agreed.  The court concluded that a race-conscious measure like the scholarship program is constitutional only if its proponent demonstrates:  (1) strong evidence that the remedial action is necessary because sufficient present effects of past discrimination exist; and (2) that it is narrowly tailored to meet the remedial goal.  <p>

The court found the scholarship program deficient on both counts.  The court decided that each present effect of past discrimination offered by the University was flawed because there was a weak causal connection between the effect and the past discrimination, the effect was of insufficient magnitude to justify the program, or the statistical proof of the claimed effect was flawed.  <p>

The court also said that the program was not narrowly tailored to meet the University's remedial goals.  The effect of the program was not limited to the problems it was intended to remedy and the University had failed to attempt to solve the problems with race-neutral alternatives.  <p>

The <EM>Podberesky</EM> case demonstrates that a public university has a very heavy burden to justify race-conscious scholarship programs.  The decision, however, probably does not affect private colleges and universities.  The basis for the court's decision was the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.  Because the challenge to the scholarship program was based on Fourteenth Amendment governmental entities, <EM>Podberesky</EM> only applies in cases involving state action.  Courts do not generally consider private colleges and universities state actors for purposes of the Fourteenth Amendment.  State action is present only when a private college or university's conduct is fairly attributable to the government, such as when the government exercised coercive power over the conduct or significantly encouraged it.  <p>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact J. Hazen Graves by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:hgraves@faegre.com"><EM>hgraves@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

<HR>

