<HEAD>
<TITLE> 1996 Minnesota Employment and Employee Benefits 
	Legislation </title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<h2>1996 Minnesota Employment and Employee Benefits 
	Legislation</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Employee Benefits Group</h4>

The 1996 Legislative Session in Minnesota was marked by comparatively little activity in the areas of labor and employment law.  Most significant initiatives stalled in committee, or  like the bill to establish a "livable wage"  were vetoed by the Governor.
<p>

Bills that became law are briefly described below.  We thoroughly analyzed these new laws and a host of other non-legislative developments at our Labor & Employment Law Groups Annual Seminar on October 9, 1996 in Minneapolis and October 10, 1996 in Denver.  Please contact <A HREF="mailto:smcgrath@faegre.com">Shannon McGrath</A> for copies of seminar materials.
<p>

<OL type=1>
<LI><STRONG><EM>School-Related Activities Leave.</EM>  Chapter 341.</STRONG>  Expands availability of unpaid leave for parents to attend their childrens "school-related activities" (a change from "classroom activities").  The bill also removed the laws requirement that an eligible employee must have been employed for at least one year.  Employers with written leave policies should revise provisions that pertain to "school conference" or "classroom activities" leave.  Effective July 1, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Damages for Bias Offenses.</EM>  Chapter 468.</STRONG>  Provides civil action to recover damages from a person who commits a "bias offense," which is defined as "conduct that would constitute a crime and was committed because of the victims or anothers actual or perceived race, color, religion, sex, sexual orientation, disability as defined in section 363.01, age, or national origin."  A plaintiff may recover the greater of $500 or actual general and special damages, including damages for emotional distress, and may also seek punitive damages under Minn. Stat. §§ 549.191 and 549.20 and injunctive or "other appropriate relief."  A jury trial is available, and the statute of limitations is six years.  The statute provides that it does not affect any other rights or remedies of the plaintiff under other laws.  Effective August 1, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Payment of Wages  Penalties.</EM>  Chapter 386.</STRONG>  Amends various procedures relating to the enforcement of wage and hour laws and other laws related to the payment of wages and permits the Commissioner of the Department of Labor and Industry to order an employer who violates the minimum wage statute on various other statutes and rules to pay "backpay, gratuities and compensatory damages less any amount actually paid to the employee by the employer and for an additional equal amount as liquidated damages."  An employer who repeatedly or willfully violates certain sections "shall be subject to a civil penalty of up to $1,000 for each violation for each employee."  This statute also amends Minn. Stat. § 177.27 to permit an employee to bring a civil action seeking redress directly in district court.  Moreover, it contains a provision permitting the recovery of attorneys fees.  Effective August 1, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Drug and Alcohol Testing.</EM>  Chapter 377.</STRONG>  Exempts employers covered by the federal Department of Transportations alcohol and controlled substances regulations from the Minnesota drug and alcohol testing statute, provided that their programs comply with the federal regulations that govern such programs for transportation workers.  Accordingly, covered employers who follow the federal rules for alcohol testing and who test only for the five drugs for which the federal regulations require testing (marijuana, cocaine, opiates, amphetamines, and phencyclidine) do not need to comply with the Minnesota rules governing drug and alcohol testing.  Effective March 28, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Workers Compensation.</EM>  Chapter 374.</STRONG>  Removes caps and limits on modifications to workers compensation base premiums and makes various other technical and pilot program changes.
<p>

The amendment also adopts a statutory rule governing independent contractor status for construction workers.  The statute now provides that, as a "general rule," "every independent contractor doing commercial or residential building construction or improvements in the public or private sector is, for the purpose of this chapter, an employee under this chapter . . . [.]"  An independent contractor is <EM>not</EM> considered an employee for the purpose of determining potential workers compensation eligibility, only if <EM>all</EM> of the following conditions are met:
<p>

<ol type=a>
<LI>the independent contractor maintains a separate business with the independent contractors own office, equipment, materials, and other facilities;
<p>

<LI>the independent contractor holds or has applied for a federal employer identification number;
<p>

<LI>the independent contractor operates under contracts to perform specific services or work for specific amounts of money and under which the independent contractor controls the means of performing the services or work;
<p>

<LI>the independent contractor incurs the main expenses related to the service or work that the independent contractor performs under the contract;
<p>

<LI>the independent contractor is responsible for the satisfactory completion of work or services that the independent contractor contracts to perform and is liable for a failure to complete the work or service;
<p>

<LI>the independent contractor receives compensation for work or service performed under a contract on a commission or per-job or competitive bid basis and not on any other basis;
<p>

<LI>the independent contractor may realize a profit or suffer a loss under contracts to perform work or service;
<p>

<LI>the independent contractor has continuing or recurring business liabilities or obligations; and
<p>

<LI>the success or failure of the independent contractors business depends on the relationship of business receipts to expenditures.
<p>

Various effective dates, some as of March 27, 1996, two retroactive to January 1, 1996.
</ol>
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Alternative Dispute Resolution Privilege.</EM>  Chapter 388.</STRONG>  Provides an evidentiary privilege for persons presiding at any alternative dispute resolution proceeding established by law, under court rules, or by an agreement to mediate.  Under this provision, parties to litigation cannot compel a mediator to testify about information that the mediator acquired during the mediation process.  Effective August 1, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Reemployment Insurance.</EM>  Chapter 417.</STRONG>  Chapter 417 makes various modifications to the reemployment insurance law.  Of particular interest is subdivision 5(b), which states that:  "benefits paid a claimant whose separation from employment was required by a law or Minnesota administrative rule mandating a background check or whose separation from employment was required by law or Minnesota administrative rule because of a criminal conviction shall not be charged to an employer that is liable for payments in lieu of contributions or to the experience rating of an employer."  This new exception is retroactive to the date of the law or the rule mandating the background check or requiring the separation.  The 51-page act makes other technical and administrative changes to the reemployment insurance statute.  Most sections effective on July 1, 1996, nine sections on April 3, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Same Sex Athletics.</EM>  Chapter 431.</STRONG>  Provides that the Minnesota Human Rights Acts sex discrimination prohibition does not apply to restricting membership on an athletic team or in a program or event to participants of one sex "if the restriction is necessary to preserve the unique character of the team, program, or event and it would not substantially reduce comparable athletic opportunities for the other sex."  Effective April 3, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Prohibition of Discrimination in Insurance Based on Domestic Abuse.</EM>  Chapter 278.</STRONG>  Prohibits, for life and health insurance coverage purposes, discrimination in rates or coverage based on whether the insured has been or is a victim of domestic abuse.  Allows certain underwriting practices if an insurer does not consider whether a condition was caused by such abuse.  Effective August 1, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Prohibition of Retroactive Termination of Benefits.</EM>  Chapter 304.</STRONG>  Generally, prohibits retroactive termination of group health and life insurance coverage without the written consent of the covered person.  The bill contains certain, limited exceptions.  Effective March 14, 1996 for coverage issued or renewed on or after that date.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>48-Hour Minimum Maternity Benefits.</EM>  Chapter 335.</STRONG>  Requires insured health plans that provide maternity benefits to provide, consistent with other contract terms, coverage for a minimum of 48 hours of inpatient care following a vaginal delivery and a minimum of 96 hours of inpatient care following a caesarean section.  Bars incentives to encourage departures prior to these minimum periods and requires specific post-delivery care coverage if the mother and newborn have less than the minimum period of inpatient care.  Effective March 20, 1996 for all health plans issued or renewed on or after that date.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Prohibition against Termination of Insurance Agents based on Government Contacts.</EM>  Chapter 433.</STRONG>  Clarifies that existing law bars insurance companies from terminating agents as a result of contacts with any branch of government regarding a problem that the agent or an insured may have with an insurance company.  Effective retroactively to May 18, 1989 (effective date of original statute).
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Omnibus Insurance Law Amendments Act.</EM>  Chapter 446.</STRONG>  118-page omnibus act.  New requirements relating to employee benefits include:
<p>

<ul>
<LI>No health policy or contract may require notice to the health carrier as a condition for receiving coverage from birth for a dependent newborn infant (including a dependent grandchild of an employee).  If the policy requires an additional premium for the additional coverage, the carrier can collect it retroactively after it becomes aware of the new dependent.
<p>

<LI>Health plans that cover lab or diagnostic tests or x-rays must provide coverage for such tests when ordered by an advanced practice nurse.
<p>

<LI>Coverage required for registered nurse who performs surgical first assistant functions.
<p>

<LI>Health plans must cover prostate cancer screening for men age 40 or older who are symptomatic or in a high-risk category and for all men age 50 or older.  Ceases to apply on August 1, 1998.
</ul>
<p>

Effective August 1, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>MNJOBS Program Act  Health Plan Requirements.</EM>  Chapter 465.</STRONG>  Article 5 of this law requires health plans to cover treatment of diagnosed Lyme disease and prohibits special deductibles, copayments, waiting periods or other restrictions on that coverage.  Applies to health plans covering Minnesota residents that are issued or renewed on or after August 1, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Mandatory Arbitration for Charitable Hospitals.</EM>  Chapter 382.</STRONG>  Expands use of mandatory arbitration by charitable hospitals and their employees.  Effective August 1, 1996.
<p>

<LI><STRONG><EM>Charitable Organization Reporting Requirements.</EM>  Chapter 384.</STRONG>  Modifies enforcement powers of the Commissioner of Commerce, specifying cease and desist order authority and procedures; expands charitable organization financial reporting and reporting of compensation of highly paid officers and employees; extends written estimate requirements to repairs costing up to $7,500; defines nonconformities for assistive listening devices; provides for pilot project to study coordinating workers compensation and insurance for state and other government employees; and requires consideration of optional long-term care insurance benefit for state employees.  Most sections effective March 28, 1996.

</OL>

<p>

This <EM>Issue Update</EM> is intended solely to alert readers to certain legislation related to employment law or employee benefits and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this <EM>Issue Update</EM>.
<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Randy Gegelman by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:rgegelma@faegre.com"><EM>rgegelma@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

<HR>

