<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Managing ERISA Risk </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<center>
<img src="ersa_rsk.gif">
</center><P><P>

<blockquote>
No. 1, February, 1996<br>
&copy; 1996, Faegre &amp; Benson, LLP<br>
All rights reserved<p>


<h3>Executive Summary . . .<p>
Avoiding disclosure to an IRS field auditor of the analysis of an employee benefit plan problem prepared by an accounting or consulting firm.</h3><p>


An outside accounting or consulting firm frequently is engaged to conduct a compliance audit or an analysis of a known problem:  Outside accounting and consulting firms frequently are engaged by employers to conduct a major portion of . . .

<OL>
<LI>A compliance audit that looks for disqualifying defects in pension or profit sharing plans.
<LI>The analysis of a disqualifying defect that the employer has itself discovered.  
</OL>

In many instances the accounting or benefits consulting firm will discover or analyze a problem that is difficult and costly to correct retroactively:  If the IRS knows of a disqualifying defect, it will frequently require the employer to make very costly retroactive corrections.  Correcting only on a going forward basis usually does not satisfy the IRS.<P>

In many instances, an employer will want to have the option to assert a privilege with respect to the work of an accounting or consulting firm:  If the privilege can be maintained, there are three troubling items that the employer may prevent the IRS from discovering:

<OL>
<LI>The existence of the defect:  The IRS might  not discover the defect on its own.
<LI>That the employer knew of the defect:  If the IRS learns that the employer had knowledge of the defect and consciously decided not to fully correct it, the IRS may be prompted to impose more severe sanctions.
<LI>A possible candid analysis of the defect:  The accounting or consulting firm may have provided a very candid written or oral analysis of the defect that is contrary to the position the employer would like to take in negotiating the matter with the IRS (or in subsequent litigation with the IRS, DOL or a private litigant).
</OL>

A number of practical lessons can be learned from a recent Second Circuit case, U.S. v. Adlman:  The most promising privilege is the attorney-client privilege.  The Adlman case presents a number of helpful lessons for maintaining the attorney-client  privilege.  See below.<P>

The lessons of U.S. v. Adlman . . .	

<UL type=square>
<LI>Avoid the factual inference that the employer is directly seeking the advice of the accounting or benefit consulting firmrather than the advice of a lawyer.
<LI>Make a contemporaneous record of the intent to maintain a privilege.
<LI>Be assured that the employer's independent auditing firm will wall-off its employee benefit consulting services.
</UL>

Or consider hiring a different firm.	
<hr>

<blockquote><EM>Material in this letter has been abridged from laws and regulations.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of these issues. For this reason, it is imperative that you consult with legal counsel before acting on any matter discussed in this letter.
</EM></blockquote><P>

<h3>Employee Benefits Group</h3>

<STRONG>Minnesota</STRONG><BR> 
