<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN" "html.dtd">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Managing ERISA Risk </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<center>
<img src="ersa_rsk.gif">
</center><P><P>

<blockquote>
No. 1, February, 1996<br>
&copy; 1996, Faegre &amp; Benson, LLP<br>
All rights reserved<p>



<h2>Avoiding disclosure to an IRS field auditor of the analysis of an employee benefit plan problem prepared by an accounting or consulting firm.<BR></h2>
Lessons from the Second Circuit's decision in . . .<BR>
<h3>United States of America v. Monroe Adlman. </h3>
By Dick Brennan, Hugh Forcier and Paul Heiring<p>


In late 1995, the Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit issued an opinion in <EM>Adlman</EM> (68 F.3d 1495) that provides meaningful instruction for an employer that wishes to minimize the risk that an IRS field auditor may discover an analysis of employee benefit plan problems prepared by the employer's consultants or independent auditor.  <p>

Frequently, an accounting firm or benefit consulting firm will be engaged to assess whether a qualified pension or profit sharing plan is at risk of losing its qualified status under the tax laws.  It is not uncommon for the firm to find that potentially disqualifying defects do exist.  And sometimes the accounting or consulting firm's analysis can be very incriminating.  In these cases, it is important to be able to keep an IRS field auditor from compelling disclosure of the analysis (see discussion below).  <P>

Although not an employee benefit plan case, the <EM>Adlman</EM> case discusses several issues that are relevant to an analysis of employee benefit plan problems prepared by accounting or consulting firms. The Adlman case involved the analysis of the tax implications of a corporate restructuring prepared by Arthur Andersen & Co. (AA) for the Sequa Corporation.  (AA also served as the independent auditor of Sequa's financial statements.)  When the analysis was requested by the IRS as part of a tax audit, Sequa attempted to prevent discovery by asserting both the attorney-client privilege and the work product doctrine.  Sequa lost on the attorney-client privilege issue.  The case was remanded on the work product doctrine.  <p>

The work product doctrine (and a related privilege, the self-evaluation privilege) would rarely apply to an analysis of employee benefit plan problems prepared by an accounting firm or consulting firm.  Therefore, in this newsletter we will focus only on the attorney-client privilege.<p>

The three lessons of the Adlman case are listed below. <P>


<STRONG>The lessons of U.S. v. Adlman . . .

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#inference">Avoid the factual inference that the employer is directly seeking the advice of the accounting or benefit consulting firmrather than 	the advice of a lawyer.</A>
<LI><A HREF="#record">Make a contemporaneous record of the intent to maintain a privilege.</A>
<LI><A HREF="#assured">Be assured that the employer's independent auditing firm will wall-off its employee benefit consulting services.  Or consider hiring a different firm.</A></STRONG></ul>

<blockquote><hr><center><strong>The three types of disclosures an employer 
will seek to avoid:</strong></center>

The accounting or consulting firm may well discover a defect that is very expensive for the employer to correct retroactivelyat least to the satisfaction of the IRS.  If the defect is not fully corrected, the analysis provided by the accounting or consulting firms may increase the employer's exposure.  This increased exposure is created if the IRS can discover the results of the analysis.  In that case, the IRS will discover three potentially troubling items:

<ol>
<li>The existence of the defect:  The IRS will find the defect (a defect it might not have discovered on its own).
<li>That the employer knew of the defect:  The IRS will learn that the employer had knowledge of the defect and consciously decided not to fully correct it (a discovery that may prompt the IRS to impose more severe sanctions).
<li>A possible candid analysis of the defect:  The IRS may obtain a candid analysis of the defect that is contrary to the position the employer would like to take in negotiating the matter with the IRS (and in potential subsequent litigation with the IRS, DOL, or plan participants). n
</oL>
<hr></blockquote>

<A NAME="inference"></A><H3>Avoid the factual inference that the employer <br>
is directly seeking the advice of the accounting <br>
or benefit consulting firm  rather than the advice of a lawyer.</H3>

In Adlman, the Second Circuit Court of Appeals relied on two key arguments to uphold the district court's finding that Sequa had not satisfied its burden of proof to establish the attorney-client privilege.  <P>

The first argument was that no attorney-client privilege should apply because Sequa had sought the advice of the accounting firmrather than the advice of its lawyer.  The remainder of this section describes why that conclusion is fatal to the establishment of the privilege, and how an employer might avoid a court reaching a similar conclusion if an accounting or consulting firm is engaged in connection with the review of a potential employee benefit plan problem.<P>


<blockquote><hr><strong>
The involvement of an accounting or consulting firm is not    protected by the attorney-client privilege if the facts establish that the client was seeking the advice of the accounting or   consulting firm rather than the lawyer.<br>
</strong><hr></blockquote>

It is well established that if a lawyer consults with an accounting (or consulting) firm for the purpose of helping the lawyer provide legal advice, the communications between the lawyer, accountant, and client are generally protected by the attorney-client privilege.

A leading case establishing the extension of the attorney-client privilege to accountants who are assisting a lawyer is <EM>United States v. Kovel</EM>, 296 F.2d 918 (2d Cir. 1961).  That case also established the limitations on the extension of the privilege.<p>

In <EM>Kovel</EM>, the court began its analysis by noting that if an attorney hired a foreign language translator to interpret communications from the lawyer's client, the attorney-client privilege would apply to the translator.  The court went on as follows:

<blockquote>Accounting concepts are a foreign language to some lawyers in almost all cases, and to almost all lawyers in some cases.  Hence the presence of an accountant, . . . while the client is relating a complicated tax story to the lawyer, ought not destroy the privilege. . . .<p>

<center>* * * * *</center><p>

What is vital to the privilege is that the communication be made <EM>in confidence</EM> for the purpose of obtaining <EM>legal</EM> advice <EM>from the lawyer</EM>.  <strong>If what is sought is not legal advice but only accounting service, . . . or if the advice sought is the accountant's rather than the lawyer's, no privilege exists.</strong></blockquote>

<EM>Id.</EM> at 92-22 (italics in original, citation omitted and bold added).<p>

In <EM>Adlman</EM>, the Second Circuit found ample support in the record for the district court's conclusion that Sequa was seeking the advice of AArather than the advice of Sequa's in-house attorney.  AA provided a variety of audit, accounting and advisory services and there was no evidence AA was acting other than in an accounting capacity.  Moreover, the in-house lawyer was not merely a lawyerhe was also the Vice President of Tax of the Company.  <p>

While the facts that will tend to prove the point one way or the other will vary from case to case, the facts that were relevant to the district court in <EM>Adlman</EM> are useful to examine in the context of a typical case.  They will be discussed in the balance of this section.<p>


<blockquote><hr><strong>
To bolster the conclusion that the client was seeking the advice of the lawyer, the lawyer should have at least as much substantive expertise as the accountant.</strong><hr></blockquote>

In its brief, the IRS relied on the fact that AA was far more experienced in the particular tax law issue being examined than was the in-house legal counsel that Sequa was claiming it had relied upon.  The government made much of this disparate expertise, which resulted in the inference being drawn that the in-house lawyer merely approved AA's conclusions on the legal issues, and that the lawyer was not using the AA analysis to assist him in reaching his own conclusions.<p>

<blockquote><hr><strong>To bolster the conclusion that the client was seeking the advice of the lawyer, the accountant's engagement should emphasize analysis of the facts and accounting issueswith any legal conclusions being reached in conjunction with the lawyer.</strong><hr></blockquote>


In its brief to the Second Circuit, the government made much of the fact that AA was independently reaching legal conclusions.  If the accounting or consulting firm is to be involved in analyzing what are essentially legal issues (and in most employee benefit plan situations that will frequently be the case), any legal analysis should be performed in conjunction with the lawyer.  Simply running the accounting or consulting firm's legal conclusions past the lawyer after those conclusions have been reached is not sufficient. <p>


<blockquote><hr><strong>To bolster the conclusion that the client was seeking the advice of the lawyer, the accountant should not express conclusions of the law directly  to the client.</strong><hr></blockquote>

Another key fact in <EM>Adlman</EM> was that AA provided a summary of its advice directly to non-lawyers and executives at Sequa and offered to discuss the summary with them.  And AA, in a different memo later sent directly to non-lawyer executives, expressed views such as No current federal tax liability will be created as a result of the restructuring, and There should be no penalty imposed as long as the transaction is adequately disclosed in the tax return.  In its brief to the Second Circuit, the government made much of the fact that AA issued these opinions directly to non-lawyer executives. <p><p>

<A NAME="record"></A><H3>Make a contemporaneous record of <br>
the intent to maintain a privilege.</H3>

The other key reason the Second Circuit refused to recognize a privilege in <EM>Adlman</EM> was that, in the words of the Second Circuit:  

<blockquote>There was virtually no contemporaneous documentation that AA was working under a different arrangement from that which governed the rest of its work for Sequa.</blockquote>

68 F.3d at 1500.<p>

It has long been the common wisdom of practitioners that, to sustain the extension of the attorney-client privilege to accountants, the lawyer should separately engage the accountant and contemporaneous records of that engagement should be kept separate from any other services that the accountant performs for the client.  In its brief to the Second Circuit, the government made much of the fact that in the Adlman case this common wisdom was not followed in practice:

<blockquote>Commentators have . . . noted that extrinsic evidence proving that an accountant and an attorney intended to enter a <EM>Kovel</EM> relationship is critical.  For example, a leading treatise states that [a] letter agreement establishing the [<em>Kovel</em>] relationship of the accountant and the representative is essential. . . .  If the accountant who performs the service is the taxpayer's accountant . . . the change in client (taxpayer to representative) becomes difficult to identify and prove.  M. Saltzman, IRS Practice and Procedure ¶ 12.04[5], at 12-54-55 (2d ed. 1991).  Similarly, a prominent tax attorney has cautioned that

<blockquote>[t]o safeguard the <EM>Kovel</EM> privilege, the attorney should send an engagement letter to the accountant which recites that the accountant is working under the direction of the attorney, in connection with the attorney's rendition of legal services to the client; that the communications between the accountant and the client are made solely for purposes of enabling the attorney to give legal advice to the client. . . .<p>

<center>* * * * *</center><p>

<strong>Assuming that the attorney and the accountant conform their conduct to the requirements of the law outlined above</strong>, the workpapers of the Kovel accountant will be immune from production to government under an IRS summons. . . .</blockquote></blockquote>

L. Feld, <EM>Tax Fraud</EM>, 254 ALI-ABA 159, 164-66 (1988) (bold added).

In its response, Sequa argued that the government's position would elevate form over substance.  The Second Circuit dismissed that argument with the following discussion:

<blockquote>Sequa claims that the district court erroneously required a separate retainer agreement or individualized billing statements distinguishing AA's work on the AA memo from other services provided to Sequa.  The district court's conclusion, and our approval of it here, establishes no such requirement.  It is the burden of the party asserting the privilege to establish facts in support thereof.  <EM>von Bulow</EM>, 811 F.2d at 144.  Deciding whether the attorney-client privilege exists requires common sense . . . in light of reason and experience, and should be determined on a case-by-case basis.  In this instance, the absence of contemporaneous documentary proof supporting Sequa's interpretation of the facts, taken together with the presence of contemporaneous documentation supporting the government's interpretation, strongly supports the district court's finding.  The district court's observation that <strong>Sequa's contention was weakened by the absence of a contemporaneous retainer agreement was merely an application of common sense to the circumstances and not, as Sequa contends, an elevation of form over substance.</strong></blockquote>

68 F.3d at 1500, n. 1 (bold added). <br>
Whether it is or is not form over substance, the <EM>Adlman</EM> case shows that making a contemporaneous record of the intent to enter into an attorney-client privileged relationship is important to establishing the privilege. <p>

<A NAME="assured"></A><H3>Be assured that the employer's 
<br>independent auditing firm will wall-off 
<br>its employee benefit consulting services.  
<P>
Or consider hiring a different firm.</H3>

The <EM>Adlman</EM> case is relevant to a troubling issue that comes up when the accounting firm engaged to assist the lawyer is also the independent auditor of the client's financial statements.  In general terms, the question is whether the accounting firm's duties as the auditor of the client's financial statement are <EM>per se</EM> inconsistent with the extension of the privilege to the accounting firm's separate consulting services.  While neither the district court or the Second Circuit specifically addressed the issue in the <EM>Adlman</EM> case, the case indicates the position that the government will take. 

<blockquote><strong>In <EM>Adlman</EM> the government took the position that any privilege that would otherwise have been extended to AA would have been waived to the extent that          information was shared with the AA staff that was responsible for the independent audit of the client's financial statement.</strong></blockquote>

The U.S. Supreme Court has held that no privilege can exist with respect to information provided by the client to the independent auditor of its financial statements in connection with accounting firm's analysis of a reserve established by the client on its financial statement for contingent liabilities.<P>

In <EM>United States v. Arthur Young & Co.</EM>, 465 U.S. 805 (1984), the government sought to subpoena tax accrual workpapers that were prepared by Arthur Young in connection with its independent audit of the financial statements of Amerada Hess Corp.  The workpapers were prepared by Arthur Young as part of its analysis of the adequacy of the reserve for contingent tax liabilities that was recorded in the Amerada Hess financial statements.<P>

The U.S. Supreme Court rejected the argument that a legal privilege (in that case the work product doctrine) should be extended to the independent auditor, at least when it is acting in its capacity as auditor.  The Court noted that an auditor's position <EM>vis-a-vis</EM> the client is very different than that of the client's lawyer: 

<blockquote>[W]e find unpersuasive the argument that a work-product immunity for accountants' tax accrual workpapers is a fitting analogue to the attorney work-product doctrine established in <EM>Hickman v. Taylor</EM>, 329 US 495, 91 L Ed 451, 67 S. Ct 385 (1947).  The Hickman work-product doctrine was founded upon the private attorney's role as the client's confidential adviser and advocate, a loyal representative whose duty it is to present the client's case in the most favorable possible light.  An independent certified public accountant performs a different role.  By certifying the public reports that collectively depict a corporation's financial status, the independent auditor assumes a <EM>public</EM> responsibility transcending any employment relationship with the client.  The independent public accountant performing this special function owes ultimate allegiance to the corporation's creditors and stockholders, as well as to the investing public.  This public watchdog function demands that the accountant maintain total independence from the client at all times and requires complete fidelity to the public trust.</blockquote>

465 U.S. at 817-18 (italics in original).<P>

The Court went on to state that the difference in the relationship required a different result:

<blockquote>To insulate from disclosure a certified public accountant's interpretations of the client's financial statements would be to ignore the significance of the accountant's role as a disinterested analyst charged with public obligations.</blockquote>

465 U.S. at 818.<P>

In <EM>Adlman</EM>, the government took the position that for non-audit services to avoid the result of <EM>Arthur Young</EM>, those services would have to be walled-off from the accounting firm's auditing functions.   At page 6 of its brief, the government stated as follows:

<blockquote>The listing of documents in AA's possession provided by <EM>Sequa</EM> reflects that no fewer than nine AA partners and associates worked on the transaction and assisted in providing tax advice.  JA 47-48.  <EM>Sequa</EM> claims that they all participated in helping <EM>Adlman</EM> render legal advice.  JA 48.  <strong>The listing does not indicate that these nine AA partners and associates were distinct from the accountants who performed audits of Sequa.</strong></blockquote>

(Bold added.)
<P>

And at page 11 of its brief, the government stated as follows:

<blockquote>Finally, [the AA representative] claimed that the memoranda are kept in a restricted file at the firm, b<STRONG>ut did not state that it was kept from AA personnel auditing Sequa or producing the firm's tax reserve analyseswork not subject to any evidentiary privilege.</STRONG>  JA 99.  
</blockquote>

(Bold added.)
<P>

Since <EM>Sequa</EM> bore the burden of proof on the privilege issue, the government argued that, by failing to establish that AA had walled-off its tax advice from its functions as an independent auditor, <EM>Sequa</EM> had failed to meet its burden of proof.
<P>

<EM>Adlman</EM> thus makes it clear that to be safe from a government challenge, the client (or lawyer) who engages the accounting firm to assist the lawyer should be assured that the accounting firm will wall-off its consulting for the lawyer from its independent auditing functions.

<blockquote><hr><strong>As a question of professional ethics, can an accounting firm wall-off its consulting services from its function as the independent auditor?</strong><hr></blockquote>

In its <EM>Adlman</EM> brief, the government implicitly assumed that an independent auditor can ethically wall-off its consulting services so that its auditing personnel cannot examine the conclusions of its consulting staff.  If that assumption turns out to be incorrect, however, the practical effect would be that the IRS can subpoena the results of all consulting services provided to a client by an accounting firm that also audits the client's financial statements. 
<P>

In many cases it may well be that the accounting firm cannot wall-off its consulting services.  Each state establishes a code of professional responsibility that applies to accountants practicing in that state.  However, the AICPA provides a nationwide code for its members.  The  AICPA rules provide as follows:

<blockquote><strong>
Article VI
<P>

Scope and Nature of Services</strong>
<P>

<EM>A member in public practice should observe the Principles of the Code of Professional Conduct in determining the scope and nature of services to be provided.</EM>
<P>

The public interest aspect of certified public accountants' services requires that such services be consistent with acceptable professional behavior for certified public accountants.  Integrity requires that service and the public trust not be subordinated to personal gain and advantage.  Objectivity and independence require that members be free from conflicts of interest in discharging professional responsibilities...
<P>

Each of these Principles should be considered by members in determining whether or not to provide specific services in individual circumstances.  In some instances, they may represent an overall constraint on the non-audit services that might be offered to a specific client.  No hard-and-fast rules can be developed to help members reach these judgments, but they must be satisfied that they are meeting the spirit of the Principles in this regard.
<P>

In order to accomplish this, members should . . .
<P>

<ul>
<li><strong>Determine</strong>, in their individual judgments, <strong>whether the scope and nature of other services provided to an audit client would create a conflict of interest in the performance of the audit function for that client.</strong>
</ul>

<center>* * * * *</center><p>

</blockquote>

(Bold added.)
<P>

Given this rule, it would seem that before awarding a consulting engagement to a firm that also audits its financial statements, a company (or better yet, the company's lawyer) should seek assurance from the auditing firm that the results of the consulting engagement will be walled-off from the firm's auditing staff.  Some accounting firms are willing to provide that assurancein writing.  Others are not.
<P>

<blockquote><hr><strong>If the auditing firm will not agree in advance to wall-off its        consulting services, consider  hiring a different firm.</strong><hr></blockquote>

In the context of consulting engagements that analyze potential defects in the company's employee benefits plans, some accounting firms are apparently unwilling to provide assurance that the consulting services will be walled-off.  If the auditing firm refuses to provide such assurance, the best response (given the large exposures that could potentially result if the IRS could subpoena the firm's consulting analysis) may be to engage a different firm. 
<P>

Even if a different firm is engaged, however, the firm that audits the company's financial statements might nevertheless effectively compel certain disclosures with respect to the plan defects that are discussed. For example, the auditing firm may learn of the other firm's analysis because it uncovers references to that analysis in other documents it examines in connection with its audit.  Or, the auditing firm may learn of the other firm's analysis from examining the billings that reference that work.  (Examining billings to determine whether questions related to plan defects have been examined by outside professionals is a standard audit technique.)
<P>

If the auditing firm learns of the existence of the other firm's analysis, it may demand to see that analysisunder the threat that, if it is not given access to the other firm's conclusions, it will issue a qualified opinion on the company's financial statements.
<P>

In our experience, if it gets to that point, the auditing firm will generally be satisfied if the potential defect is identified to itwithout providing to the auditing firm the risk analysis of the other firm.<p>

Disclosing even the existence of a defect to the auditing firm can be problematic.  It increases the chance that the IRS will discover the defect and discover that the employer knew of the defect.  And disclosure to the auditing firm might provide the IRS (or the DOL or a private litigant) with a basis to argue that the privilege has been waived as to the underlying analysis.  However, if the disclosure to the auditing firm is handled properly, the employer may be able to avoid a waiver.<p>

<hr>

<blockquote><EM>Material in this letter has been abridged from laws and regulations.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of these issues. For this reason, it is imperative that you consult with legal counsel before acting on any matter discussed in this letter.
</EM></blockquote><P>

