<TITLE> Managing ERISA Risk </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<center>
<img src="ersa_rsk.gif">
</center><P><P>

<blockquote>
No. 2, February, 1996<br>
&copy; 1996, Faegre &amp; Benson, LLP<br>
All rights reserved<p>


<h3><em>Executive Summary . . .</em><p></h3>
January 26, 1996:  The IRS announces a "deal killer" position <br>
on a popular executive perk:
<h3>
Equity Split Dollar Life Insurance.</h3><p>


<STRONG>Why equity split dollar has been popular for providing retirement benefits:</STRONG>  Since the mid-'60s, equity split dollar was thought to have a rather unique combination of advantages:

<OL>
<LI>During an executive's working career, assets could be accumulated (in the form of cash values) for the purpose of providing retirement benefits.  Those assets were beyond the reach of the employer's general creditors.
<LI>It was thought that the executive was not taxable during his/her working career on the assets as they accumulated.  At most, the executive was taxable only when he/she received payouts during his/her retirement years.  And with the creative use of policy loans he/she might not even be taxable in retirement.  
</OL>

	
<STRONG>On January 26, 1996, the IRS announced a deal killer position:</STRONG>  The IRS announced that an executive was taxable during his/her working career on the cash values as they accumulate.<P>

<STRONG>We do not expect most employers to collapse existing split dollar arrangements in the near term:</STRONG>  The insurance industry will fight the IRS position.  The industry is politically powerful and has some credible arguments that it can advance to either:

<OL>
<LI>Obtain a total reversal of the IRS position. 
<LI>Or at least limit the application of the IRS position to policies issued in the future.
</OL>


<STRONG>But some risk management issues need to be addressed immediately:</STRONG>  Even if the split dollar arrangements are not collapsed in the near term, the very existence of an officially announced, adverse IRS position will cause almost all employers to (re)evaluate certain issues.  These issues include:

<OL>
<LI>Does the IRS position clearly apply to the specific split dollar agreements currently in effect between the employer and its executives?  If yes, what changes in the split dollar arrangement could be made?
<LI>What is the past, current, and future income tax exposure of the executive and the income tax reporting and withholding exposure of the employer?  
<LI>Many employers will conclude that their executives should receive information about, and an evaluation of, the newly announced IRS position.  
<LI>Many employers will probably now have to decide whether the employer will provide the executive with a tax gross up should the IRS ultimately be able to sustain its position.  
<LI>What is the possible effect on other employee benefit plans?  Would the IRS position result in additional compensation to be recognized in determining benefits under the employer's plans?  Would the unexpected additional taxable income cause tax qualified pension and profit sharing plans to lose their tax favored status?
</OL>

<hr>

<blockquote><EM>Material in this letter has been abridged from laws and regulations.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of these issues. For this reason, it is imperative that you consult with legal counsel before acting on any matter discussed in this letter.
</EM></blockquote><P>

