<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Managing ERISA Risk </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<center>
<img src="ersa_rsk.gif">
</center><P><P>

<blockquote>
No. 2, February, 1996<br>
&copy; 1996, Faegre &amp; Benson, LLP<br>
All rights reserved<p>

January 26, 1996:  The IRS announces a 'deal killer' position <br>
on a popular executive perk:
<BR>
<h3>Equity Split Dollar Life Insurance.</h3><BR>
By Hugh Forcier and Doug Heffernan<p>


Since the mid-'60s, equity split dollar life insurance arrangements have been considered by the insurance industry to have significant income tax and gift tax advantages.  The income tax advantages thought to be obtained when split dollar arrangements are used to provide retirement benefits to executives are briefly reviewed in the section beginning with the first link.  

<hr>
<H4>Contents:<P>

<A HREF="#advantages">The income tax advantages when equity split dollar insurance is used to provide<BR>
retirement benefits for executives according to the historic, virtual<BR>
consensus view of the insurance industry</A><P>

<A HREF="#positions">The IRS position made public on January 26, 1996:  TAM 9604001</A></h4>
<hr>

Since the mid-'80s, IRS staffers would occasionally make statements that indicated that they did not necessarily agree with the insurance industry's view.  However, over this long period the IRS never took any formal action to question the industry, that is, not until Technical Advice Memorandum (TAM) 9604001 (Sept. 8, 1995) was made available to the public on January 26, 1996.
<p>

Some employers and executives entered into these arrangements without knowing that there was any reason to question the tax advantages described by the industry.  Other employers and executives entered into the arrangements with the knowledge that some risk existedbut judged the potential rewards to be well worth the risks.<br>


<blockquote><hr><strong>The industry's historic view:    Equity split dollar permits assets to be dedicated during an executive's working career for the purpose of providing retirement benefits without any current income taxation.</strong><hr></blockquote>

As a general principle of tax law set out in Section 83 of the federal tax code, if assets are dedicated for retirement purposes (that is, placed beyond the reach of the employer's general creditors) the executive is currently taxed.  In other words, the executive is taxed on the dedicated assets as they are dedicated during his/her working careereven though he/she will not receive cash payment until his/her retirement years.  The only clear exceptions to this general principle under Section 83 are statutory planssuch as 401(a)/(k) tax qualified plans or 403(b) tax sheltered annuity arrangements.  
<p>

The consensus view of the insurance industry was that (even without a statutory exemption) assets could be accumulated under an equity split dollar arrangement that were dedicated to provide retirement benefits (i.e., protected from the employer's general creditors) and, at worst, the executive would not be taxable until he/she actually received cash payouts during retirement.  And, under some variations, the industry contended that (through the use of policy loans) he/she would not even be taxable when he/she receives cash payouts in retirement.
<br>

<blockquote><hr><strong>The risk was that the industry's consensus view was too good to be true.  But the IRS was aware of the industry's views and never officially challenged those views  that is, not until TAM 9604001.</strong><hr></blockquote>

For decades, the IRS was well aware of the industry's use of equity split dollar arrangements and of the industry's view that under such arrangements, assets could be dedicated for retirement programs without current taxation.  During that period the IRS never formally questioned the industry's position.
<p>

In 1988, the IRS specifically refused to rule on a rather typical equity split dollar arrangementstating that equity split dollar arrangements were the subject of a pending Revenue Ruling project.  However, a Revenue Ruling was never issued.
<p>

On January 26, 1996, the IRS TAM was made publicly available.  It announced a radically adverse IRS position with respect to equity split dollar.  (A Technical Advice Memorandum is formal written advice issued by the IRS National Office to IRS field auditors in connection with the examination of a specific taxpayer.  Although the TAM is technically applicable only to the specific taxpayer, TAMs reflect general IRS positions.)  The IRS position is described in the section beginning on page 5. 
<p>
 
In general terms, the IRS has taken the view that the executive is currently taxable on his/her equity in the cash value (i.e., the excess of the cash value over the cumulative employer premium payments) when, and as, the amounts become dedicated for the purpose of providing future retirement benefits.
<br>

<blockquote><hr><strong>Prediction:  Most employers and executives will not collapse arrangements in the near term.</strong><hr></blockquote>

The insurance industry will expend considerable effort seeking to overturn the IRS position.  The insurance industry is the most politically powerful financial services industry in the country.  And it is not without credible arguments.  For those reasons, it may well obtain a total reversal of the IRS position.  Even more probable is that the industry will be successful in preventing the IRS position from being applied to existing split dollar arrangements.  Employers and executives that accept this view (which we expect to be the majority) will not be inclined to collapse existing arrangements in the near term and will continue to claim the tax advantages.
<br>

<blockquote><hr><strong>But even if the arrangements are continued, the IRS position presents new risk management issues.</strong><hr></blockquote>

Even if the arrangements are not collapsed in the near term, the very existence of an officially announced, adverse IRS position will cause almost all employers to (re)evaluate certain issues.  These issues include:

<OL>
<LI>Does the IRS position clearly apply to the specific split dollar agreements currently in effect between the employer and its executives?  If yes, what changes could be made?
<LI>What is the past, current, and future income tax exposure of the executive and the income tax reporting and withholding exposure of the employer?  (Gift tax exposure must also be analyzed if an irrevocable trust established by the executive has an equity interest in the cash value of the policy.)
<LI>Many employers will conclude that their executives should receive information about, and an evaluation of, the newly announced IRS position.  
<LI>Many employers will probably now have to decide whether the employer will provide the executive with a tax gross up if the IRS should sustain its position as to existing and future split dollar arrangements.  
<LI>What is the possible effect on other employee benefit plans?  Would the IRS position result in additional compensation to be recognized in determining benefits under the employer's plans?  Or, under the TAM, would there be additional compensation to be recognized for discrimination testing purposes (under such tests as a 401(k) ADP test or a 401(a)(4) general test)?  For example, will some persons previously thought to be non-highly compensated employees now be highly compensated employees?  Or do some persons who would remain non-highly compensated persons in all events now have a lower benefit expressed as a percent of pay?  Either consequence could cause past or future 401(k) ADP tests or 401(a)(4) general tests to fail. 
</OL>


<A NAME="advantages"></A><H3>The income tax advantages when equity split dollar<BR>
insurance is used to provide retirement benefits for <BR>
executives  according to the historic, virtual <BR>
consensus view of the insurance industry</H3><BR>


Split dollar life insurance arrangements take many forms and can be used to achieve various objectives.  This area is further complicated by the fact that there is no standardized terminology.
<p>

However, equity split dollar is a term commonly used to refer to a broad class of split dollar arrangements.  Under these arrangements, the employer advances funds to purchase a cash value policy insuring the life of an executive and the incidents of ownership are divided (or split) between the executive and the employer.  
<p>

A cash value life insurance policy has two basic features:  A death benefit and a cash value.  If the employer retains all of the cash value and the executive only receives the right to have a death benefit paid to his/her beneficiary, the arrangement is usually called traditional split dollar.  If both the death benefit and the cash values are split, the arrangement is called equity split dollar.  Today, most split dollar arrangements are of the equity type.
<p>

Note:  Under both traditional and equity split dollar, it is universally accepted that the executive is subject to income tax each year on the value of the death benefit protection that has been provided by the employer during the year for the executive's beneficiaries.  The taxable benefit is measured by what would have been the cost of providing a like amount of term insurance coverage.  For more information on this aspect of split dollar, see the box on this page.


<blockquote><hr><strong>Income tax advantages in the  retirement context.</strong><hr></blockquote>

Equity split dollar is frequently used to provide retirement benefits.  Usually, the employer pays all of the premiums and the employer's share of the cash value is limited to the cumulative amount of the premiums it has paid (i.e., with no adjustment for earnings). 
<p>

Under this type of arrangement, during an executive's working career assets are being dedicated to provide for income during his/her retirement years.  The assets are being dedicated as the cash value accumulates above the cumulative amount of the employer's premium payments.  
<p>

The respective interests of the employer and executive can be secured in one of two ways:

<OL>
<LI><em>Endorsement method:</em>  The employer is the owner of the policy but the policy is endorsed by the insurance company to reflect the interest the employee has in the policy proceeds as set out in the split dollar agreement.
<LI><em>Collateral assignment method:</em>  The executive is the owner of the policy but an assignment filed with the insurance company recognizes that the employer has rights in the insurance proceeds pursuant to the split dollar agreement.
</OL>

In both cases, the interest of the executive in the cash value is beyond the reach of the employer's general creditors.
<P>

During the executive's retirement years, the employer's cumulative premiums can be left in the policy and the executive can be permitted to make withdrawals from the cash value to provide retirement incomeso long as the withdrawals do not bring the cash value below the amount of the employer's cumulative premium payments.
<P>


<blockquote><hr><center><h3>How is the taxable value of<br>
the death benefit protection<br>
calculated?</h3></center>

Under IRS authority, the taxable value of the death protection is calculated by<br>
multiplying the amount of protection provided by the lower of two rates:

<OL>
<LI>The P.S. 58/38 rates:  This is a rate (based on the insured's age) that<br>
provides a value per $1,000 of coverage.
<LI>The rate per $1,000 of coverage charged by the insurance company for term<br>
insurance.
</OL>

At least at some insurance companies, the practice of using the rates for desk drawer term insurance has evolved.  Desk drawer term insurance means a term insurance policy that the insurance company has developed with extraordinarily low premium ratesand which, as a practical matter, the insurance company never actually offers to sell to anyone.
<hr></blockquote>

The income tax advantages that historically have been thought to exist are substantial:  From the executive's perspective, he/she is not subject to any income tax until he/she begins to withdraw amounts during retirement.  At worst, withdrawals would be taxable when received.  The P.S. 58/38 costs (see box) might constitute basis, permitting some withdrawals to be received tax-free. And if the executive makes withdrawals in the form of tax-free policy loans, and if he/she
 dies before the policy must be surrendered, all income tax would be avoidedboth with respect to the amounts withdrawn by the executive and with respect to the death benefit paid to the executive's beneficiaries.  The industry's view on the issue was well stated in a newsletter published in 1992 by Connecticut Mutual Life Insurance Company.  See box on page 4.<br>

<blockquote><hr><strong>A rollout at retirement is common.</strong><hr></blockquote>

Under some of the most common variations of equity split dollar, the split dollar arrangement ends when the executive retires, even though the life insurance policy may continue.  This is called a rollout.  There are many variations of rollouts.  Sometimes the employer receives a return of its cumulative premium payments.
<p>

Other times, the employer simply foregoes its right to receive its cumulative premium payments at the executive's retirement, and the employer's interest is rolled out to the executive.  If that happens, it is generally accepted that the executive is taxable on that amount at that time.  
<p>

Some commentators have expressed concern that (at least if the endorsement method is used) the executive may be taxable on his/her split of cash values at the time of a rollout (in addition to the clear consequence that he/she is taxable on the portion of the employer's split that the employer may have foregone as described in the preceding paragraph).
<p>


<blockquote><hr><center><strong>The virtual consensus view of the insurance industry.</strong></center>
<p>

As described in the section beginning on page 5, the IRS has taken the position that the executive is taxable during his/her working career as his/her split of cash value increases.  Historically, the insurance industry has not thought this result to be likely.  One of the clearest statements of the industry's view was set out in the April 1992 issue of Connecticut Mutual's <EM>The Advanced Underwriter</EM> at page 6 (italics added):
<p>

Because equity plans differ from traditional split-dollar plans and because there are no cases or official IRS rulings directly on point regarding equity split-dollar, the income tax treatment becomes uncertain as the employee's equity arises (when the cash surrender value exceeds the cumulative employer premiums).  This uncertainty relates to whether and when the equity in the policy is taxed to the employee.  <strong><em>It is the virtual consensus in the insurance industry that the employee is taxed just as in the traditional split-dollar plan</em></strong>, pursuant to the principles of Revenue Rulings 64-328 and 66-110, based on the economic value of the death benefit.  <em>This means that the employee is not taxed on the equity build up while the plan is in effect</em>.
<p>

A minority view is that an equity split-dollar plan is a departure from the situation described in Revenue Ruling 64-328 and that the IRS would perhaps include in the employee's income the increase in cash value each year, or a portion of the gross premium of the policy, or the IRS might apply Section 7872 dealing with below market interest loans.
<hr></blockquote>


<A NAME="positions"></A><H3>The IRS position made public<br>
on January 26, 1996:  TAM 9604001.</H3>

In general terms, the IRS basic position publicly announced on January 26, 1996 is easy to understand:

<blockquote>[U]nder sections 61 and 83 of the Code, Taxpayer must include in income each year that the [split dollar] arrangement is in force (a) an amount equal to the one-year term cost of declining life insurance and (b) any cash surrender buildup in the policies that exceeds the amount that is returnable to [the employer] when the arrangement is discontinued.
</blockquote>

TAM 9604001.


<blockquote><hr><strong>Literal application of IRS position makes no sense.</strong><hr></blockquote>

Read literally, the IRS position leads to double taxation.  Each year the executive's taxable income under Section 83 would be calculated as follows:
<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>The cash value at the end of the year
<p>
MINUS
<p>
<li>The employer's cumulative premiums (assumed to be returnable to it under the terms of the split dollar agreement).
<li>But never less than $0.
</ul>

This interpretation, however, by focusing on the entire cash value rather than increases in cash value, would result in repetitive taxation of amounts previously taken into income.  Over the life of a split dollar arrangement, this would result in taxable income many times greater than the cash value interest of the executive.
<p>

<blockquote><hr><strong>Presumably, the executive would at least be entitled to an offset to avoid double taxation.</strong><hr></blockquote>

Although not expressed in the TAM, the IRS presumably would permit the executive to claim an offset for amounts previously taken into income.  The formula to calculate each year's taxable income would be as follows:
<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>The cash value at the end of the taxable year.
<p>
MINUS
<p>
<li>The employer's cumulative premiums paid at the end of the current year.
<li>Less the amount of cash values that the executive had included in taxable income in prior years.
<li>But never less than $0.
</ul>

However, even this method would not allow the executive to gain the advantage of his or her cost basis normally associated with cash value policies.  That is, the increase in cash value (earnings) attributable to amounts previously recognized as income by the executive would be taxed currently even though such amounts would not be taxed currently if the executive had paid that part of the premium directly.
<p>

<blockquote><hr><strong>Further refinements under section 83 would seem to be necessary.</strong><hr></blockquote>

The IRS position announced in the TAM is based on an underlying theory that something of value is being transferred to the executive under equity split dollar arrangements.  The IRS has focused on the increase in cash surrender value as the event resulting in taxable income.  To make this theory better conform to economic reality, the IRS position should be modified to treat only the earnings (reflected in the increase in cash value) <em>attributable to the employer's premiums</em> as being transferred to the executive each year after the cash value exceeds cumulative employer premiums.  However, several amounts should not be viewed as being transferred by the employer to the executive, and therefore should not be taxable currently: 

<ul type=square>
<li>Amounts already taken into income by the executive in prior years.

<li>Earnings (reflected in the increase in cash value) attributable to amounts already taken into income by the executive.

<li>Increases occurring after rollout.
</ul>

<blockquote><hr><strong>Or the IRS might shift to an interest-free loan theory.</strong><hr></blockquote>

Alternatively, the typical equity split dollar arrangement could be viewed as an interest free loan to the executive equal to the cumulative amount of premiums paid by the employer.  Arguably, the IRS rejected the interest-free loan theory in 1964.  However, as the debates progress, the IRS might be forced to adopt that theory as best reflecting economic substance.  
<p>

An interest-free loan theory, if applied, would result in a different amount of taxable income:

<ul type=square>
<li>Presumably the value of the interest-free loan would be includable in the executive's income even in the early years of the arrangement when the executive has no equity in the cash values.
<li>In the later years of the arrangement, the executive would probably have less taxable income than he/she would under TAM 9604001.  This is because the actual return on the cash values would likely exceed the imputed interest on the loan from the employer.
<br>

<blockquote><hr><strong>Other unresolved questions.</strong><hr></blockquote>

A number of other questions come to mind.  For example, how would policy loans be treated under the TAM?  If they are viewed as a reduction in cash values, would an executive escape taxation by borrowing the cash value?  Presumably not, but the IRS TAM provides no clear guidance. 
<p>

Another question is whether taxable income would continue to be calculated under the TAM after a rollout has occurred.  Presumably there would be no taxation under the TAM after the rollout because the arrangement is no longer in force.  But the TAM does not specifically address this question.
<p>

Also, how would the IRS position be applied in the case of a variable life policy where a significant investment loss could be sustained?  Presumably, under the IRS position there would be no taxable income in the year of a decrease in cash value due to investment loss.  Some observers might conclude that the executive should be entitled to a loss deduction equal to the decrease in cash value previously taken into income.
<br>

<blockquote><hr><strong>Conclusions.</strong><hr></blockquote>

These and other unresolved questions will provide a basis for the insurance industry to attack the logic of TAM 9604001.  In the end, it would seem that to be on an intellectually sound basis and to be able to impose any current taxation, the IRS will have to adopt a position that more closely recognizes the economic substance of the transaction.  
<p>

Unless the IRS begins to more closely recognize the economic substance of the transaction, there is a good chance that the insurance industry will be able to obtain a reversal of the IRS position. 
<p>

<hr>

<blockquote><EM>Material in this letter has been abridged from laws and regulations.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of these issues. For this reason, it is imperative that you consult with legal counsel before acting on any matter discussed in this letter.
</EM></blockquote><P>

