<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Proposed IRS Regulations on Plan Loans </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<center>
<img src="irs_regs.gif">
</center>

<blockquote>
January 24, 1996<p align=left>


<H3>TO:	Our Employee Benefits and Employment Law Clients and Friends
RE:  Proposed IRS Regulations on Plan Loans
</H3>

The IRS recently issued proposed regulations regarding loans to participants and beneficiaries from employee benefit plans, including 401(k), profit sharing, money purchase, and 403(b) plans.  The proposed regulations describe the requirements for a plan loan and the tax and reporting consequences triggered by failure to satisfy those requirements.  This letter summarizes the key aspects of the proposed regulations.

<H3>I.   REQUIREMENTS FOR A LOAN
</H3>

<STRONG>Enforceable agreement.</STRONG>  The proposed regulations state that a plan loan must be evidenced by an enforceable agreement that specifies the amount of the loan, the term of the loan, and the repayment schedule.  The agreement can be set forth in more than one document, and can be in writing or in another form that is approved by the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.  This latter provision leaves open the possibility that the IRS will eventually approve paperless loans, such as purely electronic or voice-response loan transactions.  However, for the present, truly paperless loans apparently will not be allowed.<P>

<STRONG>Amount of loan.</STRONG>  In general, the total amount of a participant's outstanding loans on the date a loan is made cannot exceed the lesser of $50,000  reduced by any loan principal repaid within the last 12 months  or 50% of the participant's vested benefit.  The proposed regulations simply note that the loan must satisfy these Internal Revenue Code limits and that the amount of the loan must be set out in the agreement.<P>

<STRONG>Term of loan.</STRONG>  The Code provides that the term of a plan loan cannot exceed five years, unless the loan is used to acquire a dwelling unit which will within a reasonable time be used as the principal residence of the participant.  The proposed regulations define principal residence by reference to the tax rules regarding rollover of a gain on the sale of a principal residence.  They also allow the use of  tracing rules to determine whether the proceeds of a plan loan were used to acquire a principal residence.  For example, if the participant borrows money from a bank to acquire his or her principal residence, and shortly thereafter obtains a plan loan to pay off the bank loan, under the tracing rules the plan loan will be treated as having been used to acquire the residence.  (The proposed regulations also note that, as a general rule, loan refinancings do not qualify as principal residence loans.)<P>

<STRONG>Repayment schedule.</STRONG>  The Code requires that a loan be repaid in substantially equal installments, not less frequently than quarterly, over the term of the loan.  The proposed regulations allow (but do not require) the plan to suspend loan repayments during a participant's unpaid leave of absence of up to one year.  If the participant takes a paid leave, loan repayments may be suspended only if the participant's pay (after tax withholding) is not sufficient to cover the loan payments.  The loan must in any event be repaid in full by the latest date permitted under the Code (i.e., the five-year or principal residence rule).<P>

For example, assume a participant is obligated to make loan payments of $825 a month for five years on a loan that is not a principal residence loan.  Assume also that the participant makes several monthly payments and then takes an unpaid leave of absence for one year.  The proposed regulations state that the plan can suspend the participant's monthly loan payments during the leave.  When the participant returns, the plan can either (1) increase the remaining monthly payments to make up for the missed payments, or (2) allow the participant to continue paying $825 a month, with a balloon payment at the end of the original five-year term.  Because the loan is not a principal residence loan, however, the maximum term of the loan cannot be extended beyond five years.  (The examples in the proposed regulations indicate that the increased periodic payments or the balloon payment would have to include accrued interest on the payments missed during the leave period.)  

<H3>II.   CONSEQUENCES OF FAILURE TO SATISFY LOAN REQUIREMENTS
</H3>

Failure to comply with the IRS loan requirements means that the loan will be treated as a deemed distribution from the plan.  This results in adverse tax consequences for the participant and imposes reporting and possibly withholding requirements on the plan administrator.<P>

Tax consequences of a deemed distribution.  A deemed distribution is treated as an actual distribution for the following federal income tax purposes:

<UL>
<LI>Ordinary income tax.
<LI>The 10% excise tax on premature distributions (generally distributions that are made before the participant reaches age 59½).
<LI>The 15% excise tax on excess distributions from qualified plans (in 1996, distributions which exceed $155,000 during the calendar year).
</UL>


A deemed distribution is not eligible for rollover or income-averaging treatment.<P>

It is important to note that a deemed distribution is not an actual distribution from the plan and does not terminate the underlying loan.  Virtually all plans require a participant to pledge his or her plan account as security for the loan.  When the loan goes into default, however, the plan cannot foreclose on the participant's account until the participant becomes entitled to a distribution from the plan.  At that point, either the note is included as part of the distribution to the participant, or the distribution is offset by the outstanding amount of the loan.<P>

<STRONG>Time and amount of the deemed distribution.</STRONG>  The proposed regulations state that a deemed distribution occurs at the time the requirements for a loan are not satisfied.  If a loan exceeds the Code limits on the amount of a loan, the excess is a deemed distribution.  If a loan does not satisfy the other IRS requirements when made, the deemed distribution is generally the full amount of the loan.  <P>

If the loan calls for monthly payments and the participant misses a monthly payment, the deemed distribution would ordinarily occur when the loan payment is missed.  However, the proposed regulations allow the plan to treat the deemed distribution as occurring at the end of any grace period the plan provides for making loan payments, as long as the grace period does not extend beyond the last day of the calendar quarter following the calendar quarter in which the missed payment was due.  The amount of the deemed distribution is the entire outstanding balance of the loan on the last day payment was due (including interest that accrued during any grace period), not just the amount of the missed payment. <P>

As noted previously, a deemed distribution does not terminate the loan.  Plan administrators frequently ask whether a plan loan that goes into default continues to accrue interest and, if so, whether the unpaid interest that accrues each year results in additional deemed distributions to the participant.  The proposed regulations do not answer this question.  We called the IRS, and an IRS representative indicated that the regulations are silent because there is a difference of opinion within the IRS on the correct answer to this issue.<P>

<STRONG>Reporting.</STRONG>  A deemed distribution is a taxable distribution and must be reported on Form 1099-R.<P>

<STRONG>Withholding.</STRONG>  If a participant defaults on a loan and a deemed distribution results, no withholding is required because no money changes hands at that point.  If a loan is a deemed distribution when made (for example, if it exceeds the five year limit and is not a principal residence loan, or if it calls for annual rather than quarterly payments), then the loan proceeds are subject to the withholding rules for distributions that are not eligible rollover distributions.  The withholding rate would be the 10% rate for non-periodic distributions.  However, the participant can elect to waive the 10% withholding.<P>

<STRONG>Interplay with DOL loan regulations.</STRONG>  In 1989, the Department of Labor issued its own set of regulations governing loans from retirement plans.  Those regulations set out the requirements necessary for a loan to be exempt from ERISA's prohibited transaction provisions.  You should keep in mind that most plans need to comply with both the DOL and IRS regulations.<P>

The IRS regulations discussed above are only proposed regulations.  However, if your plan permits loans to participants, you may want to amend your loan procedures and your note form to take advantage of some of the rules provided in the proposed regulations (such as the grace period).  If you wish to submit comments on the proposed regulations, the deadline is March 20, 1996.<P>
<hr>
If you have any questions about how these proposed loan regulations affect your loan program or about any other employee benefit matter, please call the lawyer in our Firm who is principally responsible for your employee benefits work.<P>

<blockquote><EM>Material in this letter has been abridged from laws and regulations.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of these issues. For this reason, it is imperative that you consult with legal counsel before acting on any matter discussed in this letter.
</EM></blockquote><P>

<h3>Employee Benefits Group</h3>

<STRONG>Minnesota</STRONG><BR> 
(612) 336-3000 or 1-800-328-4393<p>	
Hubert V. Forcier	(612) 336-3135<br>	
Richard A. Nelson	  336-3176<br>	
Douglas J. Heffernan  336-3253<br>	
James E. Bowlus   	336-3405<br>
Paul W. Heiring  336-3339<br>
Randy L. Gegelman  336-3453<br>
Bradley J. Schlichting  336-3433<br>
Pamela S. Schmidt  336-3367<p>

George E. Harding (retired)	336-3106<br>
Ronald B. Hemstad (retired)	  336-3119<p>

<STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG><BR>
(202) 783-3880 or 1-800-628-4322<p>
G. Daniel Miller  (202) 783-3881<br>
David W. Powell  (202) 783-3884<br>
