<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Proposed DOL Regulations Regarding Participant Contributions </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<center>
<img src="dol_regs.gif">
</center>

<blockquote>
January 24, 1996<p align=left>


<H3>TO:	Our Employee Benefits and Employment Law Clients and Friends<P>
RE:  Proposed DOL Regulations Regarding Participant Contributions</h3>



The Department of Labor (DOL) recently released proposed regulations that would revise the rules regarding when participant contributions to an employer sponsored pension or welfare benefit plan become plan assets for purposes of various ERISA rules.  (Under the DOL's interpretation, participant contributions include pre-tax salary reduction contributions to a 401(k) plan or to a health plan through a cafeteria plan arrangement.)  Because of the ERISA fiduciary duty and prohibited transaction rules regarding plan assets, and the ERISA requirement that plan assets must be held in trust (subject to certain exceptions), the proposed regulations could require significant changes in the administration of many plans.<P>

Under current DOL Regulations, participant contributions become plan assets as of the earliest date the contributions can reasonably be segregated from the employer's general assets, but in no event later than 90 days from the date the contributions are received by the employer (e.g., by withholding them from the employee's pay).  The DOL believes that a number of abuses have occurred because employers are violating this rule, at least in part because some employers are under the mistaken impression that the 90 day rule is a safe-harbor.  The proposed regulations would shorten the 90-day outer limit so that the DOL and plan participants can more quickly and easily determine that a violation has occurred.  (Participant contributions would continue to become plan assets as soon as they can reasonably be segregated from the employer's assets if that is earlier than the new outer limit rule described below.)<P>

Under the proposed regulations, participant contributions would become plan assets within the same time frame that the employer is required to segregate and deposit withheld income and employment taxes.  This period is measured from the date such amounts are received by the employer or otherwise would have been payable to the participant in cash (if withheld from pay).  The outer limit would depend on the amount of the employer's withheld income taxes and employment taxes:

<UL>
<LI>If an employer has accumulated $100,000 or more of federal income, Social Security, and Medicare taxes on any date, participant contributions would become plan assets on the next banking day after they are made.  (The DOL specifically invited comments on whether this time frame is appropriate for the regulations.)
<LI>If an employer reported more than $50,000 of federal income, Social Security and Medicare taxes for the 12-month period ending on the previous June 30,  the employer is a semi-weekly depositor.  Under the semi-weekly depositor rules, participant contributions made on Wednesday, Thursday, or Friday would become plan assets no later than the following Wednesday.  Participant contributions made on Saturday, Sunday, Monday, or Tuesday would become plan assets no later than the following Friday.
<LI>If an employer reported $50,000 or less of federal income, Social Security, and Medicare taxes for the 12-month period ending on the previous June 30, the employer is a monthly depositor.  Under the monthly depositor rules, participant contributions made in any calendar month would become plan assets no later than the 15th day of the following month.
</UL>

Absent an applicable exception, plan assets must be held in trust.  Under the proposed regulations, this means that, in general, participant contributions to a retirement plan, health plan, or other welfare benefit plan must be deposited in an ERISA trust, used to pay insurance premiums, or used to pay plan benefits or expenses no later than the time frame described above.  While the preamble to the proposed regulations note that the DOL has previously announced that it will not assert a violation of the ERISA trust requirement in connection with cafeteria plans solely because of the failure to hold participant contributions in trust, it is not clear how long that DOL position will last if the proposed regulations become final.  In any event, it is likely that many health plans would be affected by the proposed regulations, notwithstanding the DOL position regarding cafeteria plans, because the proposed regulations specifically indicate that COBRA premium payments by former employees are subject to the participant contribution plan asset rules.<P>

The DOL has specifically requested comments from employers on whether the proposed regulations would impose an undue burden on plan sponsors.  Written comments must be received by the DOL by February 5, 1996.  A public hearing on the proposed regulations is scheduled to be held February 22, 1996.<P>

The DOL expects to issue final regulations 45 days after the close of the comment period.  As proposed, the regulation would be effective 60 days after a final regulation is published.  This means that final regulations could be effective as early as late May of 1996.  For plan sponsors for whom the revised regulations would require significant changes in plan administration, it may be appropriate to start considering now the potential impact and the feasibility of making changes to comply with the regulations.<P>
<HR>
If you have questions regarding the proposed regulations or their implications for your plans, or if you would like assistance in preparing comments to submit to the DOL, please call the lawyer in our Firm who is principally responsible for your employee benefits work.

      
.<P>

<blockquote><EM>Material in this letter has been abridged from laws and regulations.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of these issues. For this reason, it is imperative that you consult with legal counsel before acting on any matter discussed in this letter.
</EM></blockquote><P>

