<HEAD>
<TITLE> Application of the Family and Medical Leave Act to Cafeteria Plans; Applicable Premiums under COBRA </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<center>
<img src="fmla.gif">
</center>

<blockquote>
January 24, 1996<p align=left>


<H3>TO:	Our Employee Benefits and Employment Law Clients and Friends<P>
RE:  Application of the Family and Medical Leave Act to Cafeteria Plans;<br> Applicable Premiums under COBRA</h3>



The Internal Revenue Service recently issued proposed regulations which discuss the effect the Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA) has on cafeteria plans.  The IRS also recently issued guidance on determining the applicable premium for COBRA health continuation coverage.  This letter describes the proposed cafeteria plan regulations and guidance on COBRA premiums and offers suggestions on how to deal with these issues.

<H3>I.  FMLA AND CAFETERIA PLANS</H3>

<STRONG>Elections.</STRONG>  According to the proposed regulations, an employee who takes FMLA leave has the right to revoke his or her election of group health plan coverage for the remainder of the coverage period.  Upon returning from FMLA leave, the employee must be allowed to reinstate coverage if he or she desires, whether coverage terminated because of revocation or nonpayment of contributions.  The employee's ability to revoke and reinstate also applies to coverage under a health care flexible spending arrangement (FSA).  An employer cannot require an employee to revoke or reinstate coverage.<p>

An employee on FMLA leave can also change his or her cafeteria plan election the same as employees who are not on FMLA leave (e.g., because of a change in family status).  For example, because returning from an unpaid leave normally is a change in family status under a cafeteria plan that allows a change in elections, an employee returning from unpaid FMLA leave could decide to change the amount of coverage elected, as well as reinstate coverage if coverage was revoked during the FMLA leave.<p>

These rules present the possibility that an employee could use the entire amount of elected coverage under a health FSA early in the year, take FMLA leave and revoke coverage, return to work, and decide not to continue coverage under the health FSA, leaving the employer with the bill.  (A similar result could happen automatically if the FMLA leave overlaps the end of a plan year.)  The proposed regulations do not address this issue.  Employers may wish to adjust the maximum amount of coverage allowed under a health FSA to reduce the likelihood of large abuses.  The cafeteria plan rules for changes of elections due to changes in family status should also be reviewed to assure they provide the best result possible.<p>

<STRONG>Payment Options.</STRONG>  Employees who elect to continue coverage during FMLA leave are responsible for the premiums and other contributions they were paying while working.  The proposed regulations give three methods that can be used to make these payments:

<OL>
<LI><U>Pre-pay.</U>  A cafeteria plan may permit (but not require) the employee to pay, prior to the beginning of the leave, the amount due for health plan coverage during the portion of FMLA leave that falls in the remainder of the plan year.  These amounts may be paid on a pre-tax salary reduction basis from any taxable compensation (including unused sick days or vacation days) owed to the employee.  Contributions under this option may also be made on an after-tax basis.
<LI><U>Pay-as-you-go.</U>  Under this option, the employee can make payments on the same schedule as payments would be made if the employee were not on leave.  Payments can also be made under other schedules permitted by the FMLA regulations (e.g., the schedule for premium payments under COBRA).  Such payments are generally made on an after-tax basis, but they may be made on a pre-tax basis to the extent the employee has taxable compensation during the leave (such as cashing out unused sick days and vacation days).
<LI><U>Catch-up.</U>  Under the catch-up method, the employer and employee agree that the employer will make the payments on the employee's behalf during the FMLA leave, and that the employee will repay the employer (on either a pre- or after-tax basis) when the employee returns from FMLA leave.  This option may be unattractive to employers, depending upon the number of individuals who do not return after FMLA leave, and therefore never catch-up.
</OL>


There are some restrictions on which options can be offered.  The pre-pay option cannot be the only option offered.  The catch-up option cannot be the only option offered unless it is the only option offered to employees on non-FMLA leave without pay.  Similarly, the pay-as-you-go option must be offered to employees on FMLA leave if it is offered to employees on non-FMLA leave without pay.  If the employee is on paid FMLA leave, the employee's payments must be made by the method normally used during other paid leave.  The proposed regulations also state that the employer may waive employee payments during FMLA leave on a nondiscriminatory basis.<P>

If the FMLA leave extends into a second cafeteria plan year, employees cannot be allowed to prepay premiums on a pre-tax basis for the second year.  For example, if a cafeteria plan runs on the calendar year, an employee beginning FMLA leave in November can prepay for November and December on a pre-tax basis, but cannot prepay for January on a pre-tax basis.  Instead, the employees would have to use another payment option for January, or prepay for January on an after-tax basis.<P>

<STRONG>Health Care Flexible Spending Arrangements.</STRONG>  Additional rules apply to coverage under a health FSA.  As long as an employee continues coverage under a health FSA, the full amount, less any prior reimbursements, must be available to the employee at all times.  If coverage under a health FSA terminates during FMLA leave, the employee cannot be reimbursed for claims incurred during the period when coverage is terminated.  If such an employee elects to be reinstated upon return from FMLA leave, the employee's coverage is equal to the employee's election for the 12-month period of coverage, prorated for the period of FMLA leave during which no payments were made, and reduced by prior reimbursements.<P>

For example, assume an employee elects $1,200 of coverage for the year, pays premiums of $100 in January and February through pre-tax salary reduction, and takes FMLA leave for March and April, during which coverage is cancelled under the health FSA.  The employee also receives reimbursement for $200 of medical expenses incurred in February.  Upon returning in May, if the employee elects to reinstate coverage under the health FSA, the initial election of $1,200 would be prorated to $1,000 to account for the two months of FMLA leave during which payments were not made.  That amount is further reduced by the reimbursement of $200, leaving the employee with $800 of coverage for the rest of the year and a $100 per month payment.<P>

<STRONG>Non-health Benefits.</STRONG>  FMLA does not require employers to maintain an employee's non-health benefits, such as a dependent care FSA, during FMLA leave.  An employee's right to such benefits (and the right to revoke an election for such benefits) under a cafeteria plan during FMLA leave would be the same as for an employee who is on non-FMLA leave (paid or unpaid).  If coverage for such benefits terminates during the FMLA leave, the employee must be permitted to reinstate coverage upon return.

<H3>II.  APPLICABLE PREMIUMS UNDER COBRA</H3> 

The IRS has also issued a Revenue Ruling on determining the applicable premium for COBRA health continuation coverage.  A plan may charge individuals who continue health care coverage under COBRA up to 102% of the applicable premium.  Applicable premium is defined as the cost to the plan for that period of coverage for similarly-situated beneficiaries who have not experienced a qualifying event entitling them to elect COBRA coverage.<p>

The Revenue Ruling gives examples of the applicable premiums where a plan uses insurance to provide benefits to employees and their dependents and charges either an individual rate (for the employee only) or a family rate (for the employee and his or her dependents).  According to the IRS guidance, the applicable premium in this situation depends on the number of individuals continuing coverage under COBRA, rather than whether the employee is the one who continues coverage.  For example, if an employee with family coverage experiences a qualifying event and elects to continue coverage, the applicable premium would be the family rate if two or more members of the family continue coverage.  However, if only one family member elects to continue coverage, the applicable premium is the individual rate, regardless of whether the individual continuing coverage is the employee, and regardless of whether the insurance company charges the plan the family rate for coverage of an individual other than the employee.<p>

The examples also show that a plan may charge the family rate to two family members who lost coverage because of the same qualifying event, even though individual coverage for each member may be less expensive.  For example, assume the individual rate is $150 per month and the family rate is $400 per month.  If an employee with family coverage for the employee and his or her spouse loses coverage and elects COBRA continuation coverage, the plan can charge the employee and spouse $400 per month for family coverage; it is not limited to charging $300 for two individual rates of coverage.<p>

Although the ruling does not directly address the issue, one could infer that the individual rate could be charged to one family member who elects continuation coverage while other family members who have not had a COBRA qualifying event continue family coverage.  For example, if a divorced employee carries dependent children under the employee's family coverage, but the employee's former spouse elects COBRA coverage, the applicable premium for the former spouse would presumably be the individual rate.

<hr>

If you have any questions about how the proposed regulations and/or COBRA guidance affect the operation of your health care plan, please call the lawyer in our Firm who is principally responsible for your employee benefits work.<P>

