<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Application of the Family and Medical Leave Act to Cafeteria Plans; Applicable Premiums under COBRA </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<center>
<img src="fica.gif">
</center>

<blockquote>
February 21, 1996<p align=left>


<H3>TO:	Our Employee Benefits and Employment Law Clients and Friends<P>
RE:  FICA Taxation of Nonqualified Deferred Compensation</h3>



The IRS recently proposed regulations concerning FICA taxes on amounts deferred under nonqualified deferred compensation plans.  As discussed in our November 9, 1994 letter on this topic, the FICA tax rule is significant because the Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993 removed the cap on wages that are taken into account for the Medicare portion of FICA tax (1.45% for both the employer and employee).  As a result, even though wages exceeding the wage base ($61,200 for 1995 and $62,700 for 1996) are not subject to the old-age, survivor and disability insurance (OASDI) portion of FICA tax, <STRONG>all</STRONG> wages (even those above the wage base) are subject to the Medicare portion of FICA tax.<P>

<STRONG>Timing of FICA Taxes on Nonqualified Deferred Compensation.</STRONG>  Under Section 3121(v)(2) of the Internal Revenue Code, amounts credited to an employee under certain nonqualified deferred compensation plans will be taken into account as FICA wages as of the later of (i) when the services giving rise to the deferred compensation are performed, or (ii) when there is no substantial risk of forfeiture of the employee's right to the payment.  This means that FICA taxes are payable as the deferred compensation <STRONG>accrues</STRONG> (or vests, if later), even though income taxes may not be owed until the deferred amounts are actually paid to the employee.  (A similar rule applies to the federal unemployment tax (FUTA), but it is seldom significant for deferred compensation arrangements because most employees receive cash compensation in excess of the $7,000 FUTA wage base.)<P>

Any deferred compensation is taken into account for FICA taxes only once.  If a deferred amount is taken into account under the special timing rule in the previous paragraph, then neither that amount nor any income attributable to it will be treated as FICA wages at any time in the future.<P>

The proposed regulations provide details for applying the statutory requirements.  In addition to offering guidance on what types of plans actually provide for the deferral of compensation, the proposed regulations permit the use of reasonable assumptions in determining the present value of deferred compensation, establish when deferred compensation is reasonably ascertainable, give employers some flexibility in withholding FICA taxes from deferred compensation, and provide good faith transition rules.<p>

<strong>Nonqualified Deferred Compensation Plan.</strong>  Under the proposed regulations, a nonqualified deferred compensation plan is any plan established and maintained by an employer which provides for the deferral of compensation.  An amount deferred may not be taken into account as FICA wages before the plan (or any amendment increasing deferral amount) is established.  This occurs on the latest of the date on which it is adopted, the date on which it is effective, or the date on which the material terms (<EM>e.g.</EM>, the amount of deferred compensation and when that amount will be paid) are set forth in writing.  A deferral of compensation occurs when an employee has a legally binding right during a calendar year to compensation that has not been actually or constructively received and that is payable in a later year, notwithstanding that the right is subject to a vesting requirement or other contingencies.  The regulations specifically discuss the following types of plans:

<ul type=square>
<li><strong>Short-term deferrals.</strong>  If an amount is deferred to a date that is no more than a brief period of time after the end of the calendar year in which the amount was earned (up to 2½ months), the employer is not required to treat that amount as deferred compensation.
<P>
<li><strong>Stock options and stock appreciation rights.</strong>  An amount received as a stock value right is not deferred compensation and therefore is subject to FICA tax only when the right is actually exercised.  The regulations define a stock value right as a right granted to an employee with respect to employer stock that, when exercised, entitles the employee to a payment equal to the excess (or a percentage of the excess) of the value of the share on the date of exercise over a specified price.  Stock options and stock appreciation rights are examples of stock value rights.  Thus, a stock option is not considered deferred compensation and is subject to FICA tax when the option is exercised, rather than when it is granted.  
<P>
<li><strong>Phantom stock.</strong>  On the other hand, deferred compensation does include an award under a phantom stock plan, which typically is equal to the full fair market value of a specific number of shares of employer stock, as opposed to an award equal to the excess of that fair market value over a specified price.  Thus, a phantom stock plan does provide deferred compensation, and FICA tax is due each year when an amount is credited to the employee.
<P>
<li><strong>Restricted stock.</strong>  There is no deferral of compensation merely because the value of restricted property or stock is not includible in income in the year of receipt by reason of the property or stock being nontransferable and subject to a substantial risk of forfeiture.  Thus, an award of restricted stock is not subject to FICA tax in the year of the award but rather when the stock is no longer subject to a substantial risk of forfeiture.
<P>
<li><strong>Welfare benefits and severance pay.</strong>  The regulations make clear that certain welfare benefits, including severance pay, vacation benefits, sick leave, disability pay, and death benefits are not considered deferred compensation and are not subject to the special timing rule.  A plan is deemed to provide severance pay if (i) the payments are not contingent upon the employee's retirement, (ii) the total amount of such payments does not exceed the equivalent of twice the employee's most recent annual compensation, and (iii) all such payments are completed within 24 months.  Termination plans not meeting these requirements may provide severance pay, depending upon the relevant facts and circumstances.  Any payment will be considered severance pay if it is available only upon the employee's involuntary termination.  
<P>
<li><strong>Benefits provided in contemplation of termination.</strong>  Benefits provided in connection with impending termination of employment are not deferred compensation.  These include window benefits (<EM>e.g.</EM>, early retirement benefits, retirement-type subsidies, and social security supplements) and plans where the employee terminates employment within 12 months of the establishment of the plan and the facts and circumstances indicate that the plan was established in contemplation of such termination.
<P>
<li><strong>Golden parachutes.</strong>  The special timing rule does not apply to golden parachute plans.
</ul>

<STRONG>Determining the amount deferred.</STRONG>  The regulations divide nonqualified deferred compensation plans into account balance plans and nonaccount balance plans.  For account balance plans, where deferrals and income on those deferrals are credited to the employee's individual account, the amount deferred which is subject to FICA tax equals the principal amount credited to the account.  Reasonable income attributable to amounts on which FICA tax was already paid is not considered deferred compensation and is not subject to FICA tax.  If, however, an unreasonable rate of interest or other index is used to determine income, then the income attributable to the principal amount is limited to the income that would result from applying the mid-term applicable federal rate.  Any income in excess of reasonable income will be considered deferred compensation (and subject to FICA tax) in the year it is credited to the account.<p>

For nonaccount balance plans, which are defined benefit-type plans, the amount deferred for a period equals the present value of the additional future payments to which the employee has obtained a legally binding right during that period.  Employers may use any reasonable actuarial assumptions and methods to determine the present value of these benefits.  Again, reasonable income on accruals under nonaccount balance plans that were previously included as FICA wages will not be subject to FICA tax when received.<p>

<STRONG>Amounts not reasonably ascertainable.</STRONG>  The regulations allow the employer to delay when a deferred amount is taken into account as FICA wages if any portion of the amount deferred is not reasonably ascertainable.  The amount of deferred compensation in a nonaccount balance plan may fluctuate depending on changes in contribution limits for qualified plans, the amount of the employee's future compensation, the date on which payments commence, or the form of benefit elected by the employee.  Deferred compensation subject to such contingencies becomes reasonably ascertainable only when no actuarial or other assumptions, other than interest, mortality, and cost-of-living assumptions, are needed to determine the amount deferred.  On the resolution date, the date when all contingencies have been determined and only interest, mortality, and cost-of-living adjustments need to be assumed, the present value of the amount calculated to be deferred must be taken into account as FICA wages.<p>

Employers have the option of estimating the eventual amount of the deferred compensation and taking it into account on an early inclusion date.  (One might wish to do this to avoid FICA taxes on the income of the deferrals.)  In this case, however, adjustments must be made later if the estimate is not accurate.<p>

<STRONG>Withholding.</STRONG>  Employers are required to withhold FICA tax from nonqualified deferred compensation only once a year, but may withhold more often.  If an amount cannot be calculated by the last day of the year, the employer may use an estimated method or a lag method to withhold FICA tax.  Under the estimated method, the employer simply takes an estimate of the deferred compensation into account as FICA wages for the year and makes adjustments later.  Under the lag method, the employer calculates the total deferred in the previous year and treats that amount as FICA wages in the first quarter of the next year.<P>

<STRONG>Transition rules.</STRONG>  The proposed regulations state that they will be in effect for compensation deferred on or after January 1, 1997.  For amounts deferred before 1997, an employer may operate under any reasonable, good faith interpretation of section 3121(v).  Four specific transition rules cover situations where compensation was mistakenly treated as deferred or not deferred or where the amount of deferred compensation actually paid to an employee on a later date was miscalculated.  The IRS generally allows a claim for refund for overpayments of FICA taxes and allows adjustments to be made for underpayments, provided the employer used a reasonable, good faith interpretation of the law.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
If you have questions regarding the proposed regulations or their implications for any nonqualified deferred compensation plans of your company, or if you would like assistance in preparing comments to submit to the IRS, please call the lawyer in our Firm who is principally responsible for your employee benefits work.  Written comments on the proposed regulations and requests for a public hearing must be received by the IRS by April 24, 1996..<P>

<blockquote><EM>Material in this letter has been abridged from laws and regulations.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of these issues. For this reason, it is imperative that you consult with legal counsel before acting on any matter discussed in this letter.
</EM></blockquote><P>

