<p>

<blockquote>

<FONT SIZE=+1>This brochure briefly describes our experience and
expertise in ERISA litigation.<p>

<A HREF="#capa">Our ERISA Litigation Capabilities</A><br>

<A HREF="#repre">Representation of Employers in ERISA Litigation</A><br>

<A HREF="#cases">Published Cases</A></FONT><p>

&copy; 1995, Faegre & Benson LLP<p>

<A NAME="capa"></A><CENTER><H2>Our ERISA Litigation Capabilities
</H2></CENTER>
<H3>Nationally Recognized Expertise</H3>
Faegre & Benson is a leading law firm in the area of ERISA litigation.  Our ERISA litigators have expertise in all areas of ERISA and employee benefits law, and when necessary can consult with other lawyers in the firm who are expert in the areas of tax law, insurance law, securities law, banking and trust law, employ-ment law, and bankruptcy law.  This interdisciplinary approach allows us to provide experienced representation for any type of ERISA case.<P>

The firm has been recognized nationally for its expert-ise in ERISA matters.  A recent survey in International Corporate Law ranked Faegre & Benson in the top ten in the nation in the ERISA & Pension category. 

<H3>Efficient Case Staffing</H3>
Case staffing varies depending on the issues presented, the size of the claim and the client's needs.  Many cases are staffed with a single ERISA litigation attorney.  Larger matters, such as class action lawsuits, may require additional lawyers.  We are committed to providing cost-effective representation and work closely with clients to ensure that files are properly staffed.

<H3>ERISA Litigation Experience</H3>
We have represented clients in a wide variety of ERISA litigation, including:

<UL type=square>
<LI>Breach of fiduciary duty claims.
<LI>Disputes between plans and their service providers.
<LI>Benefit claims under retirement plans, severance pay plans, and life, health and disability plans (self-funded and insured).
<LI>Fiduciary insurance matters.
<LI>Withdrawal liability and delinquent con-tribution claims.
<LI>Claims involving multiple employer arrange-ments, including MEWAs.
<LI>Benefit discrimination and other employment-related claims under Section 510 of ERISA.
<LI>Bankruptcy Court matters involving employers, providers or participants.
<LI>Disputes with the Department of Labor, the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation and the Internal Revenue Service.
</UL>

The firm handles all stages of employee benefit/ERISA litigation, from litigation prevention to appeals.  We also assist clients by providing advice on plan admini-strative procedures to avoid or minimize liability.

<H3>ERISA Litigation Database</H3>

We have developed an in-house ERISA litigation database containing the full text of all briefs, memo-randa, and seminar materials written by members of the ERISA litigation team.  The database is full-text searchable so that lawyers doing research and writing briefs do not have to continually reinvent the wheel.  The database also contains summaries of all Supreme Court ERISA cases, and all of the recent ERISA cases from the Eighth Circuit and District of Minnesota.

<H3>The Firm</H3>
Founded in Minneapolis in 1886, Faegre & Benson is one of the 100 largest law firms in the United States.  The firm consists of over 270 lawyers practicing in virtually all areas of law from offices located in/<p>
<center>
<img src="wrld_map.gif">
</center><P>
In ERISA-related matters, Faegre & Benson has regularly represented employers, plans, insurance companies, bank trust departments, trust companies, brokerage firms, actuaries, Taft-Hartley plan trustees, and other types of service providers.

<A NAME="repre"></A><CENTER><h2>Representation of Employers in ERISA Litigation</h2></CENTER>
	
<H3>Type of Claims</H3>

Employers that offer plans providing retirement, health, life, severance or other employee benefits are increasingly being sued in connection with those plans.
<P>

Claims can be brought by participants or their beneficiaries for benefits denied by the plan administrator because of disputes over either the facts or the appropriate interpretation of plan terms.  Sometimes employees or their beneficiaries claim that the plan should have been designed in a way that would have provided the benefit they seek.  Sometimes a claimant alleges that the employer failed to give adequate information or notices, such as failure to provide notices regarding health coverage continuation rights, or failure to provide an adequate summary plan description.  Frequently, these claims are mixed with other types of claims against the employer, such as wrongful discharge or employment discrimination based on age, sex, or disability.
<P>

Claims can also be brought by plan participants or the Department of Labor for improperly carrying out various duties with respect to benefit plans, including:

<UL type=square>
<LI>Breach of fiduciary duty for imprudent investments or imprudent selection of other fiduciaries or service providers (e.g., trustees, investment managers, insurance companies, recordkeepers or claims administrators).
<LI>Failure to operate the plan for the exclusive purpose of providing benefits to participants or their beneficiaries.
<LI>Engaging in ERISA prohibited transactions with plan assets.
<LI>Failure to file annual reports and make other disclosures required by ERISA, or to otherwise follow procedures required by ERISA.
</UL>

An employer may also find it necessary to sue a plan fiduciary or other service provider for wrongful acts or omissions in connection with the employer's plans.

<H3>Specialized Knowledge</H3>

Representing employers in litigation involving employee benefit plans requires specialized knowledge -- knowledge of special ERISA procedures and remedies; knowledge of the interaction of various employment and labor laws with ERISA and tax laws related to employee benefit plans; knowledge of the duties, responsibilities and liabilities imposed by ERISA on employers and other fiduciaries; and knowledge of the design and operation of employee benefit plans.

We are well-versed on ERISA litigation issues, including:

<UL type=square>
<LI>Federal subject matter jurisdiction and removal under the complete preemption doctrine.
<LI>ERISA's special venue, service of process and standing provisions.
<LI>ERISA preemption and the scope of the savings clause for laws regulating insurance, banking and securities.
<LI>The standard of review.
<LI>Failure to exhaust administrative remedies.
<LI>Availability of punitive and other extra-contractual damages.
<LI>Recovery of attorneys' fees.
</UL>


Faegre & Benson has the expertise necessary to represent employers successfully in all types of ERISA litigation.  As is demonstrated from the list of published cases on the next page, Faegre & Benson has handled many of these kinds of cases.

<A NAME="cases"></A><CENTER><H2>Published Cases</H2></CENTER>

Many of the cases we have litigated have been published in federal and state reporters, including:

<UL type=square>
<LI><EM>American Federation of Grain Millers v. International Multifoods Corporation</EM>, 1993 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 9420 (W.D.N.Y. 1993) (class action brought by union-represented retirees challenging the cutback of retiree medical benefits on ERISA and LMRA grounds).  
<LI><EM>Basich v. Board of Pensions of the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America</EM>, 493 N.W.2d 293 (Minn. App. 1992) (derivative action by plan participants alleging misuse of pension funds to promote social and political goals of church), and ____ N.W.2d ____, 1995 WL 697382 (Minn. App. 1995) (separate breach of contract action by individual  plan participants involving similar allegations).
<LI><EM>Bennett v. Soo Line Railroad Co.</EM>, 35 F.3d 334 (8th Cir. 1994) (class action to enforce the pension-related terms of an asset purchase agreement).
<LI><EM>Childers v. Northwest Airlines, Inc.</EM>, 688 F. Supp. 1357 (D. Minn. 1988) (case alleging that airline breached its fiduciary duty when it adopted amendments to the airline's ESOP that resulted in cessation of future benefit accruals for certain employees).  
<LI><EM>Erickson v. Aetna Life Ins. Co.</EM>, 777 F. Supp. 1463 (D. Minn. 1991)  (an ERISA welfare plan case in which the plaintiff sought to recover ongoing medical benefits totaling more than $60,000 per year for an 18-year-old boy in a persistent vegetative state; the plan at issue contained no lifetime maximum).  
<LI><EM>Hunt v. Magnell</EM>, 766 F. Supp. 727 (D. Minn. 1990)  (suit by the current trustees of a plan against several former trustees for contribution).  
<LI><EM>Leavitt v. Northwestern Bell Telephone Co.</EM>, 921 F.2d 160 (8th Cir. 1990)  (action alleging breach of fiduciary duty by former employee claiming entitlement to benefits under severance plan).  
<LI><EM>Maxa v. John Alden Life Ins. Co.</EM>, 972 F.2d 980 (8th Cir. 1992), <U>cert. denied</U> 113 S.Ct. 1048 (1993)  (case involving the coordination of plan benefits with Medicare and an allegedly faulty summary plan description).  
<LI><EM>Minnesota Chamber of Commerce & Industry v. Hatch</EM>, 627 F. Supp. 393 (D. Minn. 1987)  (challenge to a state statute requiring employers with self-funded health plans to post a surety bond guaranteeing benefits).  
<LI><EM>MNVA Railroad v. John Alden Life Ins. Co.</EM>, 507 N.W.2d 15 (Minn. App. 1993)  (case in which plaintiffs alleged they were fraudulently induced to enter into a group health plan).  
<LI><EM>Pension Committee for Farmstead Foods Pension Plan v. PBGC</EM>, 778 F. Supp. 1020 (D. Minn. 1991), <U>aff'd</U> 991 F.2d 1415 (8th Cir. 1993)  (action involving a pension plan that was involuntarily terminated by the PBGC).
<LI><EM>Peterson v. Norwest Corporation</EM>, 1988 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 16766 (D. Minn. 1988)  (wrongful discharge case in which plaintiff alleged, among other things, that she had been discharged to prevent her pension from vesting).  
<LI><EM>Richards v. Union Labor Life Ins. Co.</EM>, 804 F. Supp. 1101 (D. Minn. 1992)  (lawsuit involving a multiemployer pension plan in which plaintiffs made claims against actuary for negligence, malpractice, breach of contract and breach of fiduciary duty, and also made a claim under the federal common law of ERISA).
<LI><EM>Weisenhorn v. Transamerica Occidental Life Ins. Co.</EM>,  769 F. Supp. 302 (D. Minn. 1991)  (ERISA welfare plan case in which plaintiff sought life insurance benefits and attorneys' fees). 
</UL>

</blockquote>
