<HEAD>
<TITLE> IRS rules on "deregistration" of U.S. qualified plan </title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>
<h2>IRS Rules On "Deregistration" of U.S. Qualified Plan</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Randy Gegelman</h4>

<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>t has become increasingly difficult to structure a pension plan so that it satisfies both the "qualification" requirements of U.S. law and the "registration" requirements of Canadian law.   A recent private letter ruling issued by the IRS (PLR 9537028, June 21, 1995) demonstrates the tax complications that can result when an employer determines that it is no longer possible to do so and allows "deregistration" of a plan in Canada.<P>

PLR 9537028 involved a situation where the Canadian affiliate of a U.S. company contributed to a U.S. qualified profit sharing plan on behalf of its employees in Canada.  The plan was "registered" in Canada prior to 1992, which entitled the Canadian employees to defer tax on contributions made to the plan and on earnings within the plan.  However, as a result of changes made to the tax laws in Canada, it was determined that it would no longer be possible to comply with both the registration requirements in Canada and the qualification requirements in the U.S.  The Canadian affiliate thus established a separate registered plan in Canada and removed its employees from the U.S. qualified plan.<P>

The employer wished to allow the Canadian employees to receive a distribution from the U.S. qualified profit sharing plan while it was still registered in Canada.  This would permit the employees to roll the distribution amount over into a "locked-in" Registered Retirement Savings Plan ("RRSP")  (which is comparable to an IRA in the U.S.) and thus defer tax in Canada until subsequent distributions were made from the RRSP.<P>

The U.S. tax laws imposed a significant obstacle to the proposed course of action.  Section 871(a) of the U.S. Internal Revenue Code ("Code") imposes a 30% tax on amounts received by a nonresident alien as wages, interest, dividends, etc. to the extent that the amounts received are "from sources within" the U.S. but are not "effectively connected" with the conduct of a trade or business in the U.S.   This 30% tax can be reduced by treaty.<P>

An employer contribution to a pension or profit sharing plan generally is viewed as compensation to the employee on whose behalf the contribution is made.  If the services giving rise to the compensation are performed outside the U.S. the compensation is not "from sources within" the U.S.  In the situation addressed in the PLR, therefore, the portion of the distribution reflecting employer contributions would not be taxed in the U.S. because the contributions were for services performed outside the U.S.   However, the investment earnings within the trust would have been income from sources within the U.S. and thus would be subject to tax in the U.S. under Code section 871(a) when distributed.  [Note:  The investment earnings were not effectively connected with a trade or business in the U.S.]  [Note also:  The Canada-U.S. Treaty reduces the tax rate to 15% in this circumstance.]<P>

To avoid any tax in the U.S., the employer proposed to structure the distributions to fit within an exception to Code section 871(a).  The exception, found in Code section 871(f), provides that tax is not imposed in the U.S. on "any amount received as an annuity" from a U.S. qualified plan if (i) all the personal services for which the annuity is payable were performed by a nonresident alien outside the U.S., and (ii) at the time the first amount is paid as an annuity, 90% or more of the employees covered by the plan are citizens or residents of the U.S.   Conditions (i) and (ii) could be met, but the distribution still would have to be structured as an "annuity" to fit within Code section 871(f).<P>

In an attempt to fit within the "annuity" definition, the employer proposed that payments be made in five equal quarterly installments with each installment computed at the outset of the distribution period based on a projected rate of return on investments.  The rate would be one percentage point below the rate of return on a GIC Fund in which the amounts to be distributed would actually be invested.  A sixth payment would be made if the actual return on the GIC Fund exceeded the projected rate used to calculate the distributions (which would almost certainly occur).<P>
  
The IRS concluded that the five quarterly installments were annuity payments and thus would be exempt from tax in the U.S. under Code section 871(f).  The IRS further concluded that the sixth payment was not an annuity payment, and thus would be taxable in the U.S. under Code section 871(a) because the Code section 871(f) exception did not apply to it.  The plan administrator was thus required to withhold 15% (the Code section 871(a) rate as modified by the Canada-U.S. Treaty) on the sixth payment.  <P>

The Canadian employees thus were subject to U.S. tax on the payment from the U.S. qualified plan.  The Canadian employees could not recapture this amount by filing a tax return in the U.S.<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Randy Gegelman by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:rgegelma@faegre.com"><EM>rgegelma@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

