<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Crediting Foreign Service and Compensation Under an RPP </title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>
<h2>Crediting Foreign Service and Compensation Under an RPP</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Randy Gegelman</h4>

<FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT> Canadian employee may be called upon by his/her employer from time to time to render services outside of Canada.  This temporary employment outside of Canada may be directly for the Canadian employer or for an affiliate of the Canadian employer (for example, a parent or subsidiary in the U.S.).  If the employee participates in a registered pension plan ("RPP"), he/she may wish to continue that participation while performing services outside of Canada.

<H5>Credit for employment outside of Canada in not permitted under the general rules.</H5>
 
An RPP can, as a general rule, provide benefits only with respect to services in Canada  this general rule is set out in Section 8503(3)(a) of the Income Tax Regulations.  In addition, Section 147.1 of the Income Tax Act (Canada) allows Revenue Canada to revoke the registration of a plan if the Pension Adjustment ("PA") of any member of the plan exceeds 18% of his/her compensation, with compensation being limited to amounts received from a participating employer while the member is resident in Canada.   <P>

Section 8507 of the Income Tax Regulations, however, allows an RPP to "prescribe" compensation to a member during any period that qualifies as an "eligible period of temporary absence."   The amount that can be prescribed generally is the amount that would have been paid by the participating employer if the member had continued working for that employer on a regular basis. <P>

Although prescribed compensation counts for purposes of calculating a PA, the regulations allowing compensation to be prescribed may not be helpful for foreign service because the period of foreign service may not qualify as an "eligible period of temporary absence," or because the actual compensation received for such service is greater than the compensation that can be prescribed.

<H5>Revenue Canada has created an exception.</H5>

Crediting service and/or full compensation under a defined benefit RPP for employment outside of Canada thus is possible only because Revenue Canada has created limited exceptions to the above general rules.  These exceptions are set out in Pension Reform Update 93-2.

<H5>Credit for eligible service outside of Canada</H5>

Revenue Canada allows unlimited credit to be given under a defined benefit RPP for  service outside of Canada if the service is for a Canadian employer that participates in the RPP and the member is, or has been, resident in Canada.  This covers the situation where a Canadian citizen or resident renders service for a foreign branch of a Canadian company.

Revenue Canada also allows credit to be given under a defined benefit RPP for service outside of Canada if the service is for a foreign affiliate of a Canadian employer (the foreign affiliate generally will not participate in the RPP) and the member is, or has been, resident in Canada and has previously rendered service for a participating employer in Canada.  In this case, however, service credit is limited to the first three years of service outside of Canada (the three-year period can start over again if the employee returns to Canada and renders service for a participating employer in Canada for at least 12 months).  In addition, only current service credit is allowed, not past service credit.

<H5>Credit for compensation earned for service outside of Canada
</H5>
If credit is permitted for service outside of Canada, the compensation received for such service generally can be counted in determining the members PA.  If the compensation is received from a foreign affiliate (which generally will not participate in the RPP), the compensation is attributed to a participating employer in the RPP for purposes of calculating the PA.  [Note: Compensation cannot be counted twice  once under Section 8507 of the Income Tax Regulations allowing compensation to be prescribed during an "eligible period of temporary absence," and again under the special rules in Update 93-2.]<P>

<H4>Money Purchase RPP</H4>

In the case of a money purchase RPP,  Revenue Canada will review requests to count the actual compensation received by a foreign affiliate for purposes of calculating the PA on a case-by-case basis.<P>

The difference can be very significant if Canadian or other foreign workers sometimes perform services in the U.S.  It can also be very significant for particular industries, such as the rail industry.<P>

U.S. employers should consider amending their U.S. qualified plans to make full use of the permissible exclusion.  If the employer wishes to go farther and exclude additional nonresident aliens, the plan must specifically do so.  However, any exclusion beyond the permissible exclusion noted above may be limited by the coverage rules under Code section 410(b).<P>


<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Randy Gegelman by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:rgegelma@faegre.com"><EM>rgegelma@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

<HR>

