<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Employees Profit Sharing Plans (EPSPs) </title>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<h2>Employees Profit Sharing Plans (EPSPs)</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Randy Gegelman</h4>

<FONT SIZE=+2>C</FONT>anada has two types of profit sharing plans  deferred profit sharing plans (DPSP) and employees profit sharing plans (EPSP).

<p>

Both are similar to a profit sharing plan in the U.S.  However, only a DPSP has the same tax advantages to an employee as a qualified profit sharing plan in the U.S.

<P>

A DPSP and EPSP each allow employees (or a designated group of employees) to share in the profits of a business.  Each year amounts are paid to a trust to be held and invested for the members in the plan.  However, contributions to an EPSP are taxable to employees when made to the trust, as are earnings allocated to the employees' accounts under the EPSP.  This is not the case for a DPSP or a qualified profit sharing plan in the U.S.  In these plans, contributions and earnings are tax-deferred.

<P>

<UL>
<LI>An EPSP is not a registered plan
<LI>An EPSP is not a registered plan in Canada (or it is not a qualified plan using tax law parlance in the U.S.).  
<LI>An EPSP trust is tax exempt
</UL>


Even though an EPSP is not a registered plan, its trust is tax exempt under Section 144(2) of the Income Tax Act (Canada).  This is the principal tax advantage of an EPSP.  If a plan does not qualify as an EPSP, its trust would be taxable.

<p>

<H4>Contributions must be computed by reference to profits
</H4>

To qualify as an EPSP, contributions made under the plan must either be computed by reference to profits, or made out of profits.  If contributions are "out of profits," the employer must file an election under Section 144(10) of the Income Tax Act (Canada)to have the plan treated as an EPSP.  An election is not necessary if contributions are "computed by reference to profits."<P>

Contributions are computed by reference to profits if the employer is obligated to make contributions under a formula where profits are the principal variable.  The formula must define the contribution as a percentage of profits and this percentage cannot be less than 1%.<P>

A plan will qualify as an EPSP if it provides for contributions out of profits and the employer files an election under section 144(10) of the Income Tax Act (Canada) to treat the plan as an EPSP.  Contributions must still be made under a formula set forth in the plan.  The formula can be:

<UL>
<LI>A percentage of pay per person.
<LI>A fixed dollar amount per person.
<LI>A matching contribution made on employee contributions.
</UL>


The formula can define a minimum employer contribution with additional contributions made at the discretion of the employer.  However, the employer contribution under the formula must be more than nominal  they generally must be at least 1% of pay or $100.

<H4>Earnings of all participating affiliates can be counted</H4>

In determining whether profits exist in order to make a contribution to an EPSP, the earnings and profits of all participating affiliates can be aggregated.  If an affiliate does not participate in an EPSP  that is, if its employees are not covered  the profits of that affiliate must be ignored.

<H4>Employee contributions allowed (but not deductible)</H4>

An EPSP may allow employee contributions, but such contributions are not deductible under the Income Tax Act (Canada) as would employee contributions to a Group RRSP.

<H4>Vesting schedules</H4>

An EPSP may impose a vesting requirement on benefits  for example, the plan could require continued employment for five years to receive a benefit.  However, contributions made on behalf of an employee (and allocated earnings) are taxable to the employee whether or not such amounts are vested when allocated.  If an employee later forfeits an amount, he/she may be allowed a deduction under Section 144(9) of the Income Tax Act (Canada) for the forfeited amount previously included in income.  Even so, a forfeiture provision is not an attractive provision for employees.

<H4>Investments in employer stock</H4>

An EPSP can be invested in stock of the sponsoring employer.  If an EPSP invests in employer stock, the stock must be purchased on the  open market and not contributed to the trust.  This is because the employer will be denied a deduction for contributions made to an EPSP in the form of its stock, and also will be denied a deduction for all cash contributions that are used to purchase treasury shares from the employer.

<H4>Section 144(10) Election</H4>

For a plan that makes contributions out of profits to be an EPSP, an election must be made under Section 144(10) of the Income Tax Act (Canada).  The election must be made by each affiliate that participates in the plan.  If an affiliate is added but it does not file the Section 144(10) election, the plan may be disqualified as an EPSP retroactive to the date the affiliate is added.

<H4>Reporting</H4>

The trustee of an EPSP (or the sponsoring employer) is required to report to participants the amounts allocated to their accounts during the year.  This is reported on Form T4PS Summary and Supplementary, which is also filed with Revenue Canada.<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Randy Gegelman by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:rgegelma@faegre.com"><EM>rgegelma@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

<HR>

Last changed 19-December-95<p>

