<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Planning for Lifetime Distributions from Qualified Plans and IRAs </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Planning for Lifetime Distributions from Qualified Plans and IRAs</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Randy Gegelman</h4>


<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he principal retirement vehicle and an important estate planning vehicle for the owners of a family business may be the qualified pension or profit sharing plan maintained by that business.  A family business owner  may wish to keep money in that qualified plan as long as possible to take full advantage of the tax-deferral provided by the plan or to accumulate as much as possible for his/her heirs upon death.  The same may be true for assets held in an individual retirement account (IRA), whether those assets have accumulated through annual contributions or by means of a rollover from a qualified plan.   However, the ability to keep money in a qualified plan or IRA is limited by minimum distribution and incidental death benefit rules imposed under the tax laws. 

<p>

The minimum distribution and incidental death benefit rules are very technical.  However, to take full advantage of the tax deferral and estate planning opportunities offered by a qualified plan or IRA (and to avoid pitfalls), at least a general understanding of these rules is essential for any person who has substantial assets accumulated in such arrangements.   To take full advantage of the rules,  you must make certain elections in a timely manner.

<p>

Because most family businesses maintain defined contribution - profit sharing, 401(k) - plans, this article is limited to a discussion of such plans, and also to IRAs.

<p>

<H4>Minimum Distribution Rule</H4>

The minimum distribution rule generally requires that a participant in a qualified plan or IRA receive at least a minimum distribution from the plan or IRA each year beginning with the year in which he/she reaches age 70-1/2.  This minimum amount must be paid from the plan or IRA by December 31 of that year.  [Note:  A special rule allows the minimum distribution amount due for the year in which the participant reaches age 70-1/2 (and that year only) to be delayed to as late as April 1 of the next year - this April 1 date is called the required beginning date.]

<p>

If a minimum distribution amount is not timely paid from a qualified plan or IRA, the participant (the payee) is subject to a 50% penalty tax on the amount that should have been distributed but was not.  [Note:  In the case of an employer  plan, the qualified status of the plan is also in jeopardy.]

<p>

The minimum distribution amount each year is generally calculated under the following formula:

<blockquote>
Account Balance at
  the End of the Prior Year  
<STRONG>/</STRONG>Applicable Life Expectancy
</blockquote>

The applicable life expectancy used in the denominator of the fraction depends upon the elections made by the individual under the qualified plan or IRA.  [Note:  It is possible, though not common, for a qualified plan to limit the elections available to a participant in order to ease administration.]

<p>

A participant is allowed the following elections:

<UL>
<LI><LI>The participant can elect to have minimum distributions paid over his/her single life expectancy or paid over the joint life expectancy of him/her and a designated beneficiary.
<LI>The participant can elect to have his/her life expectancy recalculated each year, or not recalculated.
<LI>The participant can elect to have the life expectancy of his/her spouse beneficiary recalculated each year, or not recalculated.  [Note: The life expectancy of a nonspouse beneficiary cannot be recalculated.]
</UL>


If a life expectancy is not recalculated, it is simply reduced by one each year.  The applicable life expectancy for a given year is the starting life expectancy when the participant reached age 70-1/2 minus the number of years that have elapsed since age 70-1/2.

<P>

If a life expectancy is recalculated, the applicable life expectancy is redetermined each year from life expectancy tables.  Although the life expectancy of a given person is shorter than it was a year before, it is not shorter by a full year (it may be shorter by 6 or 9 months, for example).

<P>

The consequence of recalculating life expectancy is that it may substantially extend the payout period and thus allow longer tax deferral.

<P>

There is a cost to having life expectancy recalculated.  If the life expectancy of a person is being recalculated, when that person dies, his/her life expectancy drops to zero in the next year.  This does not happen if life expectancy is simply being reduced by one, and a drop to zero  greatly accelerates the payout period.

<P>

Charts A and B (below) illustrate the payout stream that would be required from a qualified plan or IRA if life expectancies are and are not recalculated.  In Chart A both the participant and spouse survive the full payout period (an unlikely event).  In Chart B both the participant and spouse die in the 14th year of the payout period.  The full account balance must be paid out the next year if life expectancies are being recalculated (but not if they are not being recalculated).

<P>

<center><H2>Chart A</H2>
<H3>Both Survive Full Payout Period</H3></center>
<img src="chart_a.gif">
<p>
<center><H2>Chart B</H2>
<H3>Both Die in 14th Year of Payout Period</H3></center>
<img src="chart_b.gif">


<H4>Incidental Death Benefit Rule
</H4>

The incidental death benefit rule operates the same way as the minimum distribution rule.  However, the incidental death benefit rule generally restricts payouts only if the designated beneficiary is someone other than the spouse of the participant, and then only if the designated beneficiary is 10 or more years younger than the participant. 

<P>

The minimum distribution amount each year under the incidental death benefit rule is generally calculated under the following formula:

<blockquote>
Account Balance at
the End of the Prior Year<STRONG>/</STRONG>
Applicable Divisor
</blockquote>

The applicable divisor used in the denominator of the fraction is determined under IRS tables.  It generally is the same as the joint life expectancy of the participant and a designated beneficiary who is 10 years younger than the participant.

<p>

The consequence of the incidental death benefit rule is that, if a beneficiary is designated who is more than 10 years younger than the participant, it shortens the minimum distribution period.  Chart C (below) illustrates the payout stream that would be required from a qualified plan or IRA under the minimum distribution rule alone, and under the incidental death benefit rule alone, assuming that a participant designates his/her child as beneficiary and the beneficiary is 25 years younger than the participant.  The payout required in any year is the greater of the two amounts for that year.

<p>

<center><H2>Chart C</H2>
</center>
<img src="chart_c.gif">

<H4>Other Considerations</H4>

Merely taking the minimum amount necessary to satisfy the minimum distribution and incidental death benefit rules may create other tax problems for an individual.  For example, subject to exceptions, the federal tax laws impose a 15% penalty tax on distributions from all qualified plans and IRAs in any year in excess of $150,000 (indexed for inflation).  Taking only the minimum distribution amount in early years may cause the minimum distribution in later years to exceed $150,000 (as indexed for inflation to that year) and thus be subject to the penalty tax.  Further, a 15% penalty tax is imposed on a deceased individual's excess retirement accumulation.  Very generally, an excess retirement accumulation is the excess of the value at death of the participant's interest in all qualified plans and IRAs over the value of a single life annuity with annual payments equal to the $150,000 threshold noted above (as indexed).  Taking only the minimum distribution amount may result in an excess retirement accumulation at death.

<p>

<H4>Conclusion</H4>

For the owner of a family business who has substantial assets accumulated for retirement in a qualified plan or IRA, proper tax and estate planning for such accumulations is essential.  The effect of the minimum distribution rule, incidental death benefit rule and penalty tax provisions of the tax laws is vital.   Early consideration of these issues may avoid later complications.

 <P>

<font size=+2><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Randy Gegelman by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:rgegelma@faegre.com"><EM>rgegelma@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


<HR>

