<HEAD>
<TITLE> Planning for the Distribution of Retirement Savings at Death </title>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<h2>Planning for the Distribution of Retirement Savings at Death</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>David J. Shannon</h4>

<FONT SIZE=+2>F</FONT>or more and more family business owners and employees, a significant portion of their wealth is accumulated in qualified retirement plans<SUPER>1</SUPER> (qualified plans) and individual retirement accounts (IRAs).  These vehicles of savings are very popular for two reasons.  First, amounts contributed to qualified plans and IRAs, subject to certain limitations, are either excludible or deductible from gross income.  Second, income earned within qualified plans and IRAs is not recognized for tax purposes until distributed.  The entire amount of such income can, therefore, accumulate within the plan or IRA and grow tax-free.<P>

Because qualified plans and IRAs are subject to a very complex set of rules and regulations, however, planning for the distribution of these assets at a participant's death is not an easy task.  Many factors must be considered carefully during the estate planning process to insure that distribution of these assets is consistent with the participant's overall estate planning objectives and accomplished in a manner which will minimize taxes.  This article will provide a brief overview of some of the issues that often arise during this planning process.

<H4>A. Tax Considerations</H4>

Although qualified plans and IRAs receive very favorable tax treatment during the lifetime of the participant, at the participant's death the exact opposite occurs.  Assets held in qualified plans and IRAs at death may be subject to several different taxes.  These taxes include the following:<P>

<blockquote><STRONG>1. Income taxes:</STRONG> Generally speaking, distributions from qualified plans and IRAs are taxed as ordinary income to the recipient.  Under current law, the federal income tax rate starts at 15% and increases to a maximum rate of 39.6%.  State income taxes may also apply.<P>

<STRONG>2. Estate taxes:</STRONG>   Under current law, federal estate taxes are imposed when a decedent's taxable estate exceeds $600,000.  At that level, the federal estate tax rate starts at 37% and increases to a maximum rate of 55% for taxable estates in excess of $3,000,000. With some minor exceptions, the full value of a decedent's qualified plans and IRAs is includible in his/her gross estate.  State death taxes may also apply.<P>

<STRONG>3. Excise tax on excess accumulation:</STRONG>  If a decedent dies with too much wealth accumulated in his/her qualified plans and IRAs, federal law imposes a 15% excise tax on the excess accumulation.  A decedent has an excess accumulation if the aggregate amount in his/her qualified plans and IRAs exceeds the present value of a certain hypothetical life annuity.<P>

<STRONG>4. Generation-skipping taxes:</STRONG>  Transfers from qualified plans and IRAs at death to a person more than one generation below the decedent may be subject to the federal generation-skipping tax.  The federal generation-skipping tax is a flat tax with a current rate of 55%.  </blockquote><P>

For some decedents, the combination of these various taxes can result in more than 50% of the aggregate amount of their qualified plans and IRAs passing to federal and state taxing authorities, rather than to their designated beneficiaries.  Proper planning, however, can often eliminate, or significantly reduce, many of these taxes.  Some of the tools and techniques relied upon by estate planners to achieve this objective are the following:<P>

<blockquote><STRONG>1. Spousal rollover IRA:</STRONG>  If a decedent's surviving spouse is the beneficiary designated to receive a lump sum distribution from a qualified plan or IRA at the decedent's death, the surviving spouse, within a certain period of time,  may roll all or any portion of this amount into an IRA registered in his/her name.  The income tax on any amount so rolled will be deferred until the surviving spouse subsequently withdraws such amount from the IRA.  Moreover, income earned on the assets rolled to the IRA can continue to accumulate tax free until the surviving spouse or his/her designated beneficiary is required to withdraw the same.<P>

<STRONG>2. Use of life expectancies: </STRONG> As discussed in more detail elsewhere in this newsletter, by April 1 of the calendar year following the calendar year in which the participant attains the age of 70-1/2 (the required beginning date), the participant must begin satisfying the minimum distribution rule .  The minimum distribution rule can be satisfied in many different ways.  Payments may be made over the life expectancy of the participant, the life expectancies of the participant and the participant's spouse (with none, one or both life expectancies being recalculated) or the life expectancies of the participant and a designated beneficiary.  If the participant dies after distributions have commenced to satisfy the minimum distribution rule, the decisions made by the participant to satisfy the minimum distribution rule will have a direct impact on how quickly the assets remaining in the participant's qualified plan or IRA must be withdrawn after the participant's death.  This, in turn, will have a direct impact on when income taxes must be paid on the assets remaining in the qualified plan or IRA.  The alternatives available to the participant to satisfy the minimum distribution rule should, therefore, be considered well in advance of the part-icipant's required beginning date.<P>

<STRONG>3. Marital deduction planning:</STRONG>  If a decedent designates his/her spouse who is a citizen of the United States or the trustee of certain qualifying trusts as the beneficiary to receive his/her qualified plan or IRA at death, the amount passing to the spouse outright or to the trustee of the qualifying trust will qualify for the estate tax marital deduction.  This deduction is an unlimited deduction which allows estate taxes to be deferred until the death of the surviving spouse or, in some cases, eliminated entirely.  If the trustee of a qualifying trust is selected as the designated beneficiary, extreme care must be taken in drafting the trust instrument to make certain that all requirements imposed by the Internal Revenue Code are satisfied.<P>

<STRONG>4. Charitable planning:</STRONG>  If a decedent designates a qualified charitable organization or the trustee of a charitable remainder trust as the beneficiary to receive some or all of his/her qualified plan or IRA at death, the amount passing to the charity outright or a portion of the amount passing to the trustee of the charitable remainder trust at death will qualify for the estate tax charitable deduction.  This deduction is an unlimited deduction which allows estate taxes to be eliminated entirely.  Moreover, since qualified charitable organizations and charitable remainder trusts are generally not subject to income tax, the income tax that would ordinarily be due and payable with respect to the distribution of the funds from the qualified plan or IRA can also be eliminated entirely.  If the trustee of a charitable remainder trust is selected as the designated beneficiary, extreme care must be taken in drafting the trust instrument to make certain that all requirements imposed by the Internal Revenue Code are satisfied.<P>

<STRONG>5. GST exemption: </STRONG> The Internal Revenue Code grants each individual a $1,000,000 generation-skipping transfer tax exemption.  Proper allocation of this exemption can allow a decedent to transfer up to $1,000,000 from his/her qualified plans and IRAs to persons more than one generation below him/her without incurring any federal generation-skipping tax.<P>

<STRONG>6. Actuarial projections:</STRONG>  For individuals who currently have a significant amount of wealth accumulated in their qualified plans and IRAs, it may be appropriate to run actuarial projections under various assumptions to examine the impact of the various taxes discussed above on such plans and IRAs and to consider what action, if any, may be taken immediately to reduce or eliminate such taxes.  For example, an individual who may be exposed to the 15% excise tax on an excess accumulation may want to consider reducing the amount he/she is contributing to his/her qualified plans and IRAs or withdrawing an amount in excess of that required by the minimum distribution rule.  Several computer software programs are available to run these types of projections.</blockquote>

<H4>B. Spousal Consent Rules</H4>

The Retirement Equity Act of 1984 (REA) prohibits a participant from designating someone other than his/her spouse as beneficiary of his/her qualified plans without such spouse's prior written consent.  The spousal consent rules of REA do not apply to IRAs.<P>

If for any reason a participant should determine that it is appropriate to designate someone other then his/her spouse as beneficiary of his/her qualified plans, it is, therefore, imperative that the prior written consent of the spouse be obtained.  Failure to obtain this consent will cause any other beneficiary designation filed with the plan administrator to be wholly ineffective.<P>

Under current law, it does not appear that a spousal consent incorporated in an antenuptial agreement satisfies the requirements imposed by REA.  If the intent of the parties is to provide for distribution of some or all of the participant's qualified plans to someone other than the spouse, it is, therefore, imperative that a proper spousal consent be executed and filed with the plan administrator after the solemnization of the marriage.

<H4>C. Family
     Considerations</H4>

The unique facts surrounding each parti-cipant's family situation can often play a critical role in determining how best to plan for the disposition of the participant's qualified plans and IRAs at death.  For example, if the participant's spouse is in poor health, it may not be appropriate to elect to recalculate the life expectancies of the participant and the participant's spouse for purposes of satisfying the minimum distribution rule.  To do so may simply accelerate the distribution of assets from the participant's qualified plans and IRAs at the participant's death, and consequently, accelerate the income tax obligation associated with these assets.<P>

Similarly, although a participant will often name his/her spouse as the primary beneficiary of his/her qualified plans and IRAs, if the participant has minor children, it may not be appropriate to name the children as the contingent beneficiaries.  Rather, the participant may want to structure his/her estate plan to provide that if the participant's spouse does not survive him/her, the assets held in his/her qualified plans and IRAs will be paid to a trustee to be administered and distributed for the benefit of the participant's minor children until they attain a certain age.  Otherwise, it may be necessary to commence a separate court proceeding to have a guardian or conservator appointed for each minor child to receive and administer such assets on his/her behalf.  This can be both costly and cumbersome for the family.

<H4>D. Conclusion</H4>

Many factors must be taken into account to properly plan for the disposition of the assets held in a decedent's qualified plans and IRAs at death.  Absent such planning, a significant portion of the participant's qualified plans and IRAs may end up in the hands of the taxing authorities, rather than in the hands of the participant's intended beneficiaries.  By properly planning for the disposition of these assets at death, however, the participant should be able to achieve his/her overall estate planning objectives at the minimum tax cost.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>1	Qualified retirement plans may be one of two types:  defined benefit plans or defined contribution plans.  A defined benefit plan is a plan that provides a specific benefit based on a number of factors, such as years of service and level of compensation.  A typical example would be a company pension plan.<P>

A defined contribution plan is a plan that allows contributions to be made to it by the participant and/or his/her employer, which contributions are then held in a separate account for the benefit of the participant.  Typical examples would include a profit-sharing plan, a 401(k) plan, a stock bonus plan or an employee stock ownership plan (ESOP).</FONT><P>

<font size=+2><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact David Shannon by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:dshannon@faegre.com"><EM>dshannon@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


