<H2>Bank Mergers and Acquisitions</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>

<blockquote>
Faegre & Benson represents clients in all phases of bank acquisitions.  We have represented buyers, sellers, investment bankers and lenders in connection with various public and private acquisition transactions.  These transactions have employed a myriad of acquisition structures and forms of consideration, including sales or purchases of stock, purchase and assumptions, mergers, exchange offers and cash tender offers.  Faegre & Benson has experience in interstate and intrastate purchases and sales of banks and thrifts (both healthy and failed) and branches.
<P>

We possess a breadth of experience in corporate and banking law, securities regulation, finance and other corporate and banking disciplines important to the successful completion of bank change-in-control transactions.  Such transactions call for specialized bank regulatory expertise, including processing applications with the OCC, FRB, FDIC, OTS, Minnesota Department of Commerce and other regulatory agencies; antitrust analysis; knowledge of the limitations on banking holding company activities; examination of intrastate and interstate banking and branching limitations; experience with issues related to failed bank and thrift transactions; and familiarity with Community Reinvestment Act compliance and capital adequacy guidelines.
<P>

Of special interest in Minnesota transactions is Faegre & Benson's active and on-going participation in the drafting, review and amendment of the business combination, control share and other relevant provisions of the Minnesota Business Corporation Act and the corporate takeover provisions of the Minnesota Securities Act.  
<P>

Our acquisition lawyers work closely with lawyers specializing in other areas of the law who provide critical support for today's complex transactions.  These areas of practice include tax, employee benefits, labor, anti-trust, real estate, environmental, government relations and litigation.  Members of our  Minneapolis-based government relations group provide up-to-date information on the latest federal and state regulatory developments.
<P>

