<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Lost Prepayment and Contract Termination Rights of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) and Farmers Home Administration (FmHA) Housing Project Owners</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BASEFONT SIZE=3>
<CENTER>

<IMG SRC="intel3.gif"><P>
<H2>Government Contract Law</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>

<H2>Lost Prepayment and Contract Termination Rights of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) and Farmers Home Administration (FmHA) Housing Project Owners</H2>

<h4>by</h4>

<h4><a href="../offices/att_mpls.html#eckland">Jeff Eckland</a></h4><br>


During October 1996 this office commenced civil actions on behalf of the owners of over 1,500 low- and moderate-income rental housing units located throughout the states of Minnesota, Wisconsin, North Dakota, South Dakota, Iowa, Alabama, and Alaska.  These units constitute housing projects financed through mortgage loans federally insured or issued by HUD and FmHA.  The civil actions, filed in the United States Court of Federal Claims in Washington, D.C., seek on behalf of those HUD and FmHA project owners named in the actions the recovery of lost profits for (i) breaches of contract; and (ii) unconstitutional takings of property without just compensation, resulting from the enactment by Congress of:

<OL type=1>
<LI>The Low-Income Housing Preservation and Resident Homeownership Act of 1990 (LIHPRHA or the 1990 legislation) affecting HUD Section 221(d)(3) and Section 236 project owners; and
<p>

<LI>Title VII of the Housing and Community Development Act of 1992 (Title VII or the 1992 legislation) affecting FmHA Section 515 and 521 project owners.
</OL>


<STRONG><EM>Lost Right To Go To Market.</EM></STRONG>  The 1990 and 1992 legislation purports to prohibit HUD and FmHA project owners from exercising their contractual right to terminate, without Government restriction, their participation in Government housing programs upon prepayment of their mortgage loans.  As a result of the Governments actions, many owners will be unable to terminate their participation in Government housing programs at any time before the forty (40) or fifty (50) year terms of their loans actually expire.  Thus, those owners who desire to exercise their contractual right to go to market either (i) by raising their rents to commercial market rates; or (ii) by selling their properties in the commercial market, are unable to do so.
<p>

<STRONG><EM>Lost Profits.</EM></STRONG>  The Governments actions have deprived owners of certain revenues including but not limited to the following:
<OL type=1>
<LI>increased rents;
<p>

<LI>the equity in the projects;
<p>

<LI>potential buyers in the unsubsidized commercial housing market;
<p>

<LI>access to reserve, residual receipts, and reserve for replacement accounts.
</OL>


Other lost opportunity costs have been incurred as a result of the Government's conscription of project owners to provide subsidized housing without compensation.		
<p>

Many housing project owners have lost thousands of dollars per unit in profits over the course of their damage periods.  The expectation of such profits constituted one of the primary incentives for owners to enter into the Government housing programs in the first place.  The pending litigation is designed to recover the profits to which owners are contractually entitled but which they have lost as a consequence of the Governments actions.
<p>

<STRONG>Cienega Gardens <em>and</em> Winstar.</STRONG>  In a related case, <EM>Cienega Gardens v. United States</EM>, the United States Court of Federal Claims rejected certain Government defenses and decided as a matter of law that the Governments restriction of the contractual right to prepay housing project mortgage loans constitutes a breach of contract.  Moreover, on July 1, 1996, in <EM>Winstar Corp. v. United States</EM>, the United States Supreme Court held that similar Government attempts to change the "rules of the game" constituted breaches of contracts with savings and loan institutions.  Both the <EM>Cienega</EM> and <EM>Winstar</EM> cases will control a number of the issues to be raised by the Government in the pending litigation.
<p>

<STRONG><EM>Statute of Limitations.</EM></STRONG>  Project owners should be aware that, depending upon individual circumstances, their claims may be time barred by the statute of limitations.  Unless an action is timely filed on behalf of a specific owner, that owners damages claim may be subject to dismissal.  Since the pending litigation is not a class action, the statute of limitations continues to run against those owners who have not joined in the litigation.  In addition, no damages can be recovered on behalf of any owner unless and until it joins a civil action as a party plaintiff.    
<p>

<STRONG><EM>All Project Owners Are Eligible.</EM></STRONG>  Those project owners that are currently parties to the pending civil actions, as well as those who wish to become parties to additional civil actions to be filed in the near future, include owners (i) who would have prepaid but for the government's breach; (ii) who intend to prepay at some point before the end of their loan terms but have been compelled to apply for incentives under the 1990 or 1992 legislation in order to avoid forced sales of their properties; (iii) who have never applied for incentives; (iv) who have actually received certain incentives; and (v) who have been compelled to transfer their properties in lieu of applying for incentives.
<p>

<STRONG><EM>Reminder:</EM></STRONG>  The pending civil actions protect and cover only those project owners who have become a party plaintiff by joining the litigation.  
<p>

This <EM>Issue Update</EM> is intended solely to alert readers to government contract related issues and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this <EM>Issue Update</EM>.

<p>
<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><br>


If you have any questions, please contact Jeff Eckland by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:jeckland@faegre.com">jeckland @faegre.com</A>. <p>

</blockquote>

<hr>
Last changed 19-Nov-96<p>

