<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Landmark Procurement Legislation:
The Federal Acquisition Streamlining Act 
(FASA) of 1994</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BASEFONT SIZE=3>
<CENTER>

<IMG SRC="intel3.gif"><P>
<H2>Government Contract Law</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>

<H2>Landmark Procurement Legislation:
The Federal Acquisition Streamlining Act 
(FASA) of 1994</H2>

<h4>by</h4>

<h4><a href="../offices/att_mpls.html#eckland">Jeff Eckland</a></h4><br>

On October 13, 1994, as a large crowd of legislators, agency-heads, general counsels and federal procurement reform well-wishers enthusiastically looked on during a Rose Garden ceremony, President Clinton signed into law the Federal Acquisition Streamlining Act of 1994 (P.L. 103-355) (FASA). This landmark legislation is designed to transform the $200 billion a year federal procurement process into a simplified, more efficient and accessible system. FASA will significantly change how the government conducts its business. <br>


However, FASA establishes only a framework for simplifying or streamlining the current federal acquisition process.  Most of FASA's sweeping changes will not impact the contracting process until the act is implemented by extensive regulatory changes in the Federal Acquisition Regulation (FAR). Only a limited number of changes are effective immediately.  The balance take effect within the earlier of 30 days after publication of final regulations or October 1, 1995.  Despite an ongoing expedited regulatory drafting process, the Act also mandates a 60-day period for public comment.  Industry therefore is well advised to monitor closely proposed revisions to the FAR.
<br>


Notable FASA improvements designed to streamline and simplify the federal acquisition process include:
<br>

<ul><li>Eliminating most paperwork and record keeping requirements for high volume acquisitions below $100,000 (Simplified Acquisition Threshold) (SAT));<br>

<li>Allowing direct micropurchases of items below $2,500 without competitive quotations or compliance with Buy American Act and certain small business requirements;<br>

<li>Exempting commercial product procurements from certain existing as well as future enacted laws, including exemptions from the submission of cost or pricing data and the cost accounting standards (CAS) requirements; establishing an agency preference for commercial items; and other continuing initiatives promoting the acquisition of commercial items to minimize time delays, research and development, and detailed design specifications and testing, thereby making government procurement easier and less costly;<br>

<li>Establishing a Government-wide  Federal Acquisition Computer Network (FACNET) to convert a current acquisition process overburdened by paperwork to an expedited electronic data interchange system (EDI) readily accessible to the public. FACNET will inform the public about federal contracting opportunities and permit the electronic submission of bids and proposals. (The EDI initiatives recently announced by the DoD and GSA will likely serve as models for implementing FACNET);<br>

<li>Establishing a six year limitation period for filing claims under the Contract Disputes Act (CDA) and increasing dollar thresholds for claim certification and the accelerated and small claims procedures; <br>

<li>Reserving all acquisitions over $2,500 but under $100,000 exclusively for small business concerns, unless the contracting agency is unable to obtain offers from at least two qualified small business firms;<br>

<li>Expanding the Small Disadvantaged Business set - aside program to civilian agency procurements;<br>

<li>Establishing a new 5 percent contracting goal for women-owned small businesses;<br>

<li>Creating a Small Business Procurement Advisory Council composed of representatives from federal agencies which will give high level attention and focus to small businesses;<br>

<li>Preserving private contractors ability to file bid protests in the U.S. District Courts, and authorizing federal district courts to obtain advisory opinions from the boards of contract appeals;<br>

<li>Improving bid protest and contract administration procedures -- particularly by providing more timely and informative debriefings to unsuccessful offerors, establishing government-wide payment protection for first-tier subcontractors and suppliers, and by extending the authority to use alternative dispute resolution procedures under the CDA until October 1, 1999.<br>

<li>Repealing that part of the Walsh-Healey Act requiring an offeror to certify that it is a regular dealer or manufacturer;<br>

<li>Requiring evaluation of past performance before contract award;<br>

<li>Raising the Truth in Negotiation Act (TINA) threshold for requiring  certified cost or pricing data to a uniform $500,000 for both civilian agencies and DoD procurements.<br>
</ul>
<font="+2"><b>FASA Highlights:</b></font>
<br>

Contract Disputes Act (CDA) Improvements.  FASA establishes a statute of limitations period of six years for filing claims.  The six year limitation period is measured from the date of accrual of the claim.  The Act also raises to $100,000 from $50,000 the dollar threshold for claim certification.  Finally, the Act increases the dollar threshold levels for expedited claim proceedings before the boards of contract appeals as follows:<br>


Accelerated Claim Procedure:  Now applies to all claims of $100,000 or less (rather than merely $50,000);<br>


Small Claims Procedure:  Now applies to all claims of $50,000 or less (rather than merely $10,000).<br>



These changes make expedited claim procedings much more accessible.  Now claims $50,000 or less can be decided within 120 days and claims $100,000 or less can be decided within 180 days.  The short time frames and larger dollar amounts make Government contract litigation much more efficient and cost effective for all Government contractors.<br>
 

<b>Travel Costs.</b>  FASA repealed that portion of the OFPP Act requiring that costs incurred by contractor personnel for travel be considered reasonable and allowable only to the extent that the costs did not exceed the maximum per diem rates specified in the Federal Travel Regulations (FTR) (prescribed by the GSA for travel in the coterminous 48 United States) or the Joint Travel Regulations (JTR) (prescribed by the DoD for travel in Alaska, Hawaii, Puerto Rico, and the territories and possessions of the United States).  Industry anticipated that this repeal would be implemented through removal of the FTR/JTR restrictions from FAR 31.205-46 and a return to the reasonableness criteria existing prior to the OFPP Act's passage in 1986.<br>


However, the FAR Council has issued a proposed rule retaining the FTR/JTR restrictions as a baseline for determining the reasonableness of travel costs incurred by Government contractors.  The rule only permits contractors to propose alternative rates subject to certain limitations. (59 Fed. Reg. 64542).  Alternative rates would be allowable only if approved before travel costs are incurred.  <br>


No public meeting on this proposed rule has been scheduled.  Interested parties may request a public meeting before January 13, 1995 and/or submit written comments on the proposed rule by February 13, 1995.<br>


Debriefings.  FASA now requires agencies to provide written notice of contract award to unsuccessful offerors and bidders within 3 days of contract award.  Upon receipt of this notice, private contractors have 3 days to file a written request with the agency for an award debriefing.  Agencies must provide, to the maximum extent practicable, any requested debriefing within 5 days of receiving a contractors written debriefing request.  As part of each debriefing, FASA requires agencies to provide the following details:<br>


Significant weaknesses or deficiencies of the unsuccessful offeror;<br>
<ul>
<li>The overall evaluated cost and technical ratings of both the awardee and the unsuccessful offeror;<br>

<li>The overall ranking of offerors;<br>

<li>A summary of the rationale for award;<br>

<li>If the procurement is for a commercial item, the make and model number of the commercial item being provided by the awardee;<br>

<li>Reasonable responses to relevant questions regarding compliance by the agency with applicable procurement rules and regulations.<br>
</ul>


To protect competitive advantages and proprietary data, FASA prohibits agencies from providing a point-by-point comparison of a debriefed offeror with other offerors. FASA also precludes the agencys release of information relating to trade secrets, manufacturing processes, and privileged financial information -- such as cost breakdowns, profit, and indirect cost rates.<br>


BID Protests.  FASA has changed several bid protest procedures at the General Accounting Office (GAO):<br>

<ul><li>Counting Days - Under FASA, the GAOs traditional working day time frame has been replaced with calendar days.  However, if a required action is to occur on a Saturday, Sunday, federal holiday, or an emergency closing, the date for taking the required action automatically extends to the following working day.<br>
</ul>

FASA therefore solves a problem that has occurred at the GAO regarding the calculation of the time period for automatic suspensions of contract performance pending resolution of GAO bid protests.<br>


Pursuant to the Competition in Contracting Act's (CICA) automatic stay provisions, an agency is required to stay performance if the protest is filed within 10 calendar days of contract award.  The GAO determined that if the 10th day fell on a Saturday, Sunday, or federal holiday, the time period could not be extended.  Thus, in many cases the GAO's interpretation significantly shortened the time period during which a protester would have to file a protest to qualify for the automatic stay.  The GAO's interpretation directly conflicted with the GSBCA's interpretation of similar suspension provisions in the Brooks Act.  The GSBCA extends the 10 day period to the next working day when the last day falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or federal holiday.  Thus, FASA makes uniform the calculation of time between the GAO and the GSBCA.<br>


<ul><li>Automatic Stay - FASA now  requires agencies to issue an automatic stay on contract performance when a protester files at the GAO within 10 calendar days after contract award, or within 5 days of an offered debriefing, whichever is later.<br>
</ul>


Theoretically, where the maximum amount of time is used by the Government and a protesting party at each step of the notification and debriefing process, a stay-generating protest could be filed up to 21 calendar days after award.<br>

<ul><li>Fees - For the first time, the Act explicitly provides authority to pay successful protesters expert witness and consultant fees at the highest rate paid by the Government.  In addition, FASA authorizes the recovery of attorneys' fees for other than small businesses at a maximum rate of $150 per hour unless the GAO determines that a higher rate is appropriate. This limitation does not apply to small businesses.  <br>

<li>Protective Orders - Congress granted the GAO in FASA specific statutory authority to issue protective orders in protests.  FASA additionally provides thathen requested, the GAO must provide full case disclosure to Congress.<br>
</ul>


Implementation of the Act.  Implementation of the provisions of the Streamlining Act began immediately after both Houses of Congress voted on the bill.  President Clinton issued Executive Order 12931 requiring agencies to align their procedures with the values stated in the Act.  A project manager within the Acquisition Reform Office of the Under-Secretary of Defense has been named. Inter-Agency teams are drafting implementing regulations covering each of the major areas of FASA, including:<br>

<OL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>Contract Award<P>
<LI>Special Contracting Methods<P>
<LI>Truth in Negotiations Act<P>
<LI>Protests and Disputes<P>
<LI>Audits<P>
<LI>Cost Principles<P>
<LI>Contract Financing and Payment<P>
<LI>Simplified Procedures and FACNET<P>
<LI>Small Business<P>
<LI>Ethics<P>
<LI>Commercial Contracting<P>
</OL>



Each team includes an administration representative who has been involved in drafting the administration's position on FASA.  Time limits even more strict than those required by FASA are being imposed on the teams.  Public hearings likely will be held on TINA, commercial contracting, and SAT.  Under one proposed schedule, the FAR Council has established a target date of March 23, 1995 for publication of the final rules to be effective April 22, 1995.  This goal is well within that set by the President -- to beat the statutory deadline (of final publication no later than 330 days after enactment) by 100 days.<br>


In addition to this governmental activity, the Council on Defense Security Industrial Associations (CODSIA) has put together industry groups which will be working in tandem with the Government.  These groups will work with the government inter-agency teams as they develop implementing guidance.<p>

<font="+2"><b>FAR Rewrite</b></font><br>


In late August, the Office of Federal Procurement Policy (OFPP) held a public meeting to discuss with members of the Bar and the business community the effort to rewrite the FAR.  The FAR rewrite is being accomplished in accordance with the Administrations National Performance Review (NPR) recommendation to change acquisition policy by converting the FAR from a set of rigid rules to guiding principles.<br>


Members of the Bar warned against changes that would jeopardize the uniformity of the FAR and result in increased litigation over established precedent in Government contract law.  The Bar stated that the current FAR rewrite effort is too narrowly focused and that the entire procurement process should be reworked.  Some noted that it may be a mistake to rewrite the FAR because a body of interpretative laws and regulations have grown around it which should not summarily be dismissed.  Another major issue discussed is the extent to which agency supplements constitute the real problem with the FAR.  Supplements result in a proliferation of rules and a lessening of government-wide standards.<br>


The NPR goal of rewriting the FAR resulted from a perception that the procurement process does not take concerns of  program customers to heart and allow them to make good procurement judgments.  Dr. Steven Kelman, the Director of the OFPP, has established an eleven member board of directors of senior government officials to examine the FAR.  The re-write of the FAR will be delayed pending implementation of the FASA. <P>

<font="+2"><b>Past Performance</font></b><br>


Past performance has become a buzz word in the government procurement community during the last several months as Dr. Kelman pushes agencies to give more consideration to the past performance of a government contractor in determining the award of new government contracts.  Indeed, past performance has been used in the past by various agencies with success, and Kelman has secured agreement of over 30 agencies to increase the use of past performance.<br>


The use of past performance, however, has been criticized by industry as constituting a vague and ephemeral criterion for determining the award of contracts.  Industry proposed that FASA: (i) include an administrative process to challenge derogatory past performance information; (ii) establish mandatory, uniform criteria; and (iii) purge information after a fixed time period.  Despite such recommendations Congress did not provide agencies in FASA itself with specific guidance for considering past performance.  Instead, FASA simply provides that (i) past contract performance is one relevant factor that should be considered; and (ii) consideration of past performance constitutes an appropriate indicator of future performance.  In addition, Congress directed the OFPP to provide specified guidance to agencies on evaluating and managing past performance evaluations.<P>

<font="+2"><b>Merger Mania</b></font><br>
 

The downsizing of the defense industry has produced further mergers, most notably the $23 billion union of Lockheed and Martin-Marietta to form Lockheed Martin.  That announcement followed by several weeks the Defense Science Boards recommendation on mergers in the defense industry caused by the downsizing of the defense community.  As a result of that report, the Defense Department has organized a better system for reviewing proposed mergers and passing on departmental views to the enforcing agencies, the Department of Justice, and the Federal Trade Commission.  Hopefully a system such as this will avert problems which occurred last year in certain merger efforts thwarted in litigation in Federal Court in the District of Columbia. These results turned largely on the fact that the Defense Department not only did not present its views with force and effect, but probably had no consistent views to present.<P>

<font="+2"><b>International Procurement</b></font><br>


In 1994 the U.S. and the European Union reached agreement on government procurement and incorporated it into the GATT Government Procurement Agreement.  GATT was ratified by the Congress in the special session after the election.  The GATT provisions cover central government procurement, i.e., by the Federal government, and subcentral government procurement by the states. This has not resulted in total uniformity but most states have agreed to provide coverage for a large number of their Executive Branch agencies.  The problem was more complicated for the U.S. with our Federal-State system of government than for European nations with a more centralized form of government.<br>


Bid protest proceedings provide for damages in the case of failure to follow national procurement rules and procedures but do not authorize the set aside of awards.  The agreement also prohibits offsets unless they are by less developed countries and only when negotiated on a countrys entry into the agreement.  Disputes will be settled with the World Trade Organization, the creation of which has become a center of controversy with critics in the Congress contending that the agency has been given powers too broad for an international body.  <P>

<font="+2"><b>Defense Contractors' Leveraged ESOPs.</b></font><br>


Leveraged employee stock ownership plans (ESOPs) may soon be subject to increased scrutiny by the Department of Defense (DoD) if recommendations made by the Office of the Inspector General (OIG) are followed.   In its Report on Department of Defense Oversight of Defense Contractor Pension Plans the OIG concluded that ESOPs are often established simply as a means for disposing of company stock and as a tactic to avoid hostile corporate takeovers.  The report further concluded that the DoD is subsidizing ESOPs that are often created solely for the financial benefit of the corporations and not for the welfare of employees, as intended by Congress.  To address its concerns, the OIG recommended that separate rules for ESOPs be established under the FAR, that the Defense Contract Audit Agency (DCAA) closely evaluate whether ESOP costs are allowable and properly allocated to the contract, and that the DCAA consistently question (and presumably disallow) interest expenses on any ESOP loans.<br>

Under a leveraged ESOP, a large block of company stock is purchased with a loan and held in the ESOP trust.  The company then is obligated to make contributions to the ESOP in amounts sufficient to repay principal and interest on the loan.  As the loan is repaid, stock is credited to employee accounts under the ESOP.  The interest paid on the loan often does not translate into a direct benefit to the employees, although the loan may have allowed the ESOP to purchase stock at a price lower than its value when later allocated to accounts.<br>


The treatment of ESOP interest expense under a cost reimbursement type contract has been unclear for some time.  In its report, the OIG recommended that such interest expense be disallowed in all cases under a current provision of the FAR that prohibits reimbursement of interest on company borrowings.  In contrast, DCAA audit guidelines in effect prior to 1993 would have allowed reimbursement of such interest expense because the borrowing is by the ESOP and not the company. <br>


The DCAA recently has changed its view to one more consistent with the position of the OIG.  Audit guidelines issued by the DCAA in 1993 (after the OIG report was circulated in draft) state that the treatment of interest expense depends upon whether the ESOP is a pension plan or deferred compensation plan as those terms are used in the FAR.  If an ESOP has a life annuity payment option for benefits (which is a very unusual feature in an ESOP), the guidelines say that the ESOP is subject to the pension plan rules of the FAR which generally would allow interest expense reimbursement.  If an ESOP does not have a life annuity option, the ESOP would be subject to the deferred compensation plan rules of the FAR which would not allow interest expense reimbursement. <br>


The DCAA has not as yet adopted the position of the OIG with respect to ESOP interest expense.  In responding to the OIGs report recommendation that the DCAA consistently question ESOP interest expense, the DCAA agreed that guidance is needed for consistent treatment of interest expense, but noted that complex accounting and policy issues are involved.  The DCAA promised further audit guidelines after proper coordination with the Office of Defense Procurement.<p>
<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><br>


If you have any questions, please contact Jeff Eckland by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:jeckland@faegre.com">jeckland@faegre.com</A>. <p>

</blockquote>

<hr>
