<HEAD>
<TITLE> Voters Will Grade 1996 Minnesota Legislature and 
Political Parties at November 5 Election </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Voters Will Grade 1996 Minnesota Legislature and 
Political Parties at November 5 Election</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Faegre & Benson Government Relations Team</h4>



<FONT SIZE=+2>M</FONT>ajority DFLers point to passage of a livable wage, insurance coverage for 48 hours of hospital care for new mothers and babies, $6 million for summer youth employment, $12 million for K-12 education technology, a crime bill, relaxation of wetlands restrictions and more than $600 million in public construction projects as accomplishments of the 1996 Minnesota Legislature.<p>

The DFL lawmakers say they could have accomplished more - including an increase in the minimum wage to $5.35 an hour from $4.25 - if Gov. Arne Carlson had not used his veto pen 26 times.<p>

Minority Republicans argue the Legislature accomplished little and failed to act on such key issues as legislative reform, overhaul of Minnesotas property tax/state aid system, welfare reform and transportation finance.  The Governor claims his 181 vetoes have saved Minnesotans $1.5 billion since 1991.<p>

Republicans say voters should consider seriously ethics violations by almost a dozen DFL legislators.<p>

Productive year or failure to meet responsibilities?  Minnesota voters will decide how they view the 1996 Legislature when all 201 members of the House and Senate face election on November 5.<p>

Lawmakers came to the Capitol on January 16 with a projected surplus of more than $800 million.  When legislators went home on April 3, they had approved $130 million in new spending and guarded against future federal cutbacks and downturns in the economy by paying back school districts $682 million that the state borrowed more than a decade ago, increasing the budget reserve to $270 million from $220 million and maintaining a $350 million cash flow account.<p>

No taxes were raised or new taxes imposed.<p>

Lawmakers also decided:
<UL>
<LI>To end the search for a new Twin Cities airport.  The airport will stay and expand where it is.
<LI>Not to issue vouchers to low-income families so that their children can attend private or church schools.
</UL>

The 1997 Legislature will convene January 7.<P>


<b>Questions</b><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Rich Forschler at <A HREF="mailto:rforschl@faegre.com"><EM>rforschl@faegre.com</EM></A> or Bob Hentges at <A HREF="mailto:rhentges@faegre.com"><EM>rhentges@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

