<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Wetlands Reform and Other Environmental Laws </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Wetlands Reform and Other Environmental Laws</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Faegre & Benson Government Relations Team</h4>
<p>


<strong>Wetlands</strong><br>
<FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT> two-year debate over changes to a 1991 wetlands law finally ended in a compromise in the final hours of the 1996 legislative session.  Highlights of the new law, effective April 12, include a streamlined and more workable process; increased local control; creation of replacement wetlands on a 1-1 ratio rather than a 2-1 ratio in areas with many wetlands; simplified guidelines for local comprehensive wetland management plans; a de minimis exception; shift of responsibility to the state to replace wetlands drained and filled during local road repair projects; $6 million of state support for wetland restoration and easements; and increased exemptions for public ditch drainage.  A toll-free number will be established to offer assistance to landowners and those with questions on the complex law and regulations.  (Chapter 462.)<p>

<strong>Marketing Claims</strong><br>

A new law places Minnesota in conformity with federal guidelines regulating deceptive trade practices and environmental marketing claims.  Any manufacturer, packager, wholesaler or retailer claiming environmental benefits from products sold in Minnesota must comply with these federal guidelines regarding the accuracy of the claims.  A Minnesota law requiring post-consumer product in recycled material is repealed.  (Chapter 359.)<p>

<strong>Project XL</strong><br>

The Economic Efficiency and Pollution Reduction Act is a pilot program established by the Legislature to encourage innovative compliance by businesses requesting environmental permits from the Pollution Control Agency.  The program gives companies that show excellence and leadership the opportunity to go outside current regulations to increase flexibility and reduce environment management costs in exchange for their efforts to reduce pollution even more than law requires.  The goal is less red tape and less pollution.  The concept was initiated by 3M.  (Chapter 437.)<p>

<strong>Sustainable Development</strong><br>

A new law directs the Office of Strategic and Long Range Planning to develop and publish a sustainable development planning guide for use by local governments and to develop a model sustainable development ordinance.  The planning guide and ordinance are to be based on the principles of sustainable development adopted by the Environmental Quality Board with the advice of the Governors Roundtable on Sustainable Development.  Sustainable development is described as development that maintains or enhances economic opportunity and community well-being while protecting and restoring the natural environment upon which people and economies depend and that meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs.  (Chapter 454.)<p>

<strong>Landfill Cleanup</strong><br>

Negotiations between the Attorney General and the insurance industry resulted in revisions to the process for resolving claims and associated damages incurred in landfill cleanups.  There now is an opportunity for voluntary settlement.  If a settlement cannot be reached after fair and reasonable efforts, the legislation authorizes action by the state for recovery from insurers.  (Chapter 370.)<p>

<strong>Pollution Control Board</strong><br>

Chapter 348 requires that one member of the nine-member Pollution Control Agency Citizens Board must now be a representative of organized labor appointed by the Governor.  The Board currently consists of the Commissioner and eight members appointed by the Governor, including three farmers, two business people, a medical doctor, an attorney for an insurance company and a chief financial officer.  Chapter 405 clarifies the powers and duties of the Citizens Board and Commissioner.  The Board will retain final decisionmaking authority over environmental reviews, permits, variances and agency rules.  The Commissioner will have all duties not expressly designated to the Board.  (Chapters 348 and 405.)<p>

<strong>Kondirator/Steam Plant</strong><br>

Numerous attempts were made by several legislators, including Representative Phyllis Kahn and Senator Larry Pogemiller, during the course of the legislative session to prohibit or slow three projects on the Mississippi River.  The projects are American Iron and Steels proposed metal shredding facility - the Kondirator - in Minneapolis, Alter Steels shredding project in St. Paul and the University of Minnesotas steam plant renovation.  Legislation forcing the projects to meet additional requirements or denying necessary permits was defeated.
<P>


<b>Questions</b><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Rich Forschler at <A HREF="mailto:rforschl@faegre.com"><EM>rforschl@faegre.com</EM></A> or Bob Hentges at <A HREF="mailto:rhentges@faegre.com"><EM>rhentges@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

