<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Property Taxes: Very Cold Spring, But No Freeze</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Property Taxes: Very Cold Spring, But No Freeze</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Faegre & Benson Government Relations Team</h4>
<p>



<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he top issue on the 1996 Business legislative agenda was property tax reform.  Reform did not occur, but a foundation was laid for likely action in 1997.<P>

Spurred by complaints from property taxpayers and a growing recognition that Minnesotas property tax/state aid system is broken, lawmakers considered a half dozen proposals to reform the system.<P>

The proposals included:
<UL>
<LI>Narrow the gap between business property taxes - highest in the nation - and taxes on homes and farms.
<LI>Pay all K-12 education expenses with state income and sales taxes instead of using local property taxes to pay much of the bill.
<LI>Establish a new state property tax, extend the sales tax to clothing and consumer services or give local governments power to impose income taxes.
<LI>Pay state property tax relief to taxpayers instead of to local governments.
<LI>Base state aid to local governments on need rather than past spending.
</UL>

Most of the proposals were essentially revenue neutral - lowering property taxes and raising others - at least in the early years.  <p>

Proposed new taxes had the potential to increase total state and local taxes in the future.<p>

A bi-partisan group of senators assembled a reform package, and the Senate Tax Committee passed it to the Senate floor.  <p>

Nervousness over new taxes in an election year caused senators to abandon the reform plan and propose instead a one-year freeze of property taxes and a sunset of the property tax/state aid system in order to encourage reform in 1997.<p>

The House refused to agree to a freeze, arguing that it would tie the hands of local governments as they tried to deal with cutbacks in federal aid and to meet local needs and would lead to higher property taxes after the freeze.<p>

Reform-minded legislators continue to refine and push their proposals, and Governor Carlson has indicated that he may make reform a priority next year.<p>

Lawmakers did pass a scaled-down tax bill (Chapter 471).  It includes:

<UL>
<LI>Reduction of the property tax classification rate for the first $72,000 of cabin value from 1.9 percent to 1.75 percent in 1997 and 1.5 percent in 1998.  The classification rate on the first $72,000 of home value, for comparison, is 1 percent.
<LI>Koch Refinerys plan to build a $300 million electricity cogeneration facility will be aided by passage of an efficiency-based personal property tax exemption for equipment.
</UL>

The Legislature did not approve a phaseout of the sales tax on manufacturers replacement capital equipment.  The phaseout was proposed to help Minnesota manufacturers compete with those in other states.  Proposals to impose a $75 a gram tax on mercury emissions and a $50 a ton tax on carbon in fuel did not pass but are likely to be considered by the 1997 Legislature.
<P>

<b>Questions</b><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Rich Forschler at <A HREF="mailto:rforschl@faegre.com"><EM>rforschl@faegre.com</EM></A> or Bob Hentges at <A HREF="mailto:rhentges@faegre.com"><EM>rhentges@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

<HR>

<font size=-1>
