<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Commerce:  Securities, Insurance 
and Banking</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Commerce:  Securities, Insurance 
and Banking</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Faegre & Benson Government Relations Team</h4>
<p>



<strong>Securities</strong><br>

Uniform Prudent Investor Act (Chapter 314):  A bill adopting the Uniform Prudent Investor Act was passed in 1996.  This legislation sets standards for investment and management of trust assets by trustees.<P>

Restructured Local Government Investment Law (Chapter 399):  Legislation rewriting local government investment law was passed.  The bill includes provisions allowing local governments to invest in mutual funds which meet rating requirements and have a portfolio with specified characteristics.<P>

<strong>Insurance</strong><BR>

Maternity Stays Coverage (Chapter 335):  This legislation mandates that health care insurance plans cover hospital care for new mothers and their babies for at least 48 hours following childbirth.  In cases involving cesarean sections, patients must be covered for 96 hours.<P>

Prostate Cancer Screening Coverage (Chapter 446):  Health care plans must cover the Prostate Specific Antigen (PSA) test for high-risk men who are 40 years old and all men 50 years of age or older.<P>

Domestic Abuse Victims (Chapter 278):  Legislation was adopted prohibiting health care plans from denying coverage to victims of domestic abuse.  Such discrimination will now be classified as illegal under the Unfair Trade Practices Act.

Lyme Disease Coverage (Chapter 465):  Health care plans are required to include coverage for Lyme disease treatment costs.

<strong>Banking</strong><BR>

The 1996 Omnibus Financial Institutions Bill (Chapter 414) made numerous changes to Minnesota banking laws.  The bills provisions include:<P>

Detached Banking Facilities:  Restrictions limiting bank branches to five branches within 100 miles of the main bank have been eliminated.<P>

Interstate Bank Mergers:  This provision allows banks, in conformity with recent federal law, to establish branches in states where they have merged with other banks.<P>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Rich Forschler at <A HREF="mailto:rforschl@faegre.com"><EM>rforschl@faegre.com</EM></A> or Bob Hentges at <A HREF="mailto:rhentges@faegre.com"><EM>rhentges@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

