<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Gas Tax 
and Speed Limits</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Gas Tax 
and Speed Limits</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Faegre & Benson Government Relations Team</h4>
<p>



<STRONG>Gas Tax</STRONG><BR>


For much of the past decade, lawmakers have debated numerous proposals to provide increased funding for highways and transit.  Each year the debate has resulted in a stalemate.  Although nearly everyone agrees on the need for increased funding, the Legislature is split into divisive factions.  Rural legislators generally favor a gas tax increase to fund construction of highways and bridges.  Legislators representing the core cities are most concerned about funding for transit.  They are reluctant to increase the gas tax, which is dedicated constitutionally to roads and bridges, without support from rural legislators for a new revenue source dedicated to transit.  Suburban legislators are split between the two camps.<P>

During the past two years, Senate leaders have managed to reconcile their differences and pass several proposals providing for increased funding for transportation.  One proposal, which did not survive in 1996, would have increased the gas tax by 5 cents a gallon and authorized a ½ percent sales tax in the Twin Cities area to fund transit.<P>

In the House, leaders have been unable to forge a coalition to adopt any significant funding proposal.  While various committees in the House have approved proposals, the full House never has been supportive of proposals to increase taxes to fund transportation improvements.<P>

While Governor Carlson has shown interest in supporting a modest gas tax increase of 2 to 5 cents, he has not become actively involved in forging a compromise and resolving the stalemate.<P>

Although legislators, Carlson Administration officials and representatives of the transportation industry devoted considerable energy to the issue of transportation funding, no proposal was adopted during the 1996 legislative session.  The Governor and Legislature will set the biennial budget in 1997, providing increased visibility for highway and transit funding issues.<P>

<STRONG>Speed Limits</STRONG><BR>

The Legislature adopted a bill authorizing an increase in the speed limit to 65 m.p.h. on rural, divided highways.  The Governor opposed the increase unless additional officers were added to the State Patrol.  Because the speed limit bill contained many other transportation provisions, the Governor signed the bill and ordered the Commissioner of Transportation to keep the speed limit to 55 m.p.h. under his discretionary power to maintain safe roadways.  (Chapter 455.)
<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Rich Forschler at <A HREF="mailto:rforschl@faegre.com"><EM>rforschl@faegre.com</EM></A> or Bob Hentges at <A HREF="mailto:rhentges@faegre.com"><EM>rhentges@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

