<HEAD>
<TITLE> Corporate Welfare and the Livable Wage</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Corporate Welfare and the Livable Wage</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Faegre & Benson Government Relations Team</h4>
<p>



<FONT SIZE=+1>M</FONT>innesota received national attention this year as lawmakers decided that some businesses receiving public subsidies must pay employees a livable wage.  Look for future assaults on tax breaks and other forms of alleged corporate welfare.<P>

Livable Wage:  Legislation mandating that businesses receiving public grants or loans pay employees at least a livable wage equal to the federal poverty level for a family of four - now $7.28/hour - including health and dental care passed both houses, but was vetoed by the Governor.  This bill would have affected businesses which receive at least $25,000 in state or local economic development assistance.<P>

Minimum Wage:  A bill which would have raised the minimum wage from $4.25 an hour to $5.35 an hour at large companies and from $4 an hour to $5 an hour at small companies - maximum gross annual sales of $500,000 - sparked significant debate in 1996.  This bill also was vetoed by the Governor.<P>

Livable Wage (Chapter 447):  Similar to the vetoed proposal mandating a wage increase to $7.28/hour, the 1996 Omnibus Jobs Bill contained provisions requiring companies receiving financial assistance from the Minnesota Investment Fund, formerly known as the Economic Recovery Grant Program, to pay a minimum wage of $8.01 an hour including benefits.  This proposal survived because it was incorporated into a bill which contained numerous initiatives that the Governor wanted enacted into law, such as a $6 million youth summer employment program.  All Economic Recovery Grant recipients are already paying at least $8.01 an hour.<P>

Other employment laws approved include:<P>
School Activities Leave (Chapter 341): The Parental Leave Law allowing a parent or guardian employed by an employer for 12 consecutive months to take unpaid time off in order to attend his or her childs school conference or classroom activity was expanded to enable a parent or guardian to qualify for unpaid leave immediately upon employment and to include school-related activities.<P>

Enforcement of Wage and Hour Laws (Chapter 386):  Under a new law, employees are entitled to bring direct action in district court for unpaid wages, damages, costs and attorneys fees.  Also, the Commissioner of Labor and Industry may hold employers liable for failing to comply with minimum wage and wage and hour laws by ordering civil penalties and reimbursement for litigation costs born by employees.<P>

The minimum wage is likely to be debated during the 1996 election and probably will resurface during the 1997 legislative session.  Opponents will continue to argue that the federal government, not the Legislature, should determine the minimum wage.  Proponents will urge the Legislature to provide leadership on the issue rather than wait for federal action.<P>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Rich Forschler at <A HREF="mailto:rforschl@faegre.com"><EM>rforschl@faegre.com</EM></A> or Bob Hentges at <A HREF="mailto:rhentges@faegre.com"><EM>rhentges@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

