<H2>Legislative Statistics</h2>

<h4>What did the 1996 Legislature do?</H4>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Faegre & Benson Government Relations Team</h4>
<p>



<FONT SIZE=+1>O</FONT>f the 1,104 bills introduced in the Minnesota Senate and the 1,294 bills introduced in the Minnesota House - identical companion bills usually are introduced in both houses - during the 1996 legislative session, 187 were signed into law.  The Governor added to his veto record with 19 vetoes and line-item vetoes in 7 other bills.  The remaining bills were either incorporated into other bills or failed in committee or on the House or Senate floor.<p>

<STRONG>Bills That Were Vetoed</STRONG><BR>
<OL>
<LI>Non-English speaking communication plan
<LI>Teachers Retirement Funds
<LI>Department of Employee Relations pilot project
<LI>Legislative Auditors office
<LI>Public employee leave of absence
<LI>Principal campaign committee or political party committee lobbying
<LI>Omnibus Health and Human Services Bill
<LI>St. Cloud land use planning
<LI>Trunk highway construction local approval
<LI>Metropolitan Council wastewater services
<LI>Advisory council on intergovernmental relations
<LI>Board of Psychology
<LI>Mail balloting
<LI>Minimum wage
<LI>MinnesotaCare
<LI>Livable wage
<LI>Public Utilities Commission/wind power
<LI>Statute of limitations extension in blood products cases
<LI>Elections
</OL>

<P>

