<HEAD>
<TITLE> Miscellaneous Minnesota 1996 Laws</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Miscellaneous Laws</h2>



<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Faegre & Benson Government Relations Team</h4>

Child Boating Safety Act (Chapter 396):  There was emotional discussion of the Aaron Sahli Child Boating Safety Act during the 1996 legislative session.  This legislation sets age requirements for operating motorboats and jet skis.  Use of motorized watercraft by all persons under 18 is regulated.  Children under 12 cannot operate motorboats larger than 75 horsepower; those under 13 cannot operate personal watercraft.  The new law was proposed after last years death of 10-year-old Aaron Sahli, who died after the pontoon-boat he was in was struck by a powerboat being driven by an 8-year-old.<p>

Pedestrian Right-of-Way (Chapter 333):  The Legislature enacted a law which makes failure of a driver to stop for pedestrians in a crosswalk a gross misdemeanor on second offense.<p>

Pawn Shop Regulation (Chapter 404):  Legislation was enacted which sets statewide standards regulating pawn-brokers.  The new law still allows local governments to exercise some regulatory authority over pawn-brokers.<p>

Slamming (Chapter 340):  The Legislature responded to consumer complaints that some telephone companies have been changing customers long-distance telephone services without customer authorization - a practice known as slamming.  The law makes slamming illegal in Minnesota.<p>

Internet Information Disclosure:  Legislation requiring a study of consumer privacy rights with regard to on-line computer services was introduced in 1996, but failed in the House.  The bill also set minimum privacy standards.<p>

Mail Balloting:  A proposal to facilitate mail balloting in some cities and towns was passed by the House and Senate, but vetoed by the Governor.  Currently, only cities and towns outside the Twin Cities area that have fewer than 400 registered voters can conduct balloting by mail.  The bill would have increased that limit to 1,000 registered voters.<p>

Handguns:  A provision which would have loosened requirements to carry a handgun was adopted by the House, but not the Senate.<p>

Vouchers:  Governor Carlsons K-12 education vouchers proposal was defeated in committee in 1996.  His proposal would have appropriated $15 million for a pilot program to test a plan allowing low-income students in Minneapolis, St. Paul, Brooklyn Center and an outstate school district to transfer $3,000 in public funding to a non-public school of his or her choice.<p>

Toll Road Hearings (Chapter 455):  Before a toll road can be constructed, the Minnesota Department of Transportation must hold public meetings in every county affected by the proposal.<p>

Recall (Chapter 429):  Voters will decide in the 1996 election whether they want to amend the Minnesota Constitution to allow recall of legislators in cases of serious malfeasance or non-feasance in office or conviction of a serious crime.<p>

New Prison (Chapter 463):  Issuance of $89 million in bonds was authorized for construction of an 800-bed prison.<p>

Tort Reform:  A proposal to require defendants to be 51 percent at fault before being held 100 percent liable under joint and several liability was defeated.
<P>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Rich Forschler at <A HREF="mailto:rforschl@faegre.com"><EM>rforschl@faegre.com</EM></A> or Bob Hentges at <A HREF="mailto:rhentges@faegre.com"><EM>rhentges@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

