<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> New Federal Antitrust Rules:  Opportunities and Challenges for Physicians and Hospitals </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">

<H2>New Federal Antitrust Rules:  Opportunities and Challenges for Physicians and Hospitals</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4><a href="../offices/att_dnvr.html#niederman">Gerald A. Niederman</a> and <a href="../offices/att_dnvr.html#bowman">Laury E. Bowman</a></h4>
<p>


Physicians and hospitals have long complained that overly restrictive antitrust rules have impeded the development of beneficial, provider-owned alternatives to insurer- and HMO-controlled health plans, to the ultimate detriment of health care consumers.  On August 28, 1996, in a promising new development, the United States Department of Justice and the Federal Trade Commission (the "Agencies") released revised "Statements of Antitrust Enforcement Policy in Health Care" (the "Revised Statements") indicating  that the Agencies have relaxed certain key enforcement positions concerning physician and multiprovider networks.<P>

The Revised Statements mark a significant departure from earlier enforcement policies issued in September 1994 (the 1994 Statements), and suggest that a more diverse array of integrated health care delivery systems may receive more lenient antitrust treatment.  Most notably, the Agencies have stated that:<P>

<UL type=disc>
<LI>Formerly prohibited agreements to set prices among providers in a network which does not share economic risk will now be evaluated under a flexible rule of reason standard of antitrust legality, and may therefore be upheld as lawful, so long as the providers are "substantially integrated" and such agreements are reasonably necessary to achieve the networks procompetitive benefits; and
<p> 
<LI>The critical concept of "substantial integration" has been broadened to encompass a more expansive examination of a networks overall clinical integration (e.g., medical management activities), in addition to more conventional indicators of shared economic risk, when evaluating whether providers are in fact "substantially integrated" for antitrust purposes.

</UL>

The Agencies have further clarified their enforcement orientation by providing additional examples of provider joint ventures which may not be challenged in view of an arrangements overall procompetitive impact in the health care marketplace.<P>

Although the Revised Statements also raise potentially significant questions which could present concerns in some settings (e.g., regarding permissible market share and exclusivity), the new rules represent a welcome change, the net effect of which should be to promote new provider alliances and more dynamic competition in many communities.


<H4>Analytic Background</H4>
Consistent with conventional antitrust principles, the Agencies generally take one of two approaches to evaluating providers conduct in health care enforcement actions:  certain activities are classified as "per se" (i.e., presumed) illegal while other activities are judged under the more detailed "rule of reason" approach which evaluates the actual impact of an activity on competition in the marketplace.  (These approaches also mirror the legal standards applicable to private antitrust suits.)  Under the per se approach, some activities undertaken by competitors (including hospitals and physicians) are viewed as being so inherently injurious to competition that they are automatically condemned as illegal.  For example, naked agreements between competing providers that fix prices or divide markets are automatically illegal under the per se rule; such arrangements cannot be defended on the basis of their alleged beneficial character in particular circumstances.<P>

Conversely, under the rule of reason analysis, the Agencies (or the courts in a judicial context) evaluate whether the positive impact on competition arising from particular challenged activities outweighs any alleged anticompetitive effects resulting from those activities.  In conducting rule of reason analysis, it is necessary to:  (1) define the relevant marketplace in which health care services are delivered;  (2) ascertain any anticompetitive effects of the provider network; (3) weigh any anticompetitive effects against procompetitive efficiencies achieved by the same activities; and (4) examine the collateral effects of the activities on participants conduct outside of the provider network joint venture.  Following a detailed factual inquiry, if the procompetitive efficiencies are found on balance to outweigh any anticompetitive effects, the conduct will not be deemed unlawful.<p>

In the 1994 Statements, the Agencies set forth illustrations of the per se and rule of reason criteria, and designated several safety zones outlining arrangements in which providers may engage in certain activities which the Agencies would not challenge under either the per se test or the rule of reason standard, absent extraordinary circumstances.  Many physicians and hospitals have regarded these safety zones as unduly narrow and unrealistic (particularly regarding their one-dimensional emphasis on the use of a  "messenger model" pricing methodology), thereby disadvantaging provider networks vis-&Agrave;-vis insurers and HMOs which are not so limited in their negotiating posture.<P>

In the Revised Statements the Agencies have taken a large step towards creating a more level playing field.  The Revised Statements indicate that certain activities of provider-controlled joint ventures - notably physician networks and multiprovider networks, including doctors, hospitals and other practitioners - may no longer face per se antitrust condemnation based upon collective pricing arrangements if the networks generate significant efficiencies (evaluated under the newly broadened standard of substantial integration) which ultimately benefit health care consumers in an overall market setting.  The Agencies have not changed the contours of the previously defined safety zones.  However, the Revised Statements provide further examples of integrated delivery systems which, although falling beyond the literal ambit of the safety zones, may nonetheless be upheld as lawful under the more flexible rule of reason since such innovative horizontal and vertical arrangements may in fact yield beneficial procompetitive efficiencies.  This change should encourage a more dynamic health care marketplace in which physicians and hospitals can compete more effectively based upon price and quality variables.<P>

The Revised Statements are detailed and the examples presented should be carefully reviewed to maximize antitrust compliance in a given instance.  Against this background, the remainder of this article highlights several key aspects of the new guidelines which may be of particular importance to doctors, hospitals and other providers.

<H4>Physician Network Joint Ventures</H4>
The Revised Statements recognize some of the remarkable changes occurring in the contemporary health care industry, and that physicians in particular have radically changed both the manner and the means through which health care services are delivered in response to market demands for reduced costs and continued quality.  The Agencies have acknowledged that physician networks not fitting perfectly within the narrow safety zones enumerated in the 1994 Statements may still have significant procompetitive benefits for the consuming public.  Applying this more tolerant perspective, the Agencies have modified their enforcement approach to physician network joint ventures in at least two substantial ways.  The government also reiterated the previously articulated principle that networks falling beyond specific safety zones are not necessarily unlawful and must be examined on a case by case basis.<P>

<STRONG>Agreements to Set Prices</STRONG>  The Revised Statements confirm that physicians who are otherwise competitors outside of their participation in a network may agree to collectively set prices for services delivered through the network if the network is sufficiently integrated.  The Agencies have meaningfully expanded the means through which the requisite integration can be demonstrated.  In this context, collective agreement to set prices must in all circumstances be characterized as reasonably necessary for the physician network joint venture to achieve the kinds of significant efficiencies that benefit consumers in the marketplace.<P>

For example, if an agreement among physician network participants provides demonstrable incentives for the physicians to cooperate in lowering costs and improving quality through the management of covered services, the Agencies may not view the agreement as per se illegal (in contrast to naked price fixing arrangements which do nothing more than create a cartel and which are still automatically condemned).  Even integrated arrangements may still be subject to potentially burdensome and expensive factual review under the rule of reason, and may still be judged unlawful depending upon specific facts if, like many such ventures, they fall outside the narrow safety zones.  Nonetheless, the physicians under scrutiny would now be permitted to defend the underlying arrangement on the grounds that it was ultimately procompetitive, rather than facing automatic condemnation under the harsh per se criteria.<P>

<STRONG>"Sufficient Integration"</STRONG>  The Agencies previously articulated a single litmus test to gauge the existence of "integration" sufficient to trigger rule of reason analysis.  Under the 1994 Statements as applied, in order for physician networks to qualify for favored treatment under the safety zones or otherwise, such networks had to prove that they shared substantial financial risk in a narrowly defined manner.  The Agencies rationale for this requirement was (and is) that sharing substantial financial risk is a "bright line" test indicating that sufficient integration exists between physicians to generate significant procompetitive benefits for purchasers of health care.  Thus, the Agencies previously opined that the requisite sharing of substantial financial risk could be achieved by a networks accepting capitated payment for services delivered, or through the withholding of a substantial sum from reimbursement otherwise due to physician participants which is subject to redistribution, if at all, on some basis other than individual productivity.<P>

In a significant departure from their previous pronouncements, the Agencies have now shifted their focus away from the limited issue of shared financial risk to a broader examination of whether a physician network is sufficiently integrated in an economic or clinical sense so as to justify rule of reason treatment.  While not a panacea for loosely-linked groups seeking to oppose managed care penetration or to forestall price competition, this broadened view of integration may offer substantial new opportunities for emerging networks.<P>

The Agencies have reiterated the view that the sharing of substantial financial risk remains an indicator that physician participants in the network are mutually motivated to control costs and to improve the quality of care - the desired and lawful result of integration.  However, the Agencies have expanded their view of other arrangements which may also yield the same legitimate results.  For example, networks which are "clinically integrated" may now meet the Agencies rule of reason standard, even if they do not limit themselves to acceptance of capitated reimbursement or otherwise share financial risk in the narrow sense.<P>

In functional terms, the Agencies current view of clinical integration largely overlaps with contemporary medical management activities, and apparently includes genuine utilization review, outcomes measurement and quality improvement programs implemented by many networks as an overall competitive strategy.  Thus, depending on market share, exclusivity of participation and other circumstances, a physician network that engages in substantial medical management may be deemed sufficiently integrated to uphold a collective fee agreement under the rule of reason, even though the network only accepts discounted fee-for-service reimbursement and does not implement other conventional economic risk sharing mechanisms.  For networks too large to fit within the safety zone, whether such non-economic integration is sufficient to allow more lenient rule of reason treatment is a determination that must be made in light of each networks particular facts and circumstances.<P>

The overriding structural and functional attributes of a particular network still require careful examination and planning to maximize compliance with antitrust requirements under the Revised Statements.  The new rules are likely to provide legal benefits and enhanced strategic opportunities for many provider groups.  However, they may complicate the initial factual and legal review necessary to assess the current legitimacy of a particular physician network under the more desirable (but more fact-intensive) rule of reason standard.

<H4>Multiprovider Networks</H4>
The Agencies have reiterated their previously expressed view that multiprovider networks, including physician-hospital organizations ("PHOs") - which vary greatly in their composition, nature and size - may produce procompetitive efficiencies.  In their current approach to multiprovider networks, the Agencies incorporate their more relaxed views on pricing agreements, discussed above, which apply to the physician network context.  Thus, in the Revised Statements, the Agencies acknowledge that multiprovider networks may achieve sufficient integration to be validated under the rule of reason analysis through such forms of clinical integration as genuine medical management, apart from the conventional standard of shared financial risk which has colored past decision-making.<P>

<STRONG>New Examples</STRONG>  The Revised Statements provide four new examples of multiprovider networks to illustrate application of the broadened standards.  In one example, the Agencies state that a non-exclusive PHO located in a medium-sized city would be analyzed under the rule of reason where the PHO members operated on a fee-for-service basis and had invested capital to purchase and operate a medical management information system to report on the cost, quantity and nature of services rendered, apart from implementing utilization review and quality assurance programs.  The Agencies concluded that they would not challenge such a PHO in view of its apparent clinical integration, because there were numerous other non-network providers in the community, and because the PHO operations would likely generate significant efficiencies for affected consumers.  As suggested above, however, such a conclusion is inherently fact-specific and in the event of legal scrutiny would only be rendered after careful review of the particular circumstances of the case.<P>

In another example, the Agencies hypothesized a PHO which had as its members all of the physicians in a small rural community.  The physicians did not participate in the PHO on an exclusive basis, but did accept scheduled discounts from their current fee-for-service charges.  The PHO additionally devised a bonus structure of up to twenty percent of total payments received if participating physicians met utilization targets.<P>

The Agencies indicated that they would not challenge the formation and operation of such a PHO under a rule of reason analysis since the PHO would not appear to limit competition in any relevant marketplace and had potential to create significant efficiencies.  The Agencies opined that the PHOs agreement to set a fee schedule was consistent with the physician participants overall risk-sharing approach to the venture, and was thus deemed reasonably necessary for the PHO to achieve its procompetitive efficiencies.<P> 

An interesting aspect of the latter example for some rural or non-metropolitan networks is the expression of a new rationale to justify participation in the PHO by a very large percentage of community physicians: the need to respond to competitive pressure from other providers and managed care plans in the nearby "Big City" environment.  The Agencies stated that since involvement of all local physicians would be necessary to respond to competitive pressure from Big City providers, and since physician participants have manifested a genuine willingness to enter into agreements outside of the PHO (i.e., the arrangement is demonstrably non-exclusive), the Agencies would not challenge the PHO.

<H4>Summary</H4>
The Agencies have clearly changed their enforcement perspectives concerning physician network joint ventures and multispecialty provider networks that meet the more flexible standard of financial or clinical integration.  However, the government has also reiterated its position that each venture falling outside the existing safety zones will be evaluated individually based upon the relevant facts involving a given network.  The Agencies have also admonished that they will concentrate on the substance of actual activities undertaken by physician or multispecialty networks, and will determine whether the providers joint activities result in any procompetitive benefits for health care consumers.<P>

Other issues such as exclusivity (in substance as well as form), market share (especially in non-metropolitan communities) and the possibility of "spillover" collusion outside the network are likely to be relevant in future determinations.  Some of these issues may be clarified through future advisory opinions rendered by the Agencies in response to specific inquiries.  Moreover, even though it has been reduced in importance, the "messenger model" of network operations does retain importance for non-risk sharing networks in some circumstances.<P>

Notwithstanding the unresolved issues, the Agencies have communicated a positive approach reasonably aimed at encouraging provider innovation and procompetitive behavior, without dispensing with the need for detailed and ongoing antitrust compliance review.  Physicians, hospitals and other providers should carefully review the Revised Statements and consider their application to the ongoing development and implementation of successful and lawful integrated delivery systems.
<P>


<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Gerald E. Niederman by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:gniederm@faegre.com"><EM>gniederm@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


