<HEAD>
<TITLE> Eighth Circuit Refuses To Adopt Hanlester Decision </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">

<H2>Eighth Circuit Refuses To Adopt Hanlester Decision</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4><a href="../offices/att_mpls.html#schroeder">Thomas S. Schroeder</a></h4>
<p>


For Medicare and Medicaid providers and their attorneys waiting to see whether the Eighth Circuit would adopt the decidedly provider-friendly decision by the Ninth Circuit in the Hanlester case, the answer is in.<P>

"We dont think so," the federal appellate court with jurisdiction over Minnesota, the Dakotas, Iowa, Nebraska, and Missouri seemed to say in an August 8, 1996 ruling.  <EM>See United States v. Jain</EM>, Nos. 95-2820, 95-3036 [1996 WL 444885].  Rejecting the more stringent scienter requirement applied in the Hanlester case, <EM>Jain</EM> serves as a warning that providers in the Eighth Circuit may be found in violation of the Medicare/Medicaid anti-kickback statute regardless of whether they knew their conduct violated the statute, so long as they knew their conduct was inherently "wrongful."  

<H4>Facts in <EM>Jain</EM></H4>  
In <EM>Jain</EM>, psychologist Swaran Kumar and his corporation, the Center for Mental Health Services, Inc., appealed their convictions for violating the Medicare/Medicaid anti-kickback statute (commonly referred to as the "fraud and abuse" provisions) and federal mail fraud statutes.  Justice Department prosecutors alleged that Dr. Jain, a psychologist in private practice who operated an outpatient therapy clinic and supervised several affiliated psychologists and counselors, had received payments for referring patients to North Hills Hospital in Kansas City, an acute-care psychiatric hospital.<P>

North Hills former hospital administrators testified that they paid Dr. Jain $1,000 per month for "marketing" - payments that in fact were in exchange for patient referrals.  Dr. Jain allegedly provided little if any tangible marketing support, yet the administrators testified that he demanded increased payments from North Hills and threatened to refer his patients elsewhere if his demands were not met.  In all, North Hills made nineteen payments to Dr. Jain between July 1989 and October 1990 totalling $40,500.  During this same period, Dr. Jain referred 49 patients to North Hills, 30 of whom were insured by the Civilian Health and Medical Program of the Uniformed Services ("CHAMPUS"), and one of whom was a Medicare beneficiary.<P>

The jury convicted Dr. Jain and his corporation on all nineteen counts contained in the governments indictment.  Dr. Jain was sentenced to five years probation, six months home detention and a $10,000 fine.  The defendants appealed their convictions, arguing that the trial courts jury instruction had erroneously defined the term "willfully" in the anti-kickback statute.<P>

The anti-kickback statute makes it a felony to "knowingly and willfully solicit or receive any remuneration" in return for referrals of Medicare patients.  Dr. Jain argued that an instruction similar to that required by the Ninth Circuit in <EM>Hanlester</EM> should have been used-namely, that conviction under the statute required the government to prove that the defendants had intentionally violated a known legal duty.

<H4>Taking a Middle Course</H4>
Both the trial and appellate courts disagreed with Dr. Jain, and in the process ended speculation concerning whether the <EM>Hanlester</EM> decisions heightened scienter requirement would be adopted in the Eighth Circuit.  The Ninth Circuit ruled in <EM>Hanlester Network v. Shalala</EM>, 51 F.3d 1390 (9th Cir. 1995), that joint ventures involving physician self-referrals could not give rise to criminal liability absent proof of both: (1) an awareness that the arrangement was prohibited under the anti-kickback statute; and (2) a specific intent to disobey the law.  The United States Supreme Court denied review of <EM>Hanlester</EM>, ignoring the pleas of more than a dozen states attorneys general who had filed or joined in amicus briefs urging review and reversal of the controversial decision.<P>

The trial court in <EM>Jain</EM> charted a middle course between the instruction sought by the government and the more rigorous instruction now applied in <EM>Hanlester</EM> jurisdictions.  The court declined to apply the governments proposed instruction - that "willfully" requires mere consciousness of the act but not consciousness that the act was unlawful - reasoning that such a lax scienter requirement might encompass some types of innocent conduct.  On the other hand, the court refused to instruct the jury that in order to be convicted, the defendant must have intentionally violated a known legal duty.  The court observed that the anti-kickback statute prohibited willful conduct rather than willful violations of the statute.  Fashioning its own compromise between the governments and Dr. Jains proposed instructions, the court instructed the jury that "the word willfully means unjustifiably and wrongfully, known to be such by the defendant."

<H4>Hanlester Criticized</H4>
The Eighth Circuit affirmed the instruction.  The appellate court conceded along with the trial court that the anti-kickback statute may potentially criminalize "conduct that is not inevitably nefarious."  Nonetheless, the appellate court made clear its view that the <EM>Hanlester</EM> decision had gone too far in attempting to safeguard innocent defendants from conviction:

<blockquote>
Both the plain language of the [anti-kickback] statute, and respect for the traditional principle that ignorance of the law is no defense, suggest that a heightened mens rea standard should only require proof that Dr. Jain knew that his conduct was wrongful, rather than proof that he knew it violated "a known legal duty."
</blockquote>

Even after distinguishing <EM>Hanlester</EM> as involving "an administrative debarment proceeding," the court went out of its way to criticize the Ninth Circuits creation of Hanlesters rigorous scienter standard "without considering other alternatives."<p>

The lesson from <EM>Jain</EM> is that while ignorance of the law - and in particular, ignorance of what constitutes a violation of the anti-kickback statute - may be a defense in jurisdictions where Hanlester defines the intent requirement, such ignorance is not a defense within the Eighth Circuit.  The federal district court for the southern district of Ohio (<EM>U.S. v. Neufeld</EM>) and a Florida state appellate court  (<EM>Medical Development Network, Inc. v. Professional Respiratory Care</EM>) had previously declined to adopt <EM>Hanlester</EM>, but <EM>Jain</EM> marks the first federal circuit court decision to do so.

Because of the legal conflict between the circuits created by <EM>Hanlester</EM> and <EM>Jain</EM>, the Supreme Court may choose to review the issue if Dr. Jain and his clinic file an appeal.  Such a prospect is sure to keep providers and their attorneys guessing for several more months about precisely what level of intent is required to establish a violation of the anti-kickback statute.

<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Thomas Schroeder by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:tschroed@faegre.com"><EM>tschroed@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


