<HEAD>
<TITLE> Court Allows Private Plaintiff to Bring Fraud and Abuse Claim </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">

<blockquote>

<H2>Court Allows Private Plaintiff to Bring Fraud and Abuse Claim</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4><a href="../offices/att_mpls.html#schroeder">Thomas S. Schroeder</a></h4>
<p>


Adding to a sparse but growing line of cases, a federal district court in Tennessee recently reversed its own prior ruling and held that private plaintiffs may sue health care providers under the so-called "<EM>qui tam</EM>" provisions of the federal False Claims Act based solely on allegations that the providers violated the Medicare/Medicaid anti-kickback law, the "Stark" anti-referral law, or similar state fraud and abuse and anti-referral laws.   If followed in other jurisdictions, the decision in <EM>United States ex rel. Pogue v. American Healthcorp, Inc.</EM>, 914 F.Supp. 1507 (M.D. Tenn. 1996), could lead to the effective "privatization" of enforcement actions under the fraud and abuse and Stark laws, the extension of False Claims Act liability beyond its traditional realm of fraudulent billing, and a dramatic increase in health care providers exposure under all three laws.

<H4>The Allegations</H4>
The plaintiff in <EM>Pogue</EM>, a former director for marketing and development at Diabetes Treatment Centers of America, Inc. ("DTCA"), filed suit on behalf of the government against DTCA, its parent company American Health-corp, Inc., West Paces Medical Center in Atlanta, Georgia (the "Hospital") and five physician staff members of the Hospital.  In <EM>Pogues</EM> third amended complaint, Pogue alleged that the Hospital had contracted with DTCA to pay DTCA a fee based on the number of diabetes patients DTCA admitted to the Hospital.  DTCA in turn entered into a medical directors contract with one of the five defendant physicians, and service contracts with the remaining physicians-contracts which Pogue claims amounted to a disguised fee-for-referral arrangement designed to reward the physicians for admitting their patients, including Medicare and Medicaid patients, to the Hospital.  Pogues federal complaint alleged that these contractual arrangements violated the Medicare Fraud & Abuse Statute, 42 U.S.C. § 1320a-7b(b), as well as the prohibited referral provisions contained in the Stark law, 42 U.S.C. § 1395nn(a)(1). <P>

The <EM>qui tam</EM> provisions of the False Claims Act, 31 U.S.C. §§ 3729-3733 (the "Act"), allow any private party to bring a civil action on behalf of the federal government against any person or entity that "knowingly" presents a "false or fraudulent claim" for payment to the government.  Penalties under the Act include a civil fine of between $5,000 and $10,000 for each false claim, three times the amount of damages sustained by the government, and payment of the governments (or qui tam plaintiffs) costs and attorneys fees.<P>

Although the Act defines "knowing" to include deliberate ignorance or reckless disregard of the falsity or fraudulent nature of the claim being presented, the Act nowhere defines what makes a claim "false or fraudulent."  Past courts have ruled that the claim at issue-in the health care context, frequently a Medicare or Medicaid reimbursement claim form such as Form 1450 or 1500-must contain misrepresentations which render them false or fraudulent on their face.  
In contrast, Pogues complaint did not allege that there was anything facially wrong with DTCAs cost reports or claims forms, nor that the services provided were unnecessary or over-billed.  Rather, Pogue asserted that the defendants claims were fraudulent because by submitting their claims for reimbursement, the defendants were "implicitly" representing their compliance with all of the statutes, rules and regulations governing the Medicare act, including the fraud and abuse and Stark laws.  In short, Pogue claimed that any violation of either the fraud and abuse or Stark laws automatically resulted in a violation of the False Claims Act, under which anyone could sue for damages as a <EM>qui tam</EM> plaintiff.<P>

<H4>The Courts Decision</H4>
Vacating an earlier decision it had issued to the contrary in September of last year, the United States District Court for the Middle District of Tennessee agreed with <EM>Pogue</EM> and refused to allow dismissal of the case.  While recognizing an earlier admonition of the United States Supreme Court that the False Claims Act "was not designed to reach every kind of fraud practiced on the Government," the court nonetheless held that the Act "was intended to cover not only those situations in which the claims themselves are false but also those situations in which a claimant engages in fraudulent conduct with the purpose of inducing payment by the government."  914 F. Supp. at 1511.<P>

Nevertheless, the court emphasized that it would not permit the transformation of the Act into a "stalking horse for enforcement of every statute, rule and regulation," and it reiterated that Pogue could proceed with his claim "only if he can show that Defendants engaged in the fraudulent conduct with the purpose of inducing payment from the government."  Id. at 1513 (emphasis added).
Despite this cautionary language, the courts decision, coupled with its September 1995 unpublished decision on the defendants motion to dismiss, creates a second ominous precedent for health care providers that participate in the Medicare and Medicaid programs.  In its September ruling, the same court had ruled that a comprehensive release and waiver signed by Pogue in May of 1994-only a month before Pogue filed his False Claims Act lawsuit-did not bar Pogue from filing his qui tam suit against DTCA and its parent company American Healthcorp.  In the release, Pogue represented that he was "releas[ing] and forever discharg[ing]" DTCA and its parent company "from any and all claims [or] causes of action . . . whatsoever at law or equity, in state or federal court."<P>

Although such broad releases are routinely sought by employers and enforced by courts in post-termination employment suits, the Tennessee court ruled that <EM>Pogues</EM> release was unenforceable as against public policy, stating:  "the public interest in detecting fraud on the government, which the [False Claims Act] seeks to promote, would be substantially impaired by the enforcement of the release[.]"  <EM>Pogue</EM>, 1995 WL 626514, *4 (Sept. 14, 1995 Memorandum Order).

<H4>A Trend of Two?</H4>
In reaching its holding, the court in Pogue cited a "recent trend of cases" allowing False Claims Act lawsuits based on fraud and abuse or Stark violations, relying most heavily on a recent decision by a federal court in Ohio that drew a similar conclusion.  In <EM>United States ex rel. Roy v. Anthony</EM>, 914 F.Supp. 1504 (S.D. Ohio 1994),  the United States District Court for the Southern District of Ohio allowed a <EM>qui tam</EM> suit to proceed against a network of medical imaging companies that provided X-rays, MRIs, and CT-scans, together with their physician-shareholders, officers and directors, even though the court conceded that the "vague assertions" contained in the plaintiffs complaint created only "a tenuous connection" between the fraud and abuse statute and the False Claims Act.  <EM>Id</EM>. at 1506.  Despite the <EM>Pogue</EM> courts reference to a "trend" favoring such suits, thus far the trend extends no further than the decisions in <EM>Roy</EM> and <EM>Pogue</EM>.<P>

An equally significant aspect of the <EM>Pogue</EM> case is the courts finding that the False Claims Act "clearly prohibits fraudulent acts even if they do not cause a loss to the government."  914 F.Supp. at 1513.  The court recognized that "there is no allegation that the Defendants overcharged Medicare or charged it for services not rendered[.]"  <EM>Id</EM>. at 1510.  Yet the court held that Pogue was not required to allege facts regarding actual damages.  The False Claims Act, the court stated, "was intended to govern not only fraudulent acts that create a loss to the government but also those fraudulent acts that cause the government to pay out sums of money to claimants it did not intend to benefit."  <EM>Id</EM>.
 
<H4>Impact on Providers</H4>
The decision in <EM>Pogue</EM> carries precedential weight only within the Middle District of Tennessee.  However, given the paucity of decisions addressing the relationship between the False Claims Act and the fraud and abuse/Stark laws, Pogue is likely to be cited by <EM>qui tam</EM> plaintiffs across the country as persuasive authority.  For that reason, the decision and the trend it may presage are attracting considerable attention from lawyers and health care professionals alike.<P>

Observers critical of the <EM>Pogue</EM> decision have raised two general objections.  First, both the <EM>Stark</em> statute and the anti-kickback statute provide detailed remedies and penalties for their violation, including civil and criminal fines, imprisonment and exclusion from the Medicare and Medicaid programs.  Notably absent from these remedies is a private right of action for damages, a remedy which Congress might easily have created had it so intended.  The decisions in Roy and Pogue create such a remedy as a matter of common law, and thereby subject health care providers to a wholly new set of liabilities under the fraud and abuse and Stark laws-including money damages to private litigants, a different type of statutory penalty, and inevitably greater exposure to frivolous plaintiffs suits.  This objection was the focus of an appeal filed in March by DTCA and American Healthcorp with the Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals.  However, largely for procedural reasons, the Sixth Circuit refused to hear the appeal.<P>

Second, with regard to the Stark law in particular, observers have expressed alarm that Roy and Pogue permit an end-run of the scienter requirement in the False Claims Act.  As noted above, the most frequently invoked provisions of the Act require the plaintiff to show that the defendant acted "knowingly" in submitting the false claim.  The Stark law, in contrast, is essentially a strict liability statute whose penalties are triggered by referrals when certain relationships exist, without regard to providers intent or knowledge in entering into those relationships or making the referrals.  While the scienter requirement formulated in the Ninth Circuits April 1995 opinion in <EM>Hanlester Network v. Shalala</EM>, 51 F.3d 1390 (9th Cir. 1995), provides some protections against False Claims Act lawsuits bootstrapped from federal fraud and abuse violations, providers may find it far more difficult to dismiss <EM>qui tam</EM> actions premised upon conclusory allegations of Stark violations.<P>

It remains to be seen whether the courts decision in <EM>Pogue</EM> is a harbinger of a new wave of <EM>qui tam</EM> actions based on alleged fraud and abuse and Stark law violations, or whether the decision is simply a blip on the map of often contradictory False Claims Act caselaw.  Rather than waiting to find out, providers would be well advised to put in place effective compliance programs that identify liability hazards before they become qui tam lawsuits.


<P>

</blockquote>
<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Thomas Schroeder by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:tschroed@faegre.com"><EM>tschroed@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

<HR>

