<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Colorado Issues Proposed Regulations for Risk-Bearing Provider Networks </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">

<blockquote>

<H2>Colorado Issues Proposed Regulations for Risk-Bearing Provider Networks</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4><a href="../offices/att_dnvr.html#bowman">Laury E. Bowman</a></h4>
<p>


Continuing its efforts to keep pace with rapidly evolving health care delivery systems, the Colorado Division of Insurance (the Division) recently issued proposed regulations which potentially impact a broad spectrum of health care providers in Colorado.  Numerous other states are closely following the Divisions regulatory process, and some can be expected to issue similar regulations.

<H4>Overview of the Proposed Regulations</H4>
The proposed regulations would require limited service licensed provider networks (referred to as LSLPNs) to obtain a license from the Division before entering into health care services agreements if providers are at risk for the services they deliver.  For example, the regulations would require LSLPNs to obtain a license prior to agreeing to deliver health care services to a self-funded employer in exchange for a capitated payment.  In its proposed regulations, the Division defines a capitated payment in part as payment to a health care provider that is based on the exposure to provide certain health care services to covered persons but does not vary on the basis of the number or type of services actually rendered.  The Division explains that agreements to deliver health care services on a capitated basis transfer risk to providers, and thus constitute the business of insurance.  Under the Divisions rationale, providers who accept capitated payment must obtain a license before transacting the business of insurance.

<H4>Scope of the Proposed Regulations</H4>
In public hearings held in May, several commentators requested clarification regarding the scope of the proposed  regulations.  The regulations define an LSLPN as a provider or provider network which directly contracts with consumers for services restricted to a medical specialty or services limited to a single type of licensed medical facility.  The definition of an LSLPN, however, also states that the LSLPNs services must, in the opinion of the [Colorado Commissioner of Insurance], fall significantly short of those offered by a health maintenance organization or under a comprehensive or major medical policy. <P>

It is unclear whether the proposed regulations in effect create a regulatory niche for those types of services which are typically carved out of  comprehensive or major medical policies (for example, mental health services).  If so, the regulations would allow providers of those services to obtain, in essence, a limited service HMO license.  If the Division adopts this more restricted approach, some physician-hospital organizations (PHOs) and independent practice associations (IPAs) may be required to obtain full-blown HMO licenses, which can be time-consuming and costly.  Conversely, the regulations may apply more broadly to  PHOs or to IPAs which provide multiple medical services that are not comprehensive in scope and that do not include many of the services encompassed by major medical policies.<P>

The Division may provide clarification on the scope of its proposed regulations in future drafts.  It is clear for now, however, that provider networks which do not take risk (e.g. do not accept capitated payments in exchange for services) are not transacting the business of insurance.  Presumably, provider networks which only accept fees for services delivered, or discounted fees for services, will not be required to obtain a license.  Further, the regulations expressly state that providers who accept risk from other licensed insurance carriers (so-called downstream risk) are exempted from the regulations scope.  However, such providers must file a certificate to that effect with the Insurance Commissioner.

<H4>Application for a License</H4>
After final regulations are issued, provider networks that fall within the scope of  the regulations may apply for a license.  Application for a license requires a provider network to submit information regarding its proposed business plan, its corporate organizational documents,  an audit of its current financial conditions, and copies of its proposed contracts with providers and purchasers of  health care services.  The provider network must also submit information regarding the measures and protections it intends to take to ensure its fiscal solvency.  In conjunction with this requirement, the provider network must maintain a minimum net worth, excluding intangible assets, in an amount of no less than $100,000, unless the Insurance Commissioner requires a greater amount.<P>

In addition to the net worth requirements, the proposed regulations also require that an LSLPN post a deposit in the amount of $100,000, unless the Commissioner requires a greater amount, to protect against insolvency.  The provider network must also demonstrate its ability to monitor and evaluate the cost effectiveness of services delivered, and access to care provided.

<H4>Future Developments</H4>
The Division had projected July 1 as the effective date for the regulations.  However, as of the date of this publication, it has yet to issue revised regulations.  While the Division may issue final regulations within the next few months, the National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC) is also expected to issue model regulations on the same topic soon.  The Division may or may not postpone its regulatory process to track the NAICs efforts.  In any case, providers and their legal counsel should carefully monitor activities in this area, consistent with each networks individual business plan, as the Divisions regulatory process and the NAICs drafting efforts proceed.


<P>

</blockquote>
<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Laury Bowman by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:lbowman@faegre.com"><EM>lbowman@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


