<HEAD>
<TITLE> FTC Considers Standards for
Using "Made In USA" Label </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>FTC Considers Standards for
Using "Made In USA" Label</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>John M. Haurykiewicz and Matt Luxton</h4>
<p>


<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he proper use of the "Made in USA" and "Made in America" labels on products sold in the United States has generated a lot of activity recently.  Beginning with the prosecution of two athletic shoe manufacturers in 1994, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) set out a standard requiring that all or virtually all of a products parts and labor be of domestic origin when using one of these labels.  Subsequently this standard has come under fire from manufacturers, while receiving support from individual consumers, and the FTC has suspended enforcement, held a public hearing (which lasted two days), and published the comments from the hearing.  Unfortunately for those seeking more certain guidance, no new or restated standard has yet been published by the FTC.<p>

<strong>Background</strong><br>

Labeling requirements for products sold in commerce are thoroughly regulated under federal law.  In general, the laws of the United States Customs Service require that "every article of foreign origin" imported into this country be properly marked to indicate its place of origin.  These labeling requirements extend to component parts that are imported by manufacturers and assembled here into finished products unless the components are substantially transformed during manufacture.  Substantial transformation requires a fundamental change in form, appearance, nature, or character of a component which adds value to the finished product.<P>

For many years, federal law was silent on the specific use of the label "Made in America."  This changed in 1994 when Congress passed the Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act, which added § 45a to title 15 of the United States Code.  Section 45a specifically charges the FTC with monitoring the use of the Made in America (or its equivalent) label on goods.  The FTC was given the power to set a standard for using these labels that considered an appropriate percentage of imported components which may be included in the product.  Thus was added another arrow in the quiver of broad powers of the FTC to police and punish unfair competition and practices domestically, including improperly labeling products.<P>

It rapidly became apparent, however, that the FTC would not consider the percentage of foreign components and labor in enforcing § 45a.  In complaints brought against two athletic shoe manufacturers in 1994, the FTC set forth an "all or virtually all" standard for using the Made in America label.  Specifically, the FTC prosecuted Hyde Athletic Industries (manufacturer of Saucony running shoes) and New Balance Athletic Shoe for using variations of the Made in America label on shoes that were not wholly made in the United States.  The FTC felt that the shoe manufacturers had represented that all or virtually all, of the component parts of the athletic shoes [were] made in the United States, and that all or virtually all, of the labor in assembling the athletic shoes [was] performed in the United States, while most of the shoes were actually assembled abroad, or assembled domestically from foreign components.<P>

The FTCs "all or virtually all" standard prompted a swift and widespread response from manufacturers, who argued that this standard was impossible to meet and unrealistic in todays global economy.  Acknowledging the groundswell reaction, the FTC suspended its enforcement activities, and announced plans to conduct a comprehensive review of consumers perceptions of Made in America claims in product advertising and labeling.  Furthermore, the FTC stated it would promulgate a new standard for using such labels and issue guidelines on how domestic content was to be measured.  Toward this end, the FTC invited public comment on consumer perceptions of Made in America labels, and what standard should be used to measure domestic content in products.  For discussion purposes the FTC proposed a standard based on a percentage of domestic content as calculated by the sum of the purchase cost of domestic parts and the cost of labor and overhead in assembly divided by the total product cost.<P>

In the interim, the FTC carved out various "safe harbor provisions" for manufacturers of products having foreign components or labor.  In the Hyde decision, the FTC suggested the following as acceptable labeling for such products:
<OL type="A,B,C">
<LI>Made (or assembled) in X (country) of Y (country) components; or
<LI>Made (or assembled) in X (country) of domestic and foreign components; or
<LI>Made (or assembled) in X (country) of primarily (or mostly) foreign and some domestic components; or
<LI>Made (or assembled) in X (country) of primarily (or mostly) domestic and some foreign components; or
<LI>Made (or assembled) in X (country) of foreign components; or
<LI>Built in X (country) of imported components.
</OL>

No guidance was given as to what constitutes "primarily," "mostly," or "some" foreign or domestic parts.<P>

<strong>The Public Response</strong><br>

The period for public comment closed on January 22, 1996.  The FTC received 258 responses to its request, all of which can be reviewed on the FTCs World Wide Web page:  http://www.ftc.gov/opp/usa.htm.  Comments came from a variety of parties, including 164 responses from individuals and 94 responses from "professionals" including manufacturers, manufacturing associations, trade associations, labor unions, congresspersons, state Attorneys General, and government agencies.<P>

The responses by individuals almost uniformly called for strict adherence to the FTCs current standard.  While a few individuals recognized the difficulty of requiring 100% domestic content and proposed allowing use of the labels on products which are merely assembled domestically, most of the individuals urged retention of the current FTC standard, stating that anything less amounts to public deception.  Many expressed a concern for U.S. jobs, arguing that reducing the current standard will allow and encourage manufacturers to move a greater part of the manufacturing process overseas.  Individuals were generally outspoken in their advocacy, with one individual being careful to preface his comments by asking the FTC not to be offended by his letter, but then ending by suggesting that FTC employees "[g]et a real job and do something worthwhile, maybe cleaning toilets in the White House."<P>

Three responses were from labor unions.  Two unions, the International Leather Goods Union and the Teamsters Union, supported the current FTC standard.  The United Auto Workers, however, in a very thoughtful response, recognized that an "all or virtually all" standard, while desirable, is not practical in todays global economy.  The union urged the adoption of a standard that would ensure the greatest amount of domestic content possible, but did not articulate what that standard might be.  It expressly stated, however, that harmonization of the FTC standard with the Customs labeling requirements, as many in industry have called for (see below), would be inadequate to maximize domestic content.<P>

There were also responses from labeling and trade associations.  These associations were divided on what standard should be applied to the "Made in USA" label.  One association advocated abolishing the use of the "Made in USA" label, stating it is protectionist in nature.  Three associations advocated reducing the current FTC standard, but each proposed a different standard: a straight 75% domestic content standard, harmonizing the FTC standard with the labeling requirements of the Customs Service, and a "flexible standard" without a percentage of domestic content.  Three other associations supported the current standard.  Similar to the individual responses, these associations were outspoken in their advocacy - the Union Label and Service Trades Department equated any modification to the "all or virtually all" standard to the "NewSpeak" destruction of words in George Orwells novel, 1984.<P>

Another group of responses represented industry views, and included responses from individual manufacturers, manufacturing associations, and legislators.  Almost all of these industry responses expressed frustration over the multitude of country of origin and labeling laws, and the inconsistent requirements under these laws.  Sixteen of the 94 industry responses (which represent 6% of all responses, and 17% of industry responses) offered a straight percentage type standard, with 50% and 75% being the two most commonly proposed percentages.  Twenty three of the 94 industry responses (9% of all responses, 24% of industry responses) called for the harmonization of the FTC standard for "Made in USA" labels with the U.S. Customs country-of-origin laws, and advocated the adoption of the customs "substantial transformation" test by the FTC.  The U.S. Customs Service and the General Services Administration also submitted comments that support the adoption of the Customs Services standards.<P>

There were two notable exceptions, however, to the general industry desire to change the current FTC standard.  Both the textile / apparel industry and the hand tool industry voiced strong opposition to any alteration of the current FTC standard.  The textile industry responses were almost unanimous in support of the current standard, and advocated that current labeling requirements for textiles and apparel are sufficient.  Members of the small hand tool industry similarly urged the retention of the current FTC standards, indicating they use American steel in their manufacturing process, and want to retain their marketing advantage over other tool manufacturers who use imported steel and cannot currently use the "Made in USA" label.<P>

Legislative responses included seven comments from Congresspersons and individual and group comments from state Attorneys General representing 18 states.  The Congresspersons generally felt that the current "all or virtually all" standard was too stringent and penalized manufacturers who attempt to produce articles in the United States.  The Attorneys General, however, advocated retaining the current standard, although they felt a 90% domestic content standard would also be acceptable.  The Attorneys General further proposed adopting an "Assembled in USA" label for products containing a "significant" percentage of domestic labor.<P>

As a general conclusion, the responding parties advocated standards that further their individual interests.  Industry generally favored a reduction in the FTC standard because of difficulties in obtaining 100% of subcomponents from domestic sources, with a 50% or 75% domestic content threshold, or a harmonization of the FTC standard with the Customs Services "substantial transformation" test being advocated.  Individual parties and certain labor unions, on the other hand, urged the FTC to retain its current "all or virtually all" standard.  These parties asserted a fear that American jobs will be lost if a reduced standard is adopted.<P>

<strong>The Workshop</strong><br>

The FTC held a workshop to consider the public comments on March 26 and 27 of this year.  A number of the parties who submitted public comments participated in this workshop, including representatives from labor unions, trade associations, the Attorneys General from individual states, and the U.S. Customs Service.  The voluminous transcripts from the workshop are available for review on the FTC Web page.<P>

Participants in the workshop discussed the FTCs current standard regarding the use of "Made in USA" labels and proposed alternatives to this standard.  While much of the discussion was a restatement of the public comments described above, three primary areas of discussion were the use of the "all or virtually all" standard, a percentage standard, and a "substantial transformation" standard.  Significant questions were raised regarding the exact application of any of these three standards, including how far back in the manufacturing process "content" is measured, what content should be measured, and definitions of terms such as "all or virtually all" and "substantial."  The workshop ended without any clear consensus on the appropriate standard for using "Made in the USA" labels.<P>

The FTC has again invited public comment on the use of the "Made in USA" labels in response to the issues raised at the workshop.  Specifically, the FTC has requested comments on the workshop transcript itself, and on questions raised in the workshop such as when content should be measured, what content should be measured, and what "substantial transformation" test should be utilized.  While originally set to close on April 30th, the FTC extended the time for these comments to June 30, 1996 due to the complexity of the issues.  The FTC has not yet published any of these new comments, but is expected to do so on their Web page when it has processed the comments.<P>

<strong>Conclusion</strong><br>

The standard for the use of "Made in America" or its equivalent in marking or marketing products is currently uncertain.  While the FTC recently required any product using such a label to be entirely comprised of domestic components and labor, they are currently considering revising this standard to take into account consumer perceptions regarding "Made in America" labels.  Interested parties have proposed a number of standards, ranging from retaining the current "all or virtually all" standard to harmonizing the FTCs marking requirements with those of the Customs Service.  As the recent workshop on this issue made clear, however, no consensus has been reached, or is likely to be reached in the near future on a single standard.  In the interim, manufacturers may choose to use the "safe harbor" provisions set forth by the FTC in marking and marketing their products in order to avoid running afoul of whatever standard is eventually adopted.
<P>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to intellectual property and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact John Haurykiewicz by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:jhauryki@faegre.com"><EM>jhauryki@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

<HR>

