<HEAD>
<TITLE> Bad Faith Patent Infringement and Increased Damages: The Federal Circuit Speaks </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Bad Faith Patent Infringement and Increased Damages: The Federal Circuit Speaks</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Jeff H. Eckland 
and William L. Roberts</h4>
<p>


<FONT SIZE=+2>U</FONT>nder patent law, a court may award up to three times the patent owners actual damages based on a finding that the defendants infringement was willful.   The Federal Circuit has long held, however, that a finding of willful infringement, whether by a court or a jury, permits but does not compel an  increased damages award.  As a result, even where a patent holder wins a willfulness verdict at trial, the trial judge has broad discretion in deciding whether and to what extent to award increased damages.<P>

But where a trial court requires the jury to make a factual finding that the infringement was done in bad faith in order to reach a verdict of willfulness, does that bad faith finding bind the trial court in deciding the issue of increased damages?  In Jurgens v. CBK, LTD., 80 F. 3d 1566 (Fed. Cir. 1996), in which Jeff H. Eckland argued for plaintiffs to the Federal Circuit, and was accompanied on the briefs by William L. Roberts and R. Carl Moy, the Federal Circuit answered this question in the affirmative.  <P>

In the process, the Federal Circuit expounded on the distinct but oft-confused concepts of willful infringement and reaffirmed the impact of a jury verdict on the trial courts discretion to award increased damages. The Jurgens case thus counterbalances the recent trend toward erosion of the right to jury trial in patent cases.  See, e.g., Markman v. Westview Instruments., Inc., 52 F.3d 967, 989 (Fed. Cir. 1995) (Mayer, J., concurring in judgment only) (this [the majoritys holding] is not just about claim language, it is about ejecting juries from infringement cases).<P>

<strong>The Opinion</strong><br>

The Jurgens case was tried in the Western District of Tennessee.  The Jurgenses claimed that CBK, LTD., a gift market wholesaler, had copied their patented windsock bird decoy products and sold them by the thousands throughout the United States.  The Jurgenses obtained summary judgment in their favor on patent validity and infringement.  The issues of compensatory damages and willfulness were tried to a jury.<P>

The jury returned a verdict in the Jurgenses favor, finding about $550,000 in compensatory damages and finding that the defendants infringement was willful as the trial court had defined that term in the jury charge.  Over plaintiffs objection, the trial court had defined willful infringement to require a finding of bad faith conduct on the part of the defendants.  Thus, in finding willfulness the jury necessarily found that the defendants had acted in bad faith.<P>

Despite the jury verdict, the trial court refused to award any increased damages.  The trial court concluded that the defendants infringement was the result of reliance upon the opinion of counsel and thus did not warrant the punishment of increased damages.
The Federal Circuit reversed and remanded.  As a threshold matter, the Court noted that a finding of bad faith is not required for a finding of willful infringement.    Bad faith, noted the Federal Circuit, has numerous patent law applications.  80 F.3d at 1570.  As it relates to predicate culpability for an increased damages award, bad faith infringement denotes merely one type of infringement.  Id. at 1571.  Bad faith infringement occurs, for example, where an infringer obtains an incompetent, conclusory opinion of counsel only to use as a shield against a later charge of willful infringement  exactly what the Jurgenses contended occurred in this case.  <P>
Deliberate copying of a patented invention with no validity or infringement inquiry at all is another example of bad faith infringement, according to the Federal Circuit.  Id.  <P>

Thus, held the Federal Circuit, the trial judge raised the hurdle for a willfulness verdict above the minimum legal threshold by requiring the jury to find bad faith.  In effect, the trial court  made the rejection of the defendants contention that they acted in good faith reliance on opinion of counsel a necessary prerequisite to a verdict of willfulness.  Considering the detailed jury instruction, which included ... an additional requirement that CBK act in bad faith, the only way the jury could have reached the decision that CBKs conduct was willful was to reject its contention that it relied in good faith on the opinion of counsel.  Id. at 1572.<P>

Once the trial court submitted the issue of bad faith to the jury and found the evidence sufficient to support the jurys verdict, the Federal Circuit held that the trial court could neither disregard the jurys bad faith finding nor make contrary findings in deciding the issue of enhanced damages.  Said the Federal Circuit, Although a trial court many times has the discretion to weigh the closeness of the case and the scope of the infringers investigation in deciding whether to increase a damages award, it does not have discretion to reweigh this evidence once the matter has been decided by the jury...  Id.  Because the trial courts refusal to award increased damages was based on a conclusion that contradicted the jurys bad faith finding, the Federal Circuit remanded the case for reconsideration with due regard for the jurys  factual findings.<P>

<strong>Analysis</strong><br>

The Federal Circuits opinion in Jurgens v. CBK, LTD.  marks the first time the Court has directly addressed the interplay between the concepts of willful infringement, bad faith infringement, and enhanced damages.  How is it that an infringer can be guilty of willful infringement warranting increased damages without having acted in bad faith?  The answer lies in the concept of willful infringement as it has developed under Federal Circuit case law.<P>

The patent law, according to the Federal Circuit, imposes an affirmative duty  on every party who engages in any potentially infringing conduct to use due care to avoid infringing anothers patent rights.  It follows that a party can be held to have willfully infringed a patent even in the absence of malice or bad faith conduct.  A party may be liable for increased damages simply because the party did not fulfill its affirmative duty of due care, i.e., did not do enough to investigate the propriety of its conduct, before it forged ahead.  For example, a party who proceeds with sales of a product sincerely believing that its conduct does not infringe is nevertheless vulnerable to a finding of willful infringement if the party fails to consult with a qualified attorney on the issue.  In such a case, there is no bad faith conduct.  There is merely a failure to take certain steps which the patent law in most cases demands as protection for the rights of patent holders.  The infringement is willful but not in bad faith.<P>

The question the trial court typically must address in deciding whether and how much to increase damages is, where on this spectrum of culpability does the defendants conduct lie?  The accepted meaning of the term bad faith and the specific examples of bad faith infringement the Federal Circuit articulated in the Jurgens opinion make clear that bad faith infringement lies at the upper end of this spectrum as the most egregious form of infringement.  Deliberate copying with no inquiry whatsoever evinces a callous disregard for the patent law which has often formed the basis for the maximum punishment available   treble damages.  And the use of a faulty attorney opinion as a mere protective device is perhaps the most egregious, form of infringement possible.  Not only does it reflect a callous disregard for the patent law, but it also demonstrates a premeditated effort to conceal such improper behavior.  It would appear such conduct similarly warrants an award of treble damages against the infringer.<P>The Jurgens opinion thus clarifies that a party may in certain circumstances be liable for willful infringement without having acted in bad faith.  A party who has infringed a patent in bad faith, on the other hand, has a culpability which exceeds the minimum threshold necessary for an award of increased damages and is a prime candidate for a judgment of treble damages.<P>

Significantly, the Jurgens opinion also strongly reaffirms the principal that jury fact findings are binding on a trial court in addressing the  issue of increased damages.  Although the principal was implicit in prior Federal Circuit cases, the Federal Circuit had never before expressly held that the trial court is bound by a jurys fact findings supporting a verdict of willfulness.  Indeed, the dissenter in Jurgens argued that Federal Circuit precedent rejected exactly this principal.  80 F.3d at 1575.  At a minimum, the Jurgens case ensures that a jury trial on the issues of willfulness will not devolve into a pointless exercise whose outcome the trial judge is free to ignore.<P>

Jeff H. Eckland and William L. Roberts of Faegre & Benson LLP represented the Jurgenses at trial in this case 
<P>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to intellectual property and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Jeff Eckland by e-mail at <a href="mailto:jeckland@faegre.com"><em>jeckland@faegre.com</em></a> or William Roberts at <A HREF="mailto:wroberts@faegre.com"><EM>wroberts@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

