<HEAD>
<TITLE> Eurasian Patent Convention </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Eurasian Patent Convention</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Iliana Haleen</h4>
<p>


<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>n the last few years, laws in the former USSR and Eastern European countries relating to intellectual property rights have been modernized to conform with comparable legislation in Western Europe.  The recently adopted Eurasian Patent Convention is an example.  It largely corresponds to the European Patent Convention and is expected to function the same way.<P>

Patent applications may now be filed with the newly established Eurasian Patent Office in Moscow. The Eurasian Patent Office may also be designated in PCT applications.<P>

At present, the Eurasian Patent Convention has the following members:

<blockquote>
Russian Federation<BR>
Belarus<BR>
Azerbaijan<BR>
Kazakhstan<BR>
Kyrgyzstan<BR>
Tadzhikistan<BR>
Turkmenistan
</blockquote>

The Convention will also enter into force in Moldova on February 16, 1996 and in Armenia on February 27, 1996. Ukraine and Georgia signed the Convention, but have not yet ratified it at this writing.  Uzbekistan and the Baltic StatesLithuania, Latvia and Estoniahave not yet joined the Convention.<p>

The Eurasian Patent Convention establishes common criteria for patentability.  Eurasian patents are granted for inventions that are new, involve an inventive step and have an industrial application. The duration of patent protection is 20 years.  The Convention also contains provisions concerning persons entitled to apply for an Eurasian patent, the rights of the patent owner, and circumstances under which compulsory licenses must be granted.  Convention member states do retain their sovereignty as to their national patent systems. Consequently, much of the Eurasian patent protection is covered by national law and not by the Conventions provisions.  Some other key provisions are as follows:

<UL>
<LI>The application and the Eurasian patent extend to all States that are members of the Convention as of the filing date.  
<LI>The application will be published after 18 months from the first priority date. Requests for examination must be filed and an examination fee paid within 6 months from the date of publication of the application.
<LI>One or more priorities may be claimed.
<LI>Generally, the examination procedure corresponds substantially to Russian patent practice; extensions of term are usually possible upon payment of an additional fee.
<LI>The application documents of a Eurasian patent application may be filed in a language other than Russian, but a subsequent filing of a Russian translation thereof is necessary.
<LI>After granting a patent, annual patent fees shall be paid for each designated state through the Eurasian Patent Office. The fees for each state are determined by that state.
<LI>Within six months after publication of the registration of a Eurasian patent in the Bulletin of the Eurasian Patent Office, an opposition can be filed which, if successful, can result in the patent being restricted or annulled.
<LI>Nullity, infringement, compulsory license and the like remain reserved to the national legislation of the member states.  National courts also may decide on such matters, but only for validity within their respective territories.
</UL>

The Eurasian Patent Convention is designed to facilitate international patent protection over the greater part of the former USSR in conformity with the provisions of the European Patent Convention.  The final list of members of the Convention and the role the Convention will ultimately play in the international scheme of protection for intellectual property rights remain to be seen.


<P>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to intellectual property and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Iliana Haleen in Frankfurt am Main by phone at 49 69 971 227 0. 
<p>

