<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Gronholz v. Sears, Roebuck & Co:  
A Lesson in Patent Trial Strategy </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Gronholz v. Sears, Roebuck & Co: <BR> 
A Lesson in Patent Trial Strategy</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Jeff H. Eckland and William L. Roberts</h4>
<p>


<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>n the recent jury trial of Marlene Gronholz v. Sears, Roebuck & Co. and Ryobi Motor Products Corp., Civil File No. 3-94-1239 (U.S. District Court, D. Minnesota, Hon. Michael J. Davis, presiding) Jeff H. Eckland and William L. Roberts of Faegre & Benson LLP successfully represented Sears and its manufacturer, Ryobi, against a claim of patent infringement potentially worth $3,000,000.00.  The jury awarded no damages and found that defendants did not infringe the patent.  The case provides a good illustration of a key aspect of patent trial strategy: utilizing one central winning theme.  <P>

Patent cases present a myriad of potential legal and factual issues.  Patent validity alone potentially raises issues of prior public use, anticipation, obviousness, inequitable conduct, and others.  Interpretation of the patent claims and comparison of the claims to the accused device typically present as many, if not more, potential issues.  And a decision in favor of the accused infringer on any one of these issues is generally fatal to the patent holders claim.<P>

Thus, parties accused of patent infringement have no shortage of potential defenses.  Indeed, the most difficult aspect of defending a patent case often is not developing defenses but instead making the strategic decisions about what arguments not to make.  The natural desire to preserve every available issue combined with uncertainty about which arguments a factfinder might find credible creates a strong temptation to use a shotgun approach, putting forth every plausible defense in the hopes that one will take hold.
Parties and their counsel must resist this temptation.  Particularly in a jury trial, the failure to drop weaker defenses in order to shape the case around one central theme can be costly.  A carefully tailored presentation of a single, consistent theme magnifies the persuasiveness of the defense.  The shotgun approach, by contrast, tends to reduce persuasiveness.  The presentation of weak arguments can distract the fact finder from the strong ones and, worse, can lead to a loss in overall credibility.  A confused, bewildered jury is unlikely to invalidate a patent which has received the seal of approval from the PTO.  Such a jury is still less likely to find noninfringement based on fine distinctions between the patent claim and the accused device.  In short, less is more when it comes to framing trial defenses in patent cases.<P>

In Gronholz, the plaintiff was the widow of deceased inventor Donald Gronholz.  Mr. Gronholz invented a device called a router guide.  He showed his invention to a Sears representative.  Sears evaluated a prototype of the device, but entered into no agreement with Mr. Gronholz.  After the Gronholz patent issued, Sears came into the market with a new Craftsman router guide.  Mr. Gronholz sued Sears and its router guide manufacturer claiming they had willfully infringed his patent.<P>

In large part because of a tortured procedural history both in the PTO and in federal court, the facts presented a multitude of potential defenses.  The challenge was to develop a defense theme that would overcome the inevitable first impression that Sears had copied and exploited Gronholzs invention without paying him a dime.<P>

A frontal assault on the patents validity was a definite possibility.  Given the prior art, one could reasonably argue that the patent should never have been issued, that the Gronholz device contributed nothing new and useful to the art of router guide design.
Such a frontal assault, however, faced two difficulties.  First, the PTO had issued the patent and had also upheld it upon reexamination.  Obviously, the examiner felt the Gronholz device disclosed something new and useful.  To win on this theory, the jury would have to conclude that the patent office was wrong.<P>

Second, the argument tended to undercut Sears defense of noninfringement.  The Sears device did look similar to the Gronholz router guide.  Indeed, plaintiffs theory of the case was that Sears copied the Gronholz device and simply omitted one thumb screw to try to avoid liability.  Sears noninfringement defense was this:  Sears and its manufacturer studied the Gronholz device, the Gronholz patent, and the prior art to determine what the unique features of the Gronholz patent were.  The manufacturer, with the advice of counsel, proceeded to design a product that did not contain the features which made the Gronholz device unique and hence patentable.  Sears used in its new router guide only what was known from the prior art and refrained from using the patentable features of the Gronholz device.  <P>

If in fact thats the way Sears and its manufacturer proceeded, then in the jurys mind there would be no good reason for Sears to attack the patents validity.  If Sears argued invalidity over the prior art, it would risk inadvertently communicating to the jury that Sears did not believe its own noninfringement argument.  Worse, Sears would be arguing against itself in saying on one hand that the patent discloses nothing new, but on the other hand that Sears carefully avoided copying the new features of the Gronholz device.  <P>

Sears did not argue the prior art invalidity defense at trial.  It presented the noninfringement defense as its one central theme.  Sears supplemented this theme with a consistent argument that the key patent claim was invalid not because of the prior art but because plaintiff had attempted to broaden the patent upon reissue to try to bring the Craftsman router guide within its scope.  Sears won.
The jury in its special verdict found that the Sears device did not infringe the patent literally or under the doctrine of equivalents.  The jury also found that the key claim of the patent was invalid because it was broadened upon reissue.  In light of its noninfringement finding, the jury found that plaintiff was entitled to no damages and did not reach the question of willfulness.<P>

Had Sears taken the tack of asserting all possible defenses, the outcome may well have been different.  But the ability to discard less persuasive theories and focus on one central winning theme enabled Sears to prevail over a sympathetic plaintiff with a claim which, on the surface, was quite appealing.<P>



Jeff H. Eckland and William L. Roberts of Faegre & Benson LLP represented Sears and its manufacturer, Ryobi, in this case.<P>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to intellectual property and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Jeff Eckland by e-mail at <a href="mailto:jeckland@faegre.com"><em>jeckland@faegre.com</em></a> or William Roberts at <A HREF="mailto:wroberts@faegre.com"><EM>wroberts@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

