<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Minnesota Narrows  Insurance Coverage for
Patent Infringement Claim </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Minnesota Narrows  Insurance Coverage for
Patent Infringement Claim</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>William L. Roberts</h4>
<p>


<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>n a case of first impression for a Minnesota appellate court, the Minnesota Court of Appeals recently held that a commercial general liability insurer is not obligated to defend or indemnify against a claim of patent infringement.  In Fluoroware, Inc. v. Chubb Group of Ins. Cos., 545 N.W. 2d 678 (1996), Fluoroware faced a suit for patent infringement based on its sales of plastic disk packages.  Fluoroware tendered the defense to its  commercial general liability (CGL) insurers, the Chubb Group and others, who denied coverage and refused to defend.  Fluoroware filed a declaratory judgment action to establish coverage.<p>

The district court, relying on the leading Minnesota federal district court case John Deere Ins. Co. v. Shamrock Indus., 696 F. Supp. 434 (D. Minn. 1988), affd , 929 F.2d 413 (8th Cir. 1991), found the claim to be covered.  Since the allegedly infringing device had been the subject of Fluoroware advertising, the district court concluded the infringement claim fell within the advertising injury clause of the CGL policy.  Consistent with John Deere, the lower court rejected the argument that, to be covered, the claimed injury must have been proximately caused by the advertising activity.  545 N.W.2d at 681.<p>

The Minnesota Court of Appeals reversed.  It held that under Minnesota law a showing of direct causation between the advertising activity and the claimed injury must be made:  [A]dvertising liability coverage does not result inevitably from infringement claims merely because a product is advertised.  Id. at 681.  Further, in order to obtain coverage, the Court of Appeals held that the insured must show that the underlying claim arguably constitutes an offense specifically listed in the policy.  The Court of Appeals proceeded to reject Fluorwares contentions that a patent infringement claim falls within the scope of misappropriation of advertising ideas or style of doing business, unfair competition, or piracy, all of which were specifically listed torts under the advertising injury CGL policy provisions at issue.  Accordingly, the Court of Appeals held, the CGL policy imposed no obligation on the insurers to defend or indemnify against the claim.<p>

In so holding, the Minnesota Court of Appeals joins a growing line of authorities holding that a claim of patent infringement does not fall within the scope of the standard CGL policys coverage.  See, e.g., Intex Plastic Sales Co. v. United Natl Ins. Co., 23 F.3d 254 (9th Cir. 1994); Bank of the West v. Superior Court, 833 P.2d 545 (Cal. 1992).  Indeed, commentators have criticized the few earlier opinions reflecting a contrary view.  See W. Savino and C. Butera, Insurance Coverage and Patent Infringement:  Beyond Insureds Reasonable Expectations, 661 PLI/Comm 103 (1993).<p>

Significantly, the Fluoroware case was before the Court of Appeals on a certified question addressing only the claim of direct patent infringement.  In its brief statement of facts, the Court of Appeals noted that Fluoroware was also accused of contributory infringement and actively inducing infringement.  However, the Court of Appeals chose not to address the issue whether a claim of contributory patent infringement or active inducement of patent infringement falls within the scope of CGL policy coverage.  A claim that an insureds advertising teaches or encourages consumers to engage in an act constituting patent infringement (a type of contributory patent infringement) appears to contain the direct causal connection between the advertising activity and the claimed injury which the Court of Appeals found essential.  Moreover, such a claim may arguably constitute a form of unfair competition.  Thus, it remains an open question in Minnesota whether coverage exists under the standard CGL policy for contributory and inducement-type patent infringement claims.  
	
<P>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to intellectual property and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

<strong><b>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact William Roberts at <A HREF="mailto:wroberts@faegre.com"><EM>wroberts@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

