<HEAD>
<TITLE>Recent patent law developments</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Introduction</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
1994 was a year of significant change for the United States Patent Law.  The GATT implementation legislation, with its provision of 20-year patent terms and provisional applications, is probably the most fundamental change made to the law since its enactment.  On the judicial front, the Federal Circuit continued its efforts to refine the law on such important topics as the doctrine of equivalents and mathematical algorithms implemented by computer.  Highlights of these and other recent developments follow.  Patent practitioners and owners alike will want to carefully consider the effects these developments.<P>
Patent law was also significantly impacted in 1994 when Congress and President Clinton enacted the Uruguay Round Agreements Act.  The Act changes the enforceable life of a patent, permits the filing of a "provisional" application which permits applicants to preserve patent rights while deferring commencement of the patent term, allows the life of a patent to be extended under certain circumstances which cause a delay in issuance of the patent, and includes an offer to sell a patented invention to the list of infringing activities.<P>
</DL>
<H2>CAFC CASES</H2>
<DL>
<DL>
<DT><B>Means-Plus-Function Claims are to be Construed According 35 USC § 112, Sixth Paragraph, for Patentability as Well as Infringement Determinations</B><P>
<B><EM>In re Donaldson Co.</EM>, 29 U.S.P.Q.2d 1845 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>The sixth paragraph of 35 USC § 112 states that a means-plus-function claim shall be construed to cover corresponding structure, material, or acts described in the specification and equivalents thereof.  However, the Patent and Trademark Office (PTO) refused to apply this paragraph during examination, and instead more broadly construed means expressions according to their literal language.  As a result, the PTO took the position that a claimed "means" element was anticipated by any structure capable of performing the recited function.<P>
The Federal Circuit, in an en banc decision, forced the PTO to narrow its interpretation of means claims during prosecution to cover only the structure, material, or acts described in the specification, and equivalents thereof.  Means claims must be construed in accordance with paragraph six during patentability determinations by the PTO, as well as during validity and infringement determinations by a court.<P>
<DT><B>Programmed Computers may be Patentable Subject Matter Under 35 USC § 101</B><P>
<B><EM>In re Alappat</EM>, 31 U.S.P.Q.2d 1545 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>The majority of an en banc panel of the Federal Circuit held that a claim to a rasterizer for converting waveform sample data into pixel illumination intensity data for subsequent display (e.g., by an oscilloscope), and written in means-plus-function language, is directed to a "machine" which is patentable subject matter under 35 USC § 101.  The decision is based heavily upon the law established only months earlier in In re Donaldson that means-plus-function claims must be interpreted for purposes of patentability as covering at least the structure disclosed in the application corresponding to the claimed "means."  Since Alappat's application disclosed known circuit elements such as a barrel shifter and an arithmetic logic unit for performing these functions, the claim was found to characterize a patentable machine.<P>
Although the embodiment of the invention described in the application was not implemented by a computer, the decision supports the proposition that a general purpose computer programmed to perform the recited functions would also be patentable.  The court states that such programming creates a new machine, because a general purpose computer in effect becomes a special purpose computer once it is programmed to perform particular functions pursuant to software instructions.<P>
Perhaps the most important aspect of this decision is its discussion of the "mathematical algorithm exception" to § 101.  Under the two-part Freeman-Walter-Abele test developed prior to this decision and used to identify unpatentable algorithms, the claim is first analyzed to determine whether it directly or indirectly recites a mathematical algorithm.  Once a mathematical algorithm is found, the claim as a whole is further analyzed to determine whether the algorithm is applied in any manner to physical elements or process steps.  If so applied, the claim passes muster under § 101.  In practice, both parts of this test are difficult to consistently apply to the ever expanding range of computer-implemented inventions.<P>
The majority in Alappat never applied the Freeman-Walter-Abele test.  Instead, they state that the claim at issue meets the appropriate test, which is "whether the claimed subject matter as a whole is a disembodied mathematical concept, whether categorized as a mathematical formula, mathematical equation, mathematical algorithm, or the like, which in essence represents nothing more than a 'law of nature,' 'natural phenomenon,' or abstract idea.'"  The use of this intuitive test could lead to more consistent and accurate determinations of computer-implemented inventions that are unpatentable algorithms.<P>
<DT><B><EM>In re Warmerdam</EM>, 31 U.S.P.Q.2d 1754 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>The method claims at issue were directed to a method for generating a data structure which represents the shape of a physical object in a position and/or motion control machine as a hierarchy of bubbles.  Analyzing these claims using the Freeman-Walter-Abele test, the Federal Circuit concluded that they recited nothing more than the manipulation of abstract ideas and were therefore unpatentable subject matter.<P>
The apparatus claim at issue was directed to a machine having memory which contains data representing a bubble hierarchy generated by the method claims.  Without any analysis, the court stated that this claim is clearly patentable subject matter.<P>
<DT><B><EM>In re Karen I. Trovato and Leendert Dorst</EM>, Civ. File No. 93-1050,-1565, (Fed. Cir. December 19, 1994).</B><P>
<DD>The inventions were the product of work in the field of computer science known as graph theory.  At issue were method and means-plus-function apparatus claims for propagating cost waves through a data structure representing a physical task space, to determine the least cost path of motion through the task space.  Using the Freeman-Walter-Abele test, the Federal Circuit concluded that both the apparatus and method claims recited nothing more than the manipulation of abstract ideas and were therefore unpatentable subject matter.<P>
<DT><B>Disclosure of an Invention to One or More Friends or Colleagues Prior to Critical Date Results in Loss of Patent Rights</B><P>
<B><EM>The National Research Dev. Corp. v. Varian Assoc. Inc.</EM>, 30 U.S.P.Q.2d 1537 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>The patented invention at issue in this case was a method and apparatus for eliminating noise produced by an NMR spectrometer.  More than one year before the patent applications filing date (the critical date), the inventor's graduate-studies advisor discussed the invention with another scientist during a one-on-one conversation at a convention.  The scientist receiving the information was not asked to keep the information confidential.  The Federal Circuit held that this disclosure placed the invention in public use under 35 USC § 102(b) and, therefore, invalidated the patent.<P>
<DT><B><EM>The Beachcombers, Int'l Inc. v. WildeWood Creative Prod. Inc.</EM>, 31 U.S.P.Q.2d 1653 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>A subsequently patented kaleidoscope was shown to party guests by the inventor more than one year before the patent application was filed.  The guests were not asked to maintain in secrecy any information about the device.  The Federal Circuit found that this activity placed the invention in public use under 35 USC § 102(b) and, therefore, invalidated the patent.<P>
<DT><B>Invention Disclosures in Continuation Patent Applications Need Not Be Updated to Comply with the Best Mode Requirement</B><P>
<B><EM>Transco Prod. Inc. v. Performance Contracting</EM>, 32 U.S.P.Q.2d 1077 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>The patent involved in this case issued from a continuation application.  Although the best mode for practicing the invention changed between the original filing date and the filing date of the continuation application, the description of the invention was not updated in the continuation application.  The district court held the patent invalid for failure to comply with the best mode requirement of 35 USC § 112 when the continuation application was filed.<P>
The Federal Circuit overruled the lower court decision, stating that there is no need to update the invention disclosure to comply with the best mode requirement when filing a continuation application.  To the extent that the continuation application is claiming only subject matter disclosed in the original application, the key date for purposes of the best mode requirement is the date of the original application.<P>
<DT><B>U.S. Courts Lack Jurisdiction to Consider Infringement of Foreign Patents</B><P>
<B><EM>Mars Inc. v. Kabushiki-Kaisha Nippon Conlux</EM>, 30 U.S.P.Q.2d 1621 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>The holder of U.S. and Japanese patents to an invention sued its competitor in the United States for infringement of both the U.S. and Japanese patents.  The Federal Circuit held that U.S. courts do not have power to consider the claim of infringement of the Japanese patent since the infringement claims are not so related that they form part of the same case or controversy, and governing laws are different.<P>
<DT><B>References Pertaining to Different Fields of Endeavor Can be Analogous Prior Art if Pertinent to Problem Being Solved</B><P>
<B><EM>Heidelberger Druckmaschinen AG v. Hantscho Commercial Prod. Inc.</EM>, 30 U.S.P.Q.2d 1377 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>One of the issues presented in this case was whether a reference showing a mechanism for converting between reciprocating and rotary motion in machines such as engines could be used to assert the obviousness of a similar mechanism in a chopper for folding sheets emerging from a printing press.  Although overturning the district court's determination of obviousness on the basis of significant evidence of commercial success and the lack of a suggestion in the prior art to combine the references, the Federal Circuit provided guidance on when references can be considered analogous prior art.  In particular, the court states that references that are not within the field of the inventor's endeavor can be relied on in patentability determinations, and are therefore described as "analogous art", when a person of ordinary skill in the art would have reasonably consulted those references and applied their teachings when seeking a solution to the problem they were facing.<P>
<DT><B><EM>In re Paulsen</EM>, 31 U.S.P.Q.2d 1671 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>One of the issues addressed by the Federal Circuit in this case was whether references showing hinges and latch mechanisms used in a desktop telephone directory, piano lid and washing machine cabinet were analogous to such devices used to secure the display housing in a laptop computer.  Using the guidelines set forth in <EM>Heidelberger Druckmaschinen AG v. Hantscho Commercial Products Inc.</EM>, the court determined that given the nature of the problem, one of ordinary skill in the art would have consulted these other mechanical arts and that the references were reasonably pertinent.  It therefore concluded that the Board's finding that the references were analogous was not clearly erroneous.<P>
<DT><B>Design Patent Obviousness Rejection Requires Primary Reference Having Basically the Same Design Characteristics as Claimed Design</B><P>
<B><EM>In re Harvey</EM>, 29 U.S.P.Q.2d 1206 (Fed. Cir. 1993).</B><P>
<DD>The design patent applications at issue were directed to vases formed by the intersection of two geometric solids.  Vases based on this concept, but with different geometric solids, were known.  Both the Patent Office and the Board rejected the applications as the obvious substitution of one common geometric solid for another.<P>
Reversing the Board's decision, the Federal Circuit states that a proper design patent rejection requires that the visual ornamental features of the claimed design appear in the prior art in a manner which suggests such features as used in the claimed design.  The primary cited reference must have design characteristics that are basically the same as the claimed design.  The designs of other references can then be relied upon for modification of the basic design.<P>
<DT><B>PTO Can Rely on Hearsay in Making Rejections During Examination</B><P>
<B><EM>In re Epstein</EM>, 31 U.S.P.Q.2d 1817 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>The Federal Circuit ruled that the Board did not err in determining that third-party software products were "in public use and on sale" more than one year before the applicant's filing date, and were therefore properly considered prior art, based upon abstracts that are not themselves prior art publications but which indicate that products were "first installed" or "released" more than one year prior to filing date.  Although the abstracts were on their face hearsay, they appeared to be accurate and reliable.  The applicant's were free to introduce rebuttal evidence, but did not.<P>
<DT><B>Printed Matter Rejection Not Appropriate for Claim to Memory Data Structure</B><P>
<B><EM>In re Lowry</EM>, 32 U.S.P.Q.2d 1031 (Fed. Cir. 1994).</B><P>
<DD>The claims at issue in this case were directed to a memory having an original data structure.  The Board analogized the data structure to printed matter, and rejected the claims on the basis that the "printed matter" data structure was not functionally related to the memory.  The court reversed the Board's decision holding that the printed matter cases have no factual relevance in situations such as that presented by this case where the claimed invention requires that the information be processed by a computer rather than the mind.<P>
<DT><B>Efforts by Third Party to Obtain Documents Used In Alternative Dispute Resolution Rejected</B><P>
<B><EM>Haworth Inc. v. Steelcase Inc</EM>, 19 F.3d 39 (Fed. Cir. 1994)</B><P>
<DD>Haworth sued Steelcase and Herman Miller in separate actions alleging infringement of Haworth patents on electrified wall panel systems.  Haworth and Steelcase agreed to submit the case to a special master for resolution by settlement or mini-trial.  Herman Miller subpoenaed Steelcase for documents relating to the Haworth-Steelcase litigation and ADR proceedings and alternatively moved to intervene in the Haworth-Steelcase litigation.  The court balanced the competing interests of public access to court records with the privacy interests of Haworth and Steelcase and held against Herman Miller.  The court noted that the use of private ADR techniques should be encouraged.<P>
<DT><B>Generic Disclosure Does Not Necessarily Prevent Patenting of Specific Species Falling Within the Generic Disclosure Under 35 U.S.C. § 102.</B><P>
<B><EM>In Re Baird</EM>, 16 F.3d 380 (Fed. Cir. 1994)</B><P>
<DD>Generic disclosure of family of chemical compounds encompassing more than one hundred million individual compounds does not render a specific compound within that family obvious unless the generic disclosure suggests the specific compound.<P>
<DT><B>Patent Specification and Scope of Invention Examined by the United States Patent and Trademark Office Defines "Function" of the Invention for Assessing Infringement under the Doctrine of Equivalents.</B><P>
<B><EM>Genentech Inc. v. Wellcome Foundation Ltd</EM>, 29 F.3d 1555 (Fed. Cir. 1994)</B><P>
<DD>Genentech owns two patents covering the production of a protein known as tissue plasminogen activator (t-PA) by means of recombinant DNA techniques.  Wellcome manufactures two competing products met-t-PA and FE1X.  When applying the standard function-way-result tripartite test used to determine infringement under the doctrine of equivalents, the court notes that the specification of the Genentech patents define the "function" of the claimed t-PA as both "stimulating the dissolution of fibrin clots through the cleavage of plasminogen to plasmin" and "catalyzing the conversion of plasminogen to plasmin and binding to fibrin."  The competing products met-t-PA and FE1X stimulate the dissolution of fibrin clots through the cleavage of plasminogen to plasmin but do not bind to fibrin.  Hence, as the court notes, the ultimate conclusion as to whether the competing products met-t-PA and FE1X infringe under the doctrine of equivalents depends entirely upon the breadth of the "function" utilized in the test.  The court resolves the matter by establishing that the Patent Office must have issued the patent based upon the more limited "catalyzing the conversion of plasminogen to plasmin and binding to fibrin" function provided in the specification and correspondingly limiting the breadth of the "function" prong in the function-way-result test.<P>
<DT><B>Patent Owner's Ability to Recover Damages for Failure to Mark Under 35 U.S.C § 287 Can Result From Imputed Licensee's Failure to Mark.</B><P>
<B><EM>Amsted Industries v. Buckeye Steel</EM>, 23 F.3d 374 (Fed. Cir. 1994)</B><P>
<DD>Failure of implied licensee to mark patented products under 35 U.S.C § 287 is imputed to patent owner.  Failure to mark precludes the patent owner from recovering damages for infringement prior to the time the infringer was actually notified of such infringement.<P>
<DT><B>Court Refuses to Issue Injunction After Conclusion of Seventeen Year Despite Extensive Infringement of Patent During Patent Term.</B><P>
<B><EM>Kearns v. Chrysler</EM>, 32 F.3d 1541 (Fed. Cir. 1994)</B><P>
<DD>Owner of patent to intermittent windshield wipers is not entitled to injunctive relief after expiration of seventeen year patent term.  Plaintiff's novel argument that infringement of patent during seventeen year period deprived him of the ability to enjoy the rights granted by the patent for the full seventeen year period was rejected by the court.<P>
</DL>
</DL>
<H2>Legislation</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
The Uruguay Round Agreements Act was signed into law by President Clinton on December 8, 1994.  This piece of legislation implements the trade agreements concluded in the Uruguay Round of multilateral trade negotiations (GATT).  Significant and fundamental changes to the U.S. Patent Law are included in this Act.  The Patent and Trademark Office has also published proposed amendments to the rules of practice to implement the changes contained in the Act.  These amendments will be the subject of a public hearing on February 16, 1995.<P>
Introduced, but not passed by, the 103rd Congress was The Patent Application Publication Act of 1994.  This Act had provisions directed to the publication of patent applications after 18 months from the application's earliest effective filing date.  Similar legislation will likely be acted upon by the 104th Congress.  The Patent and Trademark Office will hold a public hearing on issues associated with the 18-month publication of patent applications on February 15, 1995.<P>
In general, the changes to the Patent Law brought about by the Uruguay Round Agreements Act will take effect one year after the date on which the WTO (World Trade Organization) Agreement is entered into force with respect to the United States.  Certain transitional procedures are effective on June 8, 1995, six months following the effective date of the Act.  The following are among the more significant changes to the Patent Law.<P>
<DL>
<DT><B>20 Year Patent Term</B><P>
<DD>All U.S. Patent applications filed on or after June 8, 1995 will be effective for a term beginning on the date of issuance and ending 20 years from the U.S. filing date.  If the application claims priority from any earlier filed U.S. parent application, the term ends 20 years from the filing date of the earliest such parent application.  Priority from an earlier filed foreign application under 35 USC § 119 is not take into account in determining the term of a patent.  The earliest U.S. filing date is the trigger for the term.<P>
Patents issued on or before June 8, 1995, and patents issuing on applications filed before that date, shall have a term which is the greater of the 20-year term as described above, or 17 years from the date of grant.  Acts that become infringing by reason of this transitional term option are not subject to the remedies of injunctive relief, damages or attorney fees if substantial investment was made prior to June 8, 1995.<P>
<DT><B>Provisional Application Filing Procedures</B><P>
<DD>A new "provisional application" filing procedure is established in § 111(b).  To obtain a filing date, a provisional application need only contain a specification in accordance with § 112 and a drawing as prescribed by § 113.  The name of the inventor(s) and the $150 filing fee ($75 for small businesses and individual inventors) can be filed later.  No claims or oath/declaration are required.  The application will not be examined, does not mature into a patent, and is not subject to interference proceedings.<P>
A provisional application is not entitled to a right of priority from any earlier-filed foreign or U.S. application, and is regarded as automatically abandoned 12 months after its filing date.<P>
A "regular" U.S. application filed under § 111(a) can claim priority from a provisional application.  The term of a patent issuing on such a § 111(a) application is determined by its filing date, not the filing date of the parent provisional application.  Provisional applications therefore enable U.S. applicants to establish a priority date while postponing by 1 year the filing event that triggers the 20-year patent term (as foreign applicants can by taking advantage of the Paris Convention priority year).  However, it is important to remember that the provisional application is a regular national filing that starts the Convention priority year.<P>
<DT><B>Patent Term Extensions</B><P>
<DD>Patent term extensions of up to 5 years are available for certain delays in the issuance of a patent.  Reasons that can be used to secure such an extension include the imposition of a secrecy order, an interference and successful appellate review before the Board of Patent Appeals and Interferences and federal courts.  The period of extension shall be reduced by any time attributable to appellate review before the expiration of 3 years from the application filing date, and for the period of time during which the applicant did not act with due diligence, as determined by the Commissioner.<P>
<DT><B>Date of Invention Can be Proved with Reference to Acts in WTO Member Countries</B><P>
<DD>Patent applicants will be entitled to establish dates of invention (e.g., for purposes of interferences and "swearing around" references) by reference to knowledge or use thereof, or other activity with respect thereto, in WTO Member Countries.  The rights of this provision are prospective.  An applicant cannot establish a date of invention that is earlier than 12 months after the effective date of the Act.<P>
<DT><B>Offers to Sell and Importing into the U.S. are Infringing Activity</B><P>
<DD>35 USC § 271 and other sections relating to infringement of patents have been amended to characterize "offers to sell" and "imports into the United States" as infringing acts.
</DL>
</DL>

<HR>

