<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>How to manage your Intellectual Property</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Introduction</H2>
<DL>
<DD>Companies dependent on technological innovation for competitive advantage have been cognizant of the potential value of their intellectual property ("IP") since at least the early 19th century.  In recent years, the idea of the "intellectual property audit" has gained great currency among engineering managers and IP lawyers.  It appears, however, that issues surrounding the creation, enhancement, exploitation and protection of IP are becoming ever more pervasive.  According to the cover story in the October 3, 1994 issue of Fortune Magazine, IP - or a more broadly defined but closely related concept, intellectual capital - is increasingly being recognized as many companies' "most valuable asset."<P>
As a result, more companies are devoting greater resources to developing disciplined means of managing IP (and also other knowledge resources whether or not they are legally protectible) from a broad business (as opposed to a legal/technical) perspective.  "What's at stake is nothing less than learning how to operate and evaluate a business when knowledge is its chief resource and result."  Fortune, Oct. 3, 1994, at 68.<P>
Even for many companies in more traditional businesses, IP assets can provide significant competitive benefits.  Of course, as with other items that vie for management attention and company resources, the trick is to apply the right amount of financial and personal resources in the right way at the right time to create and exploit the IP that has the best effect on the company's bottom line.  Following are some broad suggestions for approaching the legal (and closely related business) components of that task.<P>
</DL>
<H2>Step 1:  Make One or More People Specifically Responsible</H2>
<UL>
<LI>In technology-driven companies, the natural place to look for IP leadership is in the ranks of scientific and engineering management; in fact, some basic level of such leadership is usually in place.  Often it is still possible and desirable to achieve greater definition of responsibility for functions such as training both new and more senior technical people in the administration of research (keeping lab books, etc.), the disclosure and evaluation of inventions, decisions whether to file patent applications, and the like.<P>
<LI>Other people who may be needed to fill out the ranks of an IP management team may include in-house counsel, strategic marketing planners, other marketing or sales executives, and other general or financial executives with strategic planning responsibilities.  In designating the team, don't overlook the importance of (and need to manage) the non-technical IP, such as trademarks, service marks and many copyrights.<P>
</UL>
<H2>Step 2:  Assess the Nature and Organization of Your Existing IP</H2>
<UL>
<LI>This step is frequently referred to as conducting an "intellectual property audit."  Depending on how much effort and attention you've already devoted to managing your IP, you may need to hold an organizational meeting or two to decide on a game plan to assess your existing IP.  IP audits come in various shapes and sizes.  Depending on the urgency of your timing, the nature of your business and the existing level of sophistication of your designated team about IP matters, you may be able to accomplish much or most of the work in house.  Thus, as with many other types of projects, a bit of organizational effort at the front end can pay considerable dividends.  Among the topics deserving of early consideration (and later revisiting as more information is gathered and greater understanding and consensus is achieved) are the following:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Does the IP management team and/or the audit project team have the necessary and appropriate members (see Step 1 above)?<P>
<LI>What preliminary information should be gathered at an early stage (e.g., lists of all patents, trademarks, etc. in existing portfolio, organizational charts and so forth)?<P>
<LI>If the enterprise is conducted through a group of related corporations or other entities rather than in a single legal entity, consider which entity owns (and which entity should own) which IP, as well as which entities actually use which IP.  This exercise may suggest additional tax planning and/or documentation of licenses between various of the related entities.  If your operations have an international component, variations in the IP laws of different countries could also result in issues and potential problems that can be alleviated with advance attention to these types of details.<P>
<LI>Make sure all team members (including outside counsel) compare notes and have some basic preliminary orientation and understanding as to the competitive significance of various types of IP in your business and industry.  For example, do companies in your industry have a propensity for patent litigation or are they at least somewhat inclined to engage in licensing or cross-licensing?  Do they even bother with patent protection at all?<P>
<LI>Determine which internal team members will gather which categories of documents and information.  To the extent time and internal resources permit, try to educate inside team members as to the key basic principles of IP law, and have them participate extensively in the fact gathering process.<P>
<LI>Determine what general level of detail appears appropriate for various categories of IP.  In technology-driven companies, you will more likely find it desirable to focus first, and possibly foremost, on patent and trade secret-related activities and issues.  Other companies may find copyright and/or trademark issues of greater moment.<P>
</OL>
<LI>As observed at the outset, one of the most important chores is to determine the appropriate level of resources to devote to the task.  Legal counsel will need to avoid the temptation to go overboard in conducting the review, while many business people will need to avoid the temptation to draw premature conclusions about their company's IP assets and potential assets without first gathering a reasonably rounded information base and engaging in some thoughtful reevaluation of their assumptions about what's important and what's not in their company's operations.
</UL>
<H2>Step 3:  Plug the Significant Holes That You Find (If You Can)</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Plugging holes is often easier said than done.  You may have subject matter that would have been patentable but has been disclosed in a published technical paper or incorporated in products that were sold long enough ago to trigger the sale bar.  You may not have an adequate form of invention agreement in place with your employees but may be unwilling or unable to provide consideration sufficient under applicable state law to support the imposition of a more adequate form on existing employees.  You may have categories of information that you would like to try to protect as trade secrets and find that you have been demonstrably lax in protecting them, to the point where there is cause for concern that you will be found to have failed to take reasonable steps to protect them within the meaning of applicable trade secrets laws.<P>
</UL>
<H2>Step 4:  Look for Additional Ways to Augment Your IP Portfolio</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Technology-driven companies, especially, have an increasing number of ways to augment their IP assets.  Some of the more popular ways are:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Acquisitions of product lines or entire businesses for their IP assets<P>
<LI>Corporate partnering: finding joint venture partners with complementary IP and other assets and competencies, and strategic plans<P>
<LI>Licensing in, i.e., finding another owner of IP assets that is willing and able to license them to you at a reasonable cost<P>
<LI>Government research grants<P>
<LI>Cooperative research with government and/or academic research labs<P>
<LI>The old-fashioned way: do it yourself<P>
</OL>
<LI>Each of these methods has its characteristic benefits, burdens, risks and pitfalls.  All entail significant up-front costs and risks of failure, and many entail ongoing risks and complexities by virtue of the fact that more than one entity obtains a permanent or extended interest in the IP in question, and all of the involved entities must plan and negotiate to protect their interests under various contingent and changing economic, competitive and technological scenarios.<P>
</UL>
<H2>Step 5:  Look for Ways to Realize a Return on Investment in Non-Core IP</H2>
<UL>
<LI>You may find that you have technology or trademarks that are more valuable to someone else than they are to you.  Many of the strategies to obtain a greater return on such forms of IP are the flip sides of some of those mentioned above in Step 4:  for example, sale of a particular product line or a patent, or licensing out.  The costs, complexities and pitfalls likewise have flip sides.<P>
</UL>
<H2>Step 6:  Vigilant Maintenance</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Once you feel you have a basic handle on your IP assets, you are ready to tackle the job of ongoing maintenance.  Among the more common methods are the following:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Hold regular periodic (at least semi-annual) meetings of your IP management team, including legal counsel.  Technology-driven companies should have the team meet as often as monthly or even bi-weekly.<P>
<LI>Keep track of what your competitors are doing.  Monitor the technical aspects of their new product offerings.  Monitor patent and trademark databases.  Technology-driven companies should think globally; there may be information available about your competitors' patent activities internationally even though the confidential nature of U.S. patent applications presently renders the cognate U.S. information unavailable during the pendency of such applications.<P>
<LI>Educate new employees and provide periodic refreshers and written materials to appropriate categories of existing employees.  Technology-driven companies frequently prepare fairly extensive manuals for their scientific and engineering employees to educate them and ensure the full capture of the record to support the company's claims to internally generated inventions.<P>
<LI>Evaluate IP disputes or potential disputes with great caution.  IP litigation is frequently very expensive, whether you win or lose.  You should take infringement risks seriously, however.  In recent years there have been a number of patent and trade secret cases in which the damages awarded have been in the range of tens of millions, and even hundreds of millions, of dollars.  Develop a policy and procedure to protect your company from liability for apparent misappropriation of unsolicited ideas and inventions of individual inventors.<P>
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>Conclusion</H2>
<DL>
<DD>The foregoing overview merely scratches the surface of an extensive topic that is of vital concern to many companies.  Hopefully, however, it can help you to begin to develop the broader perspective that is frequently absent if you have been in the habit of managing your IP one item at a time.
</DL>

<HR>

Last changed 1-May-95<P>

