<HEAD>
<TITLE>The role of insurance in Intellectual Property disputes</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Introduction</H2>
<DL>
<DD>Intellectual property litigation is on the rise.  Intellectual property litigation is expensive.  These two fundamental facts have led to increased attention in recent years to the role of insurance coverage in intellectual property disputes.  Insurance can save defendants hundreds of thousands of dollars in litigation expenses as well as provide protection against exposure to potentially multi-million dollar judgments.  Insurance can also impact the litigation strategy of both plaintiffs and defendants.  Because every business is a potential litigant in an intellectual property dispute, an appreciation of the issues surrounding the existence and enforcement of insurance coverage for such disputes is critical.<P>
</DL>
<H2>Insurance Coverage under the Standard CGL Policy</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Businesses commonly purchase Comprehensive General Liability (CGL) insurance to protect against business tort claims.  Absent a specific endorsement or policy for intellectual property claims, the CGL is frequently the only potential source for intellectual property claim coverage.<P>
<LI><B>"Advertising Injury"</B><P>
Of course, the exact coverage afforded depends on the wording of the individual policy.  CGL policies typically use the standard language of Insurance Services Office (ISO) CGL forms, often with modifications.  For many intellectual property claims, the most likely source of coverage is the "Advertising Injury" coverage clause.<P>
<OL>
<LI><B>Pre-1986 Broad Form Endorsement</B><P>
In 1986, ISO revised its standard CGL form, including the "Advertising Injury" coverage sections.  Many businesses, however, continue to purchase policies utilizing the pre-1986 "Advertising Injury" provisions.  In addition, most of the litigation concerning coverage for intellectual property claims has focused on the pre-1986 language.<P>
The pre-1986 CGL standard policy typically defines "Advertising Injury" for which coverage is provided as:  "Injury arising out of an offense committed during the policy period occurring in the course of the named insured's advertising activities, if such injury arises out libel, slander, defamation, violation of right of privacy, piracy, unfair competition or infringement of copyright, title or slogan."<P>
<LI><B>Post-1986 CGL Standard Form</B><P>
The post-1986 Advertising Injury language generally provides:<P>
"'Advertising Injury' means injury arising out of one or more of the following offenses:<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>Oral or written publication of material that slanders or libels a person or organization or disparages a person's or organization's goods, products, or services;<P>
<LI>Oral or written publication of material that violates a person's right of privacy;<P>
<LI>Misappropriation of advertising ideas or style of doing business; or<P>
<LI>Infringement of copyright, title or slogan."<P>
</OL>
The current standard CGL policy also contains a provision stating that the insurance applies only to "advertising injury" caused by an offense committed in the course of advertising goods, products or services.<P>
</OL>
<LI><B>Rules of Insurance Policy Interpretation.</B><P>
<OL>
<LI>State law governs.<P>
<LI>As a contract of adhesion, ambiguities are to be resolved against the drafter and in favor of the insured.<P>
<LI>The policy is to be interpreted in accordance with the "reasonable expectations" of the insured.  Atwater Creamery Co. v. Western Nat'l Mut., 366 N.W.2d 271 (Minn. 1985).<P>
<LI>Duty to Defend Broader than Duty to Indemnify.<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>If any part of the cause of action arguably falls within scope of coverage, the insurer must defend the entire action.  John Deere Ins. Co. v. Shamrock Indus., Inc., 929 F.2d 413, 417 (8th Cir. 1991); Josten's, Inc. v. CNA Ins. Co., 336 N.W.2d 544 (Minn. 1983).<P>
<LI>Doubts resolved in favor of the insured.  Lanoue v. Fireman's Fund American Ins. Co., 278 N.W.2d 49, 53 (Minn. 1979).<P>
<LI>Non-intellectual property infringement claims can form basis for duty to defend against IP claims.  John Deere, 696 F. Supp. at 434, aff'd 929 F.2d 413 (8th Cir. 1991).<P>
</OL>
</OL>
<LI><B>Patent Infringement</B><P>
<OL>
<LI><B>Patent Infringement As "Advertising Injury."</B><P>
Some courts have found coverage for a patent infringement claim under the CGL advertising injury clause.  Several well-reasoned recent cases, however, have held that a CGL affords no coverage for such claims.  As with many issues, the existence of coverage for a patent infringement claim requires case-specific analysis.  Leading cases:<P>
Intex Plastics Sales Co. v. United Nat'l Ins. Co., 23 F.3d 254 (9th Cir. 1994).<P>
Bank of the West v. Superior Court, 833 P.2d 545 (Cal. 1992).<P>
<LI><B>Inducement To Patent infringement.</B><P>
Aetna Casualty & Sur. Co. v. Superior Court, 19 Cal. App. 4th 320 (4th Dist. 1993).<P>
<LI><B>Patent Infringement As "Personal Injury."</B><P>
Everest & Jennings v. American Motorists Inc., 23 F.3d 226 (9th Cir. 1994)<P>
</OL>
<LI><B>Trademark Infringement and Lanham Act Claims</B><P>
<OL>
<LI>Strong Arguments Support Coverage.<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>Trademark and trade dress use is quintessentially advertising activity.<P>
<LI>Falls within "misappropriation of advertising ideas or style ..." and "infringement of ... title or slogan."<P>
</OL>
<LI>Some Policies Have Express Exclusion.<P>
<LI>Case Law Is Sparse:<P>
The P.J. Noyes Co. v. American Motorists Ins. Co., 31 USPQ 2d 1790 (D.N.H. 1994)(Coverage found as alleged trademark infringement would not have occurred but for use of term in packaging, literature, and advertisements.)<P>
Parameter Dunes Software v. Massachusetts Bay Ins. Co., 31 USPQ 2d 1202 (6th Cir. 1994)(Insurance company had no duty to defend suit for, inter alia, trademark infringement in view of policy exclusion for advertising offenses although policy provides coverage for advertising injury occurring in course of "unfair competition").<P>
Safeco Insurance Co. v. Pencon Int'l, Inc., 922 F. 2d 845 (9th Cir. Jan. 10, 1991)(Finding no coverage-designated as not precedential).<P>
AC Circuit Breakers v. Hartford Ins. Co., CV 92-0255 RG(SX)(C.D. Cal., July 8, 1992)(Finding no coverage for trademark infringement claim, but ordering insurer to defend based on unfair competition claims).<P>
American Motorists Ins. Co. v. Mars Sales Co., 9 F.3d 1550 (9th Cir. Nov. 5, 1993) (Finding duty to defend exists).<P>
</OL>
<LI><B>Copyright Infringement</B><P>
<OL>
<LI>Claims for copyright infringement expressly covered in standard CGL policy.<P>
<LI>Beware of causation defense.  The alleged loss must flow from "advertising activity."<P>
<LI>Beware of intentional conduct exclusion.<P>
<LI><B>Leading case:</B>  Sentry Ins. v. R. J. Weber Co., Inc., 2 F.3d 554 (5th Cir. 1993).<P>
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>Insurance Tailored for Intellectual Property Infringement Claims</H2>
<UL>
<LI>In light of the uncertainties involved in the existence of coverage for IP disputes under the standard CGL policy, it is not surprising that some insurance companies market insurance products tailored for coverage of intellectual property infringement claims.  On the market today are policies designed for patent infringement and trademark infringement claims coverage.<P>
<LI>Each business must make its own cost/benefit analysis with respect to purchasing additional policies specifically for intellectual property disputes.  In light of the trend finding no coverage for patent infringement claims under standard CGL language, high technology businesses and others who deal extensively with patented or potentially patentable products should consider this alternative.<P>
</UL>
<H2>Insurance for Plaintiffs</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Insurance is no longer available exclusively to defendants in intellectual property disputes.  The high cost of prosecuting intellectual property infringement claims has led to the advent of insurance policies which will pay expenses a business incurs in enforcing its intellectual property rights. This product may be attractive to small businesses which otherwise lack the financial resources to aggressively pursue infringers.  At least one company markets insurance of this type with respect to patents, trademarks, and copyrights.<P>
</UL>
<H2>Insurance and Litigation Strategy</H2>
<UL>
<LI>When faced with defending a claim of intellectual property infringement, a business and its counsel must promptly determine whether insurance coverage exists.<P>
<LI>If coverage arguably exists, notification and tender of defense should be made.  If insurer rejects tender, consider filing a declaratory judgment action.<P>
<LI>Watch for allocation issues where indemnification is available on one claim but not others.<P>
<LI>Plaintiff should consider the issue of insurance coverage for the defendant in preparing its case.<P>
<OL>
<LI>Insurance can ease collection of judgment.<P>
<LI>Insurance can enable a more vigorous defense.<P>
<LI>Strategic pleading of facts and claims can maximize/minimize chances of insurance coverage.
</OL>
</UL>

<HR>

Last changed 1-May-95<P>

