<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>UCC issues and Intellectual Property</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Introduction</H2>
<DL>
<DD>Intellectual Property can be the subject of many of the provisions of the UCC, but there are only three places in the UCC where Intellectual Property is directly addressed: once in Article 2, Sales, and twice in Article 9, Secured Transactions.  A basic understanding how these provisions of the UCC effect your company's intellectual property is necessary to ensure adequate protection of your interests in any sales transactions.
</DL>
<H2>UCC INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY PROVISIONS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>A warranty against infringement is imposed by UCC 2-312 (3) on  sellers who are "merchants" (i.e., a person who deals in goods of the kind or...holds himself out as having knowledge or skill peculiar to the practices or goods involved in the transaction...).<P>
<LI>The risk of infringement shifts, however, if the buyer furnishes specifications for the goods to the seller.<P>
<LI>Turning now to Article 9, UCC 9-106 encompasses Intellectual Property inferentially in the definition of "General Intangibles" as "any personal property...other than goods, accounts, chattel paper, documents, instruments, and money."  The Official Comment expressly states that patents, trademarks, copyrights and rights to receive payments under licenses thereof are examples of general intangibles.<P>
<LI>Finally, UCC 9-104 excludes from Article 9 security interests subject to federal statute when that statute "governs the rights of parties to and third parties affected by transactions in particular types of property...."<P>
<LI>The Official Comment mentions both the Federal Copyright Act and a provision of a prior version of the federal patent laws and says that "the filing provisions under these Acts...are recognized as the equivalent to filing under this Article."
</UL>
<H2>CASES</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The courts have had little trouble applying UCC 2-312 (3), possibly because the risk allocation is logical and straightforward.  In <EM>Dolori Fabrics, Inc. v. Limited Inc.</EM>, 662 F. Supp. 1347, 3 U.S.P.Q. 2d (BNA) 1753 (S.D.N.Y. 1987), the court stated that the "policy underlying this statute -- that a merchant who regularly deals in like goods has a duty to insure that no claim of infringement by a third party mars the buyer's title - applies equally well to claims of copyright infringement." Id. at 1358.<P>
<LI>To obtain the protection of the warranty by a seller in UCC 2-312 (3), a buyer must first notify the seller that a claim of infringement has been made against the goods purchased from the seller. <EM>Gates Energy Prod., Inc. v. Yuasa Battery Co.</EM>, 599 F. Supp 368, 223 U.S.P.Q. (BNA) 660 (D. Colo. 1983).<P>
<LI>A buyer cannot "tag" a seller for the warranty against infringement unless the products sold by the seller are the items giving rise to the claim of infringement.  In <EM>Chemtron, Inc. v. Aqua Prods.</EM>, 830 F. Supp. 314, 28 U.S.P.Q. 2d (BNA) 1877 (E.D. Va. 1993), the court declined to hold the seller of non-infringing component parts liable on the UCC warranty against infringement when it was the total apparatus, and not the component parts, that was accused.<P>
<LI>There is considerable variation in the opinions as to the proper place to file financing statements to perfect a security interest in Intellectual Property.  The usual choices are: i) the appropriate Secretary of State (under the UCC), and/or ii) the appropriate assignment branch of the federal Patent and Trademark or Copyright Office.  Evidencing this split of authority, the court in In <EM>re Peregrine Entertainment Ltd.</EM>, 16 U.S.P.Q. 2d (BNA) 1017 (C.D. Cal. 1990) in an appeal from a bankruptcy court decision, decided that the Federal Copyright Office was the proper place to file, citing federal preemption.  In reaching this result, the court expressly rejected other district court cases and bankruptcy court cases holding that the state system (UCC filing) was the appropriate place of filing a financing statement.
</UL>
<H2>THE FUTURE</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Efforts are being made to legislate the proper place for filing financing statements, however, there is no clear indication that a single system will be implemented in the foreseeable future; because of this, the cases are expected to continue to diverge, with some ratifying state filing and some upholding federal filing.<P>
<LI>Revision of Article 2 of the UCC is underway in attempt to address issues arising in connection with software transactions.  Certain provisions regarding the extension of warranties of "merchantability," accuracy of data, and "fitness for purpose" to the delivery of intangibles (such as software) are under consideration at this time.<P>
<LI>One approach is to provide an "implied" warranty of quality instead of merchantability; this proposal focuses on the description or documentation offered by the transferor or agreed to by the parties and is embodied in Option 1 of Proposed Section 2-2222, as a "transaction-based" approach.  Option 2 provides a more general standard, that of "merchantability" of the performance and media of the intangibles delivered.  However, this option shifts to the standard presented in Option 1 when there are no comparable uses to establish a general level of merchantability for the intangibles in question.<P>
<LI>Another proposed section provides an implied warranty as to the correctness or accuracy of information and data supplied as the intangible. Proposed Section 2-2223 gives an implied warranty that the supplier will use reasonable care and workmanlike effort, but that "zero errors" are not the standard.  Furthermore, the warranty is not implied when the data are in public records known to the transferee, when the data or information is only incidental (and therefore not "material") to the transaction, and when the intangibles are created by a third party and identified as such.<P>
<LI>As to warranties of fitness, Proposed Section 2-2224 provides that the supplier will use reasonable care and workmanlike effort to achieve the transferee's objectives and purposes when the supplier has at least reason to know that the transferee is relying on the supplier's expertise.  There is a special subsection that obligates a system supplier to a warranty that the [hardware and software] parts of the system selected by that supplier will "function together as a system consistent with the goals of the licensee known or communicated to the licensor."<P>
</UL>
A complete listing of the sections and proposed sections discussed above follows. 
<H2>336.2-312 Warranty of Title and Against Infringement; Buyer's Obligation Against Infringement</H2>
<OL>
<LI>Subject to subsection (2) there is in a contract for sale a warranty by the seller that<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>the title conveyed shall be good, and its transfer rightful; and<P>
<LI>the goods shall be delivered free from any security interest or other lien or encumbrance of which the buyer at the time of contracting has no knowledge.<P>
</OL>
<LI>A warranty under subsection (1) will be excluded or modified only by specific language or by circumstances which give the buyer reason to know that the person selling does not claim title in himself or that he is purporting to sell only such right or title as he or a third person may have.<P>
<LI>Unless otherwise agreed a seller who is a merchant regularly dealing in goods of the kind warrants that the goods shall be delivered free of the rightful claim of any third person by way of infringement or the like but a buyer who furnishes specifications to the seller must hold the seller harmless against any such claim which arises out of compliance with the specifications.
</OL>
<H2>336.9-106 Definitions:  "Account;" "General Intangibles"</H2>
<DL>
<DD>"Account" means any right to payment for goods sold or leased or for services rendered which is not evidenced by an instrument or chattel paper whether or not it  has been earned by performance.  "General Intangibles" means any personal property (including things in action) other than goods, accounts, chattel paper, documents, instruments and money.  All rights earned or unearned under a charter or other contract involving the use or hire of a vessel and all rights incident to the charter or contract are accounts.
</DL>
<H2>336.9-104 Transactions Excluded From Article</H2>
<DL>
<DD>This article does not apply<P>
<OL>
<LI>to a security interest subject to any statute of the United States such as the Ship Mortgage Act, 1920, to the extent that such statute governs the rights of parties to and third parties affected by transactions in particular types of property; or<P>
<LI>to a landlord's lien; or<P>
<LI>to a lien given by statute or other rule of law for services or materials except as provided in section 336.9-310 on priority of such liens; or<P>
<LI>to a transfer of a claim for wages, salary or other compensation of an employee; or<P>
<LI>to a transfer by a government or governmental subdivision or agency to the extent that this article conflicts with special statutory provisions relating to such a transfer; or<P>
<LI>to a sale of accounts or chattel paper as part of a sale of the business out of which they arose, or an assignment of accounts or chattel paper which is for the purpose of collection only, or a transfer of a right to payment under a contract to an assignee who is also to do the performance under the contract or a transfer of a single account to an assignee in whole or partial satisfaction of a preexisting indebtedness; or<P>
<LI>to a transfer of an interest or claim in or under any policy of insurance, except as provided with reference to proceeds (section 336.9-306) and priorities in proceeds (section 336.9-312); or<P>
<LI>to a right represented by a judgment (other than a judgment taken on a right to payment which was collateral); or<P>
<LI>to any right to setoff; or<P>
<LI>except to the extent that provision is made for fixtures in section 336.9-313, to the creation or transfer of an interest in or lien on real estate, including a lease or rents thereunder; or<P>
<LI>to a transfer in whole or in part of any claim arising out of tort; or<P>
<LI>to a transfer of an interest in any deposit account (subsection (l) of section 336.9-105), except as provided with respect to proceeds (section 336.9-306) and priorities in proceeds (section 336.9-312); or<P>
<LI>except to the extent this article is not superseded by sections 327.61 to 327.67, to the repossession of a manufactured home meeting the definition contained in section 327.62.<P>
</OL>
</DL>
<H2>PROPOSED SECTION 2-2222. IMPLIED WARRANTY, QUALITY OF PRODUCT</H2>
<DL>
<DD>Option 1<P>
<OL>
<LI>If intangibles are delivered to a licensee in a form directly capable of use in a machine or otherwise to produce a practical result other than mere communication, processing, or reproduction of the information or data that comprise the intangible and the licensor is a merchant with respect to intangibles of this kind, the licensor warrants that the intangibles will perform in substantial conformance with any documentation, specifications, or other descriptions provided by the transferor or agreed to by the parties.<P>
<LI>In a mass market license within subsection (a), the implied warranty is a warranty of merchantability to be interpreted as in Section ---- [merchantability in sales of goods].<P>
</OL>
<DD>Option 2<P>
<OL>
<LI>If intangibles are delivered to a licensee in a form directly capable of use in a machine or otherwise to produce a practical result other than mere communication, processing, or reproduction of the information or data that comprise the intangibles and the licensor is a merchant with respect to intangibles of this kind, the licensor warrants that the performance of the intangibles and the quality of any media on which they are transferred will be of merchantable quality.  Merchantable quality is to be interpreted as in Section ---- [merchantability in sales of goods].<P>
<LI>In cases covered by subsection (a), if there is no ordinary use to which the intangibles can be compared, the warranty is a warranty that the intangibles as delivered will perform in substantial conformance with any documentation, specifications, or other descriptions provided by the transferor or agreed to be the parties.<P>
</OL>
</DL>
<H2>PROPOSED SECTION 2-2223. IMPLIED WARRANTY, INFORMATION AND SERVICES</H2>
<OL>
<LI>If the licensor provides services, information, data, data processing or the like, there is a warranty that the licensor will use reasonable care and workmanlike effort in providing the services and in collecting, compiling, or transmitting the information or data.<P>
<LI>The warranty in subsection (a) is not breached merely because  the services do not yield a result consistent with the objectives of the transferee or because the information or data are not accurate.<P>
<LI>The warranty under subsection (a) does not apply:<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>to information or data publicly available in Patent Office or similar public records of which the transferee has knowledge;<P>
<LI>if the information is merely incidental to the transfer of rights and does not constitute a material portion of the value in the transaction; or<P>
<LI>to a licensor with reference to information or other intangibles prepared or created by a third party if the licensor merely makes available the intangibles in a form that identifies them as being the work product of the third party.<P>
</OL>
</OL>
<H2>PROPOSED SECTION 2-2224. WARRANTY OF FITNESS; SYSTEM INTEGRATION</H2>
<OL>
<LI>In a software contract in which a computer program is to be developed, designed, selected, compiled, manufactured, or substantially modified for the transaction and the licensor has reason to know that the licensee is relying on the expertise of the licensor to develop or select appropriate software, the licensor warrants that it will use reasonable care and workmanlike effort to complete its performance in a manner that will achieve the licensee's objectives and purposes as communicated or known to the licensor.<P>
<LI>In contracts governed by subsection (a), there is a warranty that the transferor will produce a product of quality and performance suitable for the transferee's particular purposes in the following circumstances:<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>the contract of the parties so provides; or<P>
<LI>from all the circumstances and actions of the parties, it appears that the licensor agreed to not be compensated for its work unless or unless or until the intangibles were fit for the purposes to which the licensee intended to put them.<P>
</OL>
<LI>If the agreement of the parties requires that the licensor provide goods and computer software to form elements of a single or integrated system, and the circumstances indicate that the licensee is relying on the expertise of the licensor to select or develop the goods or software there is a warranty that the units selected or developed if delivered in proper condition will function together as a system consistent with the goals of the licensee known or communicated to the licensor.  This warranty is not made by a consultant who advises on the selection or development of the system, but does not itself sell or license any of the goods or software.<P>
<LI>This section applies whether or not the intangibles contract includes a transfer of goods or other means, physical or otherwise, of using the intangibles without substantial additional manufacturing, development, analysis, or other work by the licensee.<P>
</OL>

<HR>

