<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>International protection for Intellectual Property</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Background</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
<H2>SCOPE</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Intellectual property protection is not global, rather it is a creature of national laws.<P>
<LI>International protection for intellectual property comes from obtaining protection in each desired country.
</UL>
<H2>PATENTS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Paris Convention<P>
<OL>
<LI>National treatment:  Each country must treat foreigners on same basis as its own nationals.<P>
<LI>One year grace period<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>A patent application filed in a foreign country which is a signatory to the Paris Convention will generally be entitled to the benefit of the filing date of a prior corresponding application filed within one year in another Paris Convention member country.<P>
<LI>Each country's novelty laws still apply, meaning that public disclosures prior to the critical date can still preclude patentability.<P>
<LI>It is important to remember that the one year priority period for patents under the Paris Convention runs from the date of application at the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office ¾ not from the actual date that the patent is granted.  This is a serious error often made by inexperienced U.S. companies, resulting in the loss of potential foreign patent protection.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Patent Cooperation Treaty (PCT)<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>Implements Paris Convention's one year grace period.<P>
<LI>Provides for an "international phase" where the initial stages of prosecution take place through the PCT.<P>
<LI>After the international phase, applicants can file patent applications in desired member countries.
</OL>
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>COPYRIGHTS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>National Law<P>
Copyright law is a creature of national law and each country has its own copyright statute.  Protection can vary from country to country.<P>
<LI>Treaties<P>
Copyright law treaties set minimum protection standards among member countries.  Most treaties are based on the principle of reciprocity.<P>
<OL>
<LI>Berne Convention<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>Administered by the World Intellectual Property Organization.<P>
<LI>An author obtaining copyright under the Convention is automatically given protection, even without separate national registrations, in all Convention countries on the same terms as an author of the nation where protection is sought.  There can be no discrimination against the works of a foreign national.<P>
<LI>Protection is granted when the work's country of origin, that is, the country where the author is resident or national or the country of first publication, is a member nation.<P>
<LI>A member nation can only impose formalities on its own nationals.<P>
<LI>Minimum duration of protection is life of the author plus fifty years.<P>
<LI>Extensive recognition and protection of moral rights.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Universal Copyright Convention (U.C.C.)<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>Attempt to reconcile the European and the U.S. Copyright systems.<P>
<LI>Administered by UNESCO.<P>
<LI>Based on the principle of National Treatment.<P>
<LI>Protection granted based on Country of Origin.<P>
<LI>Minimum duration of protection is twenty-five years.<P>
<LI>No explicit recognition of moral rights.
</OL>
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>TRADEMARKS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Treaties<P>
<OL>
<LI>Paris Convention<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>National Treatment:  Each country must treat foreigners on same basis as its own nationals.<P>
<LI>No automatic protection.  Protection is granted upon registration of the mark in each country.<P>
<LI>Priority Period:  Six-month period after first application for registration in a member country during which applicant receives on any subsequent applications the original filing date of the first application.<P>
<LI>Famous Marks:  Convention grants limited protection for "famous marks," even if unregistered in the country where the dispute arises.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Madrid Protocol<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>The Madrid Protocol is an ongoing attempt to adopt a treaty creating an international trademark registration filing system.  The negotiations have stalled due to differences regarding the role of intergovernmental organizations such as the European Union.
</OL>
</OL>
</UL>
</DL>
<H2>GATT UPDATES</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
<H2>GENERAL</H2>
<UL>
<LI>GATT is a worldwide agreement covering multiple facets of international trade.  The new body overseeing trade is the World Trade Organization (WTO).<P>
<LI>The latest revisions to GATT are known as the Uruguay Round.  The Uruguay Round includes many sets of Codes dealing with different trade aspects.<P>
<LI>GATT can only be accepted as a package - countries cannot accept only select Uruguay Round Codes.<P>
<LI>The Uruguay Round negotiations on the trade-related aspects of intellectual property rights resulted in the TRIPS Agreement.  This agreement, which establishes international property rights (IPR) standards and strong enforcement measures, covers seven areas:<P>
<OL>
<LI>copyrights<P>
<LI>patents<P>
<LI>trademarks<P>
<LI>industrial designs<P>
<LI>trade secrets (undisclosed information)<P>
<LI>integrated secrets (semiconductor chip mask works)<P>
<LI>geographical indications
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>LEVEL OF PROTECTION</H2>
<UL>
<LI>While strengthening many of the current worldwide intellectual property standards, the TRIPS provisions still provide a minimal level of protection.<P>
<LI>In order to gain more effective protection, the United States is continuing to negotiate bilateral agreements with many countries.
</UL>
<H2>BASIC REQUIREMENTS - 3 PRONGS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>National Treatment:  Each country must treat foreigners on same basis as its own nationals.<P>
<LI>Most Favored Nation ("MFN") Treatment<P>
<OL>
<LI>Any advantage afforded nationals of one member country must be given to nationals of all member countries.<P>
<LI>The MFN requirement will effectively extend grace period provided under the Paris Convention to all TRIPS member countries which have a treaty providing for a grace period with at least one other TRIPS member country.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Minimum standards:  TRIPS goes beyond trade related aspects of intellectual property.  It requires that each member country adopt intellectual property laws meeting minimum standards.
</UL>
<H2>IMPLEMENTATION</H2>
<UL>
<LI>National treatment and MFN treatment<P>
<OL>
<LI>These provisions take effect immediately.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Implementation depends on the industrial level of the country:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Developed countries have one year;<P>
<LI>Developing countries and countries which are being transformed from a centrally planned economy into a market economy have five years; and<P>
<LI>Least developed countries have ten years.<P>
</OL>
<LI>There are no definitions of the terms "developed" and "developing."  The United States is attempting, through bilateral negotiations, to hasten the timetable for many countries to enact the TRIPS provisions, including negotiations with China and Taiwan.
</UL>
<H2>HIGHLIGHTS OF TRIPS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Patents<P>
<OL>
<LI>Compulsory licenses<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>The Paris Convention permits nonexclusive compulsory licenses f a patent is not "worked."  In other words, if a patent holder does not industrially use the patent, the government may grant other parties the right to use the patent without the patentee's permission and without compensating the patentee.<P>
<LI>TRIPS also provides for nonexclusive compulsory licenses, but in very limited circumstances.  Compulsory licenses are limited in scope and duration.  TRIPS also requires that the patentee be compensated and provides for judicial review of the grant of the compulsory license and the amount of compensation.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Patent Term:  The Paris Convention does not require a minimum patent term.  TRIPS proposes a 20 year term from the filing date.<P>
<LI>Rights conferred:  The Paris Convention does not specify the rights conferred by a patent.  TRIPS, on the other hand, expressly grants a patentee the rights of excluding others from making, using, selling, offering for sale, or importing infringing products or processes.<P>
<LI>Patentable inventions<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>The Paris Convention does not provide for what subject matter is patentable.<P>
<LI>TRIPS provides that patents will be available for inventions that are new, involve an inventive step, and are capable of industrial application, with a few exceptions.  Protection is provided for pharmaceutical and agricultural chemicals.<P>
<LI>Member countries may deny patent protection for inventions for public order, morality, health, or environmental reasons.<P>
</OL>
</OL>
Trademarks<P>
<OL>
<LI>Term<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>Minimum term of seven years.<P>
<LI>The term is renewable.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Cancellation:  A trademark registration may be cancelled if the mark is not used for at least three years.<P>
<LI>Rights conferred:  The owner of a registered trademark has the right to prevent third parties from using a similar mark for goods where such use would result in confusion.<P>
<LI>Extension to service marks:  Service marks as well as trademarks are protected under TRIPS.<P>
<LI>Geographically misdescriptive marks<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>Marks cannot be registered if they falsely designate their geographic origin.<P>
<LI>This provision has a grandfather clause.<P>
</OL>
</OL>
<LI>Copyrights<P>
<OL>
<LI>In general, TRIPS is very similar to the Berne Convention, and generally requires adherence to the Berne Convention.<P>
<LI>The term of protection is 50 years plus the life of the author.<P>
<LI>Original compilations of data are protectable.<P>
<LI>Computer Software<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>TRIPS provides that computer software, in source code and object code, shall be protected as literary works under the Berne Convention.<P>
<LI>TRIPS is silent on whether computer programs embodied in microelectronic devices are protectable under copyright law.<P>
<LI>TRIPS is silent on reverse engineering.<P>
<LI>TRIPS provides for rental rights.  The copyright holder has the right to authorize or prohibit the commercial rental to the public of original or copies of copyrighted works, as least as to computer programs.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Moral Rights<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>TRIPS does not oblige member nations to enforce the Moral Rights provisions of the Berne Convention.<P>
<LI>This is the major exception to the general statement that TRIPS requires the same level of protection as Berne Convention.<P>
</OL>
<LI>"New" Rights or "New" Beneficiaries.<P>
TRIPS does not require national treatment for any "new" rights or "new" beneficiaries that are not included in existing international copyright conventions, such as levies on the sale of blank tapes to compensate copyright owners for private copying.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Trade Secrets<P>
<OL>
<LI>TRIPS expressly protects "undisclosed information", i.e. trade secrets.<P>
<LI>Member countries must implement laws to prevent the disclosure and use of trade secrets.<P>
<LI>TRIPS requires protection of trade secrets for chemical and pharmaceutical products while they are being submitted to governments for approval.<P>
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>DISPUTE SETTLEMENT</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The Uruguay round of GATT provides improved dispute settlement provisions.  This contrasts with the weak to non-existent provisions in prior international treaties.
</UL>
<H2>ENFORCEMENT PROVISIONS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>TRIPS requires member nations to provide civil and administrative procedures and remedies for the enforcement of intellectual property rights, including:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Preliminary measures;<P>
<LI>Border measures for prohibiting importation of infringing goods<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>required for copyright and trademark infringement<P>
<LI>permitted for other types of infringement (e.g. patents);<P>
</OL>
<LI>Criminal penalties<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>required for willful copyright and trademark infringement<P>
<LI>permitted for other types of infringement (e.g. patents).<P>
</OL>
<LI>Unlike prior treaties which simply required member nations to provide protection, TRIPS specifies some of the details of such protection, including:<P>
<LI>timely written notice to defendants;<P>
<LI>an opportunity to be represented by counsel;<P>
<LI>an opportunity to present evidence; and<P>
<LI>protection of confidential information.
</OL>
</UL>
</DL>
<H2>NAFTA UPDATES</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
<H2>HISTORY OF THE NAFTA AGREEMENT</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Negotiations over the NAFTA began in earnest in 1991, and concluded on October 7, 1992.  As of today, Canada, Mexico, and the United States are signatories of the NAFTA treaty.  Negotiations to include other countries, such as Chile, are underway.<P>
<LI>The NAFTA Intellectual Property provisions came into effect on January 1, 1994.  Exceptions are:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Border control provisions need not be implemented by Mexico until 1997;<P>
<LI>Protection of semiconductor layout designs need not be implemented in Mexico for four years;<P>
<LI>Protection for encrypted programs had to be implemented by January 1, 1995; and<P>
<LI>Adherence to the International Convention for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants, 1978, or the International Convention for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants, 1991, need not be implemented by Mexico until 1996.<P>
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>CANADA/U.S. FTA</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Prior to signing NAFTA, the United States and Canada had entered into the Canada-United States Free Trade Agreement.  This agreement contains very few provisions relating to intellectual property.  However, it does grant Canada's "Cultural Industries" (essentially any form of multimedia) an exclusion with respect to all NAFTA IPR obligations, except those resulting from Canada's adherence to the Berne Convention.
</UL>
<H2>GENERAL</H2>
<UL>
<LI>By the time NAFTA became effective on January 1, 1994, the intellectual property laws of all NAFTA countries had already been amended to be in substantial compliance with NAFTA obligations.<P>
<LI>Enforcement:  Some of the most significant IPR provisions in NAFTA are directed to expedite and assure enforcement.  NAFTA outlines a "Bill of Rights" for parties and sets minimum powers to be wielded by judicial authorities.<P>
<LI>National Treatment:  Each member is required to accord to nationals of another member the same "treatment that it accords its own nationals with regard to the protection and enforcement of all intellectual property rights."
</UL>
<H2>PATENTS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>NAFTA mandates the availability of patent protection and effective enforcement.<P>
<LI>Patentability Criteria:  Remains basically the same.  That is, utility, novelty, and non-obviousness.<P>
<LI>Patentable Subject Matter:  Member nations must provide patent protection for an invention, unless the subject matter is immoral, unsafe, or the subject of diagnostic, therapeutic and surgical methods and procedures.  Plants, pharmaceuticals, and the layout design of integrated circuits must be protected.<P>
<LI>Patent Term:  A minimum term of 17 years from the date of grant or 20 years from the date of filing is required.<P>
<LI>Date of Invention:  Consistent with the national treatment provisions of NAFTA, dates of invention may be established by proof of activities in any NAFTA country.<P>
<LI>Compulsory Licensing:  Member countries may still require compulsory licensing of certain inventions.<P>
<LI>Parallel Importation:  Parallel importation is not mentioned in NAFTA and therefore it remains a question of each member country's national law.  Article 1709(5) authorizes the patent owner to prevent the importation of a product made by a patented process.  A comparable provision does not exist with respect to patented products.
</UL>
<H2>COPYRIGHTS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Berne Convention:  Each member country must comply with the substantive provisions of the Berne Convention.  However, NAFTA does not require the recognition of the author's moral rights against misattribution, mutilation, or other alteration of a copyrighted work.<P>
<LI>National treatment applies.  However, Canada is allowed to discriminate against other member countries cultural industries based on its cultural industries exception.<P>
<LI>Computer Programs:  NAFTA explicitly protects computer programs as literary works protectable under copyright laws.  Copyright owners are given the right to control the commercial rental of computer programs and sound recordings.<P>
<LI>Satellite Broadcast Signals:  Satellite Broadcast Signals are explicitly protected by NAFTA.<P>
<LI>Work for Hire:  Work for hire agreements are recognized in all NAFTA countries.<P>
<LI>Enforcement:  NAFTA requires the imposition of criminal penalties at least in cases of copyright piracy on a commercial scale.  NAFTA also requires that judicial authorities have the power to prevent the importation of merchandise which infringes copyrights.
</UL>
<H2>TRADEMARKS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Registration:  Each NAFTA country must provide a system for the registration of trademarks.  Actual use cannot be a requirement for filing an application.  Use is required to maintain a registration.<P>
<LI>Famous Marks:  Each member country shall adopt the requirements of the Paris Convention Article 6bis regarding famous marks.<P>
<LI>Term:  Marks are registered for indefinite renewable periods of ten years.<P>
<LI>Compulsory Licensing:  Compulsory Licensing is prohibited.<P>
<LI>Enforcement:  NAFTA requires the imposition of criminal penalties at least in cases of willful trademark counterfeiting.  NAFTA also requires that judicial authorities have the power to prevent the importation of merchandise which infringes trademarks.  Under NAFTA, judicial authorities in member countries will have the power to dispose of or destroy infringing products.
</UL>
<H2>TRADE SECRETS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>NAFTA requires protection of trade secrets from unauthorized disclosure.  The information to be protected must be (1) secret; (2) have commercial value due to its secrecy; and (3) be protected from unauthorized dissemination by reasonable steps.<P>
<LI>Unauthorized disclosure under NAFTA occurs only when the third party acquires the information in a manner contrary to honest commercial practices, and the third party knew or was grossly negligent in failing to know that such practices were involved in the acquisition.
</UL>
</DL>
<H2>MIDDLE EAST UPDATES</H2>
<DL>
<DD>According to estimates by the United States Commerce Department, intellectual property accounts for nearly 25% of U.S. Exports, and this percentage is on the rise.  However, the United States continues to lose billions of dollars in exports because of inadequate intellectual property protection in foreign countries.<P>
The Arab Gulf states, also known as the Gulf Cooperation Council Countries (Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates), have been considered a haven for piracy and counterfeiting activities in the Middle East.  Until recently, most of these countries had little if any intellectual property rights laws.  The lack of these laws and the extremely liberal trading policies of these countries have resulted in wide distribution of counterfeit and pirated material throughout the region.<P>
In recent years, however, a number of factors have led to significant changes, not only in the laws, but also in the attitude of the governments regarding intellectual properties.  There is a growing recognition among the GCC Countries that the lack of intellectual property protection is hurting them economically and hampering their technological development efforts.  Many high technology U.S. and European countries have simply stayed away from the region depriving the GCC countries of the latest technological advances in the medical, telecommunication and the computer industries.<P>
Another factor that is changing attitudes toward intellectual property rights is the desire of some GCC countries to join GATT and consequently to comply with GATT's IP provisions.  The U.A.E. joined GATT in March 1994, after having enacted copyright, trademark and patent laws in 1992.<P>
Finally, the United States government continues to exert enormous pressure on the GCC Countries to adopt and implement laws that protect intellectual property rights.  In many instances, the U.S. government has sent teams of experts to work with the various governments in the area on developing mechanisms for stronger enforcement of existing laws.<P>
What follows is a brief outline of the recent developments in trademark and copyright laws in the GCC Countries.
<H2>TRADEMARK</H2>
<UL>
<LI>By 1993, all the GCC Countries have adopted or modified their trademark laws, the U.A.E. being the last one to implement its laws on January 12, 1993.  Most of the trademark laws of these countries have been based on the Model Trademark Law for Arab Countries and therefore contain similar provisions.  They contain, for instance, strong provisions against trademark infringement including fines, jail terms and in some instances the possibility of a civil action against the infringer:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Bahrain:<P>
Legislative Decree No. 10, (1991).<P>
<LI>Kuwait:<P>
Part of the Commercial Code (Book 1, Part III) issued by Decree No. 68 (1980).<P>
<LI>Oman:<P>
Sultanate Decree No. 68/78 (1987) Implementing Regulation:  Ministerial Resolution 103 (1988).<P>
<LI>Qatar:<P>
Law No. 3 (1987) on Commercial Marks and Indications, amended by Law Decrees No. 17 (1987) and No. 37 (1988).<P>
<LI>Saudi Arabia:<P>
New Trademark Law:  Royal Decree No. M/5 (1984).<P>
<LI>U.A.E.:<P>
Federal Law No. 37 (1992).
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>COPYRIGHT</H2>
<UL>
<LI>U.S. software publishing and distribution industries lose millions of dollars annually because of piracy in the GCC Countries.  In Kuwait for instance, the piracy rate of computer software was about 98% in 1993 which resulted in an estimated $25.5 [million] loss for these industries.  Similarly, in 1993 Saudi Arabia had a piracy rate of 90% for an estimated loss of $82.3 million, and the U.A.E. had a piracy rate of 99% for estimated losses of $54.5 million.  However, copyright laws have seen the most dramatic changes in the GCC.<P>
<LI>In December of last year, the Saudi government announced that it was acceding to two international conventions on copyright protection, the Berne Convention and the Universal Copyright Convention.  Enforcement of these conventions in the Kingdom went into effect in July of this year.  The action of the Saudi government is significant because Saudi Arabia is the first country in the GCC group to join international conventions on the protection of intellectual property rights.  Other GCC Countries are likely to follow in the coming few years.<P>
<LI>As of 1994, the status of copyright laws in the GCC is as follows:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Bahrain:  Decree No. 10 (1993) (No implementing regulations).<P>
<LI>Kuwait:  No Copyright law.<P>
<LI>Oman:  No Copyright law.<P>
<LI>Qatar:  No Copyright law.<P>
<LI>Saudi Arabia:  Copyright Law issued under Ministerial Decision No. 30 (September 25, 1989) Regulation governing the deposit of Copyright Application were issued under Royal Decree No. M/26 (March 11, 1992).<P>
<LI>U.A.E.:  Law No. 40 (1992) and subsequent amendments.
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>CONTINUING CONCERNS FOR U.S. BUSINESSES</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Despite the recent positive development in Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates, significant problems remain for U.S. companies doing business in the GCC.  Chief among these problems are:<P>
<OL>
<LI>The uncertainty about the new IP laws and the commitment of GCC governments to enforcement of these laws;<P>
<LI>Lack of procedural law;<P>
<LI>Judges who are unfamiliar with intellectual property rights;<P>
<LI>Lack of import controls; and<P>
<LI>Lack of public awareness.
</OL>
</UL>
</DL>
<H2>SELECTED WORLDWIDE UPDATES</H2>
<DL>
<DD>
<H2>JAPAN</H2>
<DL>
The Japanese Patent Office has introduced a bill which would revise Japanese law relating to the industrial property.  This bill is expected to be passed.  Highlights include:<P>
</DL>
<UL>
<LI>Prolongation of the patent term.<P>
<OL>
<LI>The patent term under the present laws is 15 years from the date of publication of the patent application, provided that the term shall not exceed 20 years from the filing date of the patent application.<P>
<LI>The proposed term will be 20 years from the filing date of the patent application.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Claiming priority based on applications filed in other TRIPS member countries.<P>
<OL>
<LI>Priority (giving an application an earlier "effective filing date") may be claimed based on applications filed in other TRIPS member countries even if they are not Paris Convention member countries.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Acceptance of English language patent applications.<P>
<OL>
<LI>Patent applications having the specifications and claims written in English will now be accepted by the Japanese Patent Office, provided that a Japanese translation is filed within two months.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Introduction of post-issuance opposition.<P>
<OL>
<LI>The current practice of allowing pre-issuance third-party opposition will be ended.<P>
Under the proposed laws, an opposition may be filed within six months from the public notice that a patent was granted.
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>ESTONIA</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Estonia enacted a new patent law.<P>
<LI>Estonia joined the Paris Convention and the PCT.
</UL>
<H2>KOREA</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Korea began a concerted effort to reduce piracy.
</UL>
<H2>POLAND</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Poland enacted a new copyright law.
</UL>
<H2>JAMAICA</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Jamaica signed a comprehensive bilateral intellectual property rights agreement.
</UL>
<H2>INDONESIA</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Indonesia issued implementing regulations for its patent law.  The regulations were necessary to carry out important elements of the 1992 understanding between the United States and Indonesia.
</UL>
<H2>EGYPT</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Egypt enacted amendments to its 1992 copyright law to treat computer software as literary works, thus ensuring that the copyright term for computer software is 50 years.
</UL>
<H2>THE UNITED ARAB EMIRATES</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The United Arab Emirates (UAE) Ministry of Information issued a circular prohibiting all importation of pirated material.  The UAE also issued a circular prohibiting use of unlicensed software.
</UL>
</DL>

<HR>

