<HEAD>
<TITLE>Intellectual Property protection for computer software</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Copyright Protection for Computer Software</H2>
<UL>
<LI>United States copyright law expressly provides for the protection of computer software.  This protection prevents someone from making "copies" of another's computer software.<P>
<LI>Under the Copyright Act, copyright protection subsists in original works of authorship fixed in any tangible medium of expression from which they can be perceived, reproduced or otherwise communicated, either directly or with the aid of a machine or device.<P>
<LI>Copyright protection exists at the moment of creation, and lasts for fifty years after the author's death.  If the work is created anonymously or is a "work for hire," the copyright lasts for 75 years from publication, or one hundred years from creation, whichever expires first.<P>
<LI>The Copyright Act expressly covers computer software.  Court decisions have clarified the Act by determining that the copyright statute extends to source and object code, microcode, applications and operating systems, and code on disk, in RAM or embedded in ROM.<P>
<LI>Registration is not needed to obtain copyright protection, however, copyright registration is highly recommended.  Registration is required before initiating suit and is a prerequisite for awards of statutory damages and attorneys' fees.  In addition, registration provides notice of your rights to others.<P>
<LI>Copyright notice is not needed for copyright protection.  Notice is recommended, however, to ensure international protection, defeat claims of innocent infringement and deter infringement.<P>
<LI>Appropriate Copyright Notice Format:<P>
&copy; YEAR OF CREATION OWNER  All Rights Reserved.<P>
<LI>Scope of protection provided by copyright law is sometimes ambiguous, especially in the computer software area.  There are general rules which help govern the proper scope of protection.<P>
<OL>
<LI>Copyright only covers the expression of ideas.  Ideas themselves are not protected by the Copyright Act.<P>
<LI>Copyright does not extend to elements which are not original to the author.  An author cannot copy elements from another source and then seek to use the copyright laws to prevent the copying of those very elements.<P>
<LI>Copyright does not extend to standard elements (Scènes à Faire).<P>
<LI>The independent creation of an element is a defense to a claim of copyright infringement.  Copyright only prevents copying.<P>
</OL>
<LI>To establish a claim of copyright infringement, the plaintiff must prove copying.  Proof of direct copying is the best evidence, but difficult to obtain.  If there is no evidence of direct copying, a plaintiff must prove access to the copyrighted work and that the defendant's work is substantially similar to the plaintiff's copyrighted work.<P>
<LI>Scope of Protection for Computer Programs is generally determined by how courts analyze substantial similarity.  Two tests predominant:<P>
<OL>
<LI>The "Look and Feel" test<P>
<LI>The "Abstraction Test"
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>Utility Patent Protection for Computer Software</H2>
<UL>
<LI>In exchange for an inventor sharing his or her invention with the public, the government may issue a U.S. patent which grants to the patent holder an exclusive right to make, use and sell the invention covered by a patent.<P>
<LI>This exclusive right originally lasted 17 years from the date of issuance of the patent.  However, the duration of a patent will be 20 years from the date of filing after June 8, 1995.<P>
<LI>The scope of protection afforded by a patent are determined by its claims.  Claims are originally drafted by a patent attorney and are often amended during "examination" of the patent application by the U.S. Patent Office.<P>
<LI>To be patentable, an idea must be new, useful and nonobvious.<P>
<LI>To be patentable, an idea must be of a type provided for by the patent statute, i.e. "Statutory Subject Matter."  The statute provides that patents may be granted for "any new and useful process, machine, manufacture or composition of matter, or any new and useful improvement thereof."<P>
<LI>What is not patentable?<P>
<OL>
<LI>Pure Mathematical Algorithms.  A mathematical formula or algorithm is analogous to a law of nature which cannot be the subject of a patent.<P>
<LI>Printed Matter.  If the invention relates merely to an arrangement of printed matter, the invention is non-statutory and nonpatentable.<P>
<LI>Method of Doing Business.  A method of doing business may be rejected as non-statutory.  The scope of this non-statutory area is not well defined.<P>
</OL>
<LI>The patent statute does not expressly provide for the patenting of computer software.  As of the early 1970s, it was unclear whether any invention which involved a computer program constituted statutory subject matter.  Courts have subsequently held that some inventions relating to computer software are patentable.  Whether or not an invention relating to computer software constitutes statutory subject matter must therefore be determined on a case by case basis.<P>
<OL>
<LI>The U.S. Patent and Trademark Office has traditionally used a test know as the Freeman/Walter/Abele test to determine whether claims relating to computer software include statutory subject matter.  This test consists of the following inquiry:<P>
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>Is a mathematical algorithm directly or indirectly recited in claims?<P>
<LI>If yes, does the claim as a whole merely recite a mathematical algorithm or a method of calculation?<P>
<LI>If yes, the claim as drafted is not directed to statutory subject matter.<P>
</OL>
<LI>Recently, the Federal Circuit reexamined whether an invention relating to computer software was patentable.  The majority decision in In Re Alapat (Fed. Cir. 1994) held that an invention relating to a system for reducing the aliasing of a wave form that a rasterizer will display on an oscilloscope was statutory subject matter, because the claims were directed at machine-based embodiments of the invention (a rasterizer).
</OL>
</UL>
<H2>Design Patents for Computer Related Inventions</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Design patents protect the ornamental features of useful articles.  Design patents must meet the same nonobvious and novelty requirements as utility patents.  Design patent protection extends for 14 years from the date of issuance.  The design of computer systems and monitors, icons used on computer screens, and fonts, may receive design patent protection.
</UL>
<H2>Trade Secret Protection for Computer Software</H2>
<UL>
<LI>A trade secret consists of information  (i.e., formula, pattern, device or compilation of information) which derives independent economic value from not being generally known and which is the subject of reasonable efforts to keep it a secret.<P>
<LI>Unlike patents and copyrights, there is no federal statute governing trade secrets.  Actions alleging the misappropriation of a trade secret arise under state law.  Many states have adopted the Uniform Trade Secrets Act.<P>
<LI>Trade secret protection has been used to protect databases, mathematical models, computer hardware and computer software.<P>
<LI>Reverse engineering of a product to a trade secret is allowed.  Generally you can decompile any software which you own to discover any trade secrets resident in the software.<P>
<LI>To avoid the right to decompile software, most software is licensed rather than sold.  The license agreement may require that any trade secrets in the software be maintained in secrecy and that the licensee not decompile the software.  As a result, if trade secrets are to be maintained in computer software which is delivered to third parties, the software should be subject to an enforceable license agreement rather than sold outright.  Note that shrink-wrap licenses often contain secrecy or non-decompilation provisions, but the enforceability of shrink-wrap licenses is unclear.<P>
<LI>It is not possible to have both patent protection and trade secret protection on a single invention.  When a patent is issued, a complete description of the invention is published making any secret in the invention public knowledge.  However, patent applications are maintained in secrecy until a patent issues.  It is possible, therefore, to file a patent application on a trade secret and, if the patent claims are rejected, withdraw the application and maintain the invention maintained as a trade secret.
</UL>

<HR>

