<HEAD>
<TITLE> Background to Trademarks </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Background to Trademarks</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Gary Weinstein</h4>
<p>


<font="+2"><b>Overview</b></font><p>


A "trademark" is a word, name, symbol, device or any combination thereof adopted and used (or intended to be adopted and used) by a manufacturer or merchant to identify its goods and to distinguish them from those manufactured and sold by others.  A service mark is similar to a trademark except that it is used in connection with services rather than goods.  (The terms trademark and mark will be used in this memorandum to refer to both trademarks and service marks.)<p>

Marks serve to (i) identify and distinguish the goods or services of one party from the goods or services of another, (ii) signify that all goods or services bearing the mark come from a common source, (iii) signify that all goods or services bearing the mark are of similar quality, and/or (iv) symbolize the goodwill of a business.<p>

<font="+2"><b>Trademark Law and Marketing Concepts</b></font><p>

The overriding principle of trademark law is that trademarks identify goods or services used with a mark as having a common source and therefore being of similar quality.  From a marketing perspective, an effective trademark provides a high level of consumer recognition that the goods or services with which the mark is used are associated with a particular source.  If a mark meets this marketing goal, it is likely that trademark law will afford that mark a high degree of protection.  Whether or not a mark is available for use similarly parallels marketing concepts.  <EM>If consumers currently do not associate a proposed mark with any goods or services that are similar to those with which the proposed mark will be used, it is likely that the proposed mark is available for use.</EM><p>

There is also a complementary policy of preserving for everyone's use those marks which tend to describe the goods or services.  Generally, descriptive terms are treated by the courts as words in the public domain that ought to be available to all competitors, and these descriptive words are regarded as failing to distinguish the goods or services of one party from other similar goods or services.  For example, the word recipes is in the public domain for use in conjunction with cookbooks.  Such a policy makes sense from a marketing standpoint because descriptive marks often serve to identify a class of goods or services rather than a particular source of the goods or services.<p>

<font="+2"><b>Selection of a Mark</b></font><p>

A mark may take substantially any format, so long as the mark is distinctive and capable of identifying and distinguishing goods or services.  By way of illustration, a mark may comprise letters ("GTO"), numbers ("747"), a combination of numbers and letters ("DC10"), a single word ("NUTRASWEET"), abbreviations ("I.B.M."), slogans ("YOU'RE IN GOOD HANDS"), a name ("TRUMP PLAZA"), symbols and designs (a fanciful swirl for aspartame), a geometrical shape (Mercedes Benz Star), the design or appearance of a building (white miniature castles), clothing (Dallas Cowboys Cheerleaders' uniforms), shape (shape of a Coca-Cola bottle), sounds (NBC chimes), smells (floral aroma) and colors (pink fiberglass insulation).<p>

One limitation on the format of a mark is that a mark may not be functional.  If a proposed mark has a utilitarian purpose in the manufacture or use of the goods on which the proposed mark is used, the proposed mark may not be protectable as a trademark.  Otherwise, an individual could monopolize a particular product under the guise of trademark protection.  For example, the shape of "ROLODEX" brand telephone index cards is unprotectable as a mark because the shape is dictated by the intended use of the cards.<p>

The general rule in the United States is that the first party to adopt and use a mark has the right to exclude another's use of a mark which is likely to cause confusion among an appreciable number of reasonably prudent purchasers as to the source, connection or sponsorship between the goods or services offered under the marks.  In order for there to be a likelihood of confusion, however, other factors need to be examined, such as the differences and similarities between the goods/services, the trade channels and the level of sophistication of consumers.<p>

Marks that are typically found to be confusingly similar are those that are identical, look alike, sound alike or mean the same thing.  For example, the marks "SQUIRT" and "QUIRST" for use in connection with soft drinks likely would be considered to be confusingly similar, because they look and sound alike and are used on similar goods; however, if one of the marks was used with tires, for example, it is unlikely there would be any confusion.<p>

Generally, the geographic scope of protection afforded a mark is limited to those areas where the mark actually is being used.  A notable exception to this rule is for marks registered on the Principal Register (see below), which are deemed to have an effective geographic scope of use of the entire United States.<p>

<font="+2"><b>Strength of a Mark</b></font><p>

The strength of a mark determines, to some degree, the breadth of protection provided by the mark.  Strong marks are given a wide range of protection as to both format variations and variety of products and services which will be deemed confusingly similar.  Conversely, weak marks are given a relatively narrow range of protection as to both format variations and variety of products and services which will be deemed confusingly similar.<p>

The strength of a mark is a function of the ability of the mark to distinguish the goods or services with which it is used.  Initially, a mark's strength is assessed based on whether the mark is categorized as fanciful, arbitrary, suggestive, descriptive or generic.<p>

Fanciful marks include coined words which have been invented for the sole purpose of functioning as a mark.  Examples of fanciful marks include "EXXON", "XEROX" and "KODAK".  Additionally, distinctive designs, symbols or other identifying features may serve as fanciful marks.  Fanciful marks are generally the strongest of all marks.<p>

Arbitrary marks consist of words, names, symbols or designs that have a common use or meaning but which, when used in conjunction with a particular good or service, neither suggest nor describe any aspect of that good or service.  Examples of arbitrary marks include "IVORY" for soap and "NOVA" for a television series.  Arbitrary marks generally are also very strong marks.<p>

Despite the general rule that fanciful and arbitrary marks are strong marks, the strength of any mark may be weakened significantly if the word, name, symbol or design is in common use as a mark in that particular or other related product fields.<p>

Due to marketing forces, a vast majority of proposed marks are either suggestive or descriptive.  Suggestive marks generally are defined as those that suggest some quality or ingredient of the goods or services, while descriptive marks generally are defined as those which describe the intended purpose, function, use or effect of the goods or services, or the class of intended consumers.  A determination of whether a mark is suggestive or descriptive is one of the most difficult issues in trademark law.  Moreover, the protection afforded to a mark can be altered dramatically depending on whether the mark is categorized as suggestive or descriptive.  A mark categorized as suggestive is deemed to be inherently distinctive and therefore capable of functioning as a mark, while <EM>a mark categorized as descriptive is deemed to be inherently indistinctive and therefore incapable of functioning as a mark unless and until secondary meaning can be proven.</EM><p>

Secondary meaning means that, while the mark has a primary meaning that belongs to the public (<EM>i.e.</EM>, the dictionary definition), the mark also has developed a secondary meaning in that purchasers have come to recognize the proposed mark as identifying and distinguishing the goods or services of one party from the goods or services of others.  For instance, the mark "SPORTS ILLUSTRATED" has come to be associated with a particular magazine rather than a broad class of illustrated publications about sports.  Developing secondary meaning usually requires significant promotions and/or advertising over an extended period of time (typically several years).<p>

Finally, a mark is generic if it is deemed to be equivalent to the goods or services with which it is used.  For example, "magazine" is generic for publications.  Note, however, that while a mark may be generic (or descriptive or suggestive) for one type of goods or services, that same mark might be arbitrary for the goods or services with which it is used (<EM>e.g.</EM>, the mark "APPLE" is generic for fruit or apples, but not for computers).  <EM>Generic marks are incapable of achieving secondary meaning and therefore cannot function as trademarks or be protected.</EM><P>

<font="+2"><b>Federal Registration</b></font><p>

While trademark protection in the United States begins when a mark is used in connection with the designated goods or services, it is also possible to register a mark.  Registering a mark affords the owner several additional advantages, as will be discussed below.  Despite the advantages afforded by registration, it is important to realize that <EM>in the United States trademark protection comes from usage, not from registration; registration only modifies and expands on those underlying trademark rights</EM> (in many foreign countries, however, this rule is reversed).<p>

In the United States, there are multiple trademark registration schemes, both on the federal level and the state level.  The federal registration scheme is broken down into (i) the Principal Register for marks which either are not descriptive or already have achieved secondary meaning, and (ii) the Supplemental Register for marks which are considered descriptive and have not yet achieved secondary meaning, but which otherwise are capable of functioning as trademarks.  Generic marks are incapable of federal registration.<p>

Before the United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) will register a mark on either the Principal Register or the Supplemental Register, an examining attorney will (i) evaluate the availability of the mark (by searching for and comparing with other federal registrations and applications) and (ii) assess whether the mark is generic, descriptive or otherwise unregistrable.  Applicants are given an opportunity to respond to and contest rejections made by the USPTO.<P>

<font="+2"><b>Incorporation of Stylization or Design</b></font><p>

Even if the textual portion of a mark (known as the block form) is descriptive or generic, it is possible that the mark may be displayed in a particular stylization (<EM>e.g.</EM>, the mark "COCA-COLA" displayed in stylized lettering) or in conjunction with a unique design (<EM>e.g.</EM>, the mark "PEPSI" with the Pepsi logo) so that the mark as a whole is not merely descriptive.  In practice, many marks are used in conjunction with either a particular stylization or design in order to increase consumer recognition of the mark.  This is particularly true when the textual portion of the mark is generic or descriptive.<p>

When registering a mark, it is possible to file an application for the block form (words only) of the mark, an application for the stylized or design form of the mark, or separate applications for each.  While a block form registration generally affords a greater scope of protection than a stylized or design registration, if the text is descriptive or generic, the USPTO most likely will require that any descriptive portions be disclaimed.  Furthermore, if the design or stylization is recognized by consumers, then obtaining a second registration for the design or stylized version is particularly advantageous.  For example, many consumers viewed T-shirts which displayed the words "Enjoy Cocaine" as being associated with or sponsored by the Coca-Cola Company when these words were displayed in the same stylization and coloring as is used for the mark "COCA-COLA".<P>

<font+"+2"><b>Identification of Goods and Services</b></font><p>

One of the required parts of a trademark application is the list of goods and services with which a mark is being used, or in the case of an intent-to-use application (see below), the goods and services with which the applicant has a bona fide intention to use the mark.  Ideally, this list is broad enough to cover all (intended) uses of the mark, yet sufficiently specific so that anyone reading the list will understand which goods and services are covered.<p>

Goods and services are broken down into various official classes, and the government filing fee for  federal applications is $245 per class.  For intent-to-use applications, the government charges an additional $100 per class upon filing evidence that the mark is being used.  Attached at the end of this memo is a list of the official classes along with a summary description of each class.<p>

Among the considerations that may be taken into account when deciding whether it is worthwhile to include any given class in an application are:  the amount of revenue earned or expected to be earned from goods or services in that class; the importance of maximizing the protection for the mark in that class; and who the competitors are in that class.<p>

As a trademark registration lists specific goods and/or services, when the registrant introduces additional goods and services under that mark, it is important to review the registration(s) and/or application(s) it already has in order to determine whether the new uses are covered or whether an additional application should be filed.<p>

<font+"+2"><b>The Federal Principal Register</b></font><p>

Federal registration of a mark on the Principal Register confers a number of benefits and legal advantages, including:<P>


<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>

<LI>recovery of profits, damages and costs for infringement, possibly including treble damages and attorneys' fees,<br> 
<LI>evidence of the registrant's ownership and exclusive right to use the mark,<br>
<LI>evidence of continuous use of the mark dating back to the filing date of the application,<br>
<LI>evidence that the mark is not confusingly similar to other registered marks,<br>
<LI>evidence that the mark has acquired secondary meaning,<br>
<LI>constructive notice that the mark is being used,<br>
<LI>ability to prevent the importation of goods bearing an infringing mark, and<br>
<LI>an effective geographic scope of use of the entire United States.<br>
</OL>



In addition, after a mark has been in continuous use for five years from the date of registration on the Principal Register, the registrant's exclusive right to use the mark can achieve incontestable status, except for certain limited defenses.<P>

<font="+2"><b>The Supplemental Register</b></font><p>

While a descriptive mark may be usable, it is registrable on the Principal Register only if the mark has achieved secondary meaning.  A mark that is only partially descriptive is registrable on the Principal Register either by disclaiming the descriptive portion or by showing that the mark has achieved secondary meaning (see above).  Marks which are considered descriptive and have not yet achieved secondary meaning, but which otherwise are capable of functioning as a mark, may be registered on the Supplemental Register.<p>

Marks registered on the Supplemental Register do not benefit from many of the advantages available from registration on the Principal Register.  However, registration on the Supplemental Register provides notice to others that the mark is being used, allows the registrant to a place the ® symbol by its mark and prevents others from federally registering similar marks. <EM> A registration on the Supplemental Register does not grant to the registrant any rights to prevent others from using the mark beyond those which are obtained by usage without registration</EM> (known as common law trademark rights).  A registration on the Supplemental Register for a period of five years coupled with continuous and substantially exclusive use of the mark typically is sufficient to show that the mark has achieved secondary meaning, thereby enabling the owner to obtain a registration on the Principal Register.<p>

<font="+2"><b>Intent-to-Use Applications</b></font><p>

Under traditional trademark law, as was discussed previously, rights in a mark are not secured until the mark actually is used in connection with specific goods and/or services.  Often, however, companies begin product development and marketing well in advance of actually offering goods or services under a proposed mark.  As such, substantial time and money may be spent, and goodwill developed, long before the proposed mark is "used" in a trademark sense.<p>

By filing a special type of federal trademark application, called an intent-to-use application, a person or company can reserve a mark for use on designated goods and/or services.  Provided that the intent-to-use application ultimately matures into a registration on the Principal Register, the application will constitute constructive use of the mark and confer nationwide priority as of the filing date of the application.  A promptly filed intent-to-use application reduces the chances that another party will obtain superior rights to use the mark in connection with the specified goods and/or services.<p>

After an intent-to-use application has been approved by the USPTO, the applicant has six months within which to file evidence that the mark is being used in connection with the goods and/or services listed in the application.  This term is renewable in six month intervals for $100 per class, for a total of up to three years.<p>

<font="+2"><b>State Registration</b></font><p>

Most states provide for some kind of trademark registration.  Unlike federal registration where the USPTO evaluates the availability of a mark and assesses whether it is descriptive, generic, confusingly similar to other marks or otherwise unregistrable, most states ordinarily do not conduct any meaningful review before registering a mark.  As such, a state registration typically has little offensive legal significance, although it might, depending on the state, serve as evidence that the facts stated in the registration are true and offer other advantages.  <EM>Priority of use, not priority of state registration, controls trademark rights.</EM>  The mere ownership of a state trademark registration does not confer trademark rights absent actual use of the mark.<p>

In many cases, state registration offers little more than a psychologically soothing effect for the registrant.  A state trademark registration (as well as a federal registration or application) may have significant value in that it will likely be found by others who conduct a trademark search and thereby may helpt to prevent reputable businesses from unintentionally adopting and using a similar mark.<P>

<font="+2"><b>Proper Use of a Mark</b></font><p>

Marks must be protected and properly used or they will be lost.  Many marks have passed into the public domain because they were misused.  Some famous former marks which have been lost include "ESCALATOR", "KEROSENE", "SHREDDED WHEAT", "CELLOPHANE" and "ASPIRIN".  A trademark is lost when it becomes generic and is no longer capable of identifying or distinguishing the goods or services of a particular individual.  Some valuable marks, such as "XEROX" and "FEDEX", currently are in danger of becoming generic.  To combat a potential loss of trademark rights, the Xerox Corporation has been running ads for several years in major newspapers telling people that "you can't 'XEROX' a document--you can photocopy it on a 'XEROX' brand copying machine."<p>

It is relatively easy to protect marks.  Proper care and maintenance includes: (i) using the mark in a manner which distinguishes it from the surrounding text (capitalization or quotation marks), (ii) using a trademark notice following the mark (® for federally registered marks and <sup><font="=1">tm</font></sup> for all others), and (iii) using the common descriptive name of the product after the mark ("BAND-AID"® brand adhesive bandages).  Marks should not be used in the possessive form ("PAMPER's" disposable diapers), in the plural form (a 6-pack of "COKES"), as a verb ("XEROX" this report), or as a noun (pick up some "WHEATIES").  <EM>Marks are adjectives and should be used as such.</EM><p>

<font="+2"><b>Licensing</b></font><p>

One of the primary functions of a mark is to indicate quality.  Consumers expect all goods and/or services bearing the same mark to be of comparable quality.  Hence, a trademark license should include not only a provision allowing the licensee to use the mark, but also a provision providing the licensor with sufficient quality control measures.  The licensor must be able to insure that the goods and/or services sold by the licensee under the licensed mark are of quality comparable to the quality of goods and/or services offered by the licensor (and/or other licensees) under that same mark.<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Gary Weinstein at 612/336-3492 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:gweinstein@faegre.com"><EM>gweinstein @faegre.com</EM></A>.   For information about additional intellectual property issues, other legal issues and about Faegre & Benson, please visit our home page at <EM>http://www.faegre.com</EM>.
<p>


