<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Has the Patent Wolf Swallowed the Trade Dress Sheep? </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Has the Patent Wolf Swallowed the Trade Dress Sheep?</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>John M. Haurykiewicz</h4>
<p>


<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he Courts of Appeal for the 7th and 10th Circuits have put a new spin on an arcane corner of intellectual property law, but one which all intellectual property owners should consider when making decisions about what species of intellectual property they select to protect their products or services:  The overlap of patents and trade dress.<P>

Utility patents protect the underlying idea and design patents protect the ornamental appearance of new, useful, and unobvious inventions.  Trademarks are used to indicate the source or origin of a product.  Trade dress is the overall image used to present a product to potential purchasers.  Patents have a limited life (previously 17 years, but for newly filed utility applications, 20 years from the date of filing of the application).  Design patents expire 14 years after issue.  Once a patent expires, the subject matter of the patent is to be freely available for use by anyone.  In contrast, trademarks and trade dress have potentially unlimited lifetimes, provided that use of the mark or trade dress continues in the marketplace.<P>

What happens after the expiration of a patent when trade dress features are claimed in the patent?  The 10th Circuit case of Vornado Air Circulation Systems, Inc. v. Duracraft Corp., 58 F.3d 1498, 35 U.S.P.Q.2d 1332 (10th Cir. 1995) holds that where a disputed product configuration is part of a claim in a utility patent, and the configuration is a described, significant, and inventive aspect of the invention, see 35 USC §112, so that without it the invention could not fairly be said to be the same invention, patent law prevents its protection as trade dress, even if the configuration is non-functional.<P>

In this situation Vornado included a spiral grill structure as an element in the claims of its fan patent.  A competitor, Duracraft, offered an inexpensive look-a-like product which did not infringe the Vornado patent.  Vornado then turned to Section 43(a) of the Lanham Act and alleged trade dress infringement because the appearance of the Vornado and Duracraft products shared the spiral grill appearance.<P>

In order to prevail in its trade dress infringement case, Vornado needed to show that the product's trade dress was inherently distinctive or that it had become distinctive through acquisition of secondary meaning, thus demonstrating that the trade dress had a source identifying meaning.<SUPER>1</SUPER>  In addition, Vornado needed to show that potential customers were likely to be confused by Duracraft's trade dress into thinking that Duracraft was affiliated, associated, or acting with the approval of Vornado.<P>

Duracraft defended by alleging that the contested trade dress was functional and, therefore, all competitors were permitted to copy it regardless of the source identifying attribute.  Functionality, in this context, has a special meaning: If competitors need to be able to use a particular configuration in order to make an equally competitive product, it is functional, but if they do not, it may be non-functional.  Vornado, supra.  In other words, functionality is not to be equated with usefulness.  The Court decided that because Vornado included the spiral grill in its patent claims, Vornado could not also use a trade dress theory, because that would prevent people from fully exploiting the patented invention after the patent expires.  <P>

What happens when trade dress features are disclosed, but not claimed, in a patent and the patent expires?  The 7th Circuit in the case of Thomas & Betts Corp. v. Panduit Corp., 65 F.3d 654, 36 U.S.P.Q.2d 1065, (7th Cir. 1995) was faced with that issue, but found that the feature of an oval head for electrical cable ties had not acquired secondary meaning and hence was free to be copied once the patent covering the cable tie expired.  In this situation, the oval head was disclosed but not claimed in the patent.  The patent was directed to a cable tie having a metal barb in the head which retained the tail of the tie once inserted into the head.  No specific configuration was claimed for the head.  The 7th Circuit stated:<P>

<blockquote><EM>Copying is not only good, it is a federal right--a necessary complement to the patent system's grant of limited monopolies..... The right to copy is even more robust when the copied product was previously patented but the original patent has expired.</EM></blockquote><P>

The court went on to say [t]he issue is not the primary meaning to consumers of a particular signifier, but is instead whether a product feature's primary significance to consumers is as an identifier of source or as an element which contributes to the inherent appeal of the product.  The 7th Circuit considered the Vornado decision, but indicated that [t]he focus on what is or is not claimed is misguided... and as much as said that the entire invention as disclosed is dedicated to the public upon expiration of the patent.  Notwithstanding this strong language regarding the consequences of patent expiration, the court based its decision on the failure of the plaintiff to demonstrate secondary meaning in the oval head.  One of the most telling points considered by the court in deciding there was no secondary meaning was that the plaintiff's advertising failed to encourage consumers to identify the particular trade dress feature with the plaintiff (e.g., look for the oval head).  Instead, the court found that the plaintiff's advertising promoted the particular feature as having desirable aspects of the product itself (low profile rounded head...won't snag...smooth body prevents breakage problems).  <P>

The Vornado and Thomas & Betts cases are consistent with other, non-patent related cases.  For example, in another recent case, Fabrication Enterprises, Inc. v. Hygenic Corporation, 64 F.3d 53, 35 U.S.P.Q.2d 1753 (2nd Cir. 1995) the Court addressed the issue of whether a color-coding system to indicate resistance levels of elastic bands used in physical rehabilitation was protectable under the Lanham Act.  The Court referred to three factors that must be considered:<P>

<OL>
<LI>The degree of functionality of similar features of the product,
<LI>The degree of similarity between the non-functional (ornamental) features of the competing products, and
<LI>The feasibility of alternative designs that would not impair the utility of the product.

</OL>

These factors must be considered by the courts to assess how application of Lanham Act protection to useful features may affect competition.  The 2nd Circuit remanded this case to the trial court for a full trial on the merits.  Although not a case where patents overlap trade dress, the Fabrication Enterprises case shows that the courts will weigh the potential competitive impact of extending Lanham Act protection to product features or designs embodied in trade dress.  Such an ad hoc approach makes it difficult to predict, at the time a potentially infringing product is introduced, how a court will view the competitive impact retrospectively.  Where a utility patent is involved, at least the 10th Circuit has indicated that the patent preempts any trade dress protection in patented elements of the product.  The Vornado case, while not directly addressing design patents, appears to be available as precedent for the proposition that filing a design patent is an election of protection preempting protection via trade dress for the product shown in the design patent.  <P>

In conclusion, both utility and design patent applicants should weigh functionality and the preemption of the patent protection over trade dress protection in deciding what features to include in the specification, drawings and claims of patent applications that may include ornamental elements of their products.  Competitors looking to copy product designs from expired patents can take comfort in the recent case developments, but should always investigate whether the patent owner has made efforts to build secondary meaning (and what the success of those efforts has been) in product features sought to be copied.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>1"'Secondary meaning' is acquired when in the minds of the public, the primary significance of a product feature...is to identify the source of the product rather than the product itself.' Qualitex Co. v. Jacobson Products Co., Inc., ___ U.S. ___, ___, 115 S.Ct. 1300,1303, 131 L.Ed.2d 248, 34 U.S.P.Q.2d 1161 (1995).</FONT><P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact John Haurykiewicz by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:jhauryki@faegre.com"><EM>jhauryki@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>

