<TITLE>White House to Ease Controls on Encryption Software</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>


<H2>White House to Ease Controls on Encryption Software</H2>



<H4>by</h4>

<h4><a href="../offices/att_mpls.html#sako">Richard Y. Sako</a></H4>

In an apparent compromise to the ongoing debate between the U.S. computer industry and U.S. law enforcement and intelligence agencies over export restrictions on encryption software products, on October 1, 1996, the Clinton Administration announced its new policy on data encryption exports which will permit U.S. companies to export more powerful forms of encryption software subject to certain conditions.
<p>

Encryption software, <EM>i.e.</EM>, software capable of scrambling information generated by such software to maintain its secrecy against unintended recipients, is subject to strict regulation restricting the export of such software from the United States to foreign countries.  
Export controls on cryptographic products have been the subject of intense debates between the computer industry and U.S. governmental agencies.  Computer companies argue that strict export controls place the American computer industry at a severe disadvantage in competing in foreign markets as U.S. companies are forced to sell products with inferior capabilities to those sold by their foreign competitors.  Law enforcement agencies counter that strict controls are necessary to ensure that cryptographic technology does not fall into the hands of foreign terrorists, drug cartels and other criminals for use in hiding transactions and communications.  
<p>

Currently, the export of most encryption software is regulated by the U.S. State Department as a "munition" under the International Traffic in Arms Regulations (ITAR), rather than the U.S. Department of Commerce which regulates the export of products having both a commercial and potential military application (see, <EM>International Law Notes</EM>, Spring 1996).  State Department approval is usually required before any item subject to ITAR can be exported.  In most cases, it is extremely difficult to export a munition subject to ITAR, whereas a product under Commerce Department jurisdiction may usually be exported, albeit with some restrictions.  
<p>

Exporters of encryption software presently have three ways in which they can attempt to have control over the export of their product transferred from the State Department to the more lenient Commerce Department.  First, subject to certain restrictions, encryption software which is being exported for personal use by an exporter may qualify for ITARs personal-use exemption.  Second, an exporter may file a request for Commodity Jurisdiction with the State Department pursuant to provisions in ITAR providing for the automatic transfer of jurisdiction over specific types of encryption software from the State Department to the Commerce Department.  For example, software specifically designed and developed for use only in machines for banking or money transactions will be subject to regulation by the Commerce Department.  Third, an exporter may apply to the State Department for transfer of jurisdiction over its product to the Commerce Department on a case-by-case basis.  ITAR provides for the transfer to the Commerce Department for certain mass-market software products which have limited data encryption capabilities.  Under current policy, case-by-case basis transfer of jurisdiction over encryption software products is limited to 40-bit encryption systems.
<p>

Under the new policy, which will become effective January 1, 1997, the Clinton Administration proposes a two-year window during which companies may export more complex 56-bit DES or equivalent data encryption products, including both hardware and software, provided that the companies commit to benchmarks and milestones for developing a key recovery system within such two-year period.  The key recovery system would enable intelligence officials and law-enforcement agents, armed with court warrants, to obtain the mathematical key to decode scrambled communications.  After the two-year period, the export of 56-bit encryption products that do not support key recovery will no longer be permitted.  
<p>

The new policy differs from the past administration proposal calling for a "key escrow" system in which the U.S. government would have been the repository of the numeric keys.  The key escrow system proposal raised fears of potential government abuse as well as concerns that legitimate foreign users would be reluctant to purchase software if its privacy capability could be compromised by U.S. government officials.  Under the new policy, decryption keys may be held by third-party companies.  A key could be divided across several companies that would handle any given message.  Thus, if an intelligence agency obtained a warrant to decode a message, the agency would have to go to several different groups with its warrant to decode the message.
The new policy also proposes that jurisdiction over exports of encryption software be transferred from the State Department to the Commerce Department.  Such a move is seen as a positive step by the computer industry as it is widely believed that the business-friendly Commerce Department will be more receptive in addressing American companies competitive interests.
<p>

Computer industry representatives, while acknowledging that the new policy is a significant step toward addressing their concerns, are reacting to the announcement with cautious optimism.  Representatives state that it will be difficult to market and sell encryption software to foreign customers if it is known that U.S. governmental intelligence agencies will have access to the codes for such products and that further liberalization will be necessary as customer demand for stronger encryption products increases.  A number of issues also remain unresolved including the definition of a key recovery system.
<p>

The success of the new policy is viewed as being dependent in part on the cooperation of foreign countries in assisting U.S. exporters with developing the infrastructure necessary to implement a key recovery system.  President Clinton is expected to sign an Executive Order during October of 1996 to make the new policy official.

<P>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to international business and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Richard Sako at 612/336-3461 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:rsako@faegre.com">rsako@faegre.com</A>. <p>


