<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Foreign Sales Corporation:  A Tax Incentive For Exporters</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<H2>The Foreign Sales Corporation:  A Tax Incentive For Exporters</H2>

<H4>By</h4>
<h4><a href="../offices/att_mpls.html#murphy">Michael E. Murphy</a></H4>

Small and mid-sized exporters that were founded after 1985 are often unaware of a tax exemption available to them under the foreign sales corporation ("FSC") provisions contained in Sections 921-927 of the Internal Revenue Code (the "Code").  The FSC provisions, enacted in 1985, are intended to encourage the export of U.S.-made goods.  The exemption also applies to architectural and construction services provided to overseas projects by U.S. persons.
<p>

<strong>Definition of an FSC</strong><br>

The FSC is a corporation organized under the laws of a foreign jurisdiction.  The jurisdiction must be one that allows the U.S. Internal Revenue Service ("IRS") access to records of the corporation; such records must be kept in the jurisdiction that relate to the corporations liability for U.S. taxes.  A list of eligible foreign jurisdictions appears on page 8.
An FSC is required to have a foreign office where it must keep certain records  including basic financial information and export sales invoices.  At least one member of the FSCs board of directors must reside abroad.  Somewhat surprisingly, the FSCs foreign office need not be in the jurisdiction of its incorporation, nor is it necessary that the foreign resident director (who may be American) reside in the jurisdiction of the FSCs incorporation.  (Lawyers in Faegre & Bensons foreign offices have served as off-shore FSC directors as an accommodation to some of our clients.)
<P>

The FSC statute prohibits an FSC from having more than 25 shareholders.  Finally, the FSC may not issue preferred stock.  The FSC and its shareholders must make an election with the IRS within 90 days before the beginning of the taxable year for which the FSC intends to have its election effective; a newly incorporated FSC may make its election within 90 days after incorporation.
<p>

<strong>Foreign Management and Foreign Economic 
Process Tests</strong><br>

Unless an FSC qualifies and elects to be treated as a "small FSC" (see below), it must meet the "foreign management test" and the "foreign economic processes test" to benefit from the statutory exemption.
<P>

Under the foreign management test, the FSC must (i) hold each shareholders and board of directors meetings outside the United States, (ii) maintain its principal bank account outside the United States, and (iii) pay certain expenditures from bank accounts maintained outside the United States (accounts in foreign branches of U.S. banks will qualify).
<P>

The foreign economic processes test consists of two distinct tests.  First, certain sales-related activities must occur outside the United States.  Second, certain percentages of costs associated with entering into export contracts and delivering goods must be incurred outside the United States and be borne by the FSC.
<P>

The sales-related activities associated with entering into export contracts include (i) the solicitation, (ii) the negotiation, and (iii) "the making of the contract relating to [the export] transaction."  The FSC (or any person acting under contract with the FSC) must have participated outside the United States in at least one of these three sales-related activities.
The statutory cost categories associated with marketing and delivering goods for export include (i) advertising and sales promotion, (ii) processing customer orders and arranging for delivery of the export property, (iii) transporting goods to the customer, (iv) determining and transmitting a final invoice or statement of account and the receipt of payment, and (v) assuming credit risk.  The FSC (or another person acting under contract with the FSC) must incur at least 50% of the total of these costs outside the United States to satisfy the foreign economic processes test.  Alternatively, the FSC can satisfy the test if it can show that 85% or more of the total costs incurred outside the United States were attributable to any two of the five categories.  If  export-related costs are incurred by the exporter in connection with one or more of the five statutory cost categories, then the alternative 50%-85% rules need only be applied to those categories.
<p>

<strong>Illustration of the Foreign Economic Processes Test</strong><br>

Since the foreign economic processes test can be difficult to understand, the following example is offered to illustrate its application in a typical situation.
<P>

Assume that Intertec Inc. is a U.S. manufacturing company that has an independent sales and service representative based in Canada.  The representative is responsible for identifying Canadian customers for Intertec, arranging for and facilitating sales, and servicing Intertecs customers.  The representatives services include relaying pricing and delivery terms from Intertec to its customers, and in turn relaying purchase orders from the customers to Intertec.  Intertec sells its products F.O.B. Minnesota, against irrevocable, documentary letters of credit.
Pursuant to the terms of a contract with Intertec, the representative arranges for Intertec ads to be placed periodically in selected industry publications distributed in Canada, and demonstrates Intertecs products at one industry trade fair in Canada each year.  This is the only investment Intertec makes in advertising and sales promotion targeted to this market.
Intertec compensates its Canadian representative with commissions based on a percentage of sales attributable to the representatives efforts plus costs and expenses incurred by the representative.
<P>

Intertec has organized an FSC and contracted with the FSC to act as Intertecs export agent.  The contract provides that Intertec will perform for the FSC all of the statutory economic process activities.  It also provides that the FSC bear all expenses related to such activities, and requires that such expenses be incurred abroad to the extent of the alternative 50%-85% statutory cost rules.  The contract permits Intertec to subcontract for the statutory economic processes activities, which Intertec does through its agreement with its Canadian representative.
<P>

Since all foreign targeted advertising and sales promotion take place outside the United States, this entire category of expenses can be considered incurred outside the United States.   Treasury Regulations provide that "processing of customer orders" means notifying the related supplier (Intertec) of the order and the requirements for delivery of the export property.  The Regulations further provide that an FSC will be considered to have arranged for product delivery if the FSC or its agent notifies the buyer of the time and place of delivery.  Assuming that these notifications are initiated outside the United States, it would appear that 100% of the category of expenses relating to the processing of customer orders and arranging for delivery of the goods may be considered incurred outside the United States.  Because more than 85% of the costs in two of the five expense categories described above were incurred abroad, Intertec would have met the foreign cost part of the foreign economic processes test.
<P>

Because Intertecs foreign customers bear all costs associated with the transportation of the goods, and because the goods are paid for with an irrevocable letter of credit as they leave Intertecs U.S. facilities, there would be no actual transportation or credit costs associated with Intertecs export sales.  Therefore, these cost categories need not be taken into account for purposes of the 50%-85% cost rules in this example.  Intertecs Canadian representative is not involved in any activities relating to the determination and transmittal of final invoices and receipt of customer payments.  Therefore, none of the expenses associated with this category are incurred outside the United States.  It would therefore appear likely that the 50% rule would also have been met in Intertecs case.
<P>

In relaying pricing and order information, Intertecs foreign representative has participated outside the United States in at least the solicitation and negotiation of the export contracts for Intertec, thus meeting the sales-related part of the foreign economic processes test.  Because the 85% rule was certainly met with respect to the foreign cost part of the foreign economic processes test, Intertec appears to have met the entire foreign economic processes test.
<p>

<strong>Figuring the FSCs Tax-Exempt Income</strong><br>

The amount of income which an FSC can shelter from federal taxation is determined first by totalling an FSCs "foreign trading gross receipts," which are gross receipts attributable to the sale or lease of "export property."  The FSC statute defines "export property" as property produced in the United States and sold or leased to customers outside the United States.  Income from services that are "related and subsidiary" to such sales and leases is included as is income from engineering or architectural services rendered for overseas construction projects.  Income from certain managerial services provided to an unrelated FSC can also be included, but only if the FSC providing such managerial services earns at least 50% of its gross receipts from the sale or lease of export property.
<p>

An FSC may earn foreign trading gross receipts by purchasing export property from related or unrelated U.S. suppliers for resale abroad, or it may earn such receipts in the form of commissions paid to it by U.S. producers on whose behalf the FSC contracts to act as an export marketing agent.  The vast majority of FSCs are involved only with their parent companies products.  They generally operate as commission agents for their parent companies, because the commission arrangement is less difficult to set up and maintain than a title transfer arrangement.
<p>

The FSC may earn its income from the export sales of its parent company either on an "arms-length" basis or on the basis of either of two "administrative pricing" rules.  Transactions between related entities are normally subject to IRS scrutiny under the reallocation rules of section 482 of the Code.  However, since the administrative pricing rules insulate FSC transactions from section 482 review, FSCs and their parent companies usually take advantage of the safe harbors provided by the two administrative pricing rules.
<p>

Under one of the administrative pricing rules, the FSC is entitled to earn 1.83% of the foreign trading gross receipts derived from export sales transactions.  Alternatively, the FSC may earn 23% of the combined taxable income of the FSC and its parent attributable to the export sales.  The FSC may apply whichever rule produces the greater amount of income.
<p>

In order for an FSC to take advantage of the administrative pricing rules, it must have performed all of the economic processes activities described above, insofar as such activities are attributable to the export transaction.   However, for purposes of this requirement, the activities may be performed either within or outside the United States, and they may be performed for the FSC under contract with its parent company (or another person).
<p>

To illustrate the application of the two administrative pricing rules, assume that Intertec manufactures and sells its product to a foreign customer at a price of $1,000, realizing taxable income (without regard to FSC benefits) of $100.  Application of the 1.83% of gross receipts rule would yield income to the FSC of $18.30 ($1,000 x 1.83%).  Application of the 23% of combined taxable income rule would yield FSC income of $23 ($100 x 23%).  Because it yields more income, the 23% of combined taxable income formula would be chosen in this case.
<p>

Once its "foreign trade income" is determined by application of the pricing rules described above, an FSC is entitled to treat a portion thereof as "exempt foreign trade income."  The portion exempted will depend on whether the FSCs foreign trade income resulted from the application of the "arms-length" rule or one of the administrative pricing rules.  In the case of foreign trade income determined by application of either of the administrative pricing rules, 15/23rds of the FSCs foreign trade income is exempt for FSCs with corporate shareholders (or 16/23rds, for FSCs with individual shareholders).
<p>

In the example given above, Intertecs tax exempt income will be 15/23rd of $23, or $15.  Thus, Intertec will have reduced its taxable income on the $1,000 export sale from $100 to $85 by using an FSC.  The $85 will be subject to current U.S. taxation at ordinary rates, but dividends from the FSC to its parent company will be entitled to the intercorporate dividends received deduction under section 245 of the Code.  Therefore, by using an FSC, Intertec will have reduced its effective tax rate on export income from 34% to about 29%.
<p>

<strong>Small FSCs</strong><br>

Companies with export sales of $5,000,000 or less will want to consider electing "small FSC" status.  If an FSC elects to be treated as a small FSC, it will not be required to meet either the foreign management or the foreign economic processes tests; nevertheless it will be eligible for the full statutory exemption with respect to $5,000,000 in gross export receipts.  However, a small FSC is not exempt from the minimal requirements that it have a foreign office and a foreign resident board member.
<p>

<strong>The Shared FSC</strong><br>

The Technical and Miscellaneous Revenue Act of 1988 amended the FSC provisions of the Code to recognize a so-called "shared FSC."  A shared FSC is one with several unrelated stockholders who use the same FSC vehicle.  By sharing the start-up and maintenance expenses of an FSC, smaller exporters should be able to begin enjoying FSC benefits at an earlier stage of development of their export sales, and all members of a shared FSC should be able to improve their FSC benefits in proportion to the number of shareholders over which FSC costs can be spread.
<p>

<strong>Popular FSC Jurisdictions</strong><br>

Those U.S. possessions that are eligible jurisdictions for FSC purposes have adopted special legislation to accommodate FSCs.  It may be useful to compare legislation enacted in the U.S. Virgin Islands and Guam, the two jurisdictions in which most of our FSC clients have preferred to be organized.
<p>

In lieu of the regular corporate income tax applicable in the Virgin Islands, legislation enacted there imposes a "franchise tax".  For small FSCs, the franchise tax will be either $400 per year (for FSCs with gross receipts under $2,000,000) or $900 per year (for FSCs with gross receipts between $2,000,000 and $5,000,000).  For all other FSCs, the franchise tax will range from $1,000 (for FSCs with gross receipts up to $10,000,000) to $25,000 (for FSCs with gross receipts in excess of $500,000,000).  An FSC may credit against the franchise tax a portion of the wages it pays directly (or indirectly, through a local FSC management firm) to Virgin Island residents.
Guams parallel FSC legislation provides for a flat franchise charge of $400 per year for small FSCs and $1,000 for other FSCs.  Like the Virgin Islands, Guam exempts all foreign trade income of FSCs from corporate income taxation.
<p>

The business corporation laws of the Virgin Islands and Guam are based on U.S. statutory and case law, and their income tax laws mirror the Code.  Therefore, U.S. exporters should be able to use domestic U.S. counsel in connection with the organization and maintenance of FSCs in these jurisdictions.
<p>

By channeling export sales through an FSC, U.S. companies can reduce their federal taxes on income from such sales by about 5%.  Many smaller and mid-sized companies have discovered that it pays to use an FSC when export sales approach  $1,000,000 .
<P>

The U.S. Department of the Treasury has certified the following countries as having satisfactory tax information exchange programs with the United States for purposes of FSC eligibility:<br>
Australia<br>
Austria<br>
Barbados<br>
Belgium<br>
Canada<br>
Costa Rica<br>
Cyprus<br>
Denmark<br>
Egypt<br>
Finland<br>
France<br>
Germany<br>
Grenada<br>
Iceland<br>
Ireland<br>
Jamaica<br>
Korea<br>
Malta<br>
Morocco<br>
Netherlands<br>
New Zealand<br>
Norway<br>
Pakistan<br>
Philippines<br>
Sweden<br>
Trinidad and Tobago<p>

<EM>Eligible U.S. Possessions are:</EM><br>
American Samoa<br>
Guam<br>
Northern Mariana Islands<br>
U.S. Virgin Islands<p>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to international business and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

