<HEAD>
<TITLE>Labor Law Aspects of Acquisitions in Germany 
and the European Union</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>


<H2>Labor Law Aspects of Acquisitions in Germany 
and the European Union</H2>



<H4>by</h4>

<h4><a href="../offices/att_frnk.html#hummel">Ralph W. Hummel</a></H4>

One of the key aspects of a corporate acquisition is often the transfer of employees.  Invariably, a buyer will not wish to retain every employee of the target company; instead, it will want to replace some of the target companys employees with its own or try to increase the targets efficiency simply by terminating some employees.
<p>

Unlike in the United States, where a seller will typically terminate each employee involved in an acquisition and have the buyer offer new terms of employment to each employee it wishes to retain, German employees (or, for that matter, employees in the European Union) are offered statutory protection during an acquisition.  This should not come as a surprise as Germanys highly valued labor laws traditionally protect employees to a greater extent than U.S. labor laws.
<p>

<strong>Acquisitions in Germany</strong><br>
A general tenet of German labor law is that a buyer of a German corporation must retain all employees under the same or similar working conditions as prior to the acquisition.
Although the identity of the shareholders will change upon a stock acquisition, the relationship between the company and the employees remains unchanged.  A change in shareholders is not sufficient cause for terminating employees.  Employees may not be terminated unless for cause directly attributable to the employee or for a legitimate business reason, e.g., decrease in sales, financial difficulties.
<P>

If a buyer purchases all, or substantially all, of the assets and liabilities of a business,  employees must rely on statutory law for protection since their employment  status does change with the sale of the assets.  Section 613(a) of the German Civil Code states that all rights and obligations regarding employees are transferred if (i) a business, or part of a business (ii) is transferred by agreement (rather than by statute) (iii) to a new owner.
<P>

Not surprisingly, "part of a business" includes divisions of a larger corporate entity.  However, units which are not necessarily thought of as independent, such as sales offices, printing facilities of publishers or repair departments of transportation companies, could also fall under this definition.  To extend this point even farther, a bank in Germany had hired a housekeeping crew; to cut down on costs, the bank decided to contract its housekeeping services out.  In a heavily criticized decision, the European Court of Justice applied Section 613(a) to the housekeepers so that neither the bank nor the independent contractor was allowed to terminate the housekeepers because of this "acquisition."
<P>

If Section 613(a) applies to an acquisition, the buyer must assume all rights and obligations associated with each employee of the target company.  Neither the buyer nor the seller (the previous employer) may terminate an employee solely because of the transfer of  a business.  This prohibition does not extend to employees.  Employees have the right to dissent to the transfer of their employment and to insist on a continuation of their employment with the seller.  The practical implications of this right, however, are clear.  If an employee demands that its employment relationship continue with its former employer, and the former employer no longer operates the business which was the subject of the sale, the employer is suddenly given an obvious and legitimate reason for termination.  The employee would, however, have a right to continued employment with the seller if a suitable position was available in another department of the sellers business.
<P>

Though there is no statutory period by which an employee must voice its dissent, German courts generally require employees to lodge their dissent within two weeks of receiving complete information regarding the transfer.
<P>

Section 613(a) also states that all collective bargaining agreements and agreements between employee representatives (commonly known as works councils) and employers shall remain valid for one year after the transfer of a business and cannot be revised to the employees detriment during that period.
<P>

Regardless, it is not at all rare that buyers will terminate some of the target companys employees.  The reason for the termination will dictate what path the buyer will follow to execute the termination.  If the buyer has a legitimate reason, as defined under German law, it may be required to do nothing more than give termination notices and observe the relavant notice periods.  If a legitimate reason is not available, employers often find severance packages to be an agreeable option for terminating employees.  The legitimacy of a termination is usually first subject to the review of the works council, and if necessary, the regional Department of Labor or a Labor Court.
<P>

Much to the surprise  and often delight  of many, service agreements with Managing Directors (Geschäftsführer) do not fall under the auspices of Section 613(a); thus buyers are not required to retain the sellers Managing Director.  Instead, the terms of an individual agreement between the Managing Director and the company generally govern their relationship.  Since Section 613(a) does not apply to Managing Directors, buyers may terminate them at will.  Of course, since Managing Directors nearly always have a written service agreement, buyers must take care not to breach this agreement upon termination.  Further, Managing Directors are often entitled to generous severance payments upon termination unless the termination is for cause.  
Sometimes overlooked or misunderstood is that a company may terminate a Managing Directors appointment as such  at any time.  Though this will not terminate the Managing Directors employment relationship with a company, it will allow a company to take away the reigns to the day-to-day-affairs of the company over which the Managing Director presided.
<p>

<strong>Acquisitions in the European Union</strong><br>
Buyers should be aware that the EC Commission passed a directive in 1977 which required member states to pass "safeguards" to protect employees rights similarly to Section 613(a).  As stated in that directive "[t]he transfer of a business shall not in itself constitute grounds for dismissal by the transferor or the transferee."
<P>

As one of the enunciated safeguards, employers must notify works councils of a pending acquisition "in good time" before the closing.  As discussed above, works councils have the right to review (i) the reasons for the acquisition, (ii) the legal, economic and social implications of the acquisition, and (iii) "measures envisaged in relation to the employees."
Although the Council Directive on the Establishment of a European Works Council (the "1996 directive"), which member states were to enact into their respective national laws by September 22, 1996, does not apply specifically to acquisitions, its terms must be kept in mind as it does add a twist to the 1977 directive.
<P>

Recognizing that many companies often operate in more than one EU member state, and that the operations in one state can directly impact the employees in another, the 1996 directive requires  management  to establish a so-called European Works Council or an information system in every "community-scale undertaking" i.e., any entity with at least 1,000 employees within the EU and at least 150 employees in each of at least two member states.  There are two significant differences between a European Works Council and a works council in Germany.  First, a works council in Germany is established solely at the initiative of  employees, while the 1996 directive requires management to take the initiative.   Second, while a German works council has the right to participate in a companys decision-making, this same right is not extended to the European Works Council.
<P>

Although many employers will look at this new directive with chagrin, its impact will probably not be great  at least not initially.  First, the threshold in terms of number of employees will allow most employers to ignore the directive.  Second, because most of the companies who are subject to the new directive will already have various works councils in place, they already know how to cooperate effectively with works councils.  Unlike many Americans who instantly become wary of works councils motives, most EU nationals can appreciate the positive aspects of engaging in dialogue with employees. As a result of the 1996 directive, this collaboration will continue, only now on a wider scale.
<p>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to international business and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Ralph Hummel at 49/69/971-227-0. <p>


