<HEAD>
<TITLE>Brazil - A Mixed Message for Investors and Traders</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>


<H2>Brazil - A Mixed Message for Investors and Traders</H2>




Like many of its South American neighbors, Brazil finds itself at a crossroads with direct foreign investors and foreign traders.  A change in Brazils monetary policy has been the direct cause of bringing the legendary inflation rate under control, lowering tax rates and increasing privatization.  Each of these factors has made Brazil a more attractive site for foreign investors.  However, Brazil has recently shown signs of backing off from its free market stance by increasing duties and imposing import quotas on certain products.  These mixed signals leave outsiders wondering whether Brazil is truly committed to opening its doors to foreigners.
<P>

<strong>Direct Investment</strong><br>

President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, often cited as the architect of Brazils change in policy from earlier decades, focused his attention first on Brazils tax rate.  In the past, Brazil restricted foreign direct investment for fear that the country would become dependent on foreign capital which, it was believed, would lead to economic and political instability.  As a result, Brazilian policymakers were able to successfully defend the traditionally high corporate tax rates.  Further, though Brazil was not one of the primary Latin American proponents of the so-called Calvo Clause  a clause formerly in many contracts with foreigners which required foreigners to rely solely on national law when pursuing remedial measures  its use was widespread enough in Latin America to deter foreigners.  Factors such as these allowed Brazil to maintain the "control" over foreigners that domestic businesses, and policymakers, sought.
<p>

Brazils change in policy started to gain acceptance domestically leading eventually to the abolishment of the supplemental tax on dividends in the early 1990s.  Not only did Brazil have some of the highest withholding taxes in the region, but it had also been imposing a supplemental tax on dividends to foreigners to the point where the repatriation of profits was simply not practical.  The decision to reduce taxes on dividends finally culminated in the enactment of Law 9249 on December 26, 1995, which abolished taxes on dividends entirely.  As a result, dividends, or other distributions of profits earned as of January 1, 1996, do not constitute taxable income.
<p>

Brazil also reduced its withholding tax on foreign companies earnings to 15%.  This reduced withholding rate is significant as it is available to all foreign companies, regardless of whether they are citizens of countries which have tax treaties with Brazil as was formerly the case.  The 15% tax applies to earnings from the rental or lease of equipment, capital gains and license fees for technology transfer.  Though the 15% withholding tax initially did not apply to royalties, a provisional decree passed earlier this year specifically includes royalties.
<p>

Finally, the maximum basic corporate income tax has been reduced from 43% to 25%.  Taxable income for income under 240,000 Reals (slightly less than  U.S.$240,000) is in an even lower tax bracket and subject to a maximum income tax of 15%.  Also, the legendary "social contribution on net profits" tax has been reduced from 10% to 8%.  Though this tax is currently deductible, experts speculate that this will not be the case as of 1997.
<p>

Although Law 9249 may cause a companys tax <EM>rate</EM> to be lower, its tax <EM>base</EM> may actually be broadened since the new law may require companies to include their subsidiaries, branches and controlled companies income and capital gains to determine their taxable profit.   Thus Brazil has dramatically changed its tax system from a territorial system to a system which can tax all profits <EM>effectively connected</EM> to the  company.  Nevertheless, proper tax planning allows most companies to minimize this otherwise heavy tax burden.
<p>

Whether this change will motivate Brazil to conclude double taxation treaties with its primary trading partners remains to be seen.  The tax treaty between Brazil and the United States signed in 1967  the first between a South American country and the United States  has, to this day, not been ratified.
<p>

Regardless, estimates provide that direct foreign investment in Brazil will increase from U.S. $3 billion in 1995 to U.S. $5 billion in 1996.  Within the past five years, many U.S.-based franchisors have either initiated or increased their operations in Brazil.  In addition, as recently as October 1, Chrysler and BMW announced that they will form a joint venture company in South America to manufacture 400,000 engines annually.  The companies have narrowed their joint venture site to either Argentina or Brazil.
<p>

<STRONG>Trade</STRONG><br>
Though the policy changes have stirred global interest, Brazil still shows some signs of wavering in its commitment to free trade.  Earlier this year, import quotas and significant tariffs were introduced.  Many argue that these changes should not be seen as evidence of a change in policy as they are nothing more than politicians  including the Trade and Industry Minister  trying to win favors from domestic businesses to gain support for their respective political ambitions.  Whatever the reason, the quotas and increased tariffs have drawn the ire of a few of Brazils trading partners such as the United States, Japan and the European Union.  In fact, the WTO will almost certainly include these oft  labeled "trade barriers" on its agenda in Singapore in December as part of that organizations proceedings regarding free trade with developing countries.
<p>

The quotas and tariffs are generally limited to specific industries  especially hard hit were the motor vehicle, clothing and toy sectors.  Not only is the introduction of these barriers troublesome, but their severity has also been a point of contention.  By way of example, quotas on textiles have caused imports to be cut by more than one-third among Brazils primary textile trading partners.  Brazil had initially set rigid quotas on the motor vehicle industry; these were renounced only after formal proceedings at the WTO.  Further, Brazil introduced a carrot and stick policy by not necessarily imposing stiff tariffs on those motor vehicle companies which demonstrated a commitment to direct foreign investment in Brazil  Mercedes, Toyota and Renault were among the first beneficiaries of this policy.  Regardless, tariffs still flourish in specific industries.  For example, duties on toys increased from 20% to 70% while the wine and footwear industry each experienced increases from 20% to 40%.  
<p>

Whether these barriers are part of a retreat to a protectionist economy or an impulsive reaction to Brazils first trade deficit is not yet known.  Regardless, the strong and widespread reaction from foreign businesses does indicate that foreigners are indeed interested in either entering or expanding their operations in the Brazilian market.

<p>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to international business and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Michael Murphy at 612/336-3229 or 800/328/4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:mmurphy@faegre.com">mmurphy@faegre.com</A>. <p>


