<HEAD>
<TITLE>United Kingdom - Unreasonable Limitation of Liability</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>


<H2>United Kingdom - Unreasonable Limitation of Liability</H2>

<H4>by</h4>

<h4><a href="../offices/att_lond.html#james">Scott M. James</a></H4>


A recent decision by the English Court of Appeal, <EM>St. Albans City and District Council v.  International Computers Ltd.</EM> (July 26, 1996), highlighted the difficulties in doing business in the United Kingdom when using standard terms and conditions.  The Unfair Contract Terms Act 1977 (the "Act") requires that certain terms in "written terms of business" must satisfy a test of "reasonableness" for such terms to be enforceable.  This standard is lower, and applies more broadly, than the concept of "unconscionability" in Section 2-302 of the Uniform Commercial Code.
<P>

In the late 1980s, St. Albans City and District Council ("St. Albans") contracted with International Computers Ltd. ("ICL") for the latter to design and implement a database for St. Albans to calculate and assess a local tax on its population.  Program errors in the database led St. Albans to conclude there would be almost 3,000 more community taxpayers than was actually the case.  The result was that St. Albans set the local tax rate too low thereby causing it to suffer a revenue shortfall of £1.3 million (over $2 million).
<p>

The agreement between the parties, an ICL form contract, provided that ICLs liability for loss caused by its performance would be limited to £100,000 (about $156,000).  When St. Albans sued, ICL raised its limitation of liability as a defense.  St. Albans responded that the clause was not enforceable because it failed to satisfy the "reasonableness" requirement in the Act.  Both the trial court and the Court of Appeal found for St. Albans.
<P>

The Acts test of "reasonableness" is a general one: "that the term shall have been a fair and reasonable one to be included having regard to the circumstances which were, or ought reasonably to have been, known to or in the contemplation of the parties when the contract was made."  The Act specifies areas of inquiry when looking at the "reasonableness" of a particular contract provision  the relative bargaining positions of the parties, whether the customer received an inducement to agree to the particular term, whether the customer knew, or should have known of the term, and whether the goods were manufactured, processed or adapted to the special order of the customer.
<P>

In making its decision, the trial court took a number of points into consideration including that St. Albans and ICL were two sophisticated organizations and should be free to make their own bargains, that St. Albans was aware of, and understood, the limitation of liability clause, that such clauses were common in the computer industry and that the software was developmental.  (In the American parlance of UCC Section 2-302, the agreement was not unconscionable and was not induced by coercion.)  
<P>

Since the ICL form contract limited the liability of ICL to a specific sum of money, the trial court and the Court of Appeal applied an additional section of the Act to determine whether limiting liability to £100,000 was "reasonable."  Applying this part of the Act, the trial court considered (i) the resources that ICL could have expected to be available to meet the liability it sought to limit and (ii) the viability of insurance to cover the relevant liability.  On these two points, the trial court and the Court of Appeal were impressed that ICL had insurance to cover this type of liability, and that the coverage far exceeded the amount set out in the limitation clause.  The trial court found, and the Court of Appeal affirmed, that the  Act applied to the St. Albans-ICL contract, and that the limitation of liability clause failed to pass a test of "reasonableness."
<P>

Should American businesses selling products in the United Kingdom be concerned with this decision? Perhaps not, since the Act states that international contracts for the sale of <EM>goods</EM> between parties from different countries are not subject to the "reasonableness" requirement.  Thus the answer depends on whether the American supplier is selling directly from the United States or through a U.K. subsidiary.  Only in the former will the "reasonableness" requirements of the Act apply.  
<P>

It is not at all clear, however, whether international service contracts would fall within the reach of the Act.  As to the distinction between "goods" and "services", one of the Court of Appeals judges in <EM>St. Albans</EM> raised a new and controversial issue.  The judge stated that software itself is not "goods", but that it could be "goods" when supplied on tangible medium such as a disk or a CD-ROM.  This analysis would help bring American-supplied software within the "international sale of goods" exception to the Act (and allow U.S. software suppliers to avoid the "reasonableness" test when disclaiming or limiting liability).  
<P>

These aspects of <EM>St. Albans</EM> mean that it will probably be some time, and only after a great deal of discussion, before the full implications of this dramatic development of English law are fully understood.


<p>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to international business and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Scott James at 44/171/623-6163. <p>


