<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>IRS Proposes to Ease Rules for Foreign Subsidiaries</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>
<BODY>

<H2>IRS Proposes to Ease Rules for Foreign Subsidiaries</H2>



<H4>by Michael E. Murphy and Peter J. Withoff</H4>

The U.S. Internal Revenue Service has proposed new regulations which, would ease tax planning for U.S. companies that conduct their overseas operations through foreign subsidiaries organized as limited liability companies.   The new regulations would replace existing regulations that govern the classification of domestic and foreign business entities, including corporations and partnerships.  Final adoption of the regulations is expected before the end of the year.<P>

When U.S. companies establish operations in a foreign country, they usually do so through the vehicle of a locally incorporated foreign company.  Two reasons for doing so include marketing advantages and limitation of liability.  Product or service acceptance in the foreign marketplace is often enhanced when the company presents itself as a locally incorporated entity.  Local incorporation also helps insulate the U.S. parent companys assets from claims arising in connection with the operations of its foreign subsidiary.<P>

However, international tax planning may sometimes indicate the use of a foreign branch of the U.S. parent company or of another U.S. affiliate, rather than a locally incorporated subsidiary.  For example, if foreign start-up losses are anticipated and the U.S. parent company wishes to offset such losses against taxable domestic income, structuring the foreign operation as a branch of the U.S. parent rather than as a separate foreign subsidiary will help, at least temporarily, to achieve this objective. <P>

Another means of permitting tax losses to flow through is to conduct the foreign operations through a local limited liability company whose articles of incorporation are tailored so that the entity will be treated as a partnership for U.S. tax purposes.  The German Gesellschaft mit beschränkter Haftung (GmbH) and the Brazilian limitada provide two common examples of foreign entities that lend themselves to this kind of international corporate and tax planning.  Each of these entities provides the foreign subsidiary with the limitation of liability desired for international corporate planning.  At the same time, the articles of incorporation of each of these entities can be drafted in such a way as to qualify it as a partnership for U.S. tax purposes, thus permitting tax losses to flow through.  This string of moves only works in the Pentagon!<P>

The problem in the past has often been finding a limited liability entity in the relevant foreign country suitable for tax loss flow-through purposes, and then investing the extra time and work (and therefore cost) required to draft foreign organizational documents to meet partnership criteria under principles of U.S. tax law.  The IRSs proposed new regulations, if adopted, should go a long way towards correcting the problem by introducing a procedure for simply electing either corporation or partnership status.<P>

<strong>Current U.S. Law</strong><BR>

Under current principles of U.S. tax law, an entity (domestic or foreign) will be treated as a corporation if it has at least three of four characteristics:  limited liability,  free transferability of interests,  continuity of life  and centralized management . If two or more of these characteristics are absent and the company has more than one shareholder, it will be treated as a partnership for U.S. tax purposes.  If partnership status can be obtained, a U.S. corporation that is a member of a foreign partnership must recognize gains, and may deduct losses, attributable to its share of the operations of the foreign partnership. <P>

In structuring foreign limited liability companies to achieve loss flow-through for U.S. tax law purposes, compromises often have been required to eliminate at least two of the four characteristics of a corporation.  It is usually desirable to leave intact the characteristics of limited liability and centralized management.  Thus, in order to preserve partnership tax status, it is necessary to eliminate both of the remaining corporate characteristics of free transferability of interests and continuity of life.<P>

Free transferability of interests is sometimes eliminated by providing in the companys organizational documents that any transfer of an interest will automatically result in the dissolution of the company.  This is obviously a risky solution, particularly because the provision should cover all interests, including those held by minority shareholders.  Alternatively, free transferability is sometimes eliminated by requiring the consent of the other shareholders as a prerequisite to a transfer.  This consent needs to be meaningful, and the U.S. parent may sometimes be unwilling to subject its transfer rights to the consent of the other independent shareholders of the company.<P>

Eliminating continuity of life is somewhat easier.  This is generally accomplished by a provision for the termination of the companys existence upon the death, disability, retirement, or bankruptcy of any shareholder.  Upon the occurrence of any of these events, the company would dissolve unless a majority of the remaining shareholders consented to its continuation.  Usually it is possible to include these provisions in the organizational documents and avoid an unacceptable level of risk that the entity would be inadvertently terminated without some ability to maintain its existence.  Nonetheless, the reconstitution mechanism still needs to be permitted under local law.<P>

It is for these reasons that U.S. companies operating overseas through foreign limited liability company affiliates could benefit from the IRSs proposed new business classification regulations.  The new regulations would eliminate the uncertainties suggested above and replace the four characteristics test with a simple election procedure.<P>

<strong>Foreign Corporate Forms
</strong><BR>

Under the corporate laws of virtually all of the European Union countries (and most other civil law jurisdictions throughout the world), two common forms of business corporations are legislated.  One form is designed for corporations whose shares are intended to be publicly traded; and the other is for more closely-held companies.  Foreign legislation governing the public corporation typically provides for a higher level of required capitalization, more rigorous public reporting requirements, share certificates representing ownership of the company (similar to share certificates representing the ownership of a U.S. company) and a supervisory board of directors that oversees the companys management (similar to the board of directors of a U.S. company).  
<P>

By contrast, legislation governing the more closely held form of foreign corporation will have lower capital requirements, less onerous public reporting requirements, a mechanism for transferring shares on the books of the company without separate share certificates and no board of directors (with direct management oversight by the shareholders).  In England, the public form of corporation is referred to as a Public Limited Company (PLC), and the closely held form is a limited company (Ltd.).  In Germany, the public form of corporation is the Aktiengesellschaft (AG), and the closely held form is the GmbH.  In Brazil the public corporation is referred to as Associate Annonyma (SA), and the closely held form is the Limitado.  (Other countries use variations of the same nomenclature as Brazils.)  <P>

<strong>The IRS Proposal</strong><BR>

The new regulations proposed by the IRS list specific foreign entities which will always be considered as corporations for U.S. tax purposes.  As far as the European Union and other civil law jurisdictions throughout the world are concerned, the IRS has listed the public form of corporation for each country as an entity that will always be considered as a corporation for U.S. tax law purposes.  The proposed regulations do not specifically list by name the closely held form of company in European and other civil law jurisdictions.  Instead, each such form of company is referred to generically as an eligible entity.  An eligible entity is  an entity that is eligible to elect classification as either a corporation or a partnership.  If no election is made with respect to such an entity, it will be assigned a default classification.<P>

Because foreign close corporations (e.g., the Brazilian limitada or the German GmbH) are simpler and less costly to organize and maintain, they are normally preferred over their public corporation counterparts by U.S. companies wishing to conduct overseas operations through controlled foreign subsidiaries.  Thus, most U.S. companies operating overseas through foreign subsidiaries will have a foreign eligible entity with respect to which a decision will need to be made as to whether a classification election should be made under the new regulations.  A foreign eligible entity with limited liability will be classified by default as a corporation.  If the U.S. parent company wishes to have the entity treated as a partnership for U.S. tax law purposes, an appropriate election will need to be filed.

<strong>Filing Procedure</strong><BR>

It appears from the proposed regulations that the filing procedure will be simple.  It merely calls for a statement of the name, address and taxpayer identification number of the entity, the chosen classification, whether the election results in a change of classification, and whether the entity is a domestic or foreign eligible entity.  Once an election change has been made, the changed classification will need to be maintained for a minimum of five years.<P>

	Liberal transition rules are provided for foreign eligible entities in existence at the time the proposed regulations go into effect.  For example, the regulations suggest that a U.S. company that has been treating its existing foreign subsidiary as a partnership for U.S. tax purposes can expect that treatment to be honored by the IRS, provided there has been a reasonable basis for partnership treatment.
<p>



<FONT SIZE=-1>1</FONT>	Proposed Treasury Regulation § 301.7701-1 through 301.7701-3 (May 13, 1996).<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>2</FONT>	Because the foreign branch is a legal extension of the U.S. entity, its income and expenses are treated for U.S. tax purposes as part of the income and expenses of the U.S. entity of which it is a branch.  Reductions in U.S. taxes resulting from foreign branch loss deductions may be recaptured under IRC § 904(f) when the foreign operations become profitable.<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>3</FONT>	Treasury Regulation § 301.7704-2<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>4</FONT>	An entity has limited liability for tax purposes if no member is liable for the debts of or claims against the organization.  Treasury Regulation § 301.7701-2(d)(1).<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>5</FONT>	An entity has free transferability of interests if substantially all of the members have the power, without the consent of the other members, to substitute for themselves in the same organization a person who is not a member of the organization.  Treasury Regulation § 301.7701-2(e)(1).<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>6</FONT>	An entity has continuity of life if the death, insanity, bankruptcy, retirement, resignation, or expulsion of any member will not cause a dissolution of the organization.  Treasury Regulation § 301.7701-2(b)(1).<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>7</FONT>	An entity has centralized management if a group consisting of less than all of the members has continuing exclusive authority to make management decisions on behalf of the entity.  Treasury regulation § 301.7701-2(c)(1). A board of directors normally exercises this function in a traditional corporate setting.<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>8</FONT>	The limited liability company laws in many of the civil law jurisdictions around the world require that the company have two or more shareholders.  A second shareholder for a German GmbH or a Brazilian limitada is conveniently supplied by the allotment of 1% of the shares to a corporate affiliate of the U.S. parent company or to the foreign subsidiarys managing director.  Foreign joint venture companies will have by definition at least two shareholders.<BR>

<P>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to international business and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>
<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Michael E. Murphy at 612/336-3229 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:mmurphy@faegre.com">mmurphy@faegre.com</A> or Peter J. Withoff at 612/336-3228 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:pwithoff@faegre.com">pwithoff@faegre.com</A>. <p>


