<HEAD>
<TITLE>Preparing to Do Business in Chinas
Special Administrative Region</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>
<BODY>

<H2>Preparing to Do Business in Chinas
Special Administrative Region</H2>



<H4>By Michelle L.D. Hanlon</H4>



The most frequently asked question regarding the integration of Hong Kong into the Peoples Republic of China is whether China as a communist regime can assume control of capitalist Hong Kong without destroying the financial freedoms important to its economic success.  Many believe that the legal and economic integrity of Hong Kong regulation will not survive a merger with a regulatory system based on favors, or guanxi and corruption.  As one investor put it, Chinese regulation works well for an economy based on making plastic flowers, but it cannot be imposed upon a sophisticated market dependent on all types of derivative financial instruments without dire consequences.<P>

Hong Kongs slow and tortured journey towards eventual integration with China, which is slated to occur on June 30, 1997, began in 1982 when British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher announced that the British would not renew the 99 year lease currently binding Hong Kong to Britain.  In 1984, the two countries entered into the Sino-British Joint Declaration (the Joint Declaration), an international treaty which transfers sovereignty from Britain to China.<P>

The Joint Declaration mandates Hong Kongs status as a Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China.  In the Joint Declaration, China pledged to permit Hong Kong a high degree of autonomy for at least 50 years, hence the phrase, One Country, Two Systems attributed to Deng Xiaoping.  Hong Kong will legislate its own rules, covering all aspects of governance except for defense and foreign affairs.  Notwithstanding Chinas reservation of control in these two areas, Hong Kong will retain some autonomy in its foreign affairs.  It will, for instance, continue to represent itself in the World Trade Organization.  As such, Hong Kong will be able to maintain an international persona separate from China.<P>

The Joint Declaration also required China to distill the obligations enumerated therein into a form that would be enforceable domestically.  As a result, a mini-Constitution of 160 articles, known as the Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR (the Basic Law), was promulgated in 1990.  This law in essence codifies the terms of Hong Kongs self-rule.  Importantly, it also reiterates Chinas commitment to preserve, among other things, Hong Kongs common law judicial system.<P>

<strong>Guanxi vs. Common Law</strong><br>

It is widely agreed that the key to an orderly transition and the maintenance of Hong Kongs economic success lies in the preservation of Hong Kongs common law legal system.  <P>

The financial markets rely and thrive upon legal certainty  a nonexistent commodity in China.  Indeed, anyone doing business in China will encounter regulations so secret they cannot be put in writing, or poorly disguised bribery practices so entrenched that fixed prices for licenses or zoning permits are the rule rather than the exception.  <P>

Even detailed contractual provisions fail to afford adequate protection in this environment where precedent and recorded case law are unknown.  The whims of local officials dictate the interpretation and enforcement of rules and regulations, and it is not uncommon to find boilerplate language construed in different ways throughout the separate provinces.  Moreover, the system of guanxi is itself inherently unreliable.  No matter who a foreign investor knows, a competitor is likely to find a connection with someone of higher rank.  <P>

By contrast, Hong Kongs legal system developed along the lines of the common law promulgated by its colonial sovereign, England.  The system is transparent, providing a level playing field with predictable rules governing both civil and criminal matters.  The free market economy of Hong Kong is shored up by a firm legal tradition of defending due process, property and contract rights. <P>
 
Both the Joint Declaration and the Basic Law recognize the significance of Hong Kongs legal system.  Indeed, China has fully sanctioned future adherence to common law in Hong Kong, agreeing recently to the formation of a Court of Final Appeal which will sit in Hong Kong and take the place of Britains Privy Council.  However, China has imposed some limits.  China reserved the right to prevent the Court of Final Appeal from hearing any matters which can be considered acts of state.<P>

The lack of a clear definition of the term act of state is causing consternation in the financial community.  Many argue, correctly, that this loophole leaves much to the discretion of the government which may choose to interpret a wide variety of actions as acts of state.  Because it is impossible to predict Chinas behavior on this point, foreign investors must accept the risk that their actions in Hong Kong may be judged against Chinese legal principles.  But what is the level of this risk?<P>

Just as two systems will emerge as Hong Kong and China integrate, so are two schools of thought emerging with respect to the effect that integration will have on the business environment in Hong Kong.<P>

The optimists, including those whose businesses derive the majority of their profits from this financial center, long for a smooth transition.  These individuals hope that China will not upset the apple cart.  After all, the Mainlanders have much to gain, economically, and much to learn from the success story of Hong Kong.  The optimists are encouraged by what they consider to be Chinas commitment to the preservation of Hong Kongs common law system.<P>

Pessimists are quick to denounce the optimists as economic opportunists striving only to make the best of a dismal situation.  Pessimists point to Chinas historic intolerance of individual and economic freedoms and the tendency of government officials at every level to assert as much control as possible over enterprise.  These critics conclude that the financial atmosphere will be drastically changed if not wholly stymied by the transition, and urge businesses with a large presence in Hong Kong to diversify or retreat before June 30, 1997.<P>

Where does the truth lie?  Will China purposely subvert the common law system it has affirmatively agreed to preserve?  When dealing with the enigmatic China, the answer is anyones guess.  The great uncertainty surrounding Chinas internal stability makes predictions of Hong Kongs future all the more speculative.  Nevertheless, close analysis of the situation suggests that China will work towards preserving the integrity of Hong Kongs financial markets.  It is quite possible that, after an initial period of hesitancy, Hong Kongs financial and service markets will emerge from the integration as an even stronger economic force.<P>

<strong>The Golden Rice Bowl</strong><br>

In China, Hong Kong is commonly referred to as Chinas golden rice bowl.  It is well recognized that the colony, which has already been instrumental in the economic development of China, can enhance and expand capital and infrastructure investment to the degree necessary to make China an economic superpower.  As such, logic would dictate that it is in Chinas best interest to approach the impending integration of Hong Kong with a flexible attitude.  This overriding principle, coupled with the six factors enumerated below, suggest that China will work towards promoting Hong Kongs free economic market.<p>

<strong>Bloodless Revolution</strong><br>

Although integration will work a dramatic change in Hong Kongs governing structure, unlike in other former colonies, this revolution promises to be peaceful.  So far, China has acted with remarkable restraint as compared, for instance, to Indonesia in its bloody takeover of East Timor or to India in its seizure of Goa, both former Portuguese colonies.  China has pursued a decidedly mature approach to integration, and as such deserves some credit as we look into the future.<p>

<strong>Fundamental Bedrock</strong><br>

China has promised in writing to the United Nations that Hong Kong will continue to operate under its own rule of law for the next 50 years.  The border will remain closed and Hong Kong will maintain the right to formulate its own trade laws, monetary and financial policies, and to safeguard the free operation of its business and financial markets.  In addition, Hong Kong will be allowed to maintain its own currency.  The Hong Kong dollar will continue to be freely convertible, and foreign exchange, gold and securities markets will continue to operate.<P>

Further, Hong Kong will maintain its current set of liberal tax policies.  Beijing has agreed that it will not tax or otherwise attempt to extract revenue from Hong Kong.  In short, the systems currently in place, including the important regulatory and supervisory framework that has fostered Hong Kongs unprecedented history of economic growth will remain unchanged.

<strong>Track Record</strong><br>

While it would be foolhardy to take promises from the Chinese government at face value, the track record of the integration to date suggests that China is committed to a smooth transition.  The communist takeover of Hong Kong has been evolving for over a decade now, and during that decade Hong Kong has experienced double digit growth.  Indeed, even in the face of two potentially disastrous events, the Tiananmen massacre in 1989 and the Taiwan Straits incident of last March, the colonys financial market maintained a strong growth rate.  Many of the companies which fled Hong Kong in 1989 in response to the market-chilling massacre found themselves back in Hong Kong a year later, playing catch up with their brethren who decided to tough it out.<p>

<strong>The Taiwan Factor</strong><br>

While a smooth integration does not mean that Taiwan will come running back into the Chinese fold, a misstep by China at this time will entirely eliminate the opportunity for a peaceful reunion with the island nation.  Regardless of the designs China may have with respect to Taiwan, it would be unwise to jeopardize a chance for peaceful resolution, or even a mutually beneficial partnership with Taiwan by setting a bad example in Hong Kong.<p>

<strong>Economic Integration</strong><br>

China and Hong Kong are in large part already integrated economically.  Indeed, for many the political integration will be little more than a formalization of the economic realities that exist today.  Hong Kong has been instrumental in fueling Chinas economic growth.  It has provided a predictable, stable environment for Western business to build Asian headquarters.  Further, as the impressive Bank of China building symbolizes, Hong Kong has become a financial center for China as well.<P>

Hong Kong owes much of its wealth and power to its proximity to the cheap labor markets across the border in southern China and the multitude of major investment opportunities in the rest of China.  Hong Kong companies are investing enormous sums in infrastructure projects such as toll roads, power stations and urban development in China, ventures that will not begin to pay off until the next century.  Hong Kong investment in China totals over U.S. $60 billion, making it Chinas largest source of capital.<P>

Chinas commercial presence and influence in Hong Kongs trade, investment, finance and tourism industries have also been growing dramatically.  Over the last few years, Chinas capital investment in Hong Kong has grown to roughly U.S. $31 billion, and Hong Kong has become a prime destination for outgoing Chinese investment funds as well as for Chinese tourists.<p>

<strong>Chinas Revolution</strong><br>

Finally, China itself is rapidly transforming.  The Chinese economy has enjoyed unprecedented growth during the past decade.  Indeed, the economic transformation in China can be likened to the Industrial Revolution in 19th century Europe.  The xenophobic tendencies which gave rise to the Cultural Revolution are losing ground to pragmatic goals and realistic forecasts.  The Chinese have grown more open to suggestion and are willing to learn and to experiment.<P>

Indeed, China already looks to Hong Kong for guidance in financial and economic matters.  Shenzhen is one of Chinas most successful Special Economic Zones and operates with legislative autonomy.  It is not by coincidence that two-thirds of the laws enacted by the Shenzhen legislature have been borrowed from Hong Kong with the blessing of the Chinese central government.<p>

<strong>Speak Confidently but Carry a Foreign Passport</strong><br>

While the six factors discussed above suggest that China is committed to preserving Hong Kongs authority, the fact remains that the Chinese government has been dogged by corruption throughout its long history.  What if the pessimists are correct and guanxi replaces the common law as Hong Kongs market guide?  How can businesses protect themselves from the uncertainties of integration?<p>

<strong>Domicile</strong><br>

The first defense is to emulate the behavior of close to half of the companies that trade on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange: maintain legal status in a jurisdiction outside of Hong Kong such as Bermuda or the West Indies, in the event that quick flight is necessary.  Many companies are also setting up parallel offices in Singapore.  The key is not to abandon Hong Kong, but to set up protective barriers to protect your company from Chinese corruption.  Assets should remain out of the reach of the Chinese government and its local officials.<p>

<strong>Dispute Resolution</strong><br>

When contractual disputes have arisen in China, foreign companies have too often been forced to try to resolve issues by relying on guanxi rather than litigation.  While it is impossible to say how much of the tradition of guanxi and corruption will leak into Hong Kongs common law system, companies should protect their interests by contractually agreeing to have disputes resolved outside of China or Hong Kong.  American companies should, in particular, refrain from corruptive practices as such actions could lead to prosecution under the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (see, International Law Notes, December 1995).<p>

<strong>The Future</strong><br>

Will the uncertainties of a legal and financial system based on connections, or guanxi, replace the certain and settled rule of law that has nurtured Hong Kongs financial success?  It is impossible to say today.  However, it is safe to assume that Beijing recognizes, as one senior Chinese official put it, that you must understand what makes an item valuable in order to preserve it.  Hopefully, China will not discard or destroy its golden rice bowl.  It has great incentives to promote Hong Kong as it exists today, and it has shown a strong intent to preserve and maintain the status quo.<P>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to international business and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>
<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Michelle L.D. Hanlon at 612/336-3439 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:mhanlon@faegre.com">mhanlon@faegre.com</A>. <p>


