<TITLE>European Business Community Hails New Technology Transfer Block Exemption</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<H2>European Business Community Hails New Technology Transfer Block Exemption</H2>

<H4>By J&ouml;rg Rehder</H4>

The Commission of the European Community (the Commission) recently enacted a new Technology Transfer block exemption (the Technology Exemption) based on a first draft introduced nearly two years ago.  The Technology Exemption entered into effect on April 1, 1996.<p>

<strong>Block Exemptions Generally</strong><br>

Over the years the Commission has enacted several block exemptions.  Block exemptions are safe harbor regulations pursuant to which the Commission will exempt certain arrangements from the anti-trust laws of the European Union (EU).  The primary benefit of a block exemption is that, if parties satisfy its conditions, they can avoid the often time-consuming and expensive procedure of individually notifying the Commission of intended arrangements; instead, they can rely on a block exemption.  Block exemptions also benefit parties in that they are public declarations on what clauses conflict with EU anti-trust laws.<P>

Block exemptions apply either to certain types of agreements or to agreements in a specific industry.  Two examples are the exemption governing distribution agreements and the exemption governing motor vehicle distribution and servicing agreements.  The block exemptions most relevant to this article are the Patent License Agreement exemption (Patent Exemption) and the Know-How License Agreement exemption (Know-How Exemption).  These two exemptions have been combined in the newly-enacted Technology Exemption.<p>

<strong>Effect of Technology Exemption</strong><br>

The stated purpose of the block exemption is to encourage the dissemination of technical knowledge in the [EU] and to promote the manufacture of technically more sophisticated products.  This goal is met by allowing parties to enter into certain types of technology transfer arrangements which would otherwise violate EU anti-trust laws.  Whether a certain clause is permissible depends on whether it is classified as a white, black or gray clause. These terms, though  not part of the Commissions official language, are commonly used by EU practitioners and in EU literature.<P>

To better understand the impact of these classifications, it is necessary to quickly discuss the lay out of EU anti-trust laws.
<p>

<strong>European Union Anti-Trust Laws</strong><br>

Articles 85 and 86 of the Treaty of Rome are the primary provisions regarding antitrust law at the EU level.  Article 86 is not pertinent for purposes of this article as it discusses the abuse of dominant market positions.<P>

Article 85 is divided into three parts.  The first, Article 85(1), prohibits agreements and other actions which may restrict competition in the EU.  For practitioners familiar with U.S.  anti-trust law, this section is comparable to primary provisions of the Sherman Anti-Trust Act.<P>

Different from U.S.  law, however, is the enforcement principles of the EU.  While the United States has adopted a rule of reason approach, the EU does not use such a balancing test.  Instead, Article 85(2) states that agreements which violate Article 85(1) are automatically void.  Article 85(3) defuses the rigidity of Article 85(2) by providing that Article 85(1) may not apply to certain agreements or actions if inter alia they benefit consumers.  Such arrangements may be exempt from Article 85(1).<P>

Those doing business in Europe should be aware that certain other avenues also exist which allow parties to avoid Article 85(1).  Probably the most common is the Notice on Agreements of Minor Importance.  Under this notice, the parties need not notify the Commission of a certain agreement if (i) it concerns less than 5% of the relevant market, and (ii) the parties combined annual aggregate revenue is less than 300 million ECU ($370 million).  Though this notice does not have the same legislative weight as a block exemption, it does provide parties with some comfort that the Commission will not review an arrangement where the parties meet the conditions of the notice.  The Commission views arrangements between smaller parties as having a negligible impact on competition, and thus, does not require notification.<p>

<strong>Classification of Clauses</strong><br>

The <a href="ib8white.html">white list</a> contains clauses which do not fall within the ambit of Article 85(1).  Contrary to what the name may indicate, the <a href="ib8black.html">black list</a> does not contain clauses which are automatically void, instead, if parties want to ensure that an arrangement which includes black-list clauses does not conflict with Article 85(1), they must notify it to the Commission for clearance.  A block exemption cannot apply to a clause on a black list.<P>

Finally, because these lists do not include all types of arrangements, the Commission has implemented an opposition procedure for arrangements not specifically mentioned in the exemption (the so-called <a href="ib8gray.html">gray list</a>).  At the parties initiative, they must obtain an individual exemption for any questionable arrangements to ensure that the Commission will not later void the arrangement and possibly subject the parties to a fine.  The opposition procedure is such that if the Commission does not oppose the arrangement for four months after notification, it is exempt.  To indicate the Commissions desire to further facilitate the transfer of technology, it shortened the opposition procedure from six months (as was the case in the Patent and Know-How Exemptions) to four months in the Technology Exemption.<p>

<strong>Amendment to Draft Technology Exemption</strong><br>

The European business community originally considered the Technology Exemption too unyielding.  The draft was written so that the exemption would not apply if an arrangement between parties would prevent competition; according to the language of the draft, this would in particular occur where the licensees market share exceed[ed] 40%.  This specific clause drew heavy criticism as the European business community believed that far too many agreements would unnecessarily need to go through the notification process, thereby causing a stifling effect on business.<P>

As a compromise, the Commission changed the wording of the exemption.  The final version of the Technology Exemption states that the Commission will pay special attention to cases where the licensee has more than 40% of the market (emphasis added).  Of course, only time will tell to what extent the Commission will pay special attention to certain arrangements.  Judging from statements made by European business leaders, they expect the Commission to adhere to the spirit of the exemption, i.e., to withdraw the exemption only if an arrangement actually impedes competition.<p>

<strong>Scope of Technology Exemption</strong><br>

The Technology Exemption does not apply to all patent and know-how licensing agreements within the EU.  The scope of the exemption is limited to agreements where the licensee either manufactures or is responsible for the manufacture of the licensed goods (if the subject of the agreement is a service, the licensee must either provide the services or be responsible for their provision).  Excluded from the Technology Exemption are franchise agreements, license agreements solely for the purpose of the sale of goods or services and joint venture agreements between competitors.<P>

Though the Commission backed off from its original intent of requiring notification for all technology transfer agreements where the licensee has a 40% market share, it expressly reserved the right not to afford parties the benefits of the exemption if an arrangement has anti-competitive effects.  Situations which may cause the Commission to withdraw the benefits of the exemption include: (i) refusing to fill unsolicited orders from within the territory of other licensees, (ii) making it difficult for buyers to obtain the licensed product from other European sellers, or (iii) prohibiting the licensee from using the technology of the licensors competitors when the licensor and licensee are in competition with one another.  <p>

<strong>Continued Applicability of Patent Exemption and Know-How Exemption</strong><br>

Though the Technology Exemption combines the Patent Exemption and the Know-How Exemption, they are not totally without effect.  The former was to have expired on December 31, 1994 (it was extended through March 31, 1996, to allow for the enactment of the new exemption), while the latter was to remain in effect through the end of 1999.  Since a large number of parties relied, and continue to rely, on exemptions granted under these regulations, the Commission has provided for a transition period.  Any exemptions granted prior to March 31, 1996, under one of these two exemptions may continue in effect until 2006.<P>

Since the Technology Exemption does not distinguish between patents and know-how, parties may incur difficulties when trying to determine whether their arrangement falls within the reach of the new exemption.  Failure to analyze the exemption correctly may cause the Commission to declare an arrangement void; it also risks the possibility that the Commission will levy a fine against the parties for violating EU anti-trust laws.  Companies engaged in the licensing of patents or know-how should analyze their arrangement carefully to avoid such an occurrence.  
<P>

<em> This article is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to international business and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this article.</EM><p>
<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact J&ouml;rg Rehder at 612/336-3445 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:jrehder@faegre.com">jrehder@faegre.com</A>. <p>


