<HEAD>
<TITLE> Harbor Maintenance Tax Refunds for U.S. Exporters </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Harbor Maintenance Tax Refunds for U.S. Exporters</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Michael E. Murphy</h4>

If your company has exported products by ocean freight at any time since April 1, 1987, it may be entitled to a refund of a Harbor Maintenance Tax ("HMT") to which all waterborne exports have been subjected since that date.
The U.S. Court of International Trade recently ruled in U.S. Shoe Corp. v. United States that the 0.125% ad valorem HMT is unconstitutional as it violates Article I, Section 9, Clause 5 of the U.S. Constitution, which prohibits the government from imposing taxes on exports.<P>

Congress enacted the HMT in 1987, ostensibly to raise revenues specifically earmarked for the maintenance of U.S. harbors.
In fact, the revenues raised by this tax have substantially exceeded the sums required to maintain the harbors.
As a result, the Treasury has accumulated some $700 million in excess of reasonable reserves for harbor maintenance -- the excess revenues have been used for other purposes.
The Court found that the HMT was more than merely a tax on users of harbors to fund the maintenance of those harbors; rather, the Court held, it was an export tax for general revenue raising purposes.
Such a tax violates Article I of the Constitution.<P>

If your company has been involved in waterborne exports at any time since April 1, 1987, and you wish to make a refund claim to recover HMT imposed on your company, our Firm's International Business Law Group would be happy to advise and assist you.<P>

<h4>Questions</h4>

If you have any questions, please contact Michael E. Murphy by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:mmurphy@faegre.com"><EM>mmurphy@faegre.com</EM></A>.<p>

<h4>Go to:</h4>
