<HEAD>
<TITLE> Foreign Joint Ventures:  Selected Corporate, Tax and Regulatory Issues </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Foreign Joint Ventures:  Selected Corporate, Tax and Regulatory Issues</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Michael E. Murphy</h4>
<p>


For companies with limited financial and human resources, the joint venture can be an ideal vehicle for developing foreign markets for the company's goods or services.  Normally, a company will consider a joint venture after it has reached three conclusions:  (1) export sales or market research indicate that a significant market exists in a foreign country or area of the world; (2) the use of foreign sales representatives or distributors is limiting development of the market because the representatives or distributors divide their time and resources among several product lines, suppliers and countries or seek high margins rather than market share; and (3) the company either lacks or cannot allocate sufficient financial resources and personnel with international business capabilities to develop the foreign markets.  The two most common forms of international joint venture are the contract joint venture and the corporate joint venture.  

<P>

<H4>Contract Joint Venture
</H4>
The contract joint venture is an arrangement made directly between the U.S. company and its foreign partner rather than through a third party vehicle, such as a jointly owned corporation.  The contract joint venture is often used where the proposed joint enterprise has discrete characteristics, such as a single construction project or the pooling of technologies and know-how for the development of a product which the parties intend to manufacture and market separately for antitrust or other business reasons.  The contract joint venture may also be used where the parties, who may not know one another well and do not wish to be tied together through a mutual investment in a corporation, may wish to make a quick, clean exit from the joint venture.  The contract joint venture, if properly structured, can be a relatively simple vehicle through which to enter and exit a joint venture.

<P>
		
This type of joint venture has three potentially significant disadvantages.  First, the parties to the joint venture will be directly responsible for any torts, breaches of contract or violations of government regulations resulting from their joint business enterprise; whereas, the interposition of a corporate joint venture vehicle, if properly structured, will insulate the parties and their personnel from these and other liabilities arising from the activities of the joint venture enterprise.  Secondly, the parties to a contract joint venture directly incur expenses and realize income associated with their joint enterprise.  This can limit the parties' options when it comes to tax planning, use of credit facilities, and reporting to shareholders.  Third, a contract joint venture may lack the air of permanence and commitment associated with the creation of a legal entity, which may be detrimental in the market.

<P>

<H4>Corporate Joint Venture</H4>

The corporate joint venture is the more common vehicle for an international joint venture because it provides the parties with an additional layer of insulation from liability and wider latitude for accounting and tax planning.  Moreover, a corporate joint venture can be a powerful marketing tool for the party whose name it bears.  For example, if Abco Inc., a U.S. company, forms a corporate joint venture with a minority shareholder in Germany and the company is called Abco GmbH, Abco can advertise in the United States, Germany and elsewhere abroad that it has direct operations of its own in Europe, thereby enhancing the public image of its size and stability.

<P>
		
A U.S. company will often find a foreign joint venture partner in its local distributor, in circumstances where both parties have come to realize that the foreign market for the U.S. company's products or services is significant and that the foreign market cannot be further developed without the distributor's full-time attention.  The distributor, who will be committing itself to the U.S. supplier, will often want an equity participation in the venture in return for its commitment.  Conversely, the U.S. company will need and want local participation in the venture; the foreign distributor will be welcomed for its investment, for its knowledge of the local market and for its foreign language skills and understanding of the local culture.  Because the parties are known quantities to each other due to their pre-existing supplier-distributor relationship, and because they both see a long term future for the U.S. company's products or services in the foreign market, the corporate form of joint venture is usually desired.  

<P>

<H4>Joint Ventures in Civil Code 
Jurisdictions</H4>
		
The vast majority of foreign countries in which American companies may be forming joint ventures will be countries that have legal systems based on European civil codes.  Corporations in civil code countries have historically been required to have two or more shareholders.  Under  civil code systems, the corporation exists by reason of an agreement between two or more persons to pool resources for a common business enterprise.  By contrast, in the U.S. it is the issuance of a certificate of incorporation by the Secretary of State of the state in which a corporation is formed that evidences the existence of a corporation.  Thus, the concept of a corporation with a single shareholder has never been an anomaly in our legal system.  In the European Union, the corporate laws of the member countries have been revised to allow single-shareholder corporations as a result of harmonization directives adopted in the 1980s.

<P>
		
All of this should be of more than academic interest to the American company with an investment in a joint venture corporation in a civil code jurisdiction.  Frequently, the joint venture agreement will provide the American party with an option to purchase its foreign partner's shares in the joint venture company.  If such an option exists and is exercised, the American party will need to be prepared to nominate a second or qualifying shareholder if the joint venture company is formed under the laws of a civil code jurisdiction that requires more than one shareholder.  The Brazilian limitada is one popular example.

<P>

<H4>Government Controls</H4>
		
Foreign host country controls restricting in-bound foreign direct investment have been largely dismantled in most countries over the past decade.  However, certain developed countries continue to require government permission for investment in or control over local business operations.  Some of these countries are becoming increasingly popular venues for foreign joint ventures by U.S. companies.  India is an example.  

<P>

With the break-up of the Soviet Union, Indian trading and investment policy has made a marked turn toward the West.  India continues to maintain, however, an in-bound direct investment control regime which U.S. companies need to take into account when planning a joint venture there. 

<P>

In general, foreign direct investment into India requires the approval of both the Reserve Bank of India and the Foreign Investment Promotion Board.  Investment in so-called priority sectors is eligible for automatic approval of up to 51 percent foreign equity ownership, provided the foreign equity meets foreign exchange requirements for imported capital goods and the foreign investor complies with guidelines relating to lump sum and royalty payments.  Priority sectors include industries relating to electrical, transportation and industrial equipment, chemicals, drugs and pharmaceuticals and numerous other sectors designated as such in Annex III of the New Industrial Policy, 1991 issued by the Indian Government.  In non-priority sectors (including most consumer goods), the permissible level of foreign equity ownership is determined on a case-by-case basis.  For export-oriented units, foreign ownership as high as 100 percent has been permitted.

<P>
		
It is commonplace today for the smaller, cash-poor but technology-rich U.S. company to use the foreign joint venture as a vehicle to produce and distribute products abroad as a means of sustaining itself, for example, pending FDA approval of its medical products.  This is particularly the case with emerging medical device companies.  Such companies can be lured into capitalizing the foreign joint venture company by transferring to it their technologies in exchange for a share in the equity of the joint venture company.  However, this could prove a costly method of capitalizing the company.  U.S. tax law allows the IRS to treat transfers of intangible property by U.S. companies to their foreign affiliates as a licensing arrangement for federal tax purposes with the effect of requiring the U.S. transferor, several years after the transfer in question, to pay substantial U.S. income taxes on a stream of royalty earnings which the U.S. company in fact never receives.  U.S. companies with foreign joint venture partners need to pay careful attention to other U.S. and foreign tax rules governing the pricing of goods and services between international affiliates.  

<P>

<H4>Entering Foreign Markets</H4>

If properly structured, however, the corporate joint venture vehicle can provide the U.S. party with the flexibility of either expanding or contracting its investment with relatively few legal complications.  With an option in the hands of the U.S. party to purchase some or all of its foreign partner's shares in the joint venture company, the U.S. party has the flexibility to expand its foreign direct investment in the host country.  With provisions in the joint venture agreement permitting the U.S. party to sell its shares in the joint venture company to its foreign partner, or with other provisions establishing criteria under which the foreign partner will assume responsibilities for the facilities and personnel accumulated in the joint venture company, the U.S. party can have an economical exit strategy as well.  The joint venture can be the ideal vehicle for smaller and medium-sized companies with limited financial and human resources to enter foreign markets where there is strong potential for the company's goods or services.

<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Michael E. Murphy by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:mmurphy@faegre.com"><EM>mmurphy@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


<HR>

