<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Transfer Pricing and the Use of Advance Pricing Agreements
in Germany and the United States </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Transfer Pricing and the Use of Advance Pricing Agreements
in Germany and the United States</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>J&ouml;rg Rehder</h4>
<p>


A 1995 Ernst & Young study indicated that approximately 50 percent of multinational corporations (MNCs) believe that transfer pricing is the most significant international tax issue they face.  Considering that the issue perceived to be the second most important  tax rates in other countries  garnered only 7 percent of the vote, this study clearly indicates what is on the minds of tax planners and advisors of MNCs.  Because most countries continue to devote more money and personnel to investigate potential transfer price abuses, MNCs will undoubtedly need to continue to focus their attention on this issue.  

<P>

<H4>Contract Joint Venture
</H4>

As tax authorities step up their enforcement measures, and the number of time-consuming and expensive audits continues to rise, MNCs are seeking an alternative which will allow them to devote fewer resources to remaining in compliance with transfer pricing regulations.  At the same time, tax authorities in many jurisdictions are looking for a way to conduct their transfer pricing enforcement measures more efficiently.  One such alternative is to enter into an Advance Pricing Agreement (APA).  An APA is an agreement between an MNC taxpayer and one or more tax authorities which binds the parties to a transfer pricing method for transactions over a fixed period.  The parties negotiate the agreement prior to the transactions in issue.

<P>
		
This article will briefly outline the increased enforcement measures undertaken by two countries  Germany and the United States  and then discuss what impact these measures have had on the use of APAs in these countries.

<P>

The corporate joint venture is the more common vehicle for an international joint venture because it provides the parties with an additional layer of insulation from liability and wider latitude for accounting and tax planning.  Moreover, a corporate joint venture can be a powerful marketing tool for the party whose name it bears.  For example, if Abco Inc., a U.S. company, forms a corporate joint venture with a minority shareholder in Germany and the company is called Abco GmbH, Abco can advertise in the United States, Germany and elsewhere abroad that it has direct operations of its own in Europe, thereby enhancing the public image of its size and stability.

<P>

<H4>Global Tax War</H4>	
	
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) has issued guidelines recommending to its members how to combat alleged transfer pricing abuses.  The OECD most recently amended its guidelines on July 27, 1995.  The three primary transfer methods discussed in the OECD guidelines are as follows: 

<P>

(i)	Comparable Uncontrolled Price Method  comparing the price actually charged to an affiliated company with the price which would be charged in a similar transaction with an unrelated buyer;

(ii)	Resale Price Method  subtracting the buyer's normal profit margin from the actual sales price to an unrelated buyer in a similar transaction; or

(iii)	Cost Plus Method  adding the costs of the seller to the profit normally realized by the seller ina similar transaction with an unrelated buyer.

<P>
		
Each of these methods is based on the principle that transactions between affiliated companies should be priced on an arm's length basis, i.e., the affiliated parties should structure their transactions as if they were not related.  In those instances where a comparable transaction does not exist, the parties may use another appropriate method consistent with the principle of an arm's length transaction.  The arm's length standard is codified in regulations promulgated under § 482 of the Internal Revenue Code in the United States and in § 1 of the International Tax Act (Außensteuergesetz) in Germany.  The transfer pricing regulations in the United States and Germany are based on the OECD's guidelines.  Failure to implement one of these pricing methods in Germany or the United States will draw the attention of the respective tax authorities and increase the likelihood of an audit.

<P>

<H4>Transfer Pricing in the United States and Germany</H4>
		
The United States was the first country to pursue transfer pricing abuses  aggressively.  Beginning with the Tax Reform Act of 1986, and continuing with the IRS's and Treasury Department's joint publication of the White Paper on Transfer Pricing two years later, the U.S. appropriated more funds and increased the size of staffs to better oversee MNCs' transfer pricing compliance.  Consequently, tax authorities reviewed tax returns more extensively, investigated potential transfer pricing abuses more thoroughly and imposed stiffer penalties for transfer pricing violations.  This effort had a domino effect in other parts of the world as other countries soon recognized that their respective tax bases would suffer if they did not follow the American example.  Germany was one of these countries. 

<P>

	
German tax authorities became more aware of transfer price abuses as they stepped up their investigatory measures.  Since 1990, the Finanz-ämter (German tax administrators) have made a concerted effort to increase their enforcement measures at both the state and federal levels.  The result has been clear  more German companies have been the subject of audits, at both the parent and the subsidiary levels. 

<P>

Evidence that German tax authorities have cracked down on transfer price abuses can be seen from a case before Germany's highest tax court (Bundesfinanzhof) in 1993, one of the few transfer pricing cases heard by this court.  The court adjusted the profits of a newly-formed German company after concluding that the company's pricing method for penetrating the German market was not comparable to that of other companies, i.e., it failed to adhere to the arm's length principle.  Instead of passing on some of the market penetration costs to its affiliated Danish companies, the German company assumed all such costs.  After investigating this arrangement, the court held it was not reasonable for a company to assume 100 percent of the market penetration costs knowing that it would not realize a profit within a reasonable time if it continued doing business in such a manner.

<P>

<H4>Advance Pricing Agreements</H4>

It is commonplace today for the smaller, cash-poor but technology-rich U.S. company to use the foreign joint venture as a vehicle to produce and distribute products abroad as a means of sustaining itself, for example, pending FDA approval of its medical products.  This is particularly the case with emerging medical device companies.  Such companies can be lured into capitalizing the foreign joint venture company by transferring to it their technologies in exchange for a share in the equity of the joint venture company.  However, this could prove a costly method of capitalizing the company.  U.S. tax law allows the IRS to treat transfers of intangible property by U.S. companies to their foreign affiliates as a licensing arrangement for federal tax purposes with the effect of requiring the U.S. transferor, several years after the transfer in question, to pay substantial U.S. income taxes on a stream of royalty earnings which the U.S. company in fact never receives.  U.S. companies with foreign joint venture partners need to pay careful attention to other U.S. and foreign tax rules governing the pricing of goods and services between international affiliates.  

<P>

One world-wide consequence of these increased efforts has been the advent of Advance Pricing Agreements (APAs).  MNCs hoped that APAs would lead to the predictability of tax liabilities and the avoidance of double taxation, while tax authorities hoped APAs would lead to a decrease in transfer price abuses.

<P>

In 1991 the IRS published a revenue procedure consisting of guidelines to enter into an APA.  The procedural ruling departed from prior IRS policy in that, in the past, the IRS had been reluctant to enter into agreements based largely on projections rather than facts.

<P>
	
The IRS changed its position regarding APAs primarily in response to the increased complexity of transactions and corporate structures and the realization that it did not have the resources to complete as many audits as would otherwise be necessary.  Some corporate taxpayers also welcomed the opportunity to enter into APAs as legislative amendments heightened their concern that they were violating transfer pricing rules, and therefore, subject to possible adjustments and penalties.  Further, many foreign corporations doing business in the United States were fearful that they were not meeting the extensive IRS reporting requirements and were subjecting themselves to potential penalties.  (Because the parties negotiate APAs with the relevant tax authority prior to the transactions, foreign corporations can be certain they are in compliance with all tax-related reporting requirement once they enter into an APA with the IRS.)

<P>

<H4>Use of APAs in the United States</H4>
	
Corporations in the United States initially viewed APAs with skepticism  due in large part to a fear of the unknown.  Few companies were willing to be the first to test the waters to determine whether APAs would be as effective as hoped.  Companies feared that if an APA was not concluded after negotiations had already been initiated, they would only increase their odds of being audited as they would have disclosed information to the IRS that they would otherwise not have disclosed.  Nevertheless, an astounding 96 percent of the American respondents to Ernst & Young's survey stated that they believed that the use of APAs would continue to grow.

<P>	

Apple Computers, having been the subject of several transfer pricing adjustments, was the first U.S. company to enter into an APA when it came to terms with U.S. and Australian tax authorities.  Apple has since also entered into APAs with tax authorities in Canada and Japan.  Citing the avoidance of potential double taxation and the advantage of predictability of tax liability, Apple has expressed satisfaction with its APAs.

<P>

<H4>Use of APAs in Germany</H4>
	

Though the future for APAs looks bright in the United States, this is not the case in Germany.  According to Ernst & Young's survey, only 68 percent of the German respondents stated that they believed the use of APAs will grow.  (Only French respondents were less confident about APAs  only 64 percent of French MNCs believed that the use of APAs would increase.)  A resounding 24 percent of the German respondents believed that the use of APAs would not increase.  (Germany was the leader in this category.)

<P>
	
Much of this wariness stems from German tax authorities' stance toward APAs.  German tax authorities have adopted a wait-and-see approach to see how APAs are received in other countries before committing resources to such agreements.

<P>
	
Not only do German tax authorities not favor the use of APAs in their home jurisdiction, they also view foreign APAs with some reservation.  According to a strongly worded announcement by the tax authorities of the state of Baden-Württemberg, tax authorities in that state should not feel compelled to honor the terms of a unilateral APA if it would have an adverse impact on Germany's tax base.  The announcement states that unilateral APAs are subject to review and to a possible adjustment.  Germany's federal tax authority, as well as the Finanzämter of Germany's other states, supported this announcement.

<P>	

If a taxpayer does not agree with a transfer pricing adjustment, it may initiate a review procedure pursuant to the Principles Relating to the Review of Income Allocation of International Affiliated Corporations (Grundsätze für die Prüfung der Einkünftsabgrenzung bei international verbundenen Unternehmen).  These Principles, which are actually the Federal Ministry of Finance's interpretation of Germany's transfer pricing rules, call for a review of disputed adjustments.  Such a review procedure can be comparable to a full-fledged audit.

<P>
	
Companies in the United States with affiliated German companies should be careful when entering into an APA which is also to have an impact in Germany.  If information shared with the IRS during the APA negotiations is not also shared with German tax authorities (with the approval of the company), and the German tax authorities determine that their tax base was not sufficiently considered during negotiations with the IRS, companies can be quite certain that German tax authorities will review the APA with great scrutiny and possibly demand an adjustment and penalties.

<P>

<H4>Use of APAs in Other 
Jurisdictions</H4>
	
Bilateral or multilateral APAs are far more likely to reduce the risk of double taxation than are unilateral APAs.  For this reason, they are preferable to unilateral APAs.  Many jurisdictions have expressed a favorable attitude towards entering into such agreements.  These jurisdictions include the United States, Canada, the Netherlands, Japan and the United Kingdom.  France and Germany have shown the greatest reluctance to enter into APAs, whether bilateral or unilateral.
	
<P>

When pursuing an APA, a company should keep the following points in mind:

<UL>
<LI>It should be prepared to cooperate with tax authorities in terms of disclosing financial information to be able to present convincingly its intended transfer pricing methodology.
<LI>It can buttress its arguments if it can also provide tax authorities with data concerning the industry and countries to be covered by the APA.
<LI>It should be able to identify uncontrolled transactions similar to the transactions to be covered by the APA.
<LI>It should request confirmation from the tax authorities that no transfer pricing adjustments will be made so long as the company complies with the terms of the APA.
<LI>An escape clause should be included in each APA to cover those circumstances where economic conditions change significantly, thereby allowing the company to change its transfer pricing methodology.
<LI>Prior to entering into negotiations with tax authorities, a company should request that the tax authorities keep the disclosed information confidential.
</UL>

<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact J&ouml;rg Rehder by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:jrehder@faegre.com"><EM>jrehder@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


