<HEAD>
<TITLE> Japan Adopts Product Liability Law </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Japan Adopts Product Liability Law</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Richard Y. Sako</h4>
<p>


After many years of debate, the Japanese Parliament approved and adopted a Product Liability Law (PL Law) in the summer of 1994.  The new law took effect on July 1, 1995.  The PL Law is modeled on its EU counterpart, which is generally regarded as being less stringent than U.S. product liability law.  

<P>

Under the PL Law, manufacturers, processors and importers are liable for damages caused by defects in any product which they have manufactured, processed or imported.  The PL Law does not cover cases in which a contract exists directly between a consumer and a manufacturer, such as in the case of the purchase of newly developed housing lots and the construction of new homes.  Nor does the PL Law  apply to services and agricultural and animal products.  Claims for compensation of damages under the PL Law are subject to a statute of limitation of (i)  the longer of three years after the victim or its legal representative becomes aware of the damage and the identity of the party responsible for the damage, and (ii)  ten years after the manufacturer, processor or importer delivered the product.

<P>

The PL Law has been criticized by consumer groups in Japan and the Japanese Bar Association in three principal respects:

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Under the PL Law, a plaintiff must prove that the product was defective at the time it was first placed for sale rather than at the time of occurrence of the injury.
<LI>Under the PL Law, the plaintiff has the burden of proving that the product was defective.  Consumer groups lobbied strongly for inclusion of an inference clause which would classify a product as defective if an accident occurs while the plaintiff was using the product correctly.  This clause was not adopted.
<LI>Under the PL Law, a manufacturer, processor or importer is not liable for a product defect if the defect was not foreseeable given the level of scientific or technological knowledge in existence at the time the product was delivered.  Consumer groups had argued that the level of knowledge should be the highest scientific and technological level available to a standard manufacturer as opposed to the average standard of knowledge of technology in the industry.
</UL>


<P>

Consumer groups maintain that the absence of an inference clause and the requirement that the plaintiff prove that the product in question was defective when initially offered for sale substantially weakens the impact of the law because the absence of pre-trial discovery in Japan and limited access to corporate records create very high problems of proof.  Notwithstanding such criticism, the PL Law appears to have accomplished its initial goal of making product safety a leading concern of manufacturers selling in Japan.  For example, manufacturers of toys and stationary products are reevaluating their products based on child safety concerns and have taken such measures as eliminating small pieces that children may choke on or coating pieces with bitter tasting resins to keep them out of children's mouths.  Manufacturers' associations have also conducted studies of European and U.S. products, which are generally recognized as being more advanced in the area of product safety, and have published guidelines available to manufacturers to assist them in making their products safer.  For example, the Japanese frozen food association has published guidelines on product labeling requirements based on its review of food product labels currently in use by European and U.S. food manufacturers.

<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Richard Y. Sako by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:rsako@faegre.com"><EM>rsako@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


<HR>

