<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Recent Changes to English Sales Laws </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Recent Changes to English Sales Laws</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Derek S. Devgun</h4>

Recent significant changes have been made to English laws governing contracts for the sale of goods.  Given that the United Kingdom has not implemented the U.N. Convention on Contracts for the International Sale of Goods into its domestic law, these changes are important for parties whose contracts are to be governed by English law whether by election of the parties or because English law is the proper law of the contract.

<P>

The Sale and Supply of Goods Act 1994 (the 1994 Act) came into force on January 3, 1995, and applies to all contracts for the sale of goods made on or after that date.  The 1994 Act amends the Sale of Goods Act 1979 (the 1979 Act) and related statutes, in an attempt to clarify certain antiquated provisions of the 1979 Act and to update and strengthen the rights of consumers.  The 1994 Act essentially implements the conclusions of Law Commissions contained in reports published in 1987 which recommended changes to the 1979 Act.

<H4>Warranty of 
Satisfactory Quality</H4>

Perhaps the major change adopted under the 1994 Act is the replacement of the concept of the implied warranty of merchantability with one of satisfactory quality.  English courts had interpreted the phrase merchantability to mean that the major factor relevant in deciding whether goods were merchantable was the fitness of the goods for their purpose.  Other characteristics were largely irrelevant, and the exact extent to which minor and cosmetic defects were to be taken into account was unclear.

<P>

The new standard, satisfactory quality, requires that the goods meet the standard that a reasonable person would regard as satisfactory, taking account of any description of the goods, the price (if relevant) and all other relevant circumstances.  This test involves a broader inquiry into the quality of the goods in question, and expressly requires that the following factors be considered when assessing breach of warranty:  fitness for purpose, appearance and finish, freedom from minor defects, safety and durability.

<P>

Like the former warranty of merchantability, the new implied warranty of satisfactory quality may be excluded by express agreement.  Where English law applies to the contract only because the parties elect it by express choice, the parties may exclude the warranty unconditionally.  Where English law would apply to the contract under choice-of-law rules, however, exclusion of the warranty must meet a standard of reasonableness.

<H4>Acceptance</H4>

The 1994 Act also amends the 1979 Act by requiring that a buyer be given a reasonable opportunity to inspect goods before a buyer accepts, or is deemed to have accepted, the goods.

<P>

The basic rule remains that acceptance of goods will be deemed to occur when (i) a buyer intimates acceptance to the seller, or (ii) the seller delivers the goods and the buyer engages in any action which is inconsistent with the seller's ownership of the goods.  However, in either case, the buyer must have had a reasonable opportunity to examine the goods before a buyer can be deemed to have accepted the goods.  Furthermore, mere delivery by the buyer to a third party under a re-sale or other disposition does not necessarily imply acceptance by the buyer.

<P>

The other method of acceptance in the 1979 Act, the lapse of a reasonable time, is also retained.  However, the availability to the buyer of an opportunity to inspect the goods is one factor to be taken into account in determining whether a reasonable time has elapsed.

<H4>Right of Partial Rejection</H4>

The 1994 Act also introduces a new concept into English sales law, the right of a buyer to reject part of a shipment of goods.  Under the 1979 Act, a buyer either had to reject the entire shipment or accept the entire shipment and claim damages from the seller.  After the 1994 Act, the buyer is entitled to accept those goods in good condition and reject the rest.  The right to reject the entire shipment remains unaffected by these changes.

<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Derek Devgun by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:ddevgun@faegre.com"><EM>ddevgun@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


<HR>

Last changed 1-Jan-96<p>

