<HEAD>
<TITLE> London Stock 
Exchange - New
Market to be Launched </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>London Stock 
Exchange - New
Market to be Launched</H2>

On February 15, 1995, the London Stock Exchange published its rules for the Alternative Investment Market (AIM). It has been specially created to meet the needs of smaller and growing companies seeking to raise public finance in the United Kingdom and to have their shares more widely traded.  AIM has been widely reported in the media as being based on the highly successful NASDAQ market familiar to readers in the United States.
	
<p>

It is intended that AIM be launched on June 19, 1995, but applications to join it may be submitted as soon as the Public Offers of Securities Regulations have been published.  This is expected to occur shortly.  They will replace Part III of the Companies Act 1985 (with Part V of the Financial Services Act 1986 no longer coming into force) and will contain the statutory requirements for the publication of prospectuses by unlisted companies.
	
<p>

Following the introduction of AIM, the Unlisted Securities Market (which is no longer accepting new members) will be abolished next year.  At that time, companies on the Unlisted Securities Market must join either AIM or move up to the Official List of the London Stock Exchange.  The latter is primarily for larger companies with a trading record of at least three years.  In contrast to the Official List, which requires that at least 25% of a company's shares be publicly held, AIM will not require a minimum number of shares to be publicly held.
	
<p>

The occasional dealing facility under Rule 4.2 of the Rules of the Stock Exchange (previously referred to as the Rule 535 facility), under which the shares of certain companies may be traded on a matched bargains basis, will disappear in its current form.  The Stock Exchange has said that when AIM opens, Rule 4.2 will be amended to apply only to suspended securities, although it has indicated that it may operate a very occasional dealing facility, but on a highly restricted basis.
	
<p>

In order for a company to be included in AIM it must meet the following requirements:<BR>

<OL TYPE=i, ii, iii, ...>

<LI>It must have a nominated adviser and a nominated broker.  The adviser will assist in the admission procedure to AIM and ensure that the company complies with the Stock Exchange's requirements.  The adviser's role is similar to that of the sponsor for admission to the Official List.  The adviser must be drawn from a register of approved advisers maintained by the Stock Exchange.  The broker must be a member of the Stock Exchange.  The broker will promote trading in the shares of the company by using its best efforts to match buyers and sellers of the company's shares and by providing information to the market via SEATS PLUS (the service on which AIM securities are to be traded).<br>
<LI>The company must be legally established under the laws of the country of incorporation as a public company.<br>
<LI>It must have published accounts that conform to the generally accepted accounting principles of either the United Kingdom or the United States or to international accounting standards.<br>
<LI>The securities to be traded on AIM must be freely transferable.<br>
<LI>The company must adopt a code for Directors' dealings with regard to acquiring or disposing of securities, as provided in AIM's rules.<br>
</OL>


<p>

AIM's admission rules provide that if the company has been generating revenue for less than two years, the directors and employees must agree not to sell their interests in the company's shares for at least a year from the date of admission to AIM.  However, AIM will not place any limitations on companies with regard to level of capitalization, length of trading record or the number of publicly held shares.

<p>

An application to AIM must be supported by a prospectus (Admission Document).  The Admission Document will need to comply with the Public Offers of Securities Regulations as well as the rules of AIM.  Included in the Admission Document will be information such as a description of the securities and the company, financial information regarding the company and recent developments and prospects of the company.

<p>

The continuing obligations of AIM are limited almost exclusively to disclosure obligations.  There is a general obligation to announce new developments or changes in the company's performance or financial condition as is also the case for companies whose shares are quoted on the Official List.  There is also a series of specific disclosure obligations regarding certain events and transactions which could be price sensitive such as changes in the shareholdings of directors or other significant shareholders, transactions with a percentage ratio of 10% or more as defined by AIM's rules and transactions with parties affiliated with the company.  There are no rules requiring the consent of shareholders for the company to engage in particular types of transactions, except with regard to a reverse takeover.

<p>

The London Stock Exchange has produced written information regarding AIM.  Titles of such publications include: <EM>Rules for Companies</EM>, <EM>A Guide for Companies</EM>, <EM>A Guide for Investors</EM> and <EM>A Guide for Advisers and Brokers</EM>.  Copies are available from the London office of Faegre & Benson.

<P>

<font="+2"><b>Questions</b></font><p>

If you have any questions, please contact Michael T. McCormick at 612/336-3401 or 800/328-4393, or by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:mmccormi@faegre.com">mmccormi@faegre.com</A>. <p>


<HR>

