<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Resisting Subpoenas for Published or Broadcast Information </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<center>
<img src="subpoena.gif">
<br>
<A HREF="../offices/att_mpls.html#borger"><H4>John P. Borger</H4></a></center>

<blockquote>

This article was originally published in <EM>Communications Lawyer</EM>, Vol. 12 No. 1 Spring 1994, a publication of the Forum on Communications Law of the American Bar Association.  Copyright &copy; 1994 American Bar Association<br>
<STRONG>Reprinted with Permission</STRONG>.
<p>

Journalists fiercely resist efforts to force disclosure of confidential sources or unpublished information, often to the point of going to jail or paying steep fines as the price of resistance.  On the other hand, many journalists complain, but comply, when confronted with subpoenas to produce published information.  However, journalists in many cases successfully can resist subpoenas even for published or broadcast information.
<P>

Attorneys direct subpoenas to journalists for testimony, videotapes, audiotapes, photographs, notes, outtakes, and other material for one very simple reason:  Journalists have, or are thought to have, information desired by attorneys in criminal cases and civil litigation.  The overwhelming majority of these subpoenas come in cases in which the journalist is not a party, according to surveys conducted by the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press in 1989 and 1991.<A HREF="#1"><B>1</B></A> 
<P>

The scenario is straightforward:  The nature of news itself means that journalists will seek out, gather, assimilate, and disseminate information involving crime, conflict, and other matters of public interest, many of which lead to criminal cases and civil lawsuits.  In a search for information, witnesses, and documents attorneys in those cases may serve subpoenas upon journalists for a number of reasons:  They do not have the time, resources, or inclination to conduct their own investigations.  They are being extremely thorough and want to exhaust every possible source of information.
<P>

When subpoenas seek confidential sources or unpublished information, journalists usually react immediately, viscerally, violently, and negatively.  These subpoenas threaten the constitutional role of the press in gathering and publishing information to benefit the public generally, as contrasted with the private benefit to parties to a particular lawsuit.  Subpoenas for confidential and unpublished information raise issues of journalists' privileges under federal and state constitutions, statutes, and rules of evidence, which have been explored in many law review articles and elsewhere since <EM>Branzburg v. Hayes</EM>. <a href="#2"><B>2</B></a>
<P>

<h3>Subpoenas for Information</h3>
In contrast, subpoenas for information contained in published articles or broadcast stories do not implicate privilege issues  and have received little attention in the overall discussion of legal discovery against the press. <a href="#3"><B>3</B></a>  However, they account for a significant percentage of the total subpoenas issued against the press.  The 1989 Reporters Committee survey found that nearly half of the subpoenas issued against news organizations were for published items and news organizations fully complied with more than 50 percent of these subpoenas.  Similar results were reported for 1991.  <a href="#4"><B>4</B></a>
<P>

A common attitude appears to be that the press must respond to subpoenas for published or broadcast information and turn over that information (and produce the journalist for testimony, if requested) because the special journalists' privilege does not extend beyond confidential and sometimes unpublished information.  Unfortunately, this attitude ignores the real costs imposed on journalists who comply with subpoenas for published information.  
<P>

Some courts do recognize those costs.  In <EM>Maurice v. NLRB</EM>, a federal judge in West Virginia set aside a subpoena for a business editor to testify concerning a published interview with a coal company executive who was a witness in a labor case, noting:  The impeachment by a reporter of her news source is a serious matter, having a negative impact on the newsgathering abilities of the media as significant as the compelled disclosure by a reporter of a confidential source.<a href="#5"><B>5</B></a>  
<P>

Compelled testimony which entangles reporters in court proceedings, especially high-profile court proceedings, can have additional long-term adverse consequences, as the district court also recognized in <EM>Maurice</EM>.<a href="#6"><B>6</B></a>  Sources who are concerned that the words will haunt them in court are likely to speak to that reporter with less candor.  Furthermore, reporters who become a part of the criminal trial or civil litigation by testifying may be unable to cover new developments in a story they have been following for a long time, either because of ethical constraints or because a party has insisted that the reporter-witness be sequestered until his or her testimony has ended.<a href="#7"><B>7</B></a>
<P>

Moreover, the temporal burdens on the press are considerable.  An Alabama broadcast outlet responded to the 1989 Reporters Committee survey as follows: [A]rchivists must find the material, a newsperson's time must be spent helping to compile scripts, and engineering time is involved in dubbing the material to tape.  The fact that the press by its nature announces to the world that it has information, and the perception among lawyers that the press may have information even if the lawyer has not yet read the particular article or seen the particular broadcast make the press recurring targets of subpoenas to a far greater extent than any other organization.  This problem becomes even greater when the subpoena is directed at the news organization, rather than at a particular reporter, and seeks all information related to a designated subject, instead of a particular article or report.
<P>

Responding to subpoenas diverts time and resources from reporters' real jobs of newsgathering and news-disseminating and imposes costs on the public in the form of delayed or suppressed information.  This diversion might be considered inconsequential in an isolated case, but the cumulative organizational burden cannot be ignored.  As stated in the conclusion to the 1989 Reporters Committee survey:

<blockquote>

<font size=-1>Inevitably, law enforcement officials and litigants seeking information from journalists will continue to argue that a few isolated subpoenas do not pose any real danger to a reporter's ability to effectively gather and disseminate news.  Yet, due to the cumulative impact of repeated subpoenas, an editor's decision whether to cover a controversial story may be motivated as much by the desire to avoid an ongoing battle to keep reporters' testimony and notes out of court as by traditional news judgments.  Until judges understand that, many of them will continue to dismiss the impact of individual requests as trivial.<a href="#8"><B>8</B></a></font>

</blockquote>

Threats of subpoenas, actual or perceived, also have caused some news organizations to discard their notes more frequently than before and to be more reluctant to use confidential sources, according to the 1991 Reporters Committee survey. 
<P>

The New York Court of Appeals recognized the dangers of allowing routine subpoenas against the press in <EM>O'Neill v. Oakgrove Const., Inc.</EM>, 523, stating:

<blockquote>

<font size=-1>The autonomy of the press would be jeopardized if resort to its resource materials, by litigants seeking to utilize the newsgathering efforts of journalists for their private purposes, were routinely permitted.  Moreover, because journalists typically gather information about accidents, crimes, and other matters of special interest that often give rise to litigation, attempts to obtain evidence by subjecting the press to discovery as a nonparty would be widespread if not restricted.  The practical burden on the time and resources, as well as the consequent diversion of journalistic effort and disruption of newsgathering activity, would be particularly inimical to the vigor of a free press.<a href="#9"><B>9</B></a></font>
</blockquote>


Although compliance may be appropriate in individual cases, the pattern of general compliance with subpoenas for published or broadcast material is not justified.  News organizations should not automatically assume that they must comply with subpoenas for published or broadcast information.  Legal arguments exist to resist those subpoenas in many situations.  Although First Amendment reasons do exist for resisting these subpoenas, many arguments can be found in the rules and laws applicable to <EM>all</EM> witnesses.  This approach helps defuse the predictable cry that the press, once again, is seeking an unjustifiable special privilege.
<P>

In criminal cases, a primary defense to subpoenas can be found under Federal Rule of Criminal Procedure 17, under which a subpoena may command a person to appear to give testimony and also to produce designated books, papers, documents, or other objects.  However, the court may quash or modify the subpoena if compliance would be unreasonable or oppressive, if the target of the subpoena makes a prompt motion. 
<P>

The law governing the issuance of a subpoena for documents in a criminal matter was settled, in <EM>United States v. Nixon</EM>.<a href="#10"><B>10</B></a>  The United States Supreme Court held that the party serving the subpoena must show that:  (1) that the documents are evidentiary and relevant; (2) the documents are not otherwise procurable reasonably in advance of trial by the exercise of due diligence; (3) the party cannot properly prepare for trial without production and inspection of the documents and failure to obtain the inspection may delay the trial unreasonably; and (4) the application is made in good faith and is not intended as a general fishing expedition.<a href="#11"><B>11</B></a>
<p>

Because criminal subpoenas reach only evidentiary and relevant<a href="#12"><B>12</B></a> materials, material held by third-parties (such as news organizations) that does not rise to the dignity of admissible evidence simply is not within the rule.<a href="#13"><B>13</B></a>  A federal judge in Boston denied the government's request to compel production of a television station's videotape containing an interview with a criminal defendant.  The court concluded that it was too early even to conduct its own <EM>in camera</EM> review of the videotape because of the possibility that there might not even be a trial (the defendant might plead guilty or be declared incompetent to stand trial).  The court further stated that if the case did proceed to trial and the government's need for the videotape as evidence actually materialized, it then would weigh the station's First Amendment interests against the needs of the prosecution.<a href="#14"><B>14</B></a>
<P>  

Vaguely worded or exhaustively comprehensive subpoenas may sweep so broadly that they amount to nothing more than an impermissible fishing expedition.<a href="#15"><B>15</B></a>  If the information sought from journalists simply repeats a point made in other admissible evidence, the court may set aside the press subpoena as cumulative.<a href="#16"><b>16</B></a>   
<P>

Unfortunately, a journalist facing a subpoena may not have the factual knowledge of a particular case or the legal background to argue effectively that the information sought in the subpoena is cumulative, irrelevant, unnecessary, or non-evidentiary.  On the other hand, it often is reasonably easy for any journalist, facing a subpoena for published information, to object on the grounds that the requesting attorney could get the same information with little difficulty from another source.<a href="#17"><B>17</B></a>
<P>  
It is hard to believe that any attorney <EM>needs</EM> to subpoena the press for a copy of a published or broadcast story in a country filled with public libraries, computer-assisted research organizations such as Westlaw and NEXIS, private clipping services, and even video clipping services.  It may be cheaper, simpler, or faster for an attorney to grind out a press subpoena than to conduct or pay for independent research, but that is not the same as showing that the materials are not otherwise procurable reasonably in advance of trial by the exercise of due diligence, as the law requires.
<P>

A 1992 Minnesota case illustrates this point.  The United States Attorney was prosecuting an indigent black man for unlawful possession of a firearm by a felon; he was accused not only of possessing the gun, but also of firing it at two white police officers.  The defendant faced a mandatory fifteen-year sentence without parole, if convicted.  His attorney sought a change of venue, claiming that racial tensions in the city had escalated recently in the wake of the murder of an off-duty white police officer, apparently by black gang members.  To support her motion, the defense attorney served subpoenas on the community's two largest newspapers for copies of all articles which appeared in your publication [during a three-week period], relative to the shooting of [the police officer], including those articles relating to racial tensions stemming from the shooting.<a href="#18"><B>18</B></a>  
<p>

The newspapers resisted, citing Rule 17, and the district court agreed that the subpoenas should be quashed as improper burdens on the newspapers:

<blockquote>

<font size=-1>Appearances by the newspapers are not necessary to authenticate the articles, to the extent they have evidentiary value.  Fed. R. Ev. 902(6).  Insofar as defense counsel seeks to have the newspapers make the search and selection concerning the articles, the subpoenas shift the burden of trial preparation from defense counsel onto the newspapers; no matter what the extent of the newspapers' resources may be relative to the criminal defendant, this sort of burden-shifting is an unfair imposition upon innocent third-parties.<a href="#19"><B>19</B></a></font>
</blockquote>

This passage highlights the next line of defense to subpoenas for testimony of the reporters.  Under the Federal Rules of Evidence, authentication of published articles does not require testimony by the reporter or other representatives of the news organization.  Those materials are self-authenticating under Rule 902(6).<a href="#20"><B>20</B></a>
<p>

The self-authentication rule, of course, applies to evidence in civil as well as criminal cases.  The scope of permissible subpoenas is much broader in civil actions, where subpoenas may issue for discovery purposes, and where the information sought need not itself be admissible evidence so long as it appears reasonably calculated to lead to the discovery of admissible evidence.  Even here, however, the requirement that the information be relevant to the case limits the scope of permissible discovery.  For example, if a news organization receives a third-party subpoena for all documents, including internal reports and memoranda, referring or relating to a particular subject, purely internal documents containing the organization's own use and interpretation of information it has received from a party or from another witness should be irrelevant and non-discoverable.<a href="#21"><B>21</B></a> 
<P>

<h3>Other Provisions from Federal Rules of Civil Procedure May Prevent "One-Stop" Shopping</h3>

The civil rules contain other provisions which should prevent attorneys from making news organizations a sort of one-stop shopping target of subpoenas.  These include:

<UL>
<LI>Rule 26 (b)(1)(i), which permits the court to limit discovery which is obtainable from some other source that is more convenient, less burdensome, or less expensive.  The rule does not specify to whom the burden or expense is less.  Because discovery requests to nonparty news organizations impose burdens upon their constitutional rights and public functions, the press can argue that this burden should be given more weight than financial costs and inconveniences of the party seeking discovery.  This argument will be stronger in jurisdictions which recognize a news process basis, rather than a more limited expectation of confidentiality basis, for a journalist's privilege.<a href="#22"><B>22</B></a>  

<LI>Rule 26 (c), which allows the target of the discovery request (including a nonparty, such as a news organization) to seek a protective order.  This could forbid the discovery entirely or specify terms and conditions (such as reimbursement of expenses) under which the discovery may be granted.  The grounds for a protective order include protecting the nonparty from annoyance, ... or undue burden or expense.<a href="#23"><B>23</B></a>

<LI>Rule 45 (c)(1), which affirmatively requires the attorney issuing the subpoena to take reasonable steps to avoid imposing undue burden or expense on a person subject to that subpoena.  Available sanctions against attorneys who violate that rule include, but are not limited to, lost earnings and a reasonable attorney's fee.<a href="#24"><B>24</B></a>

<LI>Rule 45 (c)(2)(B), which provides an inexpensive alternative to the motion for a protective order available under Rule 26.  Persons responding to subpoenas to produce documents, including photographs and videotapes, can deflect the subpoena simply by serving written objection to inspection and copying of the documents.  The burden then falls to the attorney issuing the subpoena to move the court for an order to compel the production.  Any order to compel production shall protect any person who is not a party or an officer of a party from significant expense resulting from the inspection and copying commanded.  If this procedure is used, the written objection must be served on the attorney issuing the subpoena within fourteen days after service of the subpoena, or before the time specified for compliance if that time is less than fourteen days after service.

</UL>
		

Rule 45 does not define significant expense.  Where amounts are uncertain, they may be determined after the materials have been produced, provided that the risk of uncertainty is fully disclosed to the discovering party.  These amounts can be substantial.  In one case, nonparties sought to recover $2.3 million in costs allegedly incurred in responding to document requests.  The United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit observed that the requesting parties were on notice throughout the production process that the nonparties intended to seek reimbursement and received periodic status reports of the costs as they were incurred, so that the parties could easily have modified or limited their discovery demands whenever they felt that their exposure to potential reimbursement exceeded the value of requested material.  . . .  Nonparty witnesses are powerless to control the scope of litigation and discovery, and should not be forced to subsidize an unreasonable share of the costs of a litigation to which they are not a party.<a href="#25"><B>25</B></a>   
<p>

<h3>State Court Rules May Help</h3>

The federal rule protects nonparties from incurring significant expense in responding to subpoenas.  State court rules can be more or less protective depending on the jurisdiction.  For example, Iowa's less-protective Civil Rule 155 (c) requires the target of the subpoena to seek a protective order and authorizes protection only if the subpoena is unreasonable and oppressive.  Iowa also allows the target of a subpoena for the production of documents (but not mere testimony) to recover the reasonable cost of producing the records sought.  
<p>

On the more protective end of the spectrum, Minnesota Rule of Civil Procedure 45.06 provides that a witness who is not a party to the action or an employee of a party and who is required to give testimony or produce documents relating to a profession, business, or trade. ... is entitled to reasonable compensation for the time and expense involved in preparing for and giving such testimony or producing such documents.  The party serving the subpoena shall make arrangements for such reasonable compensation prior to the time of the taking of such testimony.  This rule leaves no room for the trial court to exercise any discretion in deciding whether to award <EM>some</EM> costs to the witness, although the court does have the power to determine what expenses are reasonable.  
<p>

This sort of provision can deter frivolous subpoenas.  A news director at a television station in Louisiana noted on the 1991 Reporters Committee survey that often individuals are persuaded to withdraw a subpoena because under state law, third parties are entitled to compensation for time and materials being sought."<a href="#26"><B>26</B></a>
<p>

Other news organizations charge hourly fees, with a minimum of $100 or $150, to anyone asking them to search for and produce published or broadcast information.  This policy can deter frivolous requests.  Organizations that follow this approach should be sure that their charges will cover or exceed all of their expenses.
<p>

<h3>Conclusion</h3>
   
These legal arguments against subpoenas are available to anyone, most emphatically <EM>including</EM> news organizations.  They will not turn aside every subpoena for published or broadcast information.  An attorney may need a higher-quality reproduction of a photograph than one available on newsprint, or the parties may refuse to stipulate to the authenticity of a broadcast report, or a witness may deny ever making the damaging admission quoted in a story.<a href="#27"><B>27</B></a>  Such cases are likely to make it worth the fight for the requesting attorney to pursue the subpoena through a court hearing and perhaps even a level or two of appeals.  Other attorneys, motivated more by battle fever or possible publicity than by practicality or economy, may simply relish a fight with the news media.  Some may even use subpoenas as a calculated effort to intimidate the press or to discourage certain types of reporting.
<p>

On the other hand, reasoned and consistent resistance to subpoenas can deflect many requests for information, particularly those from attorneys who served a subpoena against the news media to reduce their own expenses, or who may not have thought about the burden they were putting on the press, or who may not have considered fully just what information they really need and why.  In many instances, deflection may require no more than a short, reasoned letter or telephone call from an editor or press attorney, at minimal cost.  The Reporters Committee surveys found that nearly one in five of all reported subpoenas were withdrawn by the issuing attorney after discussions with an editor or media lawyer, with anecdotal comments confirming the effectiveness of telephone calls.  If this approach fails, the subpoenaed journalist can consider the relative burdens of complying with the subpoena or incurring additional legal costs to challenge the subpoena in court. 
<p>

Of course, news organizations may decide in particular cases not to resist a subpoena for any of a number of reasons.  However, greater awareness of the possibilities for objecting to subpoenas, even routine subpoenas seeking publicly available published or broadcast information, at least should reduce any sense of fatalistic resignation that led to the high level of compliance found in the Reporters Committee surveys.
<p>

The Reporters Committee surveys confirm the effectiveness of challenges to subpoenas' even when the challenges are not based on state shield laws or a constitutional reporters privilege.  Of the relatively few subpoenas actually challenged in court, judges quashed nearly three out of four.  Courts that blocked subpoenas frequently did so on the grounds that the information sought was available from other sources, that the information sought was irrelevant or not needed, and that the subpoenas were overly broad.<a href="#28"><B>28</B></a>  
<p>

