<p>

<A NAME="11"></A>11.  <EM>Id</EM>. at 699-700.  In the pre-indictment grand jury context, the party objecting to the subpoena has the burden of showing that compliance would be unreasonable or oppressive.  <EM>R. Enterprises</EM>, 498 U.S. at ___, 112 L.Ed.2d at 807.  The Court held that the <EM>Nixon</EM> standards do not apply to grand jury subpoenas, noting in particular that evidentiary restrictions from the rules of evidence for trial are not applicable before grand juries.  <EM>Id</EM> at 805-06.  The Court delineated a standard for <EM>relevance</EM> of subpoenaed materials, but did not address oppressive subpoenas or reasonableness generally.
<p>

<A NAME="12"></A>12.  In Tribune Co. v. Green, 440 So. 2d 484, 486 (Fla. Dist. Ct. App. 1983), <EM>rev. denied</EM>, 447 So. 2d 886 (Fla. 1984), the court set aside an order compelling a reporter to testify about his interview with a criminal defendant, in part because the defendant's statements to the reporter were irrelevant to proof of the particular charges against the defendant.  In Florida v. Kangus, 8 Med. L. Rptr. 2045 (Fla. Cty. Ct. 1982), the court held that a reporter's testimony about statements made in a published article by a prosecuting attorney would be inadmissible hearsay, <EM>id</EM>. at 2046, and went on to state:  Although the motion to quash [the subpoena against the reporter] is granted upon those narrow [evidentiary] grounds, the Court would note that above and beyond the evidentiary considerations, the reporter's constitutional claims of privilege are well-founded, <EM>id</EM>.  Another subpoena seeking to compel a reporter to testify about statements attributed to a source in a published article was quashed on both evidentiary and constitutional privilege grounds in New York v. Bova, 9 Med. L. Rptr. 1329, 1331, 1333 (N.Y. Sup. Ct. 1983). 
<p>

<A NAME="13"></A>13.  United States v. Cuthbertson, 651 F.2d 189, 195 (3d Cir. 1981).
<p>

<A NAME="14"></A>14.  United States v. Shay, 21 Med. L.Rptr. 1415, 1416 (D.Mass. 1993).
<p>

<A NAME="15"></A>15.  In United States v. Myerson, 684 F. Supp. 41 (S.D.N.Y. 1988), the court quashed in part a subpoena duces tecum directed to a city investigator by a criminal defendant.  The basis for quashing certain documents was because they are newspaper articles which can easily be obtained from newspaper morgues by the defendant if she seeks them.  <EM>Id</EM>. at 45.  The court held that the <EM>Nixon</EM> test precluded production of the documents.
<p>
In United States v. Orsini, 424 F. Supp. 229 (E.D.N.Y. 1976), <EM>aff'd</EM>, 559 F.2d 1206 (2d Cir.) (table), <EM>cert. denied</EM>, 434 U.S. 997 (1977), the court quashed a subpoena duces tecum directed to a <STRONG>Newsweek</STRONG> magazine reporter by a criminal defendant seeking disclosure of confidential sources.  The court granted the motion to quash because the subject matter sought bears no reasonable relationship to the defense.  <EM>Id</EM>. at 231.  It found the subpoena irrelevant and immaterial.  <EM>Id</EM>. at 232.  The court further ruled that the subpoena should be quashed, on the separate and independent ground of a journalist's privilege under the First Amendment.
<p>
In United States v. Reed, 726 F.2d 570 (9th Cir.), <EM>cert. denied</EM>, 469 U.S. 871 (1984), the court upheld the quashing of a subpoena duces tecum issued by a criminal defendant charged with arson seeking city records on other fires.  The court found the documents were not shown to be relevant, that there was no foundation for believing the reports would aid the defense, and that Rule 17(c) does not allow a blind fishing expedition seeking unknown evidence.  <EM>Id</EM>. at 577.  <EM>See also</EM> United States v. Hughes, 895 F.2d 1135 (6th Cir. 1990) (applying <EM>Nixon</EM> standards, affirms quashing of subpoena duces tecum seeking pharmacy invoices not relevant, admissible or specifically described).
<p>
The standards are lower for quashing a subpoena in a civil case.  <EM>See</EM> Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum Comm. v. National Football League, 89 F.R.D. 489 (C.D. Cal. 1981) (quashes Fed. R. Civ. P. 45 subpoena duces tecum directed to newspaper reporters as unreasonable and oppressive because of First Amendment concerns, a state shield law, and doubtful the information sought was relevant; includes thorough discussion of case law on civil subpoenas directed to journalists).
<p>
<A NAME="16"></A>16.  <EM>See, e.g.</EM>, United States v. Burke, 700 F.2d 70, 77-78 (2d Cir. 1983); United States v. Paez, 13 Med. L. Rptr. 1973 (S.D. Fla. 1987); Illinois v. Fort, 15 Med. L. Rptr. 2251 (Cir. Ct. Cook Cty. 1988).
<p>

<A NAME="17"></A>17.  The Seventh Circuit discussed the general background of this rule in <EM>In re</EM> Special April 1977 Grand Jury, 581 F.2d 589 (7th Cir.) (per curiam), <EM>cert. denied</EM> by Scott v. United States, 439 U.S. 1046 (1978),  explaining that the rule is used to avoid allowing a party who may have the needed document in its own possession, or could easily obtain it from another source, to force the subpoenaed party to bear the costs of searching for the document.  Placing such a burden on the subpoenaed party when another source is available is deemed unreasonable and oppressive.  <EM>Id</EM>. at 594.  When possible, journalists should provide specific examples of possible alternative sources for the information sought, or for equivalent information.  <EM>See, e.g.</EM>, United States v. Blanton, 534 F. Supp. 295, 296 (S.D. Fla. 1982).  Department of Justice regulations require the exhaustion of all reasonable sources of the information sought before its lawyers will issue subpoenas to compel production of the information from journalists.  <EM>See</EM> 28 C.F.R. §§ 50.10 (b) & (f)(3).
<p>

<A NAME="18"></A>18.  This tactic appears to be fairly common in some areas of the country.  Nineteen news organizations responding to the 1989 Reporters Committee survey reported that they were frequently subpoenaed in connection with change of venue proceedings.
<p>

<A NAME="19"></A>19.  United States v. Ford, No. 4-92-112, (D. Minn. filed October 19, 1992) at p. 2.  Improper burden arguments under Rule 17 are similar to, and can be strengthened by, need to exhaust alternative sources arguments under the journalist's privilege applicable in some jurisdictions.  <EM>See, e.g.</EM>, North Carolina v. Hagaman, 9 Med. L. Rptr. 2525, 2527 (N.C. Gen. Ct. 1983).  
<p>

<A NAME="20"></A>20.  <STRONG>Fed. R. Evid.</STRONG> 902(6) does not refer to videotapes of television broadcasts, nor do there appear to be reported cases involving self-authentication of videotaped broadcasts.  The same rationale for permitting self-authentication of newspaper articles and periodicals should apply to videotaped television broadcasts, however, perhaps with some additional testimony required to lay the foundation for the accuracy of the reproduction of the broadcasts, an issue not present with published printed material.<p>
Concerning videotapes as evidence generally, <em>see, e.g.</em>, State v. Woolridge, 581 P.2d 403 (Kan. App. 1978) (television news film authenticated in same manner as any photograph when truth of matter asserted is at issue); G<STRONG>. Joseph, Modern Visual Evidence</STRONG>, at § 6.02[3] (1992).  Concerning the rationale for self-authentication of newspaper articles generally, <EM>see, e.g.</EM>, Price v. Rochford, 947 F.2d 829 (7th Cir. 1991) (article self-authenticating as evidence of publicity, notice to public, but not as to truth of matter asserted); New England Mut. Life Ins. Co. v. Anderson, 888 F.2d 646 (10th Cir. 1989) (article inadmissible hearsay for truth of matter asserted).
<p>

<A NAME="21"></A>21.  <EM>Cf. In re</EM> Scott Paper Company Securities Litigation, 20 Med. L. Rptr. 2164, 2165 (E.D. Pa. 1992) (Information about [Standard & Poor's] internal procedures and deliberations bears no demonstrable relevance to plaintiffs' case.).
<p>


<A NAME="22"></A>22.  <EM>See, e.g.</EM>, Damico v. Lemen, 14 Med. L. Rptr. 1031, 1032 (Fla. Cir. Ct. 1987) (Although the plaintiffs' affidavit indicates there are no other sources for photographic evidence, there has been no showing of exhaustion of alternative sources who could help reconstruct the scene of the accident. ... Alternative sources need not have viewed the exact scene or heard the same conversations as the press, but must merely have knowledge or evidence of the same facts.); Johnson v. Skurow, 10 Med. L. Rptr. 2463 (N.C. Super. Ct. 1984).  
<p>

<A NAME="23"></A>23.  <STRONG>Fed. R. Civ. P.</STRONG> 26(c).
<p>

<A NAME="24"></A>24.  <STRONG>Fed. R. Civ. P.</STRONG> 45(c)(1).
<p>

<A NAME="25"></A>25.  <EM>United States v. Columbia Broadcasting System, Inc.</EM>, 666 F.2d 364, 368, 371 (9th Cir. 1982).  
<p>

<A NAME="26"></A>26.  <EM>Supra</EM> note 1 (second report).
<p>

<A NAME="27"></A>27.  Courts have reached different conclusions concerning the evidentiary value of this sort of prior statements by witnesses.  <EM>Compare</EM> United States v. Cuthbertson, 651 F.2d 189, 195 (3d Cir. 1981) (prior inconsistent statement may cease to be hearsay, and therefore become admissible evidence, but only after the witness has testified in a manner inconsistent with the prior statement), <EM>with</EM> State v. Siel, 444 A.2d 499, 503 (N.H. 1982) (information sought in a criminal case solely to show a prior inconsistent statement by a witness will <EM>never</EM> overcome a qualified journalist's privilege against disclosing confidential or unpublished information, because that sort of information does not go to the heart of the criminal case).  
<p>

<A NAME="28"></A>28.  Courts that blocked subpoenas frequently did so on more than one legal ground.  As might be expected, state shield laws were the single most frequently cited basis for blocking subpoenas in 1991.  <EM>Supra</EM> note 1, <STRONG>Agents of Discovery</STRONG> 11, 13 (second report).  In 1989, however, shield laws were cited as the basis for blocking subpoenas less frequently than the availability of the information from other sources and the overbreadth of the subpoenas.  <EM>Supra</EM> note 1, <STRONG>Agents of Discovery</STRONG> 15 (first report).<BR>

