<HEAD>
<TITLE> IRS Issues Proposed Regs 
on Gift Substantiation </title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>
<h2>IRS Issues Proposed Regs 
on Gift Substantiation</H2>
<h4>by</h4>

<h4>J. Hazen Graves and John E. Harris</h4>


<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he Internal Revenue Service has published proposed regulations interpreting  the 1993 tax laws requiring that charitable contributions be documented in a certain  manner.                                                                               
<br>
                                  
The proposed regulations are likely to be revised before they become final, but they do provide some helpful guidance as to the IRSs current thinking on the gift substantiation requirements. 
<p>
<strong>Current Law</strong>
<br>
                                                     
The law now provides that a donor who intends to claim a deduction for a charitable gift of $250 or more must obtain a written receipt from the charity stating (a) the amount of the gift if in cash, or a description of any non-cash gift, and (b) whether the donor received any benefits in exchange for the gift, and if so, a description and estimate of the value of such benefits.
<br>
                                  
For contributions of $75 or more, where the donor receives something of value in exchange for the contribution (a quid pro quo gift), the charity must provide the donor with a written acknowledgement estimating the value of the benefits provided to the donor, and stating that the donors tax deduction is limited to the amount by which the contribution exceeds the value of the benefits. 
<p>
Here are some of the highlights of the proposed regulations:                      
<br>
<UL>
                                                                        
<LI><STRONG>Intent to Make Gift:</STRONG>  A charitable deduction is available only if the amount of  the payment exceeds the value of any benefits received in return, and the donor intended to make a gift.  This may be an issue, for example, at a charity auction, where items are purchased for prices above market value.
<p>
<LI><STRONG>Membership Benefits:</STRONG>  In determining whether a donor received anything of value in exchange for the gift, a membership benefit may be disregarded if--

<UL>

-	The payment is $75 or less, and
<br>
-	The benefit consists of--
</ul>
Free admission to members-only events and the charitys costs per person (per event) will not be more than $6.60 (adjusted annually for inflation); or
<br>
Privileges that members can exercise frequently during the membership period (such as free admission to a museum or gift shop discounts).
<p>
<LI><STRONG>Benefits to Donors Employees:</STRONG>  Any benefits that may be disregarded when provided directly to the donor (such as free museum admission) may also be disregarded when provided to the donors employees.  The acknowledgement provided to the donor must describe all other benefits provided to employees, but need not give an estimate of the value of the benefits described.
<p>
<LI><STRONG>Valuation of Benefits:</STRONG>  In estimating the value of benefits provided to donors, if the goods or services are not available commercially, the valuation may be based on the value of similar goods or services that are sold commercially, even if the commercial goods or services do not have the unique qualities of those provided by the charity.
<p>
<LI><STRONG>Celebrities:</STRONG>  The celebrity status of a person providing a service to the donor is deemed not to add any value to the service.  For example, a round of golf with Bob Hope has no more value than a round of golf with John Doe, for these purposes.
<p>
<LI><STRONG>Charitable Remainder Trusts:</STRONG> No acknowledgement is required for contributions to charitable remainder trusts or charitable lead trusts.
<p>
<LI><STRONG>Out-of-Pocket Expenses:</STRONG>  Out-of-pocket expenditures of $250 or more incurred in connection with volunteer service will be deductible if substantiated by the volunteers normal records (receipts, cancelled checks, etc.) and an abbreviated written acknowledgement from the charity. The acknowledgement must contain the following information:
<br>
<ul>
-	A description of the services provided by the volunteer
<br>
-	The date the services were provided
<br>
-	Whether or not the volunteer received any benefits in return, and if so, a description of the benefits and an estimate of their value
</ul>
<p>
<LI><STRONG>Gifts from Partnerships, S-Corporations:</STRONG>  A single acknowledgment is to be provided to the partnership or S-corporation, even though each partner or shareholder will be claiming the contribution deduction.
<p>
<LI><STRONG>Matching Gifts:</STRONG>  Where a taxpayer receives a benefit from a charity as a result of a matching gift made to the charity by another party, the entire value of the benefit must be reflected in the acknowledgment provided to the recipient of the benefit.
<p>
<LI><STRONG>Effective Date:</STRONG>  The proposed regulations are just that--proposed.  If final regulations are adopted, taxpayers will be able to rely on the regulations for all contributions made on or after January 1, 1994. Written comments on the proposed regulations will be considered by the IRS, and a public hearing will be held in Washington, D.C., on November 1, 1995.
<br>
</UL>

<strong>Questions</strong><br>

If you have any questions, please contact Hazen Graves or John Harris.  Hazen Graves is available at  <A HREF="mailto:hgraves@faegre.com">hgraves@faegre.com</A>.  John Harris is available at  <A HREF="mailto:jharris@faegre.com">jharris@faegre.com</A>.<P>


<HR>

