<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Thousands Become Defendants in Gift Annuity Lawsuit </title>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>Thousands Become Defendants in Gift Annuity Lawsuit
</H2><P>

<h4>by</h4>

<h4>J. Hazen Graves</h4>


<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>f your organization has issued charitable gift annuities, you most likely are well aware of the lawsuit in the U.S. District Court in Texas against The American Council on Gift Annuities, some 21 other charities, and all others similarly situated.  (Ozee et al. v. The American Council on Gift Annuities, Inc., et al.)<P>

In an order dated October 25, 1995, the judge approved the creation of an entire class of charities, likely to number in the thousands, that are now defendants in the lawsuit.  If your organization receives a notice that it is a defendant in this case, do not ignore it!<P>

The lawsuit has been brought by several Texas residents who claim (among many other things) that charities across the country have violated federal and Texas antitrust laws by issuing charitable gift annuities using the payment rates published by The American Council on Gift Annuities, formerly known as the Committee on Gift Annuities.  The plaintiffs allege that use of the published rates constituted price-fixing that violated the federal Sherman Antitrust Act and Texas antitrust laws.<P>

<strong>Class Action</strong><br>

The suit has been structured as both a plaintiff class action and a defendant class action.  Plaintiff class actions are relatively common, and allow a small number of plaintiffs to sue on behalf of all other persons who are similarly situated.  Defendant class actions are quite rare, and permit a plaintiff to pursue claims against a large group of similarly situated defendants by suing only a few members of the group who are representative of all of them.  As a result, a member of the defendant class could be found liable in a lawsuit in which it did not actively participate.<P>

In the October 25 order, the court certified the defendant antitrust class, including as defendants in the lawsuit all organizations meeting both of the following criteria:<P>

<UL>
<LI>The organization is or was a sponsor or member of The American Council on Gift Annuities (or an affiliate of such a sponsor or member).
<LI>During the period December 30, 1990, to the present the organization had outstanding gift annuities or other life income products pursuant to the rates of return published by the Council.
</UL>


If your organization meets these criteria, it is a defendant in this lawsuit unless it opts out as described below.  The American Council on Gift Annuities, Concordia Lutheran College, The Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod, The Lutheran Foundation of Texas, and the Texas District Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod, have been designated by the court as the representatives who will defend the antitrust claims on behalf of the defendant class.  Other members of the defendant class may choose to be represented by their own legal counsel if they desire.<P>

The court has also certified the plaintiff antitrust class, which includes all persons in the United States who, at any time since December 30, 1990, have owned gift annuities issued by members of the defendant antitrust class based on the published annuity rates.  As a result, charities and their donors are placed at odds with each other in the suit.  <P>

<strong>Potential Liability</strong><br>

The prospect of being a defendant in a lawsuit where you are not personally represented is not appealing.  It is made even less appealing in this case because of the damages provisions of the federal antitrust laws that will apply if the defendants are found liable:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Damages will be set at three times the amount of actual damages proven by the plaintiffs.
<LI>Defendants will also be liable for the plaintiffs attorneys fees and expenses.
<LI>Liability is joint and several, so that the plaintiffs may attempt to collect the entire liability of all defendants from a few deep pocket defendants.
<LI>Defendants who are forced to pay such damages generally have no right to charge other non-paying defendants for their fair share of the damages. 
</UL>


Under the rules of procedure, members of the defendant class may opt out of the class, meaning that they would not be governed by any judgment in this lawsuit.  They would, however, then be exposed to the risk of individual lawsuits against them, which the plaintiffs attorneys reportedly have vowed to pursue.  <P>

If a defendant does not opt out, and if a plaintiff attempts to enforce a judgment against that defendant, the defendant most likely would be entitled to a hearing to determine whether there were any material facts or defenses unique to that defendant that had not been addressed at trial.<P>

<strong>Legislation Pending</strong><br>

Some relief may be in sight for defendant charities.  Legislation has been introduced in both the U.S. House and the Senate that would exempt most charities from federal antitrust laws.  The exemption would apply in all lawsuits pending on or after enactment of the law, although retroactive application may be subject to challenge.  The exemption would apply to state antitrust laws as well, except where the state legislature affirmatively voted to keep its antitrust laws applicable to charitable gift programs.  The legislation appears to have strong support in Congress and is moving forward.  It may, however, encounter procedural snags in this contentious session.<P>

<strong>In the Meantime</strong><br>

In the meantime, defendants in the Ozee case may receive demands to produce documents and provide other information to the plaintiffs' attorneys.  Before responding to such demands, it is important that each organization carefully consider several questions, including the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Does the court in Texas have jurisdiction over the organization?
<LI>Should the organization opt out of the defendant class?
<LI>If the court ruled against the defendant antitrust class, would there be any material facts or defenses unique to the organization?  

</UL>

<strong>Planning
</strong><br>

Finally, organizations that are issuing gift annuities using rates that are in any way based on those published by The American Council on Gift Annuities should determine whether their policies or practices should be revised in any way to reduce the risk of future litigation and liability.<P>

This <EM>Alert</EM> is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to nonprofit organizations and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this <EM>Alert</EM>. <P>

If you have questions about the issues raised in this <EM>Issue Alert</EM>, please contact Hazen Graves at <a href="mailto:hgraves@faegre.com"> hgraves@faegre.com</a>.<P>


<HR>

<font size=-1>
