<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Intermediate Sanctions Pass Congress </title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>
<H2>Intermediate Sanctions Pass Congress
</H2><P>

<h4>by</h4>

<h4>Thomas S. Schroeder</h4>

<FONT SIZE=+2>O</FONT>n July 30, President Clinton is signed into law the Tax Payer Bill of Rights 2 bill containing, among things, provisions that allow the Internal Revenue Service to impose financial penalties on managers of exempt organizations and insiders who engage in transactions resulting in private inurement.  The penalties, commonly referred to as intermediate sanctions, provide the IRS with a long-sought enforcement mechanism short of exemption revocationa catastrophic, and in most cases, politically unacceptable, result.  The new law also requires that public charities provide a copy of their IRS Form 990 to anyone who requests one, and it increases the penalties for late filing of Form 990.<P>

Despite drawing support from both the public and private sectors, the intermediate sanctions provisions fell hostage to months of disagreement between the President and Congress over how best to balance the federal budget and, more recently, whether to raise the minimum wage.  Exempt organizations now need to act quickly to ensure that they are not among its first targets, especially in light of the laws retroactive reach to include transactions occurring on or after September 14, 1995.  <P>

<strong>Taxes on Excess Benefit Transactions</strong><br>

The new law creates a two-tiered system of penalty taxes in cases where an organization exempt from tax under section 501(c)(3) or 501(c)(4) of the Internal Revenue Code engages in an excess benefit transaction.  In such a case, the IRS could impose taxes of up to 200% on disqualified persons (primarily insiders and their relatives) who improperly benefit from an excess benefit transaction, and a 10% tax on organization managers who take part in the transaction knowing that it is improper.  The law does not impose any tax on the exempt organization itself.<P>

The law defines an excess benefit transaction as: (1) any transaction in which an economic benefit is provided to, or for the use of, any disqualified person if the value of the economic benefit exceeds the value of consideration (including performance of services) received by the organization; and (2) any transaction in which the amount of any economic benefit provided to, or for the use of, any disqualified person is determined in whole or in part by the revenues of the organization, provided that the transaction constitutes prohibited inurement under present law.  Excess benefit transactions include transactions in which a disqualified person engages in a non-fair-market-value transaction with an organization or receives unreasonable compensation.  The new law effectively extends private inurement prohibitions to social welfare organizations that are exempt under section 501(c)(4)organizations which until now had operated without any specific prohibitions against private inurement.<p>

<strong>Managers and Insiders Targeted </strong><br>

The law defines disqualified person to include any individual who is in a position to exercise substantial influence over the affairs of the organization, or any individual who was in such a position within the five-year period preceding the challenged transaction.  This definition includes not only officers and directors of public charities, hospitals, and such 501(c)(4) organizations as HMOs, but may also include private physicians serving on hospital medical staffs.  In addition, the law defines disqualified persons to include spouses, siblings, children, grandchildren, the spouses of children and grandchildren, and entities in which disqualified persons own more than 35% of the voting power or beneficial interest.<P>

The organization managers subject to the penalty tax include any officers, directors, or trustees of 501(c)(3) or (c)(4) organizations, or any individual[s] having powers or responsibilities similar to those of officers, directors, or trustees of the organization.  Presumably, any exempt organization employee who has the authority to approve or otherwise participate in transactions providing excess benefits to insiders may be subject to the tax, regardless of his or her official title or position. <P>

Previous versions of the intermediate sanctions bill had contained a statutory safe harbor which established a rebuttable presumption of reasonableness if the challenged transaction was approved by an independent board that relied upon appropriate comparability data (e.g., data concerning the compensation levels paid by similarly situated organizations) and if the board adequately documented the basis for its determination.  Although this safe harbor was deleted in the final version of the bill passed by Congress, it is expected to resurface in the new laws implementing regulations expected to be issued by the Treasury Department.<p>

<strong>Two-Tiered Penalties are Retroactive</strong><br>

The sanctions provided under the new law are analogous to the excise taxes currently imposed for excess lobbying activities and those that apply to private foundations.   The intermediate sanctions law imposes a tax equal to 25% of the amount of the excess benefit on the disqualified person who receives the benefit.  The excess benefit is equal to the amount by which the transaction price differs from fair market value, the amount of compensation exceeding reasonable compensation, or the amount of a prohibited transaction based on the organizations gross or net income.  Managers of organizations who participate in an excess benefit transaction knowing that the transaction is not reasonable are personally liable for a penalty tax of 10% of the amount of the excess benefit, subject to a maximum penalty of $10,000.  <P>

If the excess benefit transaction is not corrected within a specified time period (either before the mailing of a notice of deficiency or before the date on which the intermediate sanction is assessed, whichever is earlier), second-tier taxes can be imposed on the disqualified person equal to 200% of the amount of excess benefit. <P>

In one of the more surprising provisions of the law, taxable organizations which were formerly tax-exempt can be subject to intermediate sanctions where private benefit or inurement occurred during their exempt years.  Specifically, the law provides that an organization will be treated as an applicable tax-exempt organization subject to the excise taxes if, <EM>at any time during the five-year period proceeding the transaction</EM>, it was a 501(c)(3) or 501(c)(4) exempt organization.  This provision, along with the provision making intermediate sanctions applicable to transactions occurring <EM>on or after September 14, 1995</EM>, may come as a surprise even to those in the industry who were tracking the legislation.  Previous versions of the bill had provided for a two-year, rather than a five-year, reach over formerly exempt organizations.<p>

<strong>Additional Disclosure Requirements and Penalties</strong><br>

The Taxpayer Bill of Rights 2 also includes provisions requiring additional public disclosures and imposing increased penalties for failure to allow public inspection or file timely returns.  Specifically, exempt organizations must now provideincluding by mail, if requestedcopies of their annual returns and exemption applications to those who request them.  These disclosure requirements are in addition to the requirements under the present law (codified at Internal Revenue Code section 6104(e)) that organizations make their annual returns and exemption applications available for inspection at their principal office, including regional or district offices.  The new law prohibits organizations from charging more than a reasonable fee for copying and mailing costs.<P>

The law also increases the penalties for willful violation of the disclosure requirements from $1,000 to $5,000.  Moreover, the penalties for failure to file timely annual returns are increased from $10 per day to $20 per day, up to an new maximum penalty of $10,000 or the lesser of 5% of the organizations annual gross receipts.  If the organization has gross receipts in excess of $1,000,000, the penalties are $100 per day up to a maximum of $50,000.<P>

 The intermediate sanctions law provides the IRS with a far more practical tool than exemption revocation for policing abuses of the charities laws.  By the same token, the new law significantly expands the exposure of tax-exempt organization insiders to potential sanctions (albeit less devastating than exemption revocation) based upon criteria which the IRS and Treasury Department have yet to fully clarify.  Moreover, the law raises new questions, such as how expansively the definition of disqualified person will be read by enforcement officials, and whether those officials will deem incentive-based compensation reasonable under any circumstances.  While no clear answers to these questions exist at present, it is clear that exempt organizations need to carefully review all transactions with insiders, and should document their compensation decisions and other insider transactions as thoroughly as possible.
<P>
This <EM>Alert</EM> is intended solely to alert readers to legal issues relating to nonprofit organizations and is not intended as legal advice.  Further details may be necessary for a complete understanding of the information in this <EM>Alert</EM>. <P>

If you have questions about the issues raised in this <EM>Issue Alert</EM>, please contact Thomas Schroeder at <a href="mailto:tschroed@faegre.com"> tschroed@faegre.com</a>.<P>


<HR>

