<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> IRS Issues Final Section 162(m) Regulations </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<basefont size=3>

<H2>IRS Issues Final Section 162(m) Regulations</H2>

<H4>by</H4>

<h4>Peter J. Withoff</h4>

<p>

Continuing its practice of providing December guidance on Internal Revenue Code section 162(m), the IRS issued final section 162(m) Regulations (Final Regulations) on December 20, 1995.  Section 162(m) was originally added to the Internal Revenue Code by the Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993 and denies deductions by publicly held corporations for compensation paid to covered employees in excess of  $1 million.  The $1 million limit is subject to certain exceptions, by far the most significant of which is the exception for performance-based compensation.  Proposed Regulations were originally issued in December, 1993 and modified significantly in December, 1994.  Now, the section 162(m) Regulations have been issued as final Regulations.

<P>

Fortunately, the Final Regulations contain few surprises.  While the Final Regulations clarify a few additional items, they extensively follow the prior versions of the Proposed Regulations.  Of perhaps greatest significance, the transitional rules that were offered in the Proposed Regulations are now contained in the Final Regulations.

<P>

The Final Regulations clarify the treatment of award pools that some taxpayers maintain.  Under an award pool, the corporation creates an award pool, the size of which is dependent on achieving certain performance targets.  Individual participants are then given a percentage interest in the pool.  Some taxpayers had awarded percentage interests exceeding 100% of the pool, but then retained the flexibility to exercise negative discretion to reduce awards at the end of the year to the 100% level (or lower).  The Final Regulations conclude that this type of arrangement is not permissible.  The award percentages may not exceed 100% in the aggregate, and a reduction in one employee's bonus may not increase any other employee's bonus.  Recognizing that this conclusion was not obvious under the Proposed Regulations, the IRS granted transitional relief to taxpayers with a pre-existing impermissible award pool arrangement.  No additional guidance is provided on the permissible exercise of negative discretion.  This will continue to be a troublesome issue as taxpayers and the IRS attempt to define the difference between permissible negative discretion and impermissible non-performance based compensation. 

<P>

The Final Regulations also clarify the treatment of dividend equivalents paid with respect to unexercised stock options.  If such payments are not contingent upon exercise of the stock option, they will not taint an otherwise qualified performance based option.  On the other hand, if the employee's right to receive the dividend equivalents is contingent upon exercise of the option, the dividend equivalents are treated as a net reduction in the option price, causing the entire option to be treated as non-performance based.

<P>

Other issues that are dealt with in the Final Regulations are of much more limited applicability and include certain technical issues dealing with former officers of previously affiliated entities, companies that become publicly traded without an initial public offering, awards that are based on a percentage of salary, and special binding contract exclusions.

<P>

The Final Regulations continue to permit performance criteria to be described to shareholders in very general terms.  However, if the compensation committee retains the flexibility to set the actual targets under an approved performance goal without disclosing such targets to shareholders, the Final Regulations provide that shareholder approval must be obtained every five years.  This approval period is substantially shorter than the ten year period allowed for other tax-oriented compensation programs such as incentive stock option plans and employee stock purchase plans.  Since virtually all section 162(m) plans take advantage of the flexibility allowed under the Final Regulations not to disclose specific performance targets, shareholder reapproval generally will be required at five year intervals. 

<P>

In addition, the Final Regulations continue to maintain the distinction between an outside director for section 162(m) purposes and a disinterested director for securities law purposes.  For example, a former officer can never be an outside director but could be a disinterested director.  The definition of outside director also contains much more stringent limitations on directors who indirectly receive compensation from the publicly held corporation, including compensation received as an employee of certain entities doing business with the publicly held corporation.  While these distinctions are supportable under the legislative history to section 162(m), the statutory language does not require such distinctions.  It would have been helpful if the Final Regulations had broadened the definition of outside director to include any person who is a disinterested director for securities law purposes.

<P>

The finalization of the section 162(m) Regulations will hopefully bring some stability to this area of the law.  While unanswered questions remain, taxpayers will now have the benefit of final Regulations on which to rely.



<h4>Questions</h4>

If you have any questions, please contact Peter J. Withoff by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:pwithoff@faegre.com"><EM>pwithoff@faegre.com</EM></A>. 
<p>


