<HEAD><TITLE>1997 Intellectual Property - Recent Developments on the Internet</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="backgrnd.gif" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#FF7F76" ALINK="#EEDFFF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4>
<TABLE cellpadding=0>
<TR>
<TD width=120><FONT SIZE=+1 face="courier">Recent Developments on the Internet
</FONT>
</TD>

<TD colspan=2 align=left><p align=center><IMG SRC="fb.gif" ALT="Letterhead GIF" HSPACE=25 ALIGN=absbottom><br>

<IMG SRC="clear.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=1>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td></td>

<td><IMG SRC="clear.gif" WIDTH=55 HEIGHT=10 hspace=20></TD>

<td>
<p align=left>

<FONT SIZE=+2>T</font>he rapid growth of the Internet as a means for communicating information and transacting business has forced courts to apply traditional principles of law to cyberspace.  This session will examine recent developments in the law relating to the Internet, including personal jurisdiction, domain name disputes, junk e-mail, trademarks on the Internet, and the E-Data patent.
</p>
</td>
</tr>
<td>
</td>

