<HEAD><TITLE>1997 Intellectual Property - Selling and Buying Online</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="backgrnd.gif" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#FF7F76" ALINK="#EEDFFF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4>
<TABLE cellpadding=0>
<TR>
<TD width=120><FONT SIZE=+1 face="courier">Selling and Buying Online
</FONT>
</TD>

<TD colspan=2 align=left><p align=center><IMG SRC="fb.gif" ALT="Letterhead GIF" HSPACE=25 ALIGN=absbottom><br>

<IMG SRC="clear.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=1>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td></td>

<td><IMG SRC="clear.gif" WIDTH=55 HEIGHT=10 hspace=20></TD>

<td width=400>
<p align=left>

<FONT SIZE=+2>B</font>ecause of the vast marketing and communications potential associated with the use of the Internet and online services, many companies are building web sites and selling their goods and services online.  This session will explore issues associated with sales of goods and services in the online environment.  In particular, we will discuss a number of the legal concerns associated with selling retail goods over the Internet, such as the implications of accepting credit card orders, gathering and using data about clients and prospective clients for marketing purposes, enforcing licenses for software distributed under webwrap agreements, and selecting and enforcing appropriate warranties and limitations on liability.
</p>
</td>
</tr>
