<HEAD><TITLE>1997 Intellectual Property - Spiders on the Web:  Avoiding Liability in the Use of the Internet</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="backgrnd.gif" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#FF7F76" ALINK="#EEDFFF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4>
<TABLE cellpadding=0>
<TR>
<TD width=120><FONT SIZE=+1 face="courier">Spiders on the Web:  Avoiding Liability in the Use of the Internet
</FONT>
</TD>

<TD colspan=2 align=left><p align=center><IMG SRC="fb.gif" ALT="Letterhead GIF" HSPACE=25 ALIGN=absbottom><br>

<IMG SRC="clear.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=1>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td></td>

<td><IMG SRC="clear.gif" WIDTH=55 HEIGHT=10 hspace=20></TD>

<td width=400>
<p align=left>

<FONT SIZE=+2>U</font>se of the Internet may involve legal risks including claims for copyright infringement, libel and slander, harassment, trade secret misappropriation, and trademark infringement.  This presentation will focus on practical suggestions for businesses using the Internet or allowing employees access to the Internet.  Specific topics to be covered will include electronic mail policies, domain name selection, web page content, use of hyperlinks, and the development of bulletin boards.
</p>
</td>
</tr>
<td>
</td>

<td colspan=2 align=center>

<A HREF="ip97.htm"><IMG SRC="invite.gif" WIDTH=66 HEIGHT=14 hspace=0></a>
