<HEAD><TITLE>1997 Intellectual Property - Recent Developments - Trademarks</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="backgrnd.gif" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#FF7F76" ALINK="#EEDFFF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4>
<TABLE cellpadding=0>
<TR>
<TD width=120><FONT SIZE=+1 face="courier">Recent Developments - Trademarks
</FONT>
</TD>

<TD colspan=2 align=left><p align=center><IMG SRC="fb.gif" ALT="Letterhead GIF" HSPACE=25 ALIGN=absbottom><br>

<IMG SRC="clear.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=1>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td></td>

<td><IMG SRC="clear.gif" WIDTH=55 HEIGHT=10 hspace=20></TD>

<td width=400>
<p align=left>

<FONT SIZE=+2>T</font>his session presents our annual review of recent developments in the always-entertaining world of trademarks and trade dress.  This year's session will address, among other topics, the developing case law interpreting the year-old Federal Trademark Dilution Act, the Warnervision opinions and their impact on intent-to-use applications, recent attempts to register sound marks, and the year's legislative developments.  The session will close with Felicia Boyd's traditional pronouncement of the Best (and Worst) of 1996, a fast-paced and energetic review of the silly and the sublime from the trademark and trade dress opinions of 1996. 
</p>
</td>
</tr>
<td>
</td>

<td colspan=2 align=center>

<A HREF="ip97.htm"><IMG SRC="invite.gif" WIDTH=66 HEIGHT=14 hspace=0></a>
