<H1>May 1996 Newsletter</H1>
<P>Welcome to Short Cuts, your monthly electronic publication keeping you
informed about Interaid&#146;s  plans to use the Internet to link schools in
Africa, Asia and the Caribbean with their British counterparts.  
</P>
<P>Interaid has been particularly active this month. Our attempt to create a
global school has caught the imagination of the British media and Interaid&#146;s
founder Nick Short, has featured in local and national press and on radio.  
</P>
<P>Our range of  Microsoft training software HOVI Help has increased and we
have been able to take on new workers to speed up our product development.  We
have submitted our software for review by some of Britain&#146;s leading
computer magazines. So far, the response has been generally favourable.  
</P>
<P>The continued success of  Hovi Help will make good our promise to create a
global so we shall not be resting on our laurels. New techniques and features
have been added to HOVI Help to enhance its appeal to first-time and
intermediate computer users. 
</P>
<P>The task of getting schools on line has proved as great as we imagined.
However, contacts have been established and we are particularly pleased with the
response we have received from the Ministry of Education in South Africa. There
is a keen interest in our plans and we can not act soon enough.  Keep your
comments coming in to Short Cuts. We reply to each message. Enjoy  
</P>
<P>Nigel Smith (editor)</P>
<P><BR></P>
<H2>IN THE NEWS    
</H2>
<H3>WORDS, WORDS, WORDS 
</H3>
<P>Oxford University&#146;s 676-year-old Bodleian Library, holds 5.6 million
books with a word count of more than 700 billion. Computer experts have
predicted that they will be able to catalogue the entire collection onto just
six Compact Discs over the next ten years.  
</P>
<H3>ORACLE MARCH ON  
</H3>
<P>Predicting the end of the PC comes Oracle, chief trumpeter of the Net
Computer (NC). Oracle claims the NC will supplant the PC in the home and office
because it offers less expensive access to the Internet and Intranet, a basic
Internet system with enhanced security, which enables the publication of
internal web sites. 
</P>
<P>Microsoft, Compaq, Sun, Philips and Apple are all rumoured to be producing
their own home Internet systems which could be available this summer.  
</P>
<H3>BLAIR&#146;S  INTERNET PLEDGE TO SCHOOLS 
</H3>
<P>British Labour Party leader Tony Blair, reaffirmed in a keynote speech this
month that if elected his government will ensure that &#147;every school and
college will be connected up to the developing information superhighway.&#148; 
</P>
<P>Mr Blair has set up a panel under the chairmanship of Dennis Stevenson which
will investigate the challenges involved in linking educational institutions to
the Internet.  The panel comprises teachers, business people, financiers and
educationalists and has been asked to identify the main technological choices
available, their consequences for the national curriculum and teacher training
and how Labour&#146;s plans can be funded by a private-public partnership.   The
panel is expected to report by summer&#146;s end.    
</P>
<H2>NEWS FEATURE      
</H2>
<H3>THE SUPERHIGHWAY&#146;S GOLDEN GOOSE  
</H3>
<P>Students of the future will learn by computer, will be taught by computer in
virtual universities open 24 hours a day and will take their examinations by
computer.  The crowded, stuffy lecture theatre will be a thing of the past. The
nervous tension of the examination room may well go the same way. Pen, paper and
crib sheets will be the cherished relics of a distant era.   Virtual students
will be able to select their own teaching schedule, work at their own pace and
have access to a tutor, library and a virtual student union association where
surfers can net-graze to their heart&#146;s content. Welcome to the new world
order of the Cybergrad. 
</P>
<P>Within 10 years, the number of Internet-users world-wide will exceed 100
million. This and the sheer capacity of the Internet to transform the provision
of education and the methods by which students learn, are the current obsessions
of university chancellors, now sniffing out every opportunity to bring in more
revenue for their embattled institutions. 
</P>
<P>Distance learning is the new buzz word among academics and the race is now
on to make real the concept of using the Internet to educate students from Accra
to Acapulco in the comfort of their own homes. 
</P>
<P>Professor Diana Laurillard, the pro-Vice Chancellor of Britain&#146;s Open
University claims that her institution has already committed &#163;10 million to
investigating the potential of distance learning and  numbers 15,000 students
with access to its on-line network.   Talks are already underway between the
university&#146;s academics and business leaders with a view to pioneering a new
programme of courses for foreign students.  Professor Laurillard told the
British Daily Express newspaper that the Open University wanted to: &#147;Integrate
the complexity of technology with course structure to expand the options open to
students.   &#147;The technology aspect opens up whole new horizons for research
with access to vast resources of information around the world.&#148;  According
to the university, students of some 59 courses use the Internet, bulletin boards
and electronic discussion groups during their academic work and the university
has allocated &#163;1.25 million towards expanding the new technology used in
the delivery of its curriculum. 
</P>
<P>The Open University has also set up the 30-strong Knowledge Media Institute
(KMI) to investigate how  multi-media can enhance learning.  The attraction of
distance learning by computer is obvious. It may relieve some of the financial
costs, on both sides, of delivering an educational curriculum to foreign
students. Moreover, it may help to stem the brain drain from South to North and
make available research material which will enable academics to keep up to date
where ever they may be located. 
</P>
<P>Yet it is the very flexibility of learning by computer which has encouraged
institutions such as the Open University to look kindly on the system.  The Open
University&#146;s current distance learning techniques require students to watch
or video-record television transmissions which often air late in the evening or
early hours of the morning. Work is prepared by students in isolation and sent
to lecturers for appraisal.   Many Open University students complain of the
isolation they feel which is only punctuated by the occasional study weekends
and retreats. 
</P>
<P>The virtual universities of the future will offer students visual
interaction with lecturers and provide on-line study groups.  Indeed, the
prestigious North American Yale and Harvard universities now offer students the
world over the chance to attend via an international video-conferencing link
beamed by satellite.    
</P>
<H2>COMMENT                     
</H2>
<P>Each month, we invite readers of these pages to give their personal view on
matters affecting development, education or information technology. 
</P>
<P>This month, Malcolm King, a natural resources consultant, gives his personal
account of  development &#145;African style.&#146;   
</P>
<H3>PLAYING THE DEVELOPMENT GAME   
</H3>
<P>For something so apparently simple, development is a maddening term to get
people to agree upon. Everyone thinks they know what it means but then for each
person consulted it has different nuances.  &#147;Oh yes,&#148; said one friend.
&#147;Development is definitely progress towards greater freedom, more skills
and material well-being.&#148;  Comprehensive, I thought, until I asked another
who said that development can also mean the provision of a safe and reliable
water supply, road building and agricultural development. 
</P>
<P>For others, it is equally the availability of teachers, volunteers and
assorted experts to bring their collective expertise to bear on particular
issues which defy local competence.  Then again, there are those who give
development the widest scope possible. For example, one British aid agency in
Kenya negotiated with government authorities to bring to the country a cricket
coach who would improve local standards. Basketball &#145;experts&#146; have
already done tours of duty on behalf of America&#146;s Peace Corps. 
</P>
<P>Of course, all of these definitions are worthy of consideration but perhaps
it is this very flexibility that has given development something of a bad name. 
Drawing together all of the above explanations leads to the general conclusion
that development at its most positive should aim to improve and uplift what
exists currently.   Yet when this maxim is applied in any examination of
development in Africa, the result is sobering. In the 30 years since most
African countries gained their independence, the evidence available to justify
any association with the words development or progress is subject to doubt. </P>
<P>Africa has changed all right but how much of it has been for the better? 
The continent can throw up precious few exemplars to make good all the work done
and the words spoken by the serried ranks of government ministers,
non-governmental organisations and donor financiers.  Africa, the playground of
the rogue and the well-intentioned, can hardly be championed as a shining model
of the successful implementation of development theories proposed by the legions
of consultants who have offered their expensive expert analysis. 
</P>
<P>In all fairness, doubt should not be cast upon the genuine development work
which continues little remarked the length and breadth of Africa and has done so
for the past three decades.   Few can seriously argue that the improvements to
infrastructure and communications have not made a huge difference to communities
hitherto isolated.  Equally, it is unquestionably true that carefully appraised
and applied water projects or immunisation programmes have contributed
enormously to the betterment of people&#146;s lives. 
</P>
<P>Yet the overriding impression left by too many development projects is one
of missed opportunities.  Who is to blame? The usual suspects can be rounded up
and used as defence witnesses in the case  against development. Mischievous
governments, unscrupulous multi-nationals, widespread corruption, climatic
stress, over-reliance on commodities, impossible foreign debt schedules, ethnic
disputes and the ravages of neo-colonialism all take their places rightfully as
contributors to Africa&#146;s malaise.  But should United Nations programmes,
NGOs, donor organisations and aid agencies escape their share of the blame?  
Surely, after more than 30 years it is time to hold such organisations up to the
full glare of public scrutiny and ask of them a few hard questions. 
</P>
<P>Why is it that all the most important economic and social indices governing
individual quality of life and national well-being reflect so unfavourably on
Africa when there is so much development work taking place across the continent?
 In these circumstances, who and what is being developed?  If Africa has first
call on the world&#146;s experts, supplemented by a thriving home-grown
development &#145;industry&#146; which exists presumably to accelerate progress
and wealth generation, what are these development professionals doing as the
continent continues its economic decline? 
</P>
<P>The 1990 United Nations review of Africa&#146;s commodity problems, revealed
that the continent has 28 of the world&#146;s 42 poorest nations.  The same
report highlighted the decline in Africa&#146;s economic fortunes at a time of 
a rapid population explosion, perpetuating environmental deterioration and an
ever increasing dependence on food imports.
</P>
<P>
During the 1980&#146;s, only six of Africa&#146;s 50 states experienced growth
exceeding more than two per cent per annum. Since 1980, income per head in
Africa has declined every year, although some analysts point to recent
improvements in countries such as Uganda and Ghana.  Moreover, in 1988, Africa
earned $18 billion dollars from the sale of its commodities, excluding oil, on
the international markets. In real terms, this was 28 per cent lower than in
1980 and 35 per cent less than the sum received in 1970.  Published data of this
kind does nothing but confirm the perception that Africa has ceased to develop
economically in comparison with other parts of the world and advances the charge
of the pessimists that this situation will only worsen.  Something clearly is
awry. </P>
<P>So much effort, so many projects, so great the number of experts when the
aggregate result is so infuriatingly meagre.  Of course, it is not wise to
censure NGOs, donors and development agencies too severely when the trying
conditions they are often forced to work under are taken into consideration.
</P>
<P>
It is also true to say that the odds against improvement, progress and
development on the African continent do seem daunting especially given the
current international economic position.  But let us not be too charitable.
Development has &#147;failed&#148; because it has become a game, a righteous
indulgence which has become somehow removed from the real lives of the
communities it was intended to serve. 
</P>
<P>The game goes something like this. Development agencies petition foreign
donors with elaborate and well meaning proposals requiring vital funding.  
Money is donated accordingly to the favoured projects which begin amid scenes of
widespread joy and energy. Evaluation is often haphazard. Failure all too
frequently ensues by which time the donor has forgotten about the project and
moved on to other interests, leaving the way clear for the agency to demand more
money for another absolutely vital concern.  Even failure itself does not always
demand a critical review. Generous allowances are made and excuses all too often
receive a fairer hearing than they might deserve.  A grotesque parody, you might
think but I would wager that it remains closer to the truth than some dare
admit. 
</P>
<P>
&#147;Progress&#148; has become something of a merry-go-round, development
agencies and their foreign sponsors twirling arm in arm while Africa awaits the
results.  Donor organisations, NGOs, environment and development agencies have
all too often been at fault in their choice of projects.  Kenya&#146;s
disastrous Turkwell Dam and the &#145;white-elephant&#146; fish processing plant
at Turkhana, are but mere cameos of development fiascos across Africa. 
</P>
<P>As the development sector blossoms, a development culture flourishes and
sloth and waste set in. With the most emotive of working briefs to dispel
criticism, NGOs in cohoots with their foreign donor counterparts, have become
adept at junketing.  The circuit of conferences, workshops and &#145;brainstorming
sessions,&#146; spans the globe. No country is too far flung to host one
activity or another. </P>
<P>Many a senior development worker has toured the world in the name of
progress.  It is not uncommon to find NGO and development agency representatives
staying in expensive hotels and eating nouvelle cuisine while they discuss the
effects of poverty, malnutrition and under-development in their home countries. 
On top of all of this, participants at such conferences can expect to receive
payment for their attendance. Those who were present at a six day &#145;development&#146;
workshop in Nakuru, Kenya in August 1994, pocketed $240 in hard currency &#147;expenses&#148;
just for turning up, even though the costs of their travel, board and lodging
were met by the conference&#146;s sponsor. 
</P>
<P>It is churlish to suggest that little of substance emerges from such
workshops or that more would be achieved if delegates gathered together in grim,
austere surroundings. Conferences are important opportunities to network and
share ideas with like-minded people. In developing countries, they are often
crucial in mobilising a national action plan.  Yet, by establishing the practice
of  paying delegates and installing them in plush hotels, organisers have become
hostage to the curse of the  &#147;going rate.&#148;  Failure to pay an
anticipated sum in hard currency could lead to a conference being abandoned by
the very people it was designed to attract. </P>
<P>A chicken and egg dilemma yes, but surely one the donors and their local
agents might have seen coming.  Foresight however, is all to uncommon given the
size of the bureaucracy spawned in the name of development. This cumbersome,
conservative and self-regarding behemoth devours enormous sums on salaries,
trips, projects, property and additional &#147;expenses.&#148; How much of this
vast fortune can truly be justified?  Moreover, far too much money is spent on
what appears to be passing whims. This years fad - population control. Last year&#146;s
- tree nurseries. And next year? The runners include sustainable energy projects
and women&#146;s groups! All very worthy but real progress requires strategic,
long-term planning and a clear vision rather than the multi-focus approach which
currently prevails.
</P>
<P>
The sheer number of players adds to this confusion. With the myriad NGO
proposals competing alongside government programmes and foreign-aided private
schemes, there is tremendous scope for deliberate misadventure.  In presenting
the case against development as it reveals itself now, it is not my intention to
challenge its legitimacy entirely, only to point out its failings.  Development
agencies can play a responsible role in improving the fortunes of Africa&#146;s
citizens. If they fail to do so, their very credibility may soon be open to
question.     
</P>
<P>So, is Malcolm King right? Is development a game played by the self-seeking
to Africa&#146;s detriment? Tell us what you think.   
</P>
<H2>
NEXT MONTH 
</H2>
<P>
1. More Interaid news 
</P>
<P>2. The Internet&#146;s false promise!  British media celebrity Janet
Street-Porter takes aim at the Net and gives both barrels to its high priests -
the Techno Nerds. 
</P>
<P>3. A computer specialist gives a personal view of the obstacles facing the
global school. 
</P>     
