<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Ogoni News December</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#db6316">
<P><CENTER></CENTER>
<P>Dear friends, supporters and interested readers,<BR>
<BR>
At last, we have our own site where we can keep you in touch with<BR>
the Ogoni news and the issues which are important for all<BR>
minority groups on this planet. We have to thank all the Oneworld<BR>
Online team who have to date been making sure that the problems<BR>
of the Ogoni's have not gone unnoticed on the Internet. Now we<BR>
have been given the opportunity to get the message out to you<BR>
with our own site and we hope that we will be able to make a good<BR>
job of it.<BR>
<BR>
<H3>THE OGONI COMMUNITY ASSOCIATION</H3>
<BR>
The Ogoni Community Association - United Kingdom (OCA-UK), was<BR>
set up in 1993 by Ogoni people living in Britain as an affiliate<BR>
of the Movement for the Survival of the Ogoni People. <BR>
Its remit is to focus world attention on the plight of the Ogoni<BR>
people through peaceful and non-violent campaigning and to<BR>
support and promote their emancipation through the Ogoni Bill of<BR>
Rights adopted by general acclaim of the Ogoni people on the 26th<BR>
day of August 1990 at Bori, Rivers State, Nigeria.<BR>
<BR>
<H3>THE OGONI FOUNDATION</H3>
<BR>
The Ogoni Foundation has been set up by the OCA-UK to relieve<BR>
poverty and sickness by appropriate charitable (whether medical<BR>
rehabilitation, financial or other) assistance in any part of the<BR>
world and in particular (but without prejudice to the generality<BR>
of the foregoing) by the provision of aid to the needy in Nigeria<BR>
or persons formerly resident there. It also aims to advance the<BR>
education of people living in the United Kingdom and Nigeria in<BR>
the Ogoni languages and traditions and cultures by the provision<BR>
of a Saturday school. Finally, it will help to protect and<BR>
preserve the environment in Africa and other parts of the world<BR>
by the provision of educational leaflets and projects and by<BR>
assisting the local conservation projects.<BR>
<H3>CONTENTS</H3>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#what"><B>WHAT IS HAPPENING?</a><LI></B><A HREF="#claude"><B>PROFESSOR
CLAUDE AKE RESIGNS FROM THE NDES</a></B>
<LI><A HREF="#ogoni"><B>OGONI UPDATE</a></B>
<LI><A HREF="#gas"><B>THE LIQUIFIED NATURAL GAS PROJECT</a></B>
<LI><A HREF="#questions"><B>QUESTIONS? AND ANSWERS</a></B>
<LI><A HREF="#events"><B>EVENTS</a></B>
<LI><A HREF="#help"><B>WHAT YOU CAN DO TO HELP</a></B>
<LI><A HREF="#publications"><B>PUBLICATIONS OF INTEREST</a></B>
<LI><A HREF="#contact"><B>CONTACT ADDRESSES</a></B>
</UL>
<HR>
<H3><a name="what"></a>
WHAT IS HAPPENING?</H3>
<BR>
Our first item brings back the memory of Ken Saro-Wiwa and raises<BR>
a few of the issues which are still important after his death.<BR>
<H4>A LETTER BY KEN SARO-WIWA</H4>
<BR>
29th July<BR>
<BR>
The Editor<BR>
The Guardian<BR>
London<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Dear Sir,<BR>
<BR>
I wish to thank you for publishing my letter in your edition of<BR>
18th may, 1995. Since that publication, I have received numerous<BR>
letters of support from the British public. As I have not been<BR>
able to answer these letters individually, please permit me to<BR>
thank, through you, all those who have sent me cheering words of<BR>
encouragement and solidarity.<BR>
<BR>
Most of those who have written have indicated their intention to<BR>
write to the British Government, their MP's or EP's, party<BR>
leaders, Amnesty International or the Nigerian Government. All<BR>
of which are welcome, and in place. Except that my predicament,<BR>
and the predicament of the Ogoni people require just a little<BR>
more urgency, in a different direction.<BR>
<BR>
At the root of my travails lies Shell, the multi-national oil<BR>
giant which has exploited, traduced and driven the Ogoni people<BR>
to extinction in the last three decades. The company has taken<BR>
over 30 billion dollars out of Ogoni and has left a completely<BR>
devastated environment and a trail of human misery.<BR>
<BR>
When I organised the Ogoni people to peacefully protest Shell's<BR>
ecological war, the Company, without the least hesitation or<BR>
compunction, invited the Nigerian military to use the lethal arms<BR>
supplied by the British Government on unarmed Ogoni people while<BR>
they were sleeping in their beds. Thousands have been murdered,<BR>
hundreds of thousands driven into the bush and tents of villages<BR>
flattened to the ground.<BR>
<BR>
Shell's coup de grace has been to goad their ally, the Nigerian<BR>
military dictatorship, to arraign me before a kangaroo military<BR>
Tribunal whose manifest unfairness and injustice have been<BR>
condemned by Article 19 (ed. International Centre on Censorship),<BR>
the Law Society of England and Wales and the Bar Human Rights<BR>
Committee of England and Wales which jointly sent a British QC,<BR>
Michael Birnbaum, to watch the Tribunal at work and play. For<BR>
good measure, Shell is represented by counsel, said to be holding<BR>
a watching brief for the Company, in what is supposed to be a<BR>
criminal trial. What the company is doing is supervising an<BR>
gloating over my torture and inevitable condemnation. Which is<BR>
meant to show the people's of the Niger delta that they dare not,<BR>
cannot, challenge the destruction of their environment by<BR>
almighty Shell.<BR>
<BR>
The World Bank, after studying the Niger delta, has warned that<BR>
&quot;an urgent need exists to implement mechanisms to protect the<BR>
life and health of the region's inhabitants and its ecological<BR>
systems from further deterioration.&quot;. The European Parliament has<BR>
also stated that oil exploration in the Niger delta has turned<BR>
the area into an &quot;environmental nightmare&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
Instead of facing the consequences of its ecological war on the<BR>
delta, stopping that war and paying reparations to its victims,<BR>
Shell is coldly planning and executing the destruction of vocal<BR>
opposition as led by me. And given the brutal nature of the<BR>
current military dictatorship in Nigeria which depends entirely<BR>
on the petrodollars and diplomatic support supplied by Shell,<BR>
there is little doubt that Shell will see me to the gallows or<BR>
have me shut up as soon as possible. (note: Shell's involvement<BR>
in making an appeal for clemency was too little and came too<BR>
late.)<BR>
<BR>
I have one suggestion for those whose conscience has been<BR>
disturbed by my story: boycott all Shell products. Picket Shell<BR>
garages. Do not allow them to profit by their destruction of the<BR>
people and ecology of the Niger delta.<BR>
<BR>
And, lest I forget, please do not allow the kangaroo military<BR>
tribunal which is supposedly trying me to condemn me to death for<BR>
a crime I know nothing about and you then make appeals for<BR>
clemency to a military dictatorship which has neither legitimacy,<BR>
nor conscience. Support the call for worldwide boycott of<BR>
Nigerian oil. Help destroy what the Wall Street Journal calls the<BR>
&quot;slick alliance&quot; of Shell and the Nigerian military dictators
and<BR>
so save life and the environment of the Niger delta.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
On the oil fields of Ogoni<BR>
laughter lies buried in blow-outs,<BR>
death romps to the drums of greed<BR>
in thick shells of earth's riches.<BR>
On the oil fields of Ogoni<BR>
exploring black gold efficiently<BR>
is the maxim of the mad mogul<BR>
and human life but cold obstacle<BR>
in the frenzied path of a search<BR>
guided by blood and flow charts,<BR>
margins, murder, rigs and leases<BR>
and out of season christmas trees.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Ken Saro-Wiwa<BR>
Port Harcourt<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</B><I>This letter, written by Ken from his prison cell has a terrible<BR>
ring of premonition. We all know that Ken's life was taken from<BR>
him at 11.30am on friday 10th November 1995, together with Dr.<BR>
Bariem Kiobel, John Kpuinen, Baribo Bera, Saturday Dobee, Felix<BR>
Nwate, Nordu Eawo, Paul Levura and Daniel Gbokoo. It seems now<BR>
that General Abacha, the military dictator responsible for the<BR>
death of these courageous men, is trying to lay the blame on the<BR>
men who advise him. Let us make our stand point clear: anyone who<BR>
did not publicly speak out in defence of these nine men, and<BR>
certainly all those who were in a position of power to prevent<BR>
this act of murder, can find no peace and no excuse for their<BR>
actions. Ken Saro-Wiwa, a very great man, with a vision that was<BR>
important for all threatened peoples, is no longer and nothing<BR>
can bring him back. We take strength in the legacy that he left<BR>
behind - the will to fight, peacefully, for our rights and for<BR>
the rights of all minorities over this whole planet. OCA-UK<BR>
supports a boycott of Shell because Shell has got to realise that<BR>
they cannot destroy an area and get away with it. OCA-UK supports<BR>
an oil embargo of Nigeria because it is oil which sustains the<BR>
military dictatorship and it is an oil embargo that will cause<BR>
its downfall.<BR>
</I><BR>
<HR>
<H3><a name="claude"></a><BR>
PROFESSOR CLAUDE AKE RESIGNS FROM THE NDES</H3>
<BR>
The next piece of news we have for you is a press statement by<BR>
Professor Claude Ake. Professor Ake is the Director of a think<BR>
tank called the Center for Advanced Social Science (CASS), based<BR>
in Nigeria. He is also laureate of the Nigerian National Order<BR>
of Merit, Nigeria's most coveted honour. He was a good friend to<BR>
Ken Saro-Wiwa and when Ken was in detention visited him and<BR>
helped to raise his morale. Professor Ake is not an Ogoni but<BR>
when he decided to serve on the Niger Delta Environment Survey<BR>
(NDES) we were very pleased since he would be an impartial,<BR>
honest and reliable representative. In the beginning, we<BR>
encouraged the formation of the NDES, though always made clear<BR>
our reservations and the need to take not only the science of the<BR>
environment into account but also the social and economic<BR>
aspects. Professor Ake's press statement says the rest for us.<BR>
<H4>PRESS STATEMENT</H4>
<H2>Resignation from the Steering Committee<BR>
of the Niger Delta Environment Survey</H2>
<BR>
      It is with regret that I announce my resignation from the<BR>
Steering Committee of the Niger Delta Environmental Survey (NDES)<BR>
which took effect from November 16, 1995.<BR>
<BR>
      I must confess that the decision to serve on that committee<BR>
has been a difficult one to begin with given the oil companies'<BR>
past record of arrogance, insensitivity to the humanity of host<BR>
communities and to environmental sustainability. But in the end<BR>
I decided to serve encouraged by Ken Saro-Wiwa who argued that<BR>
NDES could be a window of opportunity for constructive<BR>
engagement.<BR>
<BR>
      Having decided to serve, I suspended my doubts and tried to<BR>
believe that the oil industry in Nigeria might quite conceivably<BR>
be willing to live up to its social responsibilities. As the<BR>
designated &quot;representative&quot; of the communities in the Committee,<BR>
I tried to sensitize the Committee to community concerns and to<BR>
develop a mechanism to facilitate communications between NDES in<BR>
particular and the Oil industry in general with Communities. This<BR>
was reflected in the fact that at the stake holders meeting in<BR>
Port Harcourt on October 24, the Ijaw National Congress, Ogbakor<BR>
Ikwerre, Ogba Solidarity, Ogbakor Etche, Movement for the<BR>
Survival of the Ogoni People, Oyigbo Forum, Bonny Indigenous<BR>
Peoples Federation, Ndoni Community Association, Uzugbari Ekpeye<BR>
and O'Elobo Eleme presented a common position paper on NDES and<BR>
it was clear that the acknowledged success of the meeting was<BR>
partly due to the fact that despite their doubts they too felt<BR>
that something positive could come out of NDES.<BR>
<BR>
      Unfortunately, the realities intruded. It was clear that<BR>
NDES did not have the enthusiastic support of the Oil industry.<BR>
Apart from that, there was nothing in the posture and practices<BR>
of the major oil companies, Shell, NAOC, Elf and Mobil to signal<BR>
the fact that NDES could be regarded as a forward movement.<BR>
Rather as the agenda of NDES developed, it became difficult<BR>
despite the good number of competent and well-meaning people on<BR>
the Steering Committee to expect much from NDES.<BR>
<BR>
      I was already seriously considering resignation before the<BR>
tragic turn of the Ogoni struggle culminating in the execution<BR>
of Ken Saro-Wiwa and his colleagues. I do not think that the oil<BR>
industry in Nigeria, particularly Shell whose crude practises and<BR>
insensitivity engendered the struggle in the first place did<BR>
enough to diffuse the situation.<BR>
<BR>
      Their reaction to the tragedy was more unfortunate still.<BR>
They have in effect been assuring everyone who cares to listen<BR>
that nothing has changed and nothing will change. I cannot help<BR>
thinking that even silence would have been better than such<BR>
unfeeling belligerence. For, given the rising tide of resentment<BR>
in the oil producing communities, this posture is bound to be<BR>
catastrophic for Nigeria and self-defeating for the oil<BR>
companies.<BR>
<BR>
      These circumstances have left me no choice but to resign.<BR>
For they have, to my mind, transformed NDES into an unwelcome<BR>
diversion and rendered it morally unacceptable.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Claude Ake<BR>
<BR>
</B><I>We are now waiting to see what will happen with the Steering<BR>
Committee in which we now have little confidence.<BR>
</I><BR>
<HR>
<H3><a name="ogoni"></a>
OGONI UPDATE</H3>
<BR>
The situation in Ogoni remains critical. The army is there is<BR>
full force and strip searches in the middle of the street are not<BR>
uncommon. Church services are still being disrupted with no<BR>
mention of Ken Saro-Wiwa allowed. In fact, Ogoni has not been<BR>
allowed to mourn their leader; any mention of his name and a time<BR>
in a prison cell awaits you. <BR>
<BR>
In January another 19 Ogoni's will face the same kangaroo<BR>
Tribunal as Ken and the others. What does it take for the world<BR>
to wake up to the Nigerian repression? Does there need to be<BR>
another death or even 19? Are not the conditions in Ogoni already<BR>
enough to call for an oil boycott? We fear for the lives of all<BR>
Ogoni's and we hope against hope that the 19 men who are facing<BR>
the death penalty without right of appeal will be exonerated. In<BR>
a later issue we will tell you more about the 19 men. For now,<BR>
remember these names:<BR>
<BR>
<table><tr><td>Bariture Bano Lebee  </td><td>               Kagbara Basseh</td><BR>
<tr><td>John Banatu        </td><td>                         Adam Kaa</td><BR>
<tr><td>Babina Vizor            </td><td>              Sampson Ntignee</td><BR>
<tr><td>Pobgbara Zorzor         </td><td>                    Godwin Gbodoo</td><BR>
<tr><td>Friday Gburuma       </td><td>                 Samuel Asigha</td><BR>
<tr><td>Yedal Naasikpo         </td><td>               Nwinbari Papa</td><BR>
<tr><td>Paul Deekor               </td><td>                  Benjamin Kabari</td><BR>
<tr><td>Elijah Lekie Badom        </td><td>                  (alias Monday
Kabari)</td><BR>
<tr><td>Blessing Isreal           </td><td>                  Baribuma Kumanwe</td><BR>
<tr><td>Taagalo K. Monsi       </td><td>                     Ngbaa Baovi</td><BR>
</table>
<BR>
In the last few days we have heard that the Nigerian military<BR>
government is putting pressure on Ogoni chiefs to sign a document<BR>
to allow Shell back into Ogoni. Do not therefore be surprised to<BR>
read or hear that the Ogoni's have &quot;permitted&quot; Shell back into<BR>
Ogoni and that there is written evidence of this. This evidence<BR>
will have been obtained through the barrel of a gun and not<BR>
voluntarily given.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<a name="gas"></a>
<H3>THE LIQUIFIED NATURAL GAS PROJECT</H3>
<BR>
You may well have read in the papers that Shell and the Nigerian<BR>
LNG Ltd. have decided to go ahead with the Liquified Natural gas<BR>
(LNG) project. They have sold this project to the general public<BR>
as being the environmental answer. We refute this, since<BR>
technical reports show that all of the gas in the first years and<BR>
most of the gas subsequently, will come from new gas reserves and<BR>
not from gas that is currently being flared.<BR>
<BR>
Shell claimed to have carried out a comprehensive environmental<BR>
impact assessment (EIA) for the LNG project. An independent<BR>
consultant has been hired to assess the EIA and the results are<BR>
damning. Our press release on the subject reads as follows:<BR>
<H4>PRESS RELEASE</H4>
<BR>
dated 11th December 1995<BR>
<H2>NEW INDEPENDENT EVALUATION SHOWS SHELL'S<BR>
LACK OF ENVIRONMENTAL COMMITMENT</H2>
<BR>
The Ogoni Community Association UK are pleased that a new<BR>
document confirms their suspicions about poor environmental<BR>
statements which were prepared for the Nigerian Liquified Natural<BR>
Gas project. This is a project which Shell Petroleum has<BR>
committed their support to.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We are vindicated&quot; says Lazarus Tamana, President of the Ogoni<BR>
Community Association UK. &quot;We knew all along these environmental<BR>
Statements for the Liquified Natural Gas project were not<BR>
thoroughly researched. They were simply not up to acceptable<BR>
standards as far as we were concerned.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The new review shows how shallow the investigation of the<BR>
environmental impact of the LNG project was. According to Shell,<BR>
the prime reason for investing in this project was that if they<BR>
pulled out the &quot;environment would be hurt&quot; and that the LNG<BR>
&quot;plant will bring more benefits, with a great reduction in the<BR>
need for gas flaring by the oil industry.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
However, the review of the environmental statements shows us that<BR>
the Nigerian LNG investigation was incredibly superficial. The<BR>
independent review prepared by Dr. Phil Smith of Aquatic<BR>
Environmental Consultants, tells us the Nigerian environmental<BR>
report is &quot;repetitive&quot; and &quot;unilluminating&quot;. In addition
they<BR>
state &quot;there is a lack of local inputs on the ecology and socio-<BR>
economics of the study area.&quot; This has always been one of the<BR>
prime concerns held by OCA-UK.<BR>
<BR>
In contradiction to Shell's stated objectives - to reduce the<BR>
quantity of gas flaring in the region - Dr. Smiths review states:<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The reports do not appear to contain any information on how much<BR>
gas flaring will be reduced by the collection of gas. Without<BR>
this information the importance of the scheme in reducing gas<BR>
flaring cannot be assessed, and any environmental benefits from<BR>
reduced gas flaring are unquantified.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Lazarus Tamana said &quot;rather than taking firm steps to benefit the<BR>
environment, Nigerian LNG Ltd. is commissioning empty, vacuous<BR>
and insubstantial reports. I am pleased to see that the review<BR>
by the Aquatic Environmental Consultants simply strengthens our<BR>
case.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H3><a name="questions"></a>
QUESTIONS? AND ANSWERS</H3>
<BR>
There has been a lot of media coverage of the Ogoni issue and we<BR>
are pleased that so many people are interested in our struggle.<BR>
However, the coverage has not always been totally accurate and<BR>
may have led to questions forming in your mind about some of the<BR>
issues. Well, this is the place where we will try to answer any<BR>
queries you have. Send us your questions (address at the end) and<BR>
mention that you read this on our web site so that we can either<BR>
answer you on this site or personally.<BR>
<BR>
There has also been some 'fight-back' press from Shell, including<BR>
some advertisements in the major papers all around the world.<BR>
Well, here is the place for you to ask us any questions that<BR>
these Shell-ads raise in your mind.<BR>
<BR>
The Nigerian military dictatorship is also finally waking up to<BR>
the fact that the Ogoni's are able to get their story spread<BR>
across the world. They have placed a number of advertisements in<BR>
the papers to try to counteract the bad publicity which they are<BR>
getting (and deserve). Now is your chance to ask us any questions<BR>
about issues that seem unclear to you.<BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately, the loyalty of all Ogoni's to their people is not<BR>
what it should be. There are some people from Ogoni who say that<BR>
Ken was guilty and that he deserved to die. They are trying to<BR>
split the Ogoni people and to make deals with the Nigerian<BR>
dictatorship on behalf of the Ogonis. We wish that life was<BR>
simple but as you know there are always a few rotten apples in<BR>
the basket. In Ken's recently published book (see above) he<BR>
explains the history of this conflict and we refer you to that<BR>
book as a first reference. However, may be you can't get it or<BR>
you still have some questions. Send them in and we will do our<BR>
best to answer them.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H2><a name="events"></a>
EVENTS</H2>
<H3>THANKS</H3>
<BR>
Our many thanks to Green Screen who organised a memorial benefit<BR>
event at the Haymarket Theatre in London. Also thanks to all<BR>
those, too many to mention, for organising events in London,<BR>
York, Reading, Bristol, Oxford, Stratford, Cambridge, Leicester<BR>
and Derby to which members of OCA-UK were invited.<BR>
<H3>UPCOMING EVENTS</H3>
<BR>
If you want more details then call or write to us at the address<BR>
shown below.<BR>
<BR>
*     LONDON: 4th January is OGONI DAY. We will be celebrating<BR>
      but also remembering those murdered on the 10th November<BR>
      1995. There is a march starting at 11.30am from Shell<BR>
      Centre York Road entrance, Waterloo and again from the<BR>
      Nigerian High Commission in Northumberland Avenue at<BR>
      1.30pm. There is a service and Ogoni Day activities taking<BR>
      place from 3.00pm to 5.00pm in St. James Church, Picadilly.<BR>
      Please come - we need your support.<BR>
<BR>
*     LONDON: 5th January - African Liberation Support campaign<BR>
      and Workers International have a discussion forum at 7.30pm<BR>
      at the Brixton Recreation Centre.<BR>
<BR>
*     GLASGOW: 15th, 19th or 26th January - A discussion evening<BR>
      will be held on the Ogoni issues.<BR>
<BR>
*     OXFORD: 19th January - As part of Oxford City Council's<BR>
      'Festival of Black Culture' there will be an event focusing<BR>
      on the Ogoni issues.<BR>
<BR>
*     YORK: 26th January - the students at York University are<BR>
      organising an event at the Global and International Centre.<BR>
<BR>
*     CAMBRIDGE: 31st January - Cambridge 6th Form College are<BR>
      organising an equal opportunities morning looking at the<BR>
      environmental damage and the situation in Nigeria.<BR>
<BR>
*     OXFORD: 1st February - The University of Oxford Union are<BR>
      holding a debate on democracy in developing countries.<BR>
<BR>
*     DERBY: 15th February - the University of Derby, Faculty of<BR>
      European and International Studies is holding a lecture on<BR>
      Ogoni which will be presented by the General Secretary of<BR>
      OCA-UK and Mr. Douglas, a Nigerian Human Rights campaigner.<BR>
<BR>
*     MAIL ORDER: There is a limited edition copy of a dance mix<BR>
      CD which has been made in memory of Ken Saro-Wiwa,<BR>
      available on mail-order. Please check the Greenpeace<BR>
      w.w.w.-site for the address.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, if you are organising an event (seminar, talk or<BR>
whatever) or know someone who is doing so then please let us know<BR>
so that we can let everyone else know. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<a name="help"></a>
<H3>WHAT CAN YOU DO TO HELP?</H3>
<BR>
1.    You can register as a supporter with the OCA-UK. Call or<BR>
      write to the address below.<BR>
2.    You can send a donation made payable to: 'The Ogoni<BR>
      Community Association - UK' if you want it to go towards<BR>
      the campaign or 'The Ogoni Foundation' (charity<BR>
      registration number 1050502) if you want it to go to the<BR>
      charity side of the organisation.<BR>
3.    You can write and state your concerns about the human<BR>
      rights and environmental abuses in Ogoni specifically and<BR>
      Nigerian as a whole, to the Nigerian High Commissioner.<BR>
      Address: The Nigerian High Commission, Nigerian House, 9<BR>
      Northumberland Avenue, London WC2B 5NX, United Kingdom.<BR>
4.    You can demonstrate outside the Nigerian High Commission in<BR>
      your country whenever you want to as an individual. If<BR>
      there are any events organised by the OCA-UK and you are on<BR>
      our register of supporters, you will be informed about the<BR>
      event in advance.<BR>
5.    Boycott Shell: demonstrate outside Shell petrol stations;<BR>
      sell (all but one) investments, pension funds or shares you<BR>
      or your company may have in Shell. Write to the Chairman of<BR>
      Shell expressing your feelings on the matter.<BR>
      Address: John Jennings, Chairman, Shell Transport and<BR>
      Trading Company Ltd, Shell Centre, London SE1 7NA.<BR>
6.    Write to your Member of Parliament, Senator, Prime Minister<BR>
      or President and ask for a boycott of Nigerian oil.<BR>
7.    You can get more information from Greenpeace (0171-3545100)<BR>
      or Friends of the Earth (0171-4901555) on environmental<BR>
      campaigns and Amnesty International (0171-8146200) on human<BR>
      rights campaigns.<BR>
