<html><head><title>VSO Volunteers working for Peace and Reconstruction</title><!!keys:VSO></head><body><img align=left alt=" [ VSO Books ] " src="vso_pix/vso_logo.gif"><br clear=all><i>The material that follows has been provided by &nbsp;</i><a href="vso_info.html"> Voluntary Service Overseas</a><hr><p><center><h2>VSO Volunteers working for Peace and Reconstruction</h2></center>

VSO has programmes in countries including Cambodia, Eritrea, Guinea Bissau, Namibia, Nigeria, Uganda, Vietnam, Zimbabwe, South Africa, Belize, Sri Lanka, and in Eastern Europe.<p>

<b>Michael Craven is a Physiotherapist at the Cambodia Trust's Limb Fitting Centre in Kompong Som, Cambodia</b><p>

Each day Michael Craven is faced with the consequences of the 'killing fields' of Cambodia. There are an estimated 7 million landmines in Cambodia and injuries from land mine explosions result in 250 amputations every month. Michael Craven works with rural communities, fitting landmine victims with artificial limbs so that they can generate income by returning to farm their land.<p>

The aim is to get these people back to work so their families don't suffer.  Treatment at the Cambodia Trust's Limb Fitting Centre gives them a chance to earn a living for their families and lead normal, active lives.<p>

An important part of Michael Craven's work is setting up an outreach programme for the centre and training local outreach workers to run the programme. Persuading patients fitted with artificial limbs to return for regular 6-monthly checks is difficult, and the outreach programme encourages these checks.  It particularly targets women and children who, finding it more difficult to visit the town clinic, often remain untreated in their villages.<p>

<b>Catherine Lillington is an English Teacher working at the Khemera Project in Cambodia.</b><p>

Khemera helps Cambodian women to take responsibility for their future. Members of this women's group work together to realise their potential and play a full role in national development.  Established four years ago, Khemera is developing a credit programme, setting up child-care centres and training village women in leadership skills.<p>

For the Khmer-speaking women of Khemera, Cambodia's first local non-governmental organisation, learning English is about empowerment. Catherine Lillington's lessons allows access to local training courses and enables them to communicate with potential funders. <p>

Command of English enables the women to lobby for political advantage and financial support, and the work of VSO volunteers has allowed the group's Deputy-Director to represent and talk about Khemera's work overseas. This will allow Khemera, in collaboration with other NGOs, to play a strong role in advocating protection of human rights and promotion of democracy in Cambodia. <p> 

<b>Matthew Agnew is a carpentry instructor at Mai Habar Vocational Training Centre in Eritrea</b><p>

After a devastating 30-year civil war, the people of Eritrea are determined to regenerate their country.  But for whole generations of Eritreans the only formal education was being taught how to fight.  Now there is a strong government commitment to regain lost technical skills.<p>

Mai Habar, an old army base, has been turned into a training college for disabled ex-fighters, and VSO technical instructors like Matthew are helping them become economically active and independent.  The college also aims to recruit other disadvantaged groups, including war widows and former refugees returning from neighbouring Ethiopia.<p>

<b>Monica Golding is a Mini-league sports coach in South Africa</b><p>

Sports development is an exciting new initiative for VSO, and Monica is the second of six sports volunteers to be posted to South Africa this year.  Mini-League is a team ballsport similar to mini-rugby which has been specially adapted to township life, and Monica coaches children aged 5-13 in Alexandra, a township outside Johannesburg.  <p>

The game can be played with teams of different sizes, abilities and ages, and the need for space and equipment is minimal.  The aim of the scheme is to give more people in the townships access to sports facilities, offering a sense of direction and commmitment to young people in the poorest parts of the country.<p><hr><p>
©Copyright: Voluntary Service Overseas 1995<hr><a href="index.html"><img src="vso_pix/vso_logo2.gif"> VSO Home Page</a><hr></body></html>

