<b><font size=4 color=5a1313>Panos AIDS Features</font></b><p>


<ul>

<b><li><a href="china.html">AIDS Prevention Better Than No Cure: China's "Last" Chance?</a></b><br>
Although the incidence of HIV infection in China is relatively low, the government has announced a plan for long term prevention and control of  HIV/AIDS. With an education programme and a crackdwn on drug abuse and prostitution, the government hopes to prevent China from becoming the  new HIV battleground, report Yuan Ye  and  Li Nu'er.<p>


<b><li><a href="aids_vaccine.html">Aids Vaccine Trials</a></b><br>
Rows over testing, and a lack of funds, have hindered the search for an AIDS
vaccine. Now, despite allegations that Ugandan soldiers have been used as
'guinea-pigs', trials on a promising new experimental vaccine are boosting
hopes, write Helen Epstein and Lillian Nsubuga - AIDS Vaccine Trials Set to
Go Ahead in Uganda.<p>

<b><li><a href="world_aids.html">World Aids Day</b></a><br>
Signs of hope.<p>


<li><b><a href="brazil_sep96.html">Brazilian Activists Win AIDS-Treatment Battle</a></b> <br>
A new drug therapy has raised hopes that AIDS may become a manageable condition. Though too expensive for the majority of people, activists have forced the government to purchase these drugs for all HIV + citizens in Brazil. By Martin Foreman<p>


<li><b><a href="aids3.html">Aids: Science at crossroads</a></b><br>Over the past 10 years, much of the research on AIDS has centred on tryingto find a cure or a vaccine, with very limited results.<p>

<li><b><a href="india.html">India's race against time</a></b><br> There is a huge danger facing countries which respond too slowly to the AIDS threat, stresses Daleep Mukarji, former head of the Christian Medical Association of India (CMA).<p>
</ul>

