<html>
<head>
<title>
NOMINATIONS NEEDED FOR BEST "UNTOLD STORIES" FROM WORLD'S 

POOREST COUNTRIES</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2><font face="arial, helvetica">
ACTIONAID RESPONDS TO NEW OECD REPORT</font></h2>
<font face="arial, helvetica">



ACTIONAID has dismissed an 'action agenda' set out in the latest OECD annual report as
pure rhetoric.  The charity says that the world's richest governments are using a rise in
private investment in some developing countries as an excuse to slash overall aid budgets.<p>

The principal goal of the 'action agenda', set by member governments of the OECD's
Development Assistance Committee (DAC), is "a reduction by one half in the proportion
of people living in extreme poverty by 2015".* <p> 

Yet the new 1996 Development Cooperation annual report highlights the trend of an
increase in flows of foreign investment to developing countries whilst official aid is on the
decline.  The report itself warns that:<p>

<blockquote>
"A continuation of that trend could be fatal to the achievement of
development goals."
</blockquote><p>

Raj Thamotheram, a spokesperson from ACTIONAID said:  "Relying on
private investment to improve the lives of the world's poorest people is
certainly not an 'action' plan.  This complacency by the world's richest
governments will not reduce global poverty and could threaten some of the
progress made over the past decades.  To call this an 'action agenda' is
naive and shortsighted."<p> 

ACTIONAID believes that this is a serious threat to development because:<p>

Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) is concentrated on a small number of
relatively wealthy countries © not the poorest.  For example sub Saharan
Africa receives only around 5% of total FDI even when developing countries receive FDI there is little evidence that the
poorest people benefit since financial flows tend to respond to market
signals not necessarily human needs.<p>


In real terms the total volume of overseas development assistance from DAC donors fell by 9% in 1995.  UK aid dropped from 0.31% of gnp in 1994 to 0.28% in 1995.<p>   

"Shaping the 21st Century: the Contribution of Development Cooperation",
Organisation for Economic Co©operation and Development 1996.<p>

1995 OECD Development Cooperation report<p>
␀ÔFor further information contact <br>Jenny Driscoll, Press Officer 0171 281 4101 <br><br><br>

<h2><font face="arial, helvetica">
NOMINATIONS NEEDED FOR BEST "UNTOLD STORIES" FROM WORLD'S 

POOREST COUNTRIES</font></h2>
<font face="arial, helvetica">





ACTIONAID is calling on programme makers, journalists and charities to nominate 1996 radio and television programmes for the "Untold Stories" award in this year's One World Media Awards.  The Awards will be held in London on 18 March 1997.<p>


The 'ACTIONAID Untold Stories Award' aims to recognise broadcasters who have succeeded in telling the stories of people, living in the world's poorest communities, who are working to improve their lives.  It will go to the programme maker who succeeds in broadcasting an original story which does not stem from the news agenda.<p>


All nominations should be sent to the ACTIONAID Press Office and programme makers should send their entries on VHS or audio cassette before <b>the closing date of Friday 7 February </b>(the description and criteria for the Award is attached).<p>


<b>SEND YOUR NOMINATION TO:</b><br>
<small>ACTIONAID Press Office, Hamlyn House, Macdonald Road, London N19 5PG or 
phone your nomination through to Jenny or Susan in the Press Office on 44 171 281 4101<p>



<b>For further information contact:</b>
Jenny Driscoll, Press Officer 44 171 281 4101 
Susan Mearns, Press Office 44 171 281 4101 <p>



ACTIONAID works in 22 countries in Africa, Asia and Latin America, helping to reduce poverty and 
improve the quality of life for people living in the world's poorest communities.  <p>


The One World '97 Awards is an annual media event organised by Media Natura with the One World Broadcasting Trust.</small><p>



   

<h3 align=center>ONE WORLD 1997 MEDIA AWARDS</h3>





<b>The ACTIONAID Untold Stories Award</b><p>






Description:		For the programme which breaks the story behind the headlines from 			the world's poorest countries<p>



Criteria:	<ul>	1. Broadcast on radio or TV in the UK during 1996<p>


			2. Tells an original story which is not related to the current news 			agenda.<p>


			3. The programme should be based on the lives of people living in 			the world's poorest countries who are working to improve their 			living conditions.<p>


			4. Where possible, the programme should reach a mainstream	 			audience.<p>


			5. It must be a story from the world's least developed countries in 			Asia, Africa or Latin <p>
America.
</ul>



The closing date for entries is <b>Friday 7 February</b>.

Entries should be sent on VHS or audio cassette.

Television finalists will be required to submit a Beta copy.<p>


 
                                                                                                                     

