<head>
<title>CALL FOR CHARITY HEALTH CHECK TO HELP THE PUBLIC</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2><font face="arial, helvetica">CALL FOR CHARITY HEALTH CHECK TO HELP THE PUBLIC</font></h2>
<font face="arial, helvetica">
ACTIONAID today called for charities to put greater effort into helping the public
choose which charities to support.  The call comes at the beginning of the
"Christmas giving season".  It also comes on the day ACTIONAID has been
shortlisted for an award at the Charities Annual Reports and Accounts Awards
organised by the Charities Aid Foundation and the Institute of Chartered
Accountants.   
<p>

Dominic Byrne, Head of Communications at ACTIONAID, says:  "Charities
need to take a consumer perspective.  We want to encourage the public to
ask questions of charities before they donate.  We've included a 
checklist of standards in our annual report.  As far as we know, 
no other charity annual report takes this approach and we want to 
encourage this "charity healthcheck" approach to help the public choose
who to support".
<p>

ACTIONAID's list of standards reflects the charity's specific policies on matters
such as reserve levels, staffing, mailing lists, and supporter feedback.  The charity
points out that appropriate policies will vary from charity to charity but in effect
questions on these areas should be asked of all charities.  The standards answer
questions such as "how effective is a charity's spending on fundraising?", "what
is a charity's policy on reserves?" (see attached sheet for a fuller list).
The initiative has been welcomed by independent voices in the charity world. 
Stephen Lee, Director of the Institute of Fundraising Managers,
commented: "I hope this checklist initiative will set a trend among
charities.  It is especially welcome since it draws the public's attention to
a range of charity governance issues, from policy on unsolicited direct
mail to open disclosure of complaint levels, that often get overlooked".
<p>

ACTIONAID hopes that its initiative will stimulate debate among charities and
wider consumer bodies.  Sheila McKechnie, Director of the Consumer's Association and      
        previously director of the charity Shelter, points out:  "As 
        people receive requests for donations to charities, more questions get         
        asked about how to decide. A number of different organisations are    
        looking at ways in which donors can make an informed choice.  There are
        no easy answers and I am aware it is a sensitive subject.  However, I
        think all charities will in future have to provide some kind of               
        performance related information.  I welcome this and all the various   
        discussions taking place about how best to do it".

<p>

ACTIONAID's move to include a checklist of its own standards in its annual
report is part of a wider move by the charity to make its annual reporting more
informative.  The report's financial summary, for example, includes a glossary of
terms designed to help make it easy for the public to understand its accounts. 
<p>


For further information contact Ruth Appiah, Press Officer, on +44 (0) 171 281
O4101 or email <a href="mailto:press@actionaid.org.uk">press@actionaid.org.uk</a>


<h3>CHARITY HEALTH CHECK QUESTIONS</h3>

<ol><li>What is the charity's policy on reserves?

<li>How effective is the charity's spending on fundraising?

<li>How well does the charity maximise share of funds available for projects?

<li>Does the charity monitor and publish complaint levels?

<li>How good is the charity's supporter loyalty?

<li>Does the charity undertake to use donations for the purposes specified and seek 
    permission from the donor if circumstances change and it needs to switch funds?

<li>Does the charity audit its operations beyond the minimum statutory               
    requirements?

<li>How are new projects developed?

<li>How are projects staffed?

<li>Does the charity sell its mailing lists to other organisations?
<ol>
</font>

