<head>
<title>ACTIONAID ACCUSES MULTINATIONALS OF KEEPING MILLIONS HUNGRY
</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center>ACTIONAID ACCUSES MULTINATIONALS OF KEEPING MILLIONS HUNGRY</h2>
<p>Today, as the world's governments meet on the first day of the World Food Summit in Rome,
ACTIONAID has issued a report which says that the current global trading system and the
activities of multinational companies are helping to keep 800 million people hungry.  The charity
says that increasingly global trade is undermining indigenous food production.
<p>
Government representatives attending the Summit have stated that their goal is to reduce the
number of chronically malnourished people by half.  But the charity says that they are likely to fail
because they have decided not to include the main causes of 'food insecurity', poverty and "free
trade", on the agenda.  

<p>ACTIONAID's report, <i>'Hunger and the Global Agenda: Who wins, who loses, who cares?' </i> says
that global trade is producing winners and losers  the losers usually being the world's poorest
people.  Research gathered by ACTIONAID from some of the 22 countries where it is working
showed that:
<ul><li>in Kenya the removal of price controls has led to small farmers being forced to sell
off their crops at low prices, because of debt commitments and lack of storage
facilities, and later buying back the same commodities at higher prices for their own use; <p><li>in Sierra Leone the effects of tobacco cultivation have exhausted the land in one
district.  The area was once forested but because large quantities of firewood are
needed for tobacco curing it has been left bare, rocky and incapable of supporting
any crops.  Extensive use of chemicals has polluted the water.</ul><p>

The report goes on to include examples of how global trade has resulted in some markets being
dominated by a small number of multinationals:
 90% of global commodities like wheat, corn and rice are marketed by just six
large transnational companies: Cargill, Continental, Ferruzi, Louis Dreyfus, Bunge &
Born and Cook; <p>in 1992 ATC, a subsidiary of British American Tobacco, had the exclusive right to
purchase tobacco from 16,000 farmers in Sierra Leone;<p>Cargill, a large North American agricultural multinational, has revenues from coffee. sales
alone which are greater than the gross domestic product (GDP) of any one of
the African countries from which it buys coffee beans.<p>Laura Kelly, ACTIONAID's Natural Resources Adviser said: <I> "Of course there are
many factors which result in millions of adults and children going hungry every day. 
But we have to realize that the decisions being made in the board rooms of a few
multinational companies are having a huge impact on the lives of millions of the
world's poorest people. ACTIONAID believes that this Summit is an ideal
opportunity to reject 'business as usual' and set up controls so that global trade does
not mean huge profits for a small number and hunger for millions."</i><p>

ACTIONAID believes that any reduction of global hunger will depend on changes of policies at
national and international levels.  The charity has written to MPs to call for the following actions:<p><ul>
<li>a parliamentary inquiry into the British Government trade policy and the operations of
UK based multinational companies on food security for the poorest people;<p><li>the establishment of a new independent body that monitors and controls the
activities of multinational companies and that tracks the impact of globalisation of
agricultural trade upon the poor; <p><li>a commitment from governments, including the UK, to implement the Summit's
recommendation to promote agriculture that supports livelihoods, contributes to food
security for the poorest and does not damage the environment.</ul><p><center><hr width=71%></center>The report, <b>'Hunger and the Global Agenda: Who wins, who loses, who cares?'</b> is available from
the
ACTIONAID Press Office on +44 (0) 171 281 4101 or susanm@actionaid.org.uk <p>For further information contact:

Jenny Driscoll, Press Officer or Susannah Cox, Head of Press, on +44 (0) 171 281 4101 or
jennyd@actionaid.org.uk / susannahc@actionaid.org.uk
<hr>
