<head>
<title>POLITICIANS UNITE TO EXPLODE THIRD WORLD MYTHS
</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<font face="arial, helvetica"><a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center>POLITICIANS UNITE TO EXPLODE THIRD WORLD MYTHS</h2>


Overseas Development Minister, Baroness Chalker and opposition
spokespeople, Clare Short MP
and Emma Nicholson MP, have joined forces to launch a new report from the charity ACTIONAID
which examines five of the most common myths and stereotypes voiced in Britain about third
world poverty.  It is the first time that the three have shared any platform.

<p>The report, <i>Fact or Fiction?</i>, challenges a range of negative views held by people in Britain about
third world poverty which are often untrue.  The report analyses statements such as:<p><ul>

<li>
"nothing ever changes for the better in the third world"<p><li>
"people in the third world are poor because they have too many children"</ul><p>In her introduction to Fact or Fiction?  TV journalist, Zeinab Badawi says these stereotypes
<i>"...contribute to an unjust view of the third world which ultimately reinforces prejudicial policies
towards the poorest countries and poverty itself".</i>   Fact or Fiction? contradicts each stereotype
with hard evidence in the report.  For example:

<p><ul><li>
official trends on life expectancy, infant mortality and education show dramatic progress;

<p><li>
poverty is a causal factor in population growth rather than the other way round. </ul><p>
Breaking the cycle of rapid population growth and poverty requires improved
conditions for the survival of children and greater choice for women. <p>Nigel Twose, ACTIONAID's Programme Development Director said:  <i>"It's not surprising that the public may hold these perceptions when they usually only
hear about the disasters which happen in developing countries.  The reality on the
ground is quite different.  For example ACTIONAID's new approach to teaching reading
and writing, called REFLECT, is producing remarkable results.  That's why it's
disappointing that these 'myths' are still popular.  They are harmful, not just because
they are wrong but because they can affect policies and attitudes towards poverty."</i><p><center><hr width=71%></center>The report, <b>Fact or Fiction? Common perceptions of third world poverty </b>
costs 3.95 + P&P (25p) and is available from<p>Fact or Fiction, <br>ACTIONAID Education,<br>
Chataway House,<br> Leach Road,<br> Chard,Somerset <br>TA20 1FA, <br>United Kingdom <p> Journalists requiring a
copy of the report should contact the ACTIONAID press office on +44 (0) 171 281
4101 or email susanm@actionaid.org.uk. <p>Photographs of ACTIONAID's work overseas
are available on request and spokespeople are available for interview or further information contact:

Jenny Driscoll, Press Officer, Susannah Cox, Head of Press, or Ruth Appiah, Press Officer on +44 (0)
171 281 4101 or email jennyd susannahc or rutha @actionaid.org.uk
<hr>
