<head>
<title>The Prince of Wales becomes Patron of ACTIONAID</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center>The Prince of Wales becomes Patron of ACTIONAID</h2>


HRH The Prince of Wales has accepted an invitation to become Royal Patron of ACTIONAID. In his first
annual message for the charity, The Prince of Wales expresses his delight at becoming Patron and
emphasises the need for a more broad-based approach to world poverty that moves away from a
narrow 'economic' view. He points out that:

<p><i>"The causes of poverty are not straightforward, they are not just a matter of economics, and
they
cannot be solved just by the generosity of more privileged societies." </i>

<p>Instead, he says, governments and individuals have "a common responsibility to tackle poverty in
all its
forms".

<p>Prince Charles highlights the importance of making improvements in people's living conditions:

<p><i>"What could be more vital for every human being, and for maintaining the proper dignity of
life, than
clean water and adequate food; what could be more important than ensuring basic health and education
for every child, no matter what his or her circumstances?"</i>

<p>The Prince notes "the sheer scale of what remains to be done as poverty deepens, for example,
among so many people in sub-Saharan Africa" but emphasises that "real, enduring improvements" can be
achieved by "unlocking the potential that can be found in all communities".

<p>John Batten, Chief Executive of ACTIONAID, echoed the Prince's message:

<p><i>"All too often world progress and development is viewed in very narrow terms. We hear about
indices such as the Dow Jones or the FTSE every day but we don't give the same attention to what is
happening to world poverty or quality of life. The Prince of Wales is also right to point to the
responsibilities and achievements of people in the third world itself. It is their ideas and
priorities that are
the building blocks of lasting progress."</i>

<p>For media enquires only, contact:
Susannah Cox, Head of Press, or Ruth Appiah, Press Officer, on +44 (0) 171 281 4101 or email
susannahc or
rutha@actionaid.org.uk
<hr>
<p>Read more about <b><a href="../cause/coca1/charles.html">Prince Charles' reasons for becoming
ACTIONAID Patron</a></b> in
Common Cause,
the magazine for ACTIONAID supporters

<p><b><a href="../lives/index.html">Changing lives:</a></b> find out about the experiences of people
whose lives have
changed with
ACTIONAID's help

