</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>REPORT ON OECD AID PROMPTS ACTIONAID TO CALL ON UK GOVERNMENT TO STOP ABUSING THE AID BUDGET</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><br><p><h2 align=center>REPORT ON OECD AID PROMPTS ACTIONAID TO CALL ON UK GOVERNMENT TO STOP ABUSING THE AID BUDGET</h2><p>An international report on aid, launched today by the charity ACTIONAID, highlights the abuse of aid by governments diverting aid away from the world's poorest people.  The charity accuses the UK government of misusing aid by prioritising wealthier countries, such as those in Eastern Europe, and funding projects which are not designed to reduce poverty.<p>The report, The Reality of Aid 1996, is prepared by a consortium of independent bodies from all 21 member countries of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).  The report, which coincides with the release in Paris of the latest figures from the OECD's Development Assistance Committee (DAC), says that:<blockquote>"Too much aid is being squandered by governments on projects which have more to do with commercial and political advantage than poverty eradication.  Aid must be targeted where the need is greatest with clear objectives and clearly defined responsibilities for government departments (page 3)." </blockquote><p>ACTIONAID believes that first and foremost aid should go the world's poorest people and more aid has to be devoted to basic human needs: primary health care and basic education.  Funding to these areas is known to bring long-term benefits to the poor.  <p>The Reality of Aid reports that during 1991/92 aid to Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union countries totalled £86 million.  By 1994/5 this figure had risen to £240 million - one tenth of the entire aid budget.*  The following projects received funding from the UK government aid budget:<ul><li>	"...help to Balkan Bulgarian Airlines to prepare for possible privatisation and has 	funded Job Ownership Limited to develop employee share ownership buy-out skills"<p><li>	(in Slovakia) "...a consultant to act as co-producer of a series of short television films on the stock market"											<p><li>	"a second in-country Parliamentary workshop, to follow one held in 1993 when a substantial cross-party group from Westminster went to Romania to discuss Parliamentary practice".**</ul><p>If this £240 million had been used to fund basic needs in developing countries it could have provided:<ul><li>a lifetime's supply of clean water for 24 million people in Africa;<p><li>	primary education for 5.9 million children in India.</ul><p>The Reality of Aid reveals that the UK government has made some progress towards a better poverty focus in its aid programme, both in terms of management and targeting.  This makes the increasing misuse of the aid budget for work in Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union unconnected with poverty reduction even more alarming.  <p>ACTIONAID points out that the squeeze on poorer countries caused by the misuse of aid is compounded by aid falling to the lowest level ever recorded.  Next year UK aid will be just 0.26 per cent of GNP and developing countries will face a three year cut of 16 per cent by 1998/9 - nearly £323 million.  The report also says that 20 per cent of the world's population are living in absolute poverty, living on less than one dollar a day, and this figure is rising.  <p><blockquote>Nigel Twose, ACTIONAID Director of Programme Development said: "The government has gone on record in stating that the purpose of their aid budget is to 'reduce poverty' and so it is inexcusable for aid to fund any project which does not have this as a primary objective.  The tragedy is that aid does work, as evidenced by the poverty focused projects supported by the government.  That is what makes this growing misuse so alarming."</blockquote><p><hr><p><b>Note to Editors:</b><br>Reality of Aid 1996 is the fourth in a series of annual reports which provides an independent analysis of official aid from 21 countries in the OECD. <p>ACTIONAID works in 20 countries in Africa, Asia and Latin America, helping to reduce poverty and improve the quality of life for people living in the world's poorest communities.<p><b>For further information:</b><br>Jenny Driscoll, Press Officer - 0171 281 4101Susannah Cox, Head of Press - 0171 281 4101<p>*	Overseas Development Administration's British Aid Statistics 1990/91 - 1994/95**	Foreign and Commonwealth Office's Know How Fund Annual Report 1993-94<p><hr><center><TABLE BORDER=0 width=500 bgcolor=#FFFFCC cellpadding=10><TR><TH><br><img src="table1.gif" width=483 height=243><p><img src="table2.gif" width=483 height=228><p><img src="table3.gif" width=484 height=173><br></TH></TR></TABLE><center><p><hr><h2>REALITY OF AID 1996 - Summary</h2><p>Aid provided by the industrialised countries of the North to the developing world is in crisis.  The amount of aid pledged by the North has fallen to its lowest level for 20 years.  Equally worrying, there is no indication that the aid that is still being provided is reaching the world's poorest people.<h3>GENERAL SUMMARY</h3><p>1. Aid falls to its lowest level for 20 years.  In 1994, in spite of commitments by donor member countries of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), with the exception of the US, to maintain aid targets, more than a third of donors cut their aid.  1995 levels look to fall further still.<p><ul><li>Least developed countries (LDC) and other low income countries have seen aid fall by a total of 7% since 1990.<p><li>Bilateral aid to sub-Saharan Africa has fallen by $670 million since 1991 (more than the entire national income of Sierra Leone).<p><li>New players are further diluting aid delivery. Vietnam, South Africa and  Cambodia have leapt to the top of some donors' tables.<p><li>Aid to Eastern Europe and North Africa from the EU is now equal to all EU aid going to Africa, the Caribbean and the Pacific combined.</ul><p>2. Increased instability in the post cold war world has meant a rise in the percentage of aid spent on emergency relief.  10% of OECD donor aid is now spent on emergency relief.<p>3. Changes in reporting rules mean that support for refugees at home in donor countries (for the first year) can be counted as ODA, reducing the funds available for poverty eradication by almost $1 billion.<p>4. The report concludes that there are basic strands to the worldwide commitment to eradicate poverty.<p><ul><li>To be effective, aid must complement wider government efforts to address social development.  Investing in human capacity is an indispensable part of the route to economic development.  Key areas of social investment are education, health, water and sanitation.<p><li>OECD donor Governments should be able to answer the question, "how much of aid money gets to the people who are in the greatest need?".  The complexities of measuring aid allocation makes it difficultto answer this question clearly, but better information should be available.  Donor reporting is improving, but this improvement reveals how little aid is reaching those key areas of social investment. Current investment is tiny, showing 0.1% of total aid going to basic education, and 0.3% of total aid going to basic health.<p><li>There has to be local "ownership" of development projects for those projects to be successful.  External control and dependency are big obstacles to effective aid programmes.<p><li>There is little capacity for evaluation of the aid that OECD countries provide.  Over $5 billion per year for the last five years has been spent on programme aid - aid designed to change the recipient country's macro-economic and political structure, without any mechanism to determine whether it does harm or good.</ul><p>5. Commercial pressures mean that much aid is being squandered on projects with political and economic advantage taking precedence over poverty reduction.<p>6. Increased private aid and Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) is no substitute for falling aid.  There is little evidence that FDI is targeting unmet demand for basic needs of food, education, primary health care, family planning or sanitation.<p><h3>UK OVERVIEW</h3><p>1. In 1996 UK aid will fall to the lowest level ever recorded.<p>2. By 1998 aid to the world's poorest people (LDC/other low-income countries) will have fallen by 16% from the 1994/5 level.<p>3. An increasing percentage of all UK aid is being channelled through the EC and other multilateral aid mechanisms.  This means that the percentage of bilateral aid - the money over which the UK maintains the most control - is shrinking significantly.<p>4. Although making some progress from a low base on improving the poverty focus of the aid programme in terms of management and targeting the majority of UK aid spending does not directly reach the world's poorest people with a much greater emphasis being placed on economic reform rather than meeting basic needs.<p>5. Aid to sub-Saharan Africa - the world's poorest region - fell by 18% from 1994/5 to 1997/8, while Eastern Europe/The Former Soviet Union received the equivalent of 11% of the aid going to the poorest countries.<p>6. The UK has no way to measure the effectiveness of its aid.  They are unwilling to implement the measurement of either the input - the amount of aid expenditure targeting basic education of health needs or the results - eg, reduction of infant/maternal mortality.<p><hr><p><a href="../home.html"><img src="../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="index.html"><img src="../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><b><li type=square><a href="../home.html">Home Page</a> <litype=square><ahref="../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a> <li type=square><a href="index.html">Latest News</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>
</DOC>
