 <html><head><title>HRH The Prince of Wales</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><br><h2 align=center> 'I have long admired ACTIONAID's work...'</h2></p><p><font size=4>HRH The Prince of Wales is ACTIONAID's new Royal Patron. Over the next five years he will carry out a series of engagements, and visit ACTIONAID's project work. In his acceptance message - which will be published in full in ACTIONAID's 1995/96 Annual Report - he outlines his reasons for accepting the invitation.</font><hr><p>Accepting his new role as the first Royal Patron of ACTIONAID, HRH The Prince of Wales notes - in a message for ACTIONAID's 1995/96 Annual Report - the 'sheer scale of what remains to be done as poverty deepens, for example among so many people in sub-Saharan Africa'. <br><p>He continues: &quot;The causes of poverty are not straightforward, they are not just a matter of economics, and they cannot be solved just by the generosity of more privileged societies.&quot; <br>His Royal Highness says he hopes that 'the special problems of the poorest people and the most neglected communities will continue to be brought to public attention and that throughout the world, governments and individuals will live up to their common responsibility to tackle poverty in all its  forms'. At the beginning of his five-year patronage, he praises ACTIONAID's work with the poor: &quot;I have long admired ACTIONAID's tireless work in providing basic human needs in so many disadvantaged communities in some of the poorer parts of the world. <br>&quot;What could be more vital for every human being and for maintaining the proper dignity of life than clean water and adequate food; what could be more important than ensuring health and education for every child no matter what his or her circumstances?&quot;<br><p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=280 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=260 bgcolor=FFCC99><TR><TD><img src="01.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=250 height=174></TD></TR><TR><TD><p><font size=small face=helvetica>Photograph shows HRH The Prince of Wales with (left to right): Ravi Narayanan, ACTIONAID Asia Region Director; Annie Kairaba, 	ACTIONAID Kenya; John Batten, ACTIONAID Chief Executive; Tiziana Fattori, Operations Manager, AZIONE AIUTO.<br>(Clive Arrowsmith</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>His Royal Highness pays particular attention to the principle of working with the community, which lies behind ACTIONAID's approach to development - and much of HRH The Prince of Wales' other charity work. He says: &quot;It is clearly a daunting challenge to find ways of fulfiling such fundamental human needs, and so it is important to recognise ACTIONAID's vital work in sustaining hope, unlocking the potential that can be found in all communities, however deprived, and bringing real, enduring improvements to the lives of some of the most cruelly impoverished people in the world.&quot;<br><p>This approach of 'unlocking potential' is in evidence in perhaps the most high profile of his charity work to date, The Prince's Trust. The Trust helps young people find employment, set up in business and successfully turn their ideas for projects into viable business plans. <br><p>Also well known is The Prince's Youth Business Trust, which has helped 16,000 businesses to get off the ground through loans and grants, and created 20,000 new jobs for young people since 1986 when it was first set up.<br><p>Business in the Community, of which the Prince of Wales is President, tackles similar problems. It has established an international reputation for its work promoting the involvement of business in a wide range of key social issues. <br><p>Through this and other work, the Prince of Wales has travelled widely, and  has visited many countries in which ACTIONAID has programmes, including Malawi, Kenya, Nepal, and India.<br>During his five-year patronage, it is expected that His Royal Highness will visit ACTIONAID project work and will also carry out a number of UK engagements on behalf of the charity. 	<p><p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><li type=square><b><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b> <<br clear=all><p></body></html>
