<html>
<head>
<title>A breakthrough in world literacy
</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center>A breakthrough in world literacy
</h2>


World literacy rates could improve dramatically as a result of a radical new adult literacy programme
launched by ACTIONAID. Pilot trials of the Reflect programme in three continents have shown it to be
two
to three times more effective than conventional approaches to reading and writing.

<p>Reflect abandons the traditional textbook and hands over the curriculum to learners. Participants
of a
Reflect group make up their own learning materials relating to a local issue, for example a calendar
of
childhood illness or a map of crop planting. These materials are used by Reflect teachers to
introduce
numbers and the written word.

<p>Baroness Chalker, Minister for Overseas Development, says:

<p><i>"Teaching people to read and write provides them with the means to develop. Reflect is
important
because it enables students to tailor the course to their needs and relate to what they are learning.
I am
delighted that a British charity has taken the initiative in this area and that the Overseas
Development
Administration has been able to play a part by researching the project's effectiveness."</i>

<p>Overall results show that Reflect has a 60-70 per cent success rate when compared with
conventional
adult literacy programmes which stand at around 25 per cent, as measured by the World Bank.

<p>Two years of intensive trials have taken place through ACTIONAID projects in Bangladesh, El
Salvador
and Uganda. 

<p>In Uganda, Reflect classes took place in 65 villages. Enrolment in local schools increased by 20
per cent
and parents in 20 villages set up their own schools and asked for the children to be taught using
this new
method.

<p>One of the key success factors is the way in which Reflect allows class participants to focus
their
reading and writing on local issues of importance to them. This also has a knock-on effect on other
improvements in living conditions. Early evidence from trial areas points to more efficient farming
techniques, improved health care and increased involvement of women in decision making.

<p>Reflect is now being extended to other countries in Africa, Asia and Latin America following
funding
from the World Bank. ACTIONAID is working with governments and other organisations to incorporate the
method into their own education programmes.

<p>According to the World Bank's Review of Priorities in Education 1995, 900 million people
throughout the
world are illiterate. If Reflect was adopted world-wide this figure could be reduced to 3-400
million. 

<p>David Archer, ACTIONAID's Education Advisor who developed Reflect, says:

<p><i>"Most adult literacy programmes are failing. This has led to a tendency in many countries to
teach
children and forget a generation of adults. ACTIONAID believes in education for all. The impact of
Reflect
may go far beyond the field of adult education, affecting approaches to poverty alleviation and
development world-wide."</i>

<p>Over the last 30 years the majority of adult literacy programmes have been disappointing and have
lost the support of donor organisations and governments. David de Ferranti, Director of Human
Development at the World Bank, recently commented: " To find a truly effective approach to literacy
would be like finding a holy grail."

<p>For media enquires only, contact:
Jenny Driscoll, Press Officer on +44 (0) 171 281 4101 or email jennyd@actionaid.org.uk
<hr>
<p>
The <a href="../pubs/index.html" target="_parent"><b>Reflect Mother Manual</b></a>, the comprehensive
guide for Reflect
practitioners, is available from ACTIONAID priced £10/$20

<p>
To read more about ACTIONAID's literacy work, see <a href="../cause/coca1/abc.html"><b>not as simple
as abc</b></a> in
Common Cause, the magazine for ACTIONAID supporters

<p>
Reflect is just one example of ACTIONAID <a href="../info/index.html#change"><b>advocating for
change</b></a>. Discover
more here.
<p>
<font face=arial, helvetica size=4><b><a
href="http://www.oneworld.org/actionaid/movs/reflect.mov">Discover what Overseas Development Minister
Baroness Lynda Chalker says about Reflect</a></b><small>[Video clip:]</font>

