<head>
<title>British aid in crisis</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center>British aid in crisis</h2>

<p><b> - ACTIONAID's reaction to Baroness Chalker's speech on the Overseas Development
Administration's Fundamental Expenditure Review</b><br>
14.2.96

<p>ACTIONAID believes Baroness Chalker, Minister for Overseas Development, is putting a brave face on
a
bleak situation.

<p>Baroness Chalker's presentation, 'ODA: New Aims and Priorities', announces the outcome of the
ODA's
Fundamental Expenditure Review (FER), the first major review in 20 years. The speech follows a report
by
the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) which states that the world's
richest governments have cut their aid to the lowest level for 20 years (as a proportion of Gross
National
Product).

<p>The FER reveals that: 

<p><ul><li>bilateral aid will decline by £660 million at the end of the decade (it is currently £1.05
billion) 

<p><li>bilateral aid to Africa will fall by 18.4 per cent

<p><li>a new 'concentration policy' will target 20 countries rather than focusing aid to help the
poorest
people

<p><li>the ODA's running costs will be frozen and staff numbers will fall
</ul>

<p>Nigel Twose, Director of Programme Development at ACTIONAID, says: 

<p><i>"British aid is now in crisis. Without significant increases in aid, the quality and reach of
the UK aid
programme will continue to fall to such an extent that the viability of the whole aid programme is
under
threat. The ODA faces stark choices about the future direction of British aid. Unfortunately the
future
strategy outlined in the FER is more about coping with a much reduced aid programme than any real
commitment to taking up the challenge of rising global poverty." </i>

<p>For media enquires only, contact:
Jenny Driscoll, Press Officer on +44 (0) 171 281 4101 or email jennyd@actionaid.org.uk

<p>
<hr>
<p>
Read more about British aid in ACTIONAID's <b><a href="../pubs/index.html#brief"
target="_parent">briefing</a></b>


