<html>
<head>
<title>The social summit: a 20/20 vision
</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center>The social summit: a 20/20 vision
</h2>
16.2.95


<p>The forthcoming World Summit for Social Development presents a major opportunity for the
international community to commit itself to the urgent task of eradicating global poverty and
beginning a
new era of North-South development co-operation. This opportunity must be grasped by the British
government. 

<p>ACTIONAID proposes a practical and realisable two-stage plan for British aid under which Britain
would at
first meet the Summit's call for 20 per cent of aid to go to basic needs, thereby:
<ul>
<p><li>providing a basic education to nearly five million extra girls

<p><li>providing over 30 million people in low income countries with a package of essential health
services
</ul>
<p>
As the World Summit for Social Development convenes in Copenhagen, attended by over 100 heads of
state and government, the international community is faced with a clear choice. It could commit
itself to
implementing an integrated anti-poverty strategy to improve the lives of the one fifth of the world's
population living in poverty. Alternatively, it could produce fine words and declarations which
result in little
practical progress towards 'a new era of international co-operation'. If the second path is taken,
the
evidence suggests that over 300 million more people will be living in absolute poverty in 10 years
time.

<p>The Social Summit is an unprecedented opportunity for real progress to be made towards eradicating
poverty. It is the first UN summit concerned specifically with the eradication of poverty and calls
on the
international community to commit itself to an integrated anti-poverty programme. It emphasises the
dual responsibility between North and South in the task of defeating poverty. This task is more
urgent
than ever since the number of people living in absolute poverty is increasing by around 30 million
people
each year. 


<h3>An opportunity for the British government?</h3>

<p>The Social Summit will consider many different, inter-related issues which can only be tackled by
Northern and Southern governments taking joint responsibility for them. There is, however, one clear
area of policy reform on the agenda of the Social Summit on which the British government can take
action and demonstrate a clear political commitment to the Summit's goals. This concerns the call for
20
per cent of donors' aid budgets to be devoted to basic needs, such as primary health care, basic
education, safe water and adequate sanitation. The 20 per cent target is the agreed position of the
UNDP, Unicef, Unesco, Unfpa and WHO. ACTIONAID believes that at the Summit, the British government
should commit itself to reaching the 20 per cent target for aid specifically called for by these
organisations.


<h3>Why emphasise basic needs?</h3>

<p>The Summit's call for the greater provision of basic needs - both by developing country
governments
and overseas aid donors - is an approach to reducing poverty and promoting development shared by
ACTIONAID. There are two main reasons for this:
<ul>
<p><li>Firstly, it is a humanitarian strategy aimed directly at the needs of the poorest, most
disadvantaged groups in society. It contributes directly to reducing poverty and providing the
essentials
of life, such as basic education and primary health care.

<p><li>Secondly, it makes economic sense since development cannot be promoted or sustained unless
there is long-term investment in the basic needs of the poor; this is especially true since the poor
often
comprise a substantial proportion of a population. 
</ul>
<p>In education, for example, there is a high rate of economic and social return to be gained by
directly
investing in the poor in developing countries. The World Bank's "experience indicates... that no
country has
been able to take off economically with a literacy rate of less than 50 per cent". Yet around half of
the
world's low income countries have literacy rates below this level. Investing in basic education -
which
primarily benefits the poorest people - is more beneficial than investing in higher-level education -
from
which the poor are usually excluded - since it is "well-known that tertiary education yields the
lowest social
rate of return". 


<h3>20 per cent for basic needs</h3>

<p>The Summit presents an opportunity for the British government to commit itself to increase the
proportion of aid going to basic needs to at least 20 per cent. ACTIONAID believes that the British
government should implement a two-stage plan to achieve this.


<h3>The two-stage plan for basic needs</h3>

<p>In the first stage, lasting from 1995-2000, Britain would increase the proportion of its bilateral
aid to
basic needs to at least 20 per cent (under the UNDP definition).

<p>In the second stage, lasting from 2000-2005, Britain would build on this increase and raise the
proportion devoted to basic needs to at least one third of bilateral aid (under the UNDP definition). 

<p>Currently, the proportion of Britain's bilateral aid devoted to basic needs is very low: the UNDP
estimates it at 6.6 per cent for 1988-91 (the most recent figures); while the government itself
admits
that the figure is just 10.7 per cent for 1992/93, using a slightly wider definition. 

<p>The figure of 6.6 per cent is the only internationally comparable figure for the proportion of
British
bilateral aid going to basic needs. It means that if Britain increased the proportion of bilateral
aid devoted
to basic needs to 20 per cent, an extra £160-170 million a year would go to such vital services as
primary
health care and basic education.

<p>Where could the extra £160-170 million come from? ACTIONAID believes there are several elements in
the aid budget which are of less value in reducing poverty than a direct focus on basic needs. We
therefore
make three suggestions for the source of that extra funding which we urge the government to consider:

<p><ul><li>Firstly, there is the amount devoted to the Aid and Trade Provision (ATP), worth £85
million in
1993/94. Several studies show the poor developmental value of many ATP projects, of which the Pergau
dam is the most notorious. If the money spent on ATP went on basic needs, the government would be
half way towards reaching the 20 per cent first stage target.

<p><li>Secondly, some of the extra resources could also come from the amount currently directed to
relatively rich countries with relatively low poverty levels. £68 million of aid went to upper-middle
income
and high income countries in 1993/94. These are countries with a per capita income of $2,696-8,355,
which
compares to low income countries' per capita income of under $676. ACTIONAID believes that these
countries are worthy recipients of aid, but their relative wealth suggests that other countries and
projects should receive priority support from British aid.

<p><li>Thirdly is the issue of resources going to the former Soviet bloc countries. In 1993/94, total
aid to
these countries amounted to £243 million, or 11.2 per cent of all British aid. ACTIONAID believes
that,
especially at a time of declining aid levels, first call on these resources should be the poorest
countries in
the developing world.
</ul>

<h3>Increasing aid resources</h3>

<p>The Social Summit's Draft Programme of Action also contains a call for donors to reach the 0.7 per
cent of GNP target for aid. The fact that the number of people living in absolute poverty is rising
shows
that it remains essential for donors to move towards this target. 

<p>The figure of 0.7 per cent GNP was first adopted by the UN in 1970 and by the British government
in
1974 - will the government set a firm date for reaching it, say by 2000, the 30th anniversary of its
adoption by the UN and the eve of a new millennium of development co-operation? 

<p>The first step towards this target should be for the government to reach the European Union
average
- 0.43 per cent of GNP in 1992, compared to 0.31 per cent for Britain. ACTIONAID is calling on the
government to set a clear timetable for firstly reaching the EU average for aid and, secondly,
reaching the
UN target.

<p>
What could be achieved if spending on basic needs increased to 20 per cent?

<p>A real impact on the lives of many poor people could be made if Britain increased the proportion
of its
aid devoted to basic needs to 20 per cent. Here are just two examples of what the extra £160-170
million
could achieve:

<p><ul><li>Britain could increase eleven-fold the amount spent on basic education (which was just
£15.8
million in 1992/93). The Overseas Development Administration states that raising the primary school
enrolment of girls to equal that of boys in the low income countries would involve educating an extra
25
million girls a year at a cost of around £938 million. With the extra resources devoted to basic
needs,
Britain could fund almost a fifth of the total costs of this programme and reach nearly five million
new
pupils. 

<p><li>Britain could provide over 30 million people in low income countries with a package of
essential health
services. The package includes family planning services, care for common illnesses which account for
millions of child deaths each year, pregnancy-related care which reduces maternal deaths and the
control
of sexually-transmitted diseases. The World Bank estimates the cost of such a health package as $8
(£5.70) per person in low income countries. 
</ul>
<hr>

<p>Read more about British aid in ACTIONAID's <b><a href="../pubs/index.html#brief"
target="_parent">briefing</a></b>


<p><b><a href="../lives/index.html">Changing lives:</a></b> find out about the experiences of people
whose lives have
changed with
ACTIONAID's help

<p><hr>
<p><a href="../home.html"><img src="../pix/home.gif" width=46
height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><img
src="../pix/globe1.gif" width=46
height=41
hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="flashback.html"><img src="../pix/back.gif"
width=46
height=41
hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><b><li type=square><a href="../home.html">Home Page</a> <li
type=square><a
href="../fight/index.html" target="_parent">Join
ACTIONAID</a> <li type=square><a href="flashback.html">News
Flashback</a></b></h6></font><br clear=all>
<p></body>
</html>
