</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>How focused on poverty reduction is British aid?
</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center>How focused on poverty reduction is British aid?
</h2>
<b> - A briefing for the House of Commons debate on the government's spending plans</b><br>
21.10.94

<p>
<i>"My duty - both to the recipients of our aid and to British taxpayers - is to ensure that our aid
is
directed to where it is needed... and where it can be effectively used."</i>
Baroness Chalker, House of Lords, 2 March 1994.

<p>At a time of parliamentary scrutiny of the government's aid spending plans, ACTIONAID believes it
appropriate to consider what should be the primary purpose of aid: its focus on poverty reduction.

<p>Last year, ACTIONAID published the results of a parliamentary poll showing that 82 per cent of MPs
believe it important that the aid programme give greater attention to basic needs - such as basic
education, primary health care and clean water. The poll also revealed that, on average, MPs said
that
48.9 per cent of all aid should be spent on basic needs. We contrasted this view with United Nations
figures
showing that less than seven per cent of the government's bilateral aid is spent on basic needs. 

<p>In an interview on BBC Radio 5 , the Overseas Development Minister, Baroness Chalker, asserted
that
what ACTIONAID said on Britain's aid focus on basic needs was "plain wrong". "Even on the narrowest
definition", the Minister continued, "we spend over 20 per cent of our bilateral programme on basic
needs." 

<p>
<h3>What is the reality of the aid programme's focus on basic needs?</h3>

<p>
<b>The importance of basic needs</b>

<p>With 1.3 billion people living in absolute poverty and the number rising by around 26 million
people a
year, there is a pressing need to ensure that government aid is effectively targeted on the reduction
of
poverty.

<p>It is now widely accepted that the most effective way of reducing poverty is to focus aid on basic
needs. In its 1990 report on poverty, for example, the World Bank called upon the international
community to implement a strategy requiring the "widespread provision to the poor of basic social
services, especially primary education, primary health care, and family planning". If this strategy
were
implemented, the Bank argued, absolute poverty could be significantly reduced. Such a bottom-up,
people-centred approach is recognised to be central to promoting economic development. 

<p>
<b>How does Britain perform on basic needs?</b>

<p>The government states that "the aid programme's greatest priority is reducing poverty". In
practice,
however, the available evidence shows that British aid is very poorly targeted on poverty reduction.

<p>(a) The bilateral aid focus on basic needs

<p>In answer to a parliamentary question, the government stated that "a minimum" of £111 million of
Britain's bilateral aid was focused on basic needs provision in 1992-93. Given that total bilateral
aid in
1992-93 was £1.03 billion, this means that just 10.7 per cent of bilateral aid went to basic needs,
by the
government's own figures.

<p>Estimates provided by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) indicate that Britain's
performance on basic needs is worse than this. According to UNDP, just 6.6 per cent of Britain's
bilateral
aid went to basic needs in 1989-91 (the latest available figures). This figure was even lower than
the
previous estimate made by UNDP for 1988-9, which was 8.8 per cent. (Unicef estimates on basic needs
are
taken from the UNDP).

<p>(b) The multilateral aid focus on basic needs

<p>As far as ACTIONAID is aware, there are no sources which provide information on the proportion of
Britain's multilateral aid which goes to basic needs. The indications are, however, that the focus is
likely to
be little better than in the bilateral part of the programme. For example, nearly half of Britain's
multilateral funds go the European Union. The EU provides no statistics on the proportion of its aid
spent
on basic needs, but its overall focus on poverty is generally held to be very poor. The second
largest
recipient of Britain's multilateral funds - accounting for nearly a third of multilateral aid, or a
quarter of a
billion pounds - is the World Bank Group. Yet the UNDP estimates that just 10.2 per cent of World
Bank aid
is focused on basic needs.

<p>Overall, the evidence suggests that the government's focus on basic needs is far less than the
government claims. ACTIONAID believes it is unacceptable for the government to claim that the aid
programme's greatest priority is reducing poverty at the same time that such a low proportion of aid
is
actually allocated to basic needs. ACTIONAID believes that to make a real impact on poverty reduction
a
greater proportion of aid should go to meeting basic needs.

<p>
<b>The future of aid to basic needs?</b>

<p>There are some signs of an improvement in the poverty focus of British aid. For example, the ODA
has
begun to improve the currently very poor focus on aid to basic education (primary schooling and adult
literacy) within its overall aid to education. It has also recently introduced a mechanism - the
Policy
Information Marker System - for measuring the impact of aid projects against a number of objectives,
including poverty reduction. 

<p>These measures are welcome, if long overdue, but they are insufficient to achieve a genuinely
comprehensive impact on poverty: for this, a wholesale reordering of priorities within the aid
programme
is required - with direct poverty reduction at the very heart of the aid programme.

<p>
<hr>
<p>
Read more about British aid in ACTIONAID's <b><a href="../pubs/index.html#brief"
target="_parent">briefing</a></b>

<p><p>
<p><b><a href="../lives/index.html">Changing lives:</a></b> find out about the experiences of people
whose lives have
changed with
ACTIONAID's help

<p><p><hr>
<p><a href="../home.html"><img src="../pix/home.gif" width=46
height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><img
src="../pix/globe1.gif" width=46
height=41
hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="flashback.html"><img src="../pix/back.gif"
width=46
