<html>
<head>
<title> Not as simple as abc</title>
<!!keys: >
</head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<p>
<h2 align=center> Not as simple as abc</h2></p>

<p>

<p><font size=4><font size=+2>L</font>iteracy in the developing world is  far more complex than
reading and writing, says David Archer. And we need to concentrate on the people most difficult to
reach - adults.</font>
<hr>
<p>
Educationalists estimate that a child needs between three and four years of schooling to acquire
basic reading and writing skills. <p>
In the UK, our children spend at least 11 years in school. In the 20 countries of Africa, Asia and
Latin America where ACTIONAID works, the average child receives just over two years of schooling and
many have no access to education at all <b><a href="#box1">(see box 1)</a></b>. Most fail to become
literate at school and enter adulthood unable to read and write.<p>
In Bangladesh, for example, the adult literacy rate stands at around 35 per cent. Though the country
has more literate people than England and sustains more than a hundred national newspapers, the
problem is one of scale and power. <p>
The literate society of Bangladesh is concentrated in urban areas. The poor, living in marginal urban
areas or villages, live in a different world where the written word is scarcely to be seen. Here, the
local school, if there is one, may be the only place where books can be found. People engage in their
daily lives with little or no need for reading and writing.<p>
In such conditions, adults may see little point in literacy or in literacy training. Recent research
by the World Bank suggests that adult literacy programmes have an average effectiveness rate of just
12.5 per cent. Half of the adults who enrol drop out within a few weeks. Of those who do continue,
half fail to complete the course - and of those who do graduate, half lose their skills through
disuse within a year.<p>
This disillusionment with the value of adult literacy has made many government and international
agencies ignore adults and instead target scarce resources at educating children. But this is not
working. Despite investments, primary school enrolment has stagnated, and in many countries children
are dropping out of school in vast numbers.<p>
To increase enrolment, governments are spending many of their resources on building schools.
ACTIONAID research in Kenya, though, shows that simply building schools is insufficient, so ACTIONAID
now focuses more on areas such as promoting pre-school education; on-the-job training for teachers;
training parent-teacher associations; and developing non-formal education for children who drop out
of school.
However, focusing on children alone will not solve the overall problem of illiteracy. Adult literacy
is vitally important because it is adults who decide whether to send their children to school - and
this is a difficult choice when children could otherwise be earning an income for the family. Unless
adults understand the   benefits of education they will not take the risk - and they will not
understand simply by being told.
Those benefits are numerous. Literate parents are not only more likely to send their children to
school but will also take a more active interest in the school (for example, through parent-teacher
associations) and reinforce their children's education at home. <p>
There are other benefits. Literate farmers tend to have more access to credit and training, and are
often more productive; literate women are more likely to immunise children and to know about basic
child healthcare and nutrition. More deeply, the process of becoming literate often builds
confidence, prompting people to overcome past fears and feelings of powerlessness.<p>
For literacy to be made attractive to adults it must be made relevant to their lives and to the wider
process of development. The Brazilian educator Paulo Freire identified this may years ago, saying
that literacy is not just about reading words but about understanding reality.<p>
The struggle for day to day survival means that the poor rarely have the opportunity to reflect upon
their lives and discuss the causes of their problems or possible solutions. A literacy class can be a
valuable space to do so (perhaps most of all for women, for whom it is sometimes their first
experience of being in a community group).<p>
 Where literacy programmes have been linked to reflection and active discussion on local issues, they
have often acted as a catalyst for people taking greater control of their own development. This in
turn can make the literacy skills relevant within their daily lives. <p>
However, most literacy programmes still fail to do this. The biggest block is in teaching methods.
Literacy teachers are usually poorly trained and yet they are expected to start interesting
discussions using just pictures from a basic textbook and a list of questions. The common response is
an awkward silence from adults who do not see the relevance of the issues to their lives. Teachers
fall back on what they know from their own experience in school and focus just on the technical
skills of reading and writing - teaching the adults like children, without any reference to life
experience. Classes become both difficult and boring, and the adults start to drop out.<p>
It is as a response to this situation that  ACTIONAID has developed a new teaching method for adult
literacy, called Reflect.<p>
Reflect has been piloted in Uganda, El Salvador and Bangladesh, and is proving extremely successful
in both teaching literacy and linking literacy to local development. The method has already spread to
10 other countries and has been taken up by many other organisations. It is hoped that this new
method will revitalise adult literacy work internationally and will help to convince governments of
the critical importance of investing in the education of adults as well as children.<p>
<a name="box1"></a>
<p>
<center><TABLE BORDER=0 bgcolor=FFCC99 align=left hspace=25 vspace=10 width=40%>
