</center>
<p>
<h3>Reflect</h3>

<p>In a Reflect programme, there is no textbook and no pre-printed materials other than a guide for
the literacy 'facilitators'. Each literacy 'circle' develops its own   learning materials through the
construction of maps, matrices, calendars and     diagrams that represent  everyday events and
issues, and use the existing       knowledge of learners. <p>
These 'graphics' might include maps of households, land use or land tenancy    or calendars of gender
workloads, illnesses or income. Each graphic is initially     constructed on the ground, using
locally available materials and local designed picture cards. Large copies of these graphics are then
made on paper and key  words are gradually introduced, all taken from the immediate lives of the
learners. <p>
<TABLE BORDER=0 width=280 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10>
<TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=260>
<TR><TD> <img src="21.jpg" hspace=4 vspace=4 width=250 height=159 border=1></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> <font size=small face=helvetica, arial>Photo: David Archer</font> &copy;.
</TD></TR></TABLE></TD>
</TR></TABLE><p>
By the end of the literacy course, each circle will have produced a range of 30 graphics. Each
learner will have a copy of these in their books, together with phrases they have written, so that
they produce a real document - not just an exercise book full of copied scribbles. The graphics
become a permanent record for communities, giving them a basis on which to plan their own development
with the minimum of manipulation by external agencies.<p>

<font face=arial, helvetica size=4><b><a
href="http://www.oneworld.org/actionaid/movs/reflect.mov">Discover what Overseas Development Minister
Baroness Lynda Chalker says about Reflect</a></b><small>[Video clip:]</font><p>

<p><i>*Regenerated Freirean Literacy through Empowering Community Techniques</i>
