 <html>
<head>
<title>Game for anything</title>
<!!keys: >
</head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>
<font face=ariel, helvetica>

<h2>Game for anything</h2>

<font face=ariel, helvetica>
<b>There's one sure thing about children all over the world - they'll
make a game out of anything.</b><p>

Wherever in the world they live, all children love to play. The
materials might vary, but in many cases the games are extraordinarily
similar. You will find boys and girls skipping, flying kites, playing
football and enjoying different versions of catch, marbles, jacks or
hopscotch anywhere from Ireland to El Salvador, Kenya and Nepal. <p>

In industrialised countries children often buy plastic playthings like
hoops, balls and dolls. Their peers in rural communities of the
developing world might make their own from readily available natural
resources. In The Gambia, creeping plants such as kaba nomboo and
trees like the batiango with its long, flexible branches are ideal for
making a hoop. You simply cross over the ends and lash them firmly
with a piece of cloth. <p>

For many games, the items are simpler still. Take jumpsticks, or
saltar palos as it's known in Bambamarca, Peru, where each player just
needs a stick for everyone else to jump over. In rural parts of Nepal,
children play dandibio while they are goat herding in the mountains -
they find a little stick and hit it with a bigger stick as far as they
can. 

<img alt="[Bangladeshi boys playing kabbadi]" hspace=15 vspace=35
align=left src="game.jpg">

<pre>


</pre><b><font size=2 face=ariel, helvetica>A game of Kabbadi in
Jahasmara Village, Bangladesh.<br>
Photo: Liba Taylor</b></font><br><br><br clear=all>

Somalian boys love to play luuf which requires only a large stone and
a hole in the ground. Whoever manages to throw the stone into the hole
from a specified distance is named "The Chief". <p>

In the provinces of Sierra Leone empty food tins get recycled into
vigorous games played by children of all ages. Bot ki di is temne (one
of the local languages of Sierra Leone) for "put it there". A player
guards a hole half a foot deep with a stick which he uses as a bat.
The rest of the players then try to throw empty tins into the hole
while the player with the stick tries to bat them away.<p> 

A girl from The Gambia watching a game of hopscotch in the UK would be
instantly reminded of padinaydee, a much more sophisticated version.
The grid for hopping (drawn on wet sandy ground in the rainy season)
has 11 "compounds". Once a player has reached the last compound with
her stone or counter and returned successfully with it on her head,
she can "buy" another compound on which only she can land. The game
gets very exciting once several of the compounds are owned and the
girls have to avoid them as they hop and jump around the grid with
their counters on their heads. <p>

The popular Nepalese game carom is reminiscent of pool in the UK,
though played on a large board in place of a table. Instead of potting
balls with cues, coloured disks are flicked into netted holes in the
corners - but the rules are otherwise the same. Also in Nepal baghchal
(literally "tiger and goat") is quite similar to chess. The idea is
for one player's tigers to eat the other player's goats, or the other
player's goats to surround the tigers. In rural areas the board is
drawn on the ground and the players use stones as tigers and goats.
<p>

<b>Holding their breath</b><p>

One popular game throughout Asia is also a national sport. Kabbadi (or
kapardi in Nepal) involves two teams standing at either end of a
pitch, divided by a line. The first player runs to the other side -
while holding their breath and chanting kabbadi - and tries to drag an
opposing player back to their side. So long as player A is on B's
territory the B team can also try to drag A into their side. If player
A starts breathing, they are declared out.<p>

Games represent more than just a bit of fun for children. They can
provide good exercise, learning skills for children with disabilities,
or those who get little access to school - and relaxation after long
hours working at domestic, agricultural or other chores. In regions of
conflict games can play a vital role in helping children to overcome
the trauma of war, or in helping to unite divided communities.
Nicaragua, Burundi and Somaliland are just three countries where
ACTIONAID has facilitated sports and leisure activities as part of its
peace building programmes.<p> 	  

Extra research by Saidu Sesay, Joanna Hill, Bimala Ghimere, Sujeeta
Mathema, Sanjay Rana, Ghanashyam Chettri, Annie Kairaba, and Margaret
Bukarin.
<p>



<p>
<p>
