 <html>
<head>
<title>Fact or fiction - nothing changes</title>
<!!keys: >
</head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>
<font face=ariel, helvetica>

<h2>Fact or Fiction -</h2> 

<b><font size=5 color="#F1B164">"Nothing changes for the better in the
third world"</b></font><p>
<center>
<table width=400 cellpadding=5 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top width=250>
<font face=ariel, helvetica>
This gloomy perception, commonly held in the West, is based on
selected facts. But essentially it's fiction. Over the last 30 years,
millions of families in Africa, Asia and Latin America have seen
dramatic improvements in healthcare and education. Life expectancy in
developing countries is now 17 years longer than it was in 1960.
Infant mortality has been halved. Enrolment in primary and secondary
schools is up by nearly 50 per cent. People's lives have changed, for
the better.<p>

So why is all this overlooked? One reason is that "good news" often
fails to get the same attention as bad news. All too often, the only
time a developing country will appear in the news is during an
emergency. Longer-term positive trends don't make dramatic stories -
so they get ignored. <p>

Yet there are plenty of arresting statistics among these trends if we
care to look for them. In the last 30 years, the proportion of the
world's population with access to safe water has almost doubled, from
36 per cent to 70 per cent. For example, in just one project area -
Bhola Island in Bangladesh - ACTIONAID has dug over 1,000 wells,
benefiting over 26,000 families.<p> 


Here's another surprising statistic - despite rapid population growth
and the stereotypical images of third world hunger, on average people
in developing countries are now producing 20 per cent more food than
they were a decade ago. (ACTIONAID has been involved in this
transformation too, providing training, tools, credit and seed in
thousands of projects around the world).<p>

On the other hand, negative images can't all be blamed on the media.
Sadly, while millions of poor people have seen real improvements in
their lives, the number of people living in absolute poverty has
actually increased. These people still lack even basic provisions,
such as clean water, basic health care or access to education. And
there are more such people now than there were 20 years ago,
particularly in sub-Saharan Africa. And this is why ACTIONAID must
increasingly work with the very poorest people - those who have been
left behind by the advances of the last few decades. <p>

So the figures show how much is left to be done, but they also show
that real change has been achieved. There's no room for complacency -
but none for despair either.<p> 

</td>

<td valign=top width=150>
<table cellpadding=2 width=150 bgcolor="#F1B164">
<tr>
<td> 	                   
<h3>All change</h3>
<font size=2 face=ariel, helvetica>
Nothing ever changes? Try telling that to Ato Bedru Badlu, who lives
in Koysha, Ethiopia. ACTIONAID has been working in this area since
1992, supported by thousands of people in the UK.<p>

"I have seen many things happening since ACTIONAID began working with
us in Koysha," says Ato. "A health post and a new clinic, a child
literacy programme, an adult literacy programme, road maintenance,
footpath construction, and a scheme organising groups of the poor to
benefit from different credit programmes. <p>

"Also, our Tercha elementary school was being eaten by termites and
was going to fall down, but now it looks like new because it has been
renovated by ACTIONAID. I am a member of the school committee and we
had a serious problem of desks. Now, ACTIONAID has equipped the rooms
which enables us to enrol more children. Not only this but a
veterinary clinic was constructed and equipped with drugs, and our
cattle are getting treatment by a veterinary assistant trained by
ACTIONAID.<p>

"Since joining ochi ditcha (development group) I have had a loan from
ACTIONAID and bought goats. I also got the chance to work in a 'cash
for work' programme, mainly on road building, and was able to increase
my income."<p>

It's hard to imagine any of these activities on News at Ten ("Bong!
Man buys goat. Bong! Ants fail to make school fall down.") but they
make a huge difference to the lives of Ato and thousands of other
Ethiopians. For them, things have really got better - and ACTIONAID
and its supporters have been the catalyst.<p>

<img height=196 width=150 hspace=5 vspace=5 src="change.jpg"><br
clear=all ><br>

<b><font size=2 face=ariel, helvetica>
The new clinic in Koysha - where many things have changed for the
better. <br>
Photo: Adrian Arbib</b></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>



<p><hr>
<p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46
height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html"
