 <html>
<head>
<title>Seam of success</title>
<!!keys: >
</head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>
<font face=ariel, helvetica>
<h2>Seam of success</h2>

<font face=ariel, helvetica>
<b>Women in Calcha, Bolivia, are finding a new source of prestige
and income, thanks to ACTIONAID - and 16th century Spanish
miners.</b><p>

<center>
<table width=400 cellpadding=5 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top width=250>

<img hspace=5 vspace=5 height=248 width=180 align=left
src="seam1.jpg">
When Spanish settlers first began mining the Cerro Rico hill which
towers over Potosi in central Bolivia, they couldn't even begin to
guess that their actions would one day help the region's traditional
weavers to survive.<p>

The hill has produced silver, lead and copper for over four
centuries but in recent years its importance to Potosi has depended
less on the value of its ore and more upon the thousands of tourists
it brings to the town. The combination of the mine and the rich
colonial architecture of Potosi have made the town one of the "must
sees" for visitors to Bolivia. And the tourists have provided an
ideal market for the textile art of the region. <p>

Until recently, textile art had been struggling to survive.
Generations of women in Calcha, south of Potosi, for example, had
learned the skills of weaving but as Bolivia developed in the 1970s
many began to feel that it was a symbol of the past. In schools,
children were fined if they arrived in traditional dress, and in
major cities you could be shouted at in the streets for wearing
traditional costume. A whole generation of women grew up believing
that weaving was backward, and there was a real danger that the
artistry would die out.<p>

From that low base, ACTIONAID and a number of independent women's
groups have worked to rescue the traditional skills - and their
potential to create income for poor households in the region. Now
there are six groups, each with around 12 women. Typically, they
meet each week to produce yarn and to dye the wool, while doing the
actual weaving at home. It's painstaking, highly-skilled work and
the results are beautiful - finely-woven cloth with ancient designs
representing objects as diverse as lakes and dogs, wells and bird's
nests. Each has a meaning. "We learned the different designs from
our mothers," explains Rita Mora of the Puca Pampa textile group.
"And though my daughter is a bit young to join a group, now she is
learning them in school."<p>

<img height=180 width=250 hspace=5 vspace=5 src="seam2.gif"><br
clear=all><br>

<b><font size=2 face=ariel, helvetica>
Soft sell: weavers exhibit their
wares to tourists in Potosi's ancient Treasury building, while
displays on the wall tell their story. <p>
Photo: Steve Morgan</b></font><p>

The textile project was established in 1993 by CIAC, a local
organisation which is supported by ACTIONAID and Ayuda en Accion,
our Spanish affiliate. It was the brainchild of Elisabeth Guisler, a
German anthropologist. Elisabeth came to Calcha in 1989 to study the
region's culture and quickly became determined not to study its
decline but to help it survive. "Some of the designs would
definitely have died out," she says. "Many weren't being produced.
Now they have them back, and the women are looking at the designs
that their grandmothers are wearing to see how to produce them."

Earlier this year, you would have found Elisabeth in Potosi's
ancient Treasury building, helping out at an exhibition and sale of
the designs. During the two-week long exhibition, the weavers were
able to display their work to Potosi's tourists, while displays told
the story of the art and the way in which the women work. The
exhibition's popularity is borne out by the enthusiastic comments in
the visitors book (see box). <p>

However, the project has done far more than simply preserve a
traditional way of life. A source of income, self-esteem, and an
opportunity to meet as a group - all of these have been vital
ingredients in the project's success. Income has been a crucial
factor. Many men in the Calcha region are forced to migrate for
months of the year to earn money for their families. Until the
project began to organise the sale of the textiles, women had little
or no income during these months to tide themselves over until
harvest. "Many husbands migrate and send some money, but not
enough," explains Marta de Auchachi, who is president of the women's
groups. "Weaving gives us a source of income so that we can look
after ourselves and our children."<p> 


Though the intricacy of the cloth means each woman can weave only
perhaps 12cm of cloth in a day, it's worth it: a metre-long piece of
cloth can sell for up to £30. This financial incentive adds a new
dimension to the importance of weaving as a source of self-esteem
for women in the region. In Calcha, there is a saying that a good
woman is a good weaver (and vice versa). In a region where decisions
tend to be taken - both inside and outside the home - by men,
textile art was one thing that women could claim as their own. But
as the art began to die out, so too did that prestige. Now it is
returning - with interest. Lucia Mora de Gira is from Calcha, and
now works with the project. She explains: "Being part of the textile
project gives the women an income and they can make a financial
contribution to the family economy. That in turn is changing the way
that men think of them - though there is still a long way to go."
<p>
The change is noticeable in villages such as Yuraj Cancha, high in
the Andes. Here, the community and CIAC have just finished building
a centre for the women to meet. "It was the community as a whole
that wanted a space for the women to meet," says Jose Colque
Miranda, one of the village's leaders (and a man). "Calcha culture
was being lost, and selling the textiles has produced another source
of income for us and our children."<p>

<b>From textiles to politics</b><p>

Centres like the one in Yuraj Cancha are taking the project onto a
new level. Before, weaving was a solitary occupation, carried out
only in the woman's home. Now, women meet together to produce yarn
or to dye the wool. These meetings offer a chance to discuss the way
the weaving is going, but also more general issues. And from these
informal meetings has come a demand for information on family
planning, on health issues - even politics: "The women think it is
important as Bolivians to vote, but they realise that they don't
know enough about the political system to make an informed
decision," says Lucia Mora de Gira. <p>

And the project is also generating a demand among the women for new
skills. Through administrating their groups, the women are finding a
real need for training in literacy and numeracy. Some have basic
skills - enough, for example, to keep track of how much wool they
have used. But increasingly the women want more advanced skills, and
the project is expanding to provide courses for them. "The aim is to
make the project sustainable," says Lucia. "If CIAC leaves, we want
a project that the women can run themselves."<p>

</td>

<td valign=top width=150>
<table with=150 cellpadding=2 bgcolor="#23B3EF">
<tr>
<td>
<font size=4 face=ariel, helvetica>
Comments from the visitors book at the Potosi exhibition<p>
</font>
<font size=2 face=ariel, helvetica>
<i>"This exhibition is marvellous. I was very impressed with the
work and very happy to see all the different cloths from my
country."</i><br>
Paulino Begarano, Bolivia<p>

<i>"A display which makes us proud to be Latin American."</i><br>
Ulises Bacho Gahona, Chile<p>

<i>"Sincere congratulations from four Frenchwomen for this
magnificent textile exhibition.
</i><br>
M. Viguie, France<p>

<i>"Fantastic weaving!"</i><br>
Karlina and Margaret, South Africa<p>

<i>"It's good to see how part of the traditions and textiles are
being recuperated as part of Calchan life."
</i><br>Fernando Unarte Alegre, Spain
<pre>


</pre>
<img width=150 height=154 src="seam3.jpg"><p>

<b><font size=2 face=ariel, helvetica>
Photo: Steve Morgan</b></font>
<font face=ariel, helvetica>
<pre>



</pre>
	  	      
ACTIONAID's work in Calcha is more broad-based than simply
supporting the textile project. For example, in Yuraj Cancha, where
a women's centre has recently been built (see main text), one of the
key problems is lack of water - a problem that the whole region
shares. <p>

Because communities in Yuraj Cancha survive by growing maize,
peaches and apples, every drop of water is vital. ACTIONAID has
helped to provide better, concrete irrigation canals. "Before, the
only irrigation was soil channels that we dug out," says community
leader Jose Colque Miranda. "They wasted a lot of water because it
seeped away. The new concrete canals don't leak and so they improve
production."<p>

Work here also includes training to help improve fruit yields (a
well pruned peach tree will produce twice as many peaches in half
the space), to diversify production into, for example, beekeeping
and vegetables, and to halt the land loss caused by the region's
worsening erosion. <p>

As well as long-term development projects, unforeseen incidents can
of course demand attention. Last year Jose's son Grover (who is
pictured playing football on the front cover) fell off a high wall
and broke his leg. With no medical help in the area, Jose carried
him on a stretcher to Calcha, some five hours away, where CIAC,
ACTIONAID's partner in the region, helped him find a doctor and pay
for treatment.<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<pre>

</pre>

<img align=left hspace=5 vspace=5 width=150 height=288
src="seam4.gif"><br><br clear=all>
<b><font size=2 face=ariel, helvetica>

Children proudly wear their traditional clothes again - once this
kind of outfit could have landed them a school fine.<p>

Photo: Pablo Alcalde</b></font><p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>




         
