 <html>
<head>
<title>Where there's a will...</title>
<!!keys: >
</head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<font face=ariel, helvetica>

<h2>Where there's a will</h2>


<b>Legacies left by supporters are a valuable source of project
funding.</b><p>

<font face=ariel, helvetica>
The residents of Giam village (pictured) in Son La Province,
Vietnam, have learned how they can use an "A-frame" to mark out
lines for planting hedgerows. <p>

Part of an expanding programme, A-frames help farmers of rice, maize
and other crops to cultivate hedgerows along the contours of this
mountainous area, thereby staving off the erosion and deforestation
which threaten their livelihoods. <p>

Having seen for themselves how effective hedgerows can be in
preventing erosion, over 2,000 farmers have now taken up hedgerow
cultivation in eight communities in Son La. As word spreads, more
farmers in neighbouring areas are trying out hedgerows for
themselves.<p>
<center>
<img width=300 height=191 src="will.jpg"><br><br>

<b><font size=2 face=ariel, helvetica>
Photo: Alan Johnson</b></font><br clear=all><br>
</center>
The farming programme in Vietnam has benefited greatly from the
largest legacy ever left to ACTIONAID - £189,000 from a supporter in
Norfolk, who requested that the money should be spent in the Far
East. The donation is also being used to fund healthcare, water, and
savings and credit schemes which allow individuals to start
enterprises by taking out small loans. Son La savings and credit
scheme now has almost 2,000 members, including some of the most
isolated people in the province. <p>

Another generous donor with a particular interest in education has
left £70,000 for education work in Merti, north-east Kenya. The
money will provide teaching and learning materials, and will help
train 40 teachers and 120 members of school committees in languages,
mathematics and management skills. <p>


<table align=left cellpadding=15 bgcolor="#23B3EF" width=200>
<tr>
<td>
<b><font size=4 face=ariel, helvetica>
Every year around £2bn is left by individuals who die without making
a will.  Imagine what a difference that money could make.
</td>
</tr>
</table>


But legacies don't have to be huge to make a difference. Even the
smallest sums bequeathed by ACTIONAID supporters reinforce our work
in parts of the world where supporters have a special interest. Or
they bolster our general funds which are used for emergencies such
as conflict or drought, for influencing policies that affect
poverty, and for research, education projects and other
activities.<p> 

So vital is the funding raised from legacies that ACTIONAID has
teamed up with five other development agencies to operate Will Aid,
through which supporters can have their wills drawn up free of
charge. Pioneered by a Scottish solicitor in 1988 Will Aid has so
far raised almost £2.5m for the six charities, while providing
clients with a cheap and efficient way of making a will to benefit
their loved ones and their chosen causes.<p>
 
The scheme, which runs during November every other year, is not just
for people who wish to donate their whole estate to ACTIONAID or
another Will Aid charity. Many clients leave only a small gift in
their wills, and some none at all. In place of the normal
solicitors' fee, Will Aid suggests that you make a donation of £40
to be passed on to the Will Aid charities. The solicitors involved
in Will Aid give their services for free. <p>

If you are one of the millions of people who intend to make a will
but never quite get around to it, bear in mind that should you die
intestate, a valued friend, relative or organisation might not
receive the special gift you wanted to leave them. Instead your life
savings may automatically be channelled to relatives specified by
the state.<p>

Every year in England and Wales alone around £2bn is left by
individuals who die without making a will. Imagine what a difference
that money could make to their bereaved families and friends - and
to desperately poor communities around the world. 

		
<p><hr>
