</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title> Islands in the storm</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><br><h2 align=center> Islands in the storm</h2></p><p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=220 align=right hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=210><TR><TD> <img src="02.jpg" align=right hspace=3 vspace=2 width=200 height=134 border=1></TD></TR><TR><TD> <p> <font size=small face=helvetica, arial>Photo: Marc Boettcher</font> &copy;</TH></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE><font size=4><font size=+2>T</font>he people who live on Bangladesh's newly-formed islands are some of its poorest - vulnerable to unscrupulous landlords, a changing landscape and, sometimes, to cyclones. ACTIONAID is one of the few charities working with them.</font><p><hr><p>Slowly, Bangladesh is changing shape. The country, which sits in the shadow of the Himalayas where the rivers Meghna, Ganges and Brahmaputra meet, is gaining new land as silt from the mountains to the north is deposited by the rivers to form new islands - chars - on which first plants and then people and animals can live. <p>For a country with the highest population density in the world, new land should be good news, giving landless people somewhere to live. But there are drawbacks. Because settlement of the chars is so new, there is no local government, and basic facilities - water, schools, proper roads - are often makeshift or non-existent. Ownership of the land is often disputed, too, as char inhabitants are forced off their land by unscrupulous landlords or made to pay rent. <p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=280 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=260 bgcolor=CCFFFF><TR><TD><img src="03.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=250 height=165> </TD></TR><TR><TD> <p><font size=small face=helvetica>Dhal Char is an isolated island of the southern tip of Bangladesh. Families survive through fishing and growing crops, but always there is the threat of cyclones, which can strike the island with little warning.<br> (Liba Taylor</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>Then there are the natural hazards. Many of the chars are out in the Bay of Bengal, off the coast of Bangladesh, where they are especially vulnerable to the cyclones which lash the country each year. And the land itself remains unstable. If a river changes direction slightly, the current may erode a part of the char, and land containing someone's home and crops may be carried away - back into the river from which it first came.<p>For all these reasons, the people living on chars are often the most vulnerable among Bangladesh's poor - which is why ACTIONAID is committed to working with them. <p>Char Monnia is a typical example. In 1972 it emerged from the turbulence of the Jamuna river, which flows through the middle of Bangladesh. Successive floods have left silt on the char, making it increasingly fertile for crops. Today, 12,000 people live here, scraping a living by growing groundnuts, rice, sugar cane and lentils. <p>ACTIONAID is the only charity working on Char Monnia, struggling to help the growing population cope with life on this flat block of land lacking a natural supply of fresh water, and without any infrastructure such as schools, clinics or roads.<p>ACTIONAID began working here in 1994, and some of its work is immediately obvious to a visitor. Water was an immediate priority, and in its first year 57 tube wells were sunk nearly 60 metres into the earth, at a cost of around 6,000 taka (about £95) each. More are planned - and needed: up to half of the people on the char still drink river water. Education is another priority, and there are now seven non-formal education centres on the char. ACTIONAID helped to build them and provides the teachers, but each community has a stake in the project too - it pays a small rent for the use of the building. <p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 align=right hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160 bgcolor=CCFFFF><TR><TD><img src="04.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=150 height=234> </TD></TR><TR><TD> <p> <font size=small face=helvetica>Jaigun Begum lives on Char Monnia, a newly-formed char which is home to 12,000 people. Jaigun bought a boat with an ACTIONAID loan and uses it to travel to the uninhabited bank of the river to collect grass for her cow. <br>(Nurjahan Chaklader </font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>Much of ACTIONAID's other work on Char Monnia - as in the rest of Bangladesh - is less visible. It takes place through shomitis - small social groups, usually composed of women. Through shomitis, loans are distributed, which members of the shomiti can use to meet immediate needs or to build income for the future. ACTIONAID provides the initial loan fund, though the members themselves distribute it and collect the repayments. But members are also required to save small amounts each week, and this eventually provides the money to be loaned out. <p>Alisa Khartun moved to Char Monnia 12 years ago, and has been a member of an ACTIONAID shomiti for one year. She had been struggling to make ends meet since her husband died of cholera in 1992 and had fallen into debt. With a T1000 (£16) loan from the shomiti last year, she has been able to pay off the money she owed to moneylenders (and was repaying at far higher interest rates) and buy hens and chickens. Now, she sells the eggs. &quot;I struggled a lot when my husband died,&quot; she says. &quot;He used to work in the field and his income helped us raise our children (Alisa has five, aged between four and 16). Life is still difficult but the loan has been a big help.&quot;<p>Alisa's home is fairly secure, well inland on the char, and erosion should not affect her. However, floods remain a constant hazard - though Alisa is long used to them. Asked how she copes when water rises ten feet, swamping her home, she replies matter-of-factly: &quot;We go on the roof.&quot;<p>Her near-neighbour on Char Monnia is also a member of an ACTIONAID shomiti. Jaigun Begum owns a cow, and needs regular supplies of grass to feed it. But grass is in short supply on Char Monnia, with every available piece of land in use to grow food. Her solution? She borrowed money from the shomiti to buy a small boat, which she uses to go to the other, uninhabited, side of the river to collect the grass.<p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160 bgcolor=CCFFFF><TR><TD><img src="05.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=150 height=258> </TD></TR><TR><TD> <p> <font size=small face=helvetica>This plaque on Dhal Char pays tribute to the ACTIONAID supporters who contributed £670,000 following the terrible cyclone of 1991. The money funded new roads, bridges and cyclone shelters, which saved hundreds of lives when another cyclone struck the island in May 1995.<br>(Marc Boettcher</font> &copy;)</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>Simple arrangements such as this - combined with the provision of water, education and health services - can transform people's lives, and the great majority of ACTIONAID's work throughout Bangladesh takes place through these small but crucial transactions.    Sometimes, though, work needs to take place on a larger scale to help people cope with out-of-the-ordinary events.<p>On Dhal Char, many kilometres off the southern tip of mainland Bangladesh, there is written testimony to this type of work - and oral testimony from people who might well not be alive today were it not for that work.<p>In 1991, Dhal Char found itself in the eye of the worst cyclone to hit Bangladesh for over 20 years. Throughout the country over 100,000 people died, and on Dhal Char the death toll was 103. In the wake of the disaster, ACTIONAID supporters contributed £670,000 to an Emergency Cyclone Programme which provided immediate relief and also funded longer-term work to prevent the disaster from happening again. Two new cyclone shelters were built, along with the roads and bridges which provide a direct route to them, and today the char is dotted with plaques recording the inhabitants' gratitude. <p>On 15 May last year those precautions were put to the test when another cyclone struck the island. Nine-year-old Mohammed Ibrahim takes up the story: &quot;It had been raining heavily for about three or four days. On the last day, the water started to come into the house. The tide rose up and my brother and I drove the cattle to the ground shelter, and then came to the cyclone shelter to take refuge.&quot;It was the evening, and all the rooms were crowded with people. There was hardly any room to spare. I was trembling with fear.<p>&quot;We stayed in the shelter all night, while the floods swept away the land and some of the roads. In the morning we left. My house was partly destroyed, and that of my neighbour was totally destroyed, but we were safe.&quot;<p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=230 align=right hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=210 bgcolor=CCFFFF><TR><TD><img src="06.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=200 height=149> </TD></TR><TR><TD> <p> <font size=small face=helvetica>These children may owe their lives to the cyclone shelters which ACTIONAID supporters funded. (Left to right) Koreem Poraji, Elias Mather, Shamchun Nahar, Balal Maji and Nahar Begum used the shelters during the cyclone of May 1995. Balal was blown from the first floor of the shelter by the heavy winds - but the knee-deep water and soft ground saved him from injury.<br>(Liba Taylor</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>No one died in the 1995 cyclone, though a few had close escapes.        Six-year-old Belal Maji was taken to another ACTIONAID-built shelter by his mother and father. When they weren't looking, he climbed up on to the top of a wall and the wind blew him off. He fell 10 metres, but a combination of mud and knee-deep water saved him from injury. <p>Without the new cyclone shelters, and the roads to them, the outcome might have been very different. The people of Dhal Char, like those of Char Monnia, know that their existence is a precarious one, subject to the vagaries of river, wind, sea and rain, and to the everyday difficulties of earning money, getting an education and keeping healthy. <p>It's a struggle in which ACTIONAID, and its supporters, is proud to play a small but vital role. <br clear=all><hr><p>Find out more about ACTIONAID's work in <b><a href="../../info/bangladesh.html">Bangladesh</a></b><p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><li type=square><b><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>
