<html><head><title> A time to die</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600" background="../../pix/circleor.jpg"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><p><h2 align=center> A time to die</h2></p><p><p><font size=4><font size=+2>I</font>n the final part of our series, we look at the rituals concerning death in some of the communities with which we work.</font><hr><p>For many people in developing countries, death is seen as an integral part of life, rather than an end to it. It is also less of a taboo subject than it has become in Western society (and in some places, funerals are popular venues for young people to meet!). Different religious beliefs give rise to various customs, yet there are many similarities in the ceremonies accompanying a person's departure from this world. Once a death has occurred, a period of mourning begins. Among the Chewa people of rural Malawi, close relations of the deceased wear a strip of cloth, or kam'bambe, around their head to denote their loss. Funerals then take place to celebrate the life of the deceased, furnish them with a good 'sending off', and to establish the social status of the dead person and surviving family members. <p>In Sapeliga in Ghana, people are expected to organise hospitality for the whole village, going on for more than 10 days. Immediate family and in-laws have to provide accommodation, food and       entertainment for hundreds of people. The Sherpas of the Sindhupalchowk area of Nepal also spend a lot of money on the ghewa, a ceremony to free the soul of a dead person from its body. The ghewa lasts for three days and in the weeks prior to it, a lama (Buddhist priest) performs various rituals. A poor family may take up to a year to save enough money to conduct the ghewa.<p>In contrast, in Muslim tradition, when a family member has died the mourners do not cook for themselves for 40 days. Instead, relatives and neighbours bring food. When the 40 days of mourning are over, the family invite all their relatives and friends to a meal, when they might cook the dead person's favourite food as an act of remembrance.<h3>New life </h3>Hindu ceremonies are founded on the belief that the soul has departed from the dead person, to be born again into a new life (reincarnation), and that the body needs to be cast off by burning it. The body of a dead person is wrapped in a cloth and put on a pile of wood. The job of lighting the cremation fire goes to a Hindu's eldest son, while ghee (clarified butter) is thrown on to the fire to help it burn. After three days, the ashes are gathered up, wrapped in a cloth and, if possible, thrown into the river Ganges, the Hindus' holy river. <p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160 bgcolor=FFCC99><TR><TD><img src="07.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=150 height=258> </TD></TR><TR><TD> <p><font size=small face=helvetica>In Galaka, Ghana, offerings of food, herbs and money are built into a pyramid shape which is covered in cloth and photographs of the deceased person.<p>(Jerry Flynn</font> &copy;)</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>Dances and processions are often important features of the funeral ceremony. In Nepal the Sherpas place the dead body in a large copper cauldron, in a sitting position, to take it for cremation. The body is wrapped in a piece of white cloth over 10 metres long which is held by the mourners as they walk to the funeral pyre. A lama leads the procession, and a wind instrument called the lapha is played. For the Chewa people in Malawi, dancers known as zilombi, or beasts, perform the gulewamkulu (or big dance) both before and after the burial to symbolise the deceased's entry into the spirit world. During the burial it is important for any young children of the deceased to throw a piece of charcoal into the grave or coffin, or have the coffin carried over their heads, so that the spirit of the dead does not come back to haunt them. <p>Even after the immediate period of mourning is complete, rituals continue. The ghewa of the Nepalese Sherpas takes place at least five weeks after the body has been cremated. An effigy of the deceased is made using clothes put aside from the cremation and taken to a specially built shed in the courtyard, where it is placed in a nanglo, a round tray made of bamboo. Money and food are placed on the nanglo, and lamas recite religious hymns. Children and close relatives then take turns to make vows to the effigy while holding a scroll with sacred inscriptions.<p>In the Andean villages of Peru, the family of a departed member goes through the ritual laying out of the dead person's clothes, one year later. For 12 months, the soul is believed to have lingered around the home. To help it along to the next world, family and friends gather for an all-night vigil. Candles are lit, mourners chew coca leaves and drink a traditional alcoholic beverage called araquito. By the time dawn breaks, the living and the dead have parted company. 	<br clear=left><p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><b><li type=square><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>
</DOC>
