<html><head><title> Briefing - aid</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><br><h2 align=left> Briefing - aid</h2></p><p><FONT SIZE=4> <font size=+2>D</FONT>espite the improvementsit can make to people'slives in the developingworld, British governmentaid is under threat of cuts. Common Cause examines some of the issuessurrounding aid, includinghow it's spent.</FONT><TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right><TR><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 bgcolor=CCFFFF width=160><TR><TD><img src="08.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=150 height=185></TD><tr><TD> <p><font size=small face=helvetica>ACTIONAID and official aid<br>Each year ACTIONAID receives around £7,000,000 from official sources - almost 20 per cent of its total income. In Mwanza, Malawi, for example, a grant from the Overseas Development Administration has funded the protection of water sources benefiting more than 12,500 people in its first year. Water management skills have been passed on to villagers who will now maintain the systems long into the future.<br>(Jenny Matthews</font> &copy;)</TD></TR></TABLE></TH></TR></TABLE><p><b>1. What do we mean by 'aid'?</b><br>Aid is money given by governments and people in relatively wealthy countries to governments or people in poorer countries. The givers tend to be in the developed world; the recipients, developing countries and those in Eastern Europe/former Soviet Union. <p><b>2. Why do we give aid?</b><br>Most people believe that aid is given chiefly for altruistic reasons - to improve the conditions of people living in poverty. This is certainly true of money given by individual members of the public, and it is also partly true of money given by governments, though not exclusively. Aid from one government to another is also used for purposes such as creating and winning markets for donor government exports, for political leverage and to improve diplomatic relations.<p><b>3. How much do we spend on it?</b><br>Worldwide, in 1993 £36.5 billion was spent in development aid - almost half given by countries in the European Union. Of this total Britain gave £1.9 billion - just under 0.31 per cent of the country's national wealth (GNP). By comparison, Britain spent over £21 billion on defence and over £70 billion on social security. In the same year non-governmental organisations (NGOs) gave over £4 billion - money mostly raised through charitable donations. British NGOs - for example, ACTIONAID and Oxfam - spent £302 million on aid to poor countries.<p><b>4. Do we spend all of it directly?</b><br>No. Of the UK aid budget, 55 per cent is given in grant form directly from the British government. This is known as bilateral aid. The remaining 45 per cent is multilateral aid, channelled through groups of countries such as the European Union (EU) or United Nations (UN). Following an agreement signed at the Edinburgh Summit in 1992, the amount of aid given through the EU is set to rise. By 1998 it is likely that two-thirds of the overall UK aid budget will be spent through multilateral organisations. <img src="09.jpg" align=left hspace=6 vspace=3 width=200 height=207 border=1><p><b>5. Who spends Britain's aid?</b><br>The Overseas Development Administration (ODA), headed by Baroness Lynda Chalker (right), is the UK government department which allocates aid. <p><font size=small face=helvetica, arial>Photo: Marc Boettcher</font> &copy;.<p><b>6. Which countries get most of our bilateral aid ...? </b><br>Last year ODA grants were received by more than 160 countries, with the biggest allocations to: India, Bangladesh, former Yugoslavia, Pakistan, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Uganda, Indonesia, Mozambique and China. Together they accounted for almost £500 million - or almost half the bilateral aid budget. <p><b>7. ...and what is it spent on?</b><br>UK official aid is spent on projects such as clean water, roads and bridges and the provision of electricity; finance for essential materials and equipment such as vehicles, fertiliser and tools; technical assistance such as training and research; and emergency aid.<p><b>8. How much reaches the poorest people?</b><br>According to UN figures, less than 10 per cent of British government bilateral aid is spent on meeting the basic needs of poor people (such as primary health care, clean water and basic education). The remaining 90 per cent is spent on activities concerned less directly with poverty reduction.<p><b>9. Does Britain benefit economically?</b><br>Around one third of the Government's aid programme is 'tied' to the purchase of goods and services from the UK. However, recent studies have shown that this practice inflates the prices of these goods and services by around 15 per cent. Additionally, tied aid stifles the growth of industry in the Third World, creates dependence on parts and maintenance from donor countries, and is less likely than aid which is not tied to be poverty-focused.<p><b>10. Do we spend more or less now than in the past?</b><br>Over the past 25 years, the UK aid budget has declined from 0.51 per cent of GNP in 1979 to 0.31 per cent in 1993. To a large extent this mirrors the decline in aid from rich countries. 	Despite an agreement more than 20 years ago by most donor countries to increase aid levels to 0.7 per cent of GNP (an amount, set by the UN, that was believed would substantially reduce poverty), few give more than half this. And apart from Norway, Denmark, Sweden and the Netherlands, which consistently meet or exceed 0.7 per cent, the general trend is for governments to move away from the target rather than towards it. <p><b>11. What is ACTIONAID's view of the situation...?</b><br>ACTIONAID is concerned at declining aid levels, at the small percentage that is targeted towards such fundamental areas as primary healthcare, clean water and basic education, and at what this demonstrates about the commitment of rich countries to reduce poverty. It is not alone. In October 1994, ACTIONAID published the results of a parliamentary poll showing that 82 per cent of MPs believe more money should be spent on these areas. In the same poll, 70 per cent said they would like to see the aid budget doubled. <p><b>12. ...and what is it doing about it?</b><br>ACTIONAID is urging the Government to make the following changes to its aid spending: <ul><li>To protect the aid budget from cuts.<li>To increase the proportion of bilateral aid spent on basic needs to 20 per cent of the total budget. (This would provide substantial extra funds to support people in extreme poverty.)<li>As a first step, to increase the total aid budget to at least equal the average of our European Partners - currently around 0.49 per cent. The second stage would be to meet the 0.7 per cent target.<li>To reduce the amount of tied aid from its current levels.</ul>	Above all, ACTIONAID believes that aid money should be spent, first and foremost, in reducing poverty and helping poor communities improve their quality of life. <p>ACTIONAID is joining forces with other development agencies to protect the UK's aid budget from potential cuts this autumn. If you would like to help, or require further information, please contact <b>ACTIONAID on 0171 281 4101.</b><p><hr><h3>The Pergau Dam affair </h3><p>The Aid and Trade Provision (ATP) is a part of the Government's aid programme which is intended to advance UK commercial interests abroad and promote development. It accounts for between five and ten per cent of the overall aid programme. <p>In 1991 the Government gave the approval to fund the construction of a hydro-electric dam in Malaysia through the ATP programme. Over time, however, it became clear that not only would the dam cost British taxpayers £234 million - more than the yearly sum spent on basic needs - it would cost the Malaysian government £100 million more in electricity costs than some cheaper alternatives. 	The project led the World Development Movement - a UK pressure group - to seek legal action. After a court case in November 1994, the Government was found guilty of abusing the 1980 Overseas Development and Cooperation Act. Funding the Pergau Dam project was ruled unlawful because it was neither economically sound nor a contribution to reducing poverty.	As a result the Government agreed to find future resources for Pergau from the Treasury rather than the aid budget. However, the government's proposed cuts to the UK bilateral aid budget are roughly equal to the amount being paid by the Treasury for Pergau, raising concern that the ODA is being 'punished' for the affair.<p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><li type=square><b><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>
