<html><head><title> Coffee break</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><p><h2 align=center> Coffee break</h2></p><p><img src="10.jpg" align=left hspace=4 vspace=4 width=200 height=184 border=1><p><font size=4><font size=+2>O</font>rganic coffee production is proving a success for farmers in El Salvador, supported by ACTIONAID sponsors</font><p><font size=small face=helvetica, arial>Photo: Marianne Manjivar</font> &copy;.<p><hr><p>Twelve years of civil war in El Salvador has brought about one unexpected benefit to the people of Usulutan. With help from COMUS, a local organisation, and from ACTIONAID, the people from the communities around Taburete Hill have been able to rehabilitate abandoned lands using organic farming techniques, and earn a living growing coffee.<p>The story goes back to the 1980s, when the campesinos (peasant farmers) took over plantations abandoned by the large landowners during the war, and set about working them for themselves. Despite the physical danger the armed conflict brought for them, the campesinos at first sowed basic crops such as maize and beans for their daily survival.<p>When the conflict came to an end in early 1992, the campesinos organised themselves into co-operatives, with the help of COMUS, so that they could make their claims to legal land titles, provided for under the UN-brokered peace accords. These stipulated that people who had been farming land would be allowed to continue doing so and would be helped to find a satisfactory legal solution to definitive land ownership. In the new climate of peace, the campesinos also sought COMUS's help in the form of credit and technical advice and support. They wanted to start planting coffee once again, to supplement their subsistence crops of beans and maize. The war was finished, and as campesino  Jose Eduardo Sigaran says: <i>&quot;Coffee planting is a long tradition. From the moment we are born we come to this world with the tradition of coffee, a tradition which comes from our dead grandparents. It is an intrinsic part of us.&quot;*</i><p>Here, they stumbled upon one of the most unexpected and unforeseen benefits of the war. For 12 years, most of the land around Taburete Hill had been free of chemicals. Once the properties had been abandoned, the campesinos had been too poor to afford the chemical fertilisers, weed killers, and chemical pesticides. The land could now be exploited in a more environmentally friendly way - to grow organic coffee, which was both cheaper to produce and fetched a better price in the marketplace.Enrique Zelaya, COMUS's organic farming advisor, says: <i>&quot;We can achieve a better standard of living, without any cost to the community's natural resources.&quot;</i><p>The only blot on the landscape is that one of the cooperatives in the area has had difficulty obtaining the legal titles giving them the de facto right to the land they have worked so hard over the last 10 years. Though COMUS has appointed a legal adviser for the campesinos, as yet the problem remains unresolved. In the meantime, those with the closest historical and ancestral ties to the land, the campesinos of Taburete, continue looking after their chief livelihood resource with organic farming methods.  <p><i>*Shortly after recording this interview, Jose Eduardo Sigaran and his nephew, an ACTIONAID sponsored child, were tragically killed in a landslide caused by heavy rains. ACTIONAID expresses its sympathy, and is helping the families affected by the landslide to rebuild their homes. </i><p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">