<html><head><title> The ties that bind</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600" background="../../pix/circleor.jpg"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><p><h2 align=center> The ties that bind</h2></p><font size=4><font size=+2>G</font>etting married is the norm for most people - but the ceremonies surrounding it are very, very different... </font><hr><img src="11.jpg" align=left hspace=4 vspace=4 width=200 height=185 border=1><p>Throughout history, marriage has been regarded as an alliance between two families, rather than the 'love match' of today's Western society, and in most countries of the world this is still the case. Often it will take place earlier than is normal in the West - half the women in Africa, 40 per cent in Asia and 30 per cent in Latin America will be married by the age of 18. In some societies, social factors - often economic ones - will give rise to polygamy. <p>These different types of marriage are reflected in the radically different customs and traditions that surround wedding ceremonies. However, their essential function remains the same, and many ceremonies contain similar rituals and customs.<p>Rituals involving symbolic items - clothes, foods and other objects - are familiar features of weddings worldwide. <p>In India, Hindu ceremonies vary greatly but they share one common symbol: fire - whether in the form of diyas (lighted lamps) or a small fire behind which the couple sit. In virtually all Hindu ceremonies, the couple walk at a significant moment clockwise around the fire or diyas seven times, to symbolise seven sacred pledges.<p>In Sella Limba, Sierra Leone, the marriage ceremony involves kola nuts, a packet of needles, thread, a mat and some money, which are put inside a calabash (the shell of a gourd) and wrapped in a thiga-ba-huheh (a piece of white cloth). They signify long life and prosperity (the gourd), economy during hard times (the needles, thread and mat), betrothal value (the money) and purity (the cloth). <p>Legal customs are also common in marriage ceremonies. Marriage - along with death - is the time of life when property is most likely to change hands. Under the dowry system, for example, women must take a substantial part of the family's wealth with them into a marriage. <p><b>Wedding bond</b><p>Once inside the marriage, this property is most likely to be controlled by the husband - though not always. Among the Amharas of central Ethiopia, the couple sign a wedding bond which asserts the right of each partner to one half of all property acquired during the time of the marriage (though not to that acquired before). This right is called Habtish be Habete ('Your chance is mine'). <p>Social customs also abound. Different societies have very different customs concerning who may marry whom, what type of courtship should be carried out and how the marriage ceremony should be conducted. <p>In highland Bolivia, indigenous Aymara traditions flourish despite conversion to Christianity many centuries ago. Courtship often involves the man stealing the possessions of the woman and waiting for her to reclaim them. <p>Among the Amharas, the wedding customs also last for a week or so. Here, the couple live with the groom's parents after the ceremony and, one week later, are invited by the bride's parents for dinner, along with friends and members of the family circle. Only after about two months do the couple leave the groom's parents' home and live by themselves. <p>Though the customs may vary in many of the communities with which ACTIONAID works, the essential function of marriage is the same: to ensure an individual's livelihood and to provide an environment in which to produce heirs. Frequently, the marriage is arranged by the parents of the bride and groom, often with the help of community elders. Though love is often expected to develop after the marriage, it is not a prerequisite for it to happen in the first place.<p>  The views of the couple may be taken into account, however. Among the Aymara of Bolivia, for example, both sets of parents, and both fianc&eacute;s, have the option of cancelling during the cohabitation period. Here, as in most Western societies, young people increasingly want more freedom in their choice. However, though this trend is increasing, the 'traditional' family-arranged marriage looks set to remain the norm in most societies well into the 21st century. <p>Research by: Milkias Lissanu, ACTIONAID Ethiopia; Adam Burke, ACTIONAID Bolivia; Isatu M Koroma, ACTIONAID Sierra Leone; Ashish Sen, ACTIONAID India. <p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><li type=square><b><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b<br clear=all><p></body></html>
